23146	40	1	1	The book of the generacioun of Jhesu Crist, the sone of Dauid, the sone of Abraham.
23147	40	1	2	Abraham bigat Isaac. Isaac bigat Jacob. Jacob bigat Judas and hise britheren.
23148	40	1	3	Judas bigat Fares and Zaram, of Tamar. Fares bigat Esrom.
23149	40	1	4	Esrom bigat Aram. Aram bigat Amynadab. Amynadab bigat Naason. Naason bigat Salmon.
23150	40	1	5	Salmon bigat Booz, of Raab. Booz bigat Obeth, of Ruth. Obeth bigat Jesse. Jesse bigat Dauid the king.
23151	40	1	6	Dauid the king bigat Salamon, of hir that was Vries wijf.
23152	40	1	7	Salomon bigat Roboam. Roboam bigat Abias.
23153	40	1	8	Abias bigat Asa. Asa bigat Josaphath. Josaphath bigat Joram. Joram bigat
23154	40	1	9	Osias. Osias bigat Joathan. Joathan bigat Achaz. Achaz bigat Ezechie.
23155	40	1	10	Ezechie bigat Manasses. Manasses bigat Amon.
23156	40	1	11	Amon bigat Josias. Josias bigat Jeconyas and his britheren, in to the transmygracioun of Babiloyne.
23157	40	1	12	And aftir the transmygracioun of Babiloyne, Jeconyas bigat Salatiel. Salatiel bigat Zorobabel.
23158	40	1	13	Zorobabel bigat Abyut. Abyut bigat Eliachym. Eliachym bigat Asor.
23159	40	1	14	Asor bigat Sadoc. Sadoc bigat Achym.
23160	40	1	15	Achym bigat Elyut. Elyut bigat Eleasar. Eleasar bigat Mathan.
23161	40	1	16	Mathan bigat Jacob. Jacob bigat Joseph, the hosebonde of Marye, of whom Jhesus was borun, that is clepid Christ.
23162	40	1	17	And so alle generaciouns fro Abraham to Dauid ben fourtene generacions, and fro Dauid to the transmygracioun of Babiloyne ben fourtene generaciouns, and fro the transmygracioun of Babiloyne to Crist ben fourtene generaciouns.
23163	40	1	18	But the generacioun of Crist was thus. Whanne Marie, the modir of Jhesu, was spousid to Joseph, bifore thei camen togidere, she was foundun hauynge of the Hooli Goost in the wombe.
23164	40	1	19	And Joseph, hir hosebonde, for he was riytful, and wolde not puplische hir, he wolde priueli haue left hir.
23165	40	1	20	But while he thouyte thes thingis, lo! the aungel of the Lord apperide `in sleep to hym, and seide, Joseph, the sone of Dauid, nyle thou drede to take Marie, thi wijf; for that thing that is borun in hir is of the Hooli Goost.
23166	40	1	21	And she shal bere a sone, and thou shalt clepe his name Jhesus; for he schal make his puple saaf fro her synnes.
23167	40	1	22	For al this thing was don, that it schulde be fulfillid, that was seid of the Lord bi a prophete, seiynge, Lo!
23168	40	1	23	a virgyn shal haue in wombe, and she schal bere a sone, and thei schulen clepe his name Emanuel, that is to seie, God with vs.
23169	40	1	24	And Joseph roos fro sleepe, and dide as the aungel of the Lord comaundide hym, and took Marie, his wijf;
23170	40	1	25	and he knew her not, til she hadde borun her firste bigete sone, and clepide his name Jhesus.
23171	40	2	1	Therfor whanne Jhesus was borun in Bethleem of Juda, in the daies of king Eroude, lo! astromyenes camen fro the eest to Jerusalem,
23172	40	2	2	and seiden, Where is he, that is borun king of Jewis? for we han seyn his sterre in the eest, and we comen to worschipe him.
23173	40	2	3	But king Eroude herde, and was trublid, and al Jerusalem with hym.
23174	40	2	4	And he gaderide to gidre alle the prynces of prestis, and scribis of the puple, and enqueride of hem, where Crist shulde be borun.
23175	40	2	5	And thei seiden to hym, In Bethleem of Juda; for so it is writun bi a profete,
23176	40	2	6	And thou, Bethleem, the lond of Juda, art not the leest among the prynces of Juda; for of thee a duyk schal go out, that schal gouerne my puple of Israel.
23177	40	2	7	Thanne Eroude clepide pryueli the astromyens, and lernyde bisili of hem the tyme of the sterre that apperide to hem.
23178	40	2	8	And he sente hem in to Bethleem, and seide, Go ye, and axe ye bisili of the child, and whanne yee han foundun, telle ye it to me, that Y also come, and worschipe hym.
23179	40	2	9	And whanne thei hadden herd the kyng, thei wenten forth. And lo! the sterre, that thei siyen in the eest, wente bifore hem, til it cam, and stood aboue, where the child was.
23180	40	2	10	And thei siyen the sterre, and ioyeden with a ful greet ioye.
23181	40	2	11	And thei entriden in to the hous, and founden the child with Marie, his modir; and thei felden doun, and worschipiden him. And whanne thei hadden openyd her tresouris, thei offryden to hym yiftis, gold, encense, and myrre.
23182	40	2	12	And whanne thei hadden take an aunswere in sleep, that thei schulden not turne ayen to Eroude, thei turneden ayen bi anothir weie in to her cuntrey.
23183	40	2	13	And whanne thei weren goon, lo! the aungel of the Lord apperide to Joseph in sleep, and seide, Rise vp, and take the child and his modir, and fle in to Egipt, and be thou there, til that I seie to thee; for it is to come, that Eroude seke the child, to destrie hym.
23184	40	2	14	And Joseph roos, and took the child and his modir bi nyyt, and wente in to Egipt,
23185	40	2	15	and he was there to the deeth of Eroude; that it schulde be fulfillid, that was seid of the Lord bi the profete, seiynge, Fro Egipt Y haue clepid my sone.
23186	40	2	16	Thanne Eroude seynge that he was disseyued of the astromyens, was ful wrooth; and he sente, and slowe alle the children, that weren in Bethleem, and in alle the coostis therof, fro two yeer age and with inne, aftir the tyme that he had enquerid of the astromyens.
23187	40	2	17	Thanne `it was fulfillid, that was seid bi Jeremye, the profete,
23188	40	2	18	seiynge, A vois was herd an hiy, wepynge and moche weilyng, Rachel biwepynge hir sones, and she wolde not be coumfortid, for thei ben noyt.
23189	40	2	19	But whanne Eroude was deed, loo! the aungel of the Lord apperide to Joseph in sleep in Egipt,
23190	40	2	20	and seide, Ryse vp, and take the child and his modir, and go in to the lond of Israel; for thei that souyten the lijf of the chijld ben deed.
23191	40	2	21	Joseph roos, and took the child and his modir, and cam in to the loond of Israel.
23192	40	2	22	And he herde that Archilaus regnede in Judee for Eroude, his fadir, and dredde to go thidir. And he was warned in sleep, and wente in to the parties of Galilee;
23193	40	2	23	and cam, and dwelte in a citee, that ys clepid Nazareth, that it shulde be fulfillid, that was seid bi profetis, For he shal be clepid a Nazarey.
23194	40	3	1	In tho daies Joon Baptist cam, and prechide in the desert of Judee,
23195	40	3	2	and seide, Do ye penaunce, for the kyngdom of heuenes shal neiye.
23196	40	3	3	For this is he, of whom it is seid bi Ysaie, the prophete, seyinge, A vois of a crier in desert, Make ye redi the weies of the Lord; make ye riyt the pathis of hym.
23197	40	3	4	And this Joon hadde clothing of camels heeris, and a girdil of skynne aboute hise leendis; and his mete was honysoukis, and hony of the wode.
23198	40	3	5	Thanne Jerusalem wente out to hym, and al Judee, and al the cuntre aboute Jordan;
23199	40	3	6	and thei weren waischun of hym in Jordan, `and knowlechiden her synnes.
23200	40	3	7	But he siy manye of the Farysees and of Saduceis comynge to his baptym, and seide to hem, Generaciouns of eddris, who shewide to you to fle fro the wraththe that is to come?
23201	40	3	8	Therfor do ye worthi fruyte of penaunce,
23202	40	3	9	and nyle ye seie with ynne you, We han Abraham to fadir; for Y seie to you, that God is myyti to reise vp of these stoones the sones of Abraham.
23203	40	3	10	And now the ax is put to the roote of the tree; therfore euery tree that makith not good fruyt, shal be kit doun, and shal be cast in to the fier.
23204	40	3	11	Y waische you in water, in to penaunce; but he that shal come after me is strongere than Y, whos schoon Y am not worthi to bere; he shal baptise you in the Hooli Goost and fier.
23205	40	3	12	Whos wynewing cloth is in his hoond, and he shal fulli clense his corn flore, and shal gadere his whete in to his berne; but the chaffe he shal brenne with fier that mai not be quenchid.
23206	40	3	13	Thanne Jhesus cam fro Galilee in to Jordan to Joon, to be baptised of hym.
23207	40	3	14	And Joon forbede him, and seide, Y owe to be baptisid of thee, and thou comest to me?
23208	40	3	15	But Jhesus answeride, and seide to hym, Suffre nowe, for thus it fallith to vs to fulfille al riytfulnesse.
23209	40	3	16	Thanne Joon suffride hym. And whanne Jhesus was baptisid, anoon he wente up fro the watir; and lo! heuenes weren openyd to hym, and he saie the Spirit of God comynge doun as a dowue, and comynge on hym; and loo!
23210	40	3	17	a vois fro heuenes, seiynge, This is my louyd sone, in which Y haue plesid to me.
23211	40	4	1	Thanne Jhesus was led of a spirit in to desert, to be temptid of the feend.
23212	40	4	2	And whanne he hadde fastid fourti daies and fourti nyytis, aftirward he hungride.
23213	40	4	3	And the tempter cam nyy, and seide to hym, If thou art Goddis sone, seie that thes stoones be maad looues.
23214	40	4	4	Which answeride, and seide to hym, It is writun, Not oonli in breed luyeth man, but in ech word that cometh of Goddis mouth.
23215	40	4	5	Thanne the feend took hym in to the hooli citee, and settide hym on the pynacle of the temple,
23216	40	4	6	and seide to hym, If thou art Goddis sone, sende thee adoun; for it is writun, That to hise aungels he comaundide of thee, and thei schulen take thee in hondis, lest perauenture thou hirte thi foot at a stoon.
23217	40	4	7	Eftsoone Jhesus seide to hym, It is writun, Thou shalt not tempte thi Lord God.
23218	40	4	8	Eftsoone the feend took hym in to a ful hiy hil, and schewide to hym alle the rewmes of the world, and the ioye of hem;
23219	40	4	9	and seide to hym, Alle these `Y schal yyue to thee, if thou falle doun and worschipe me.
23220	40	4	10	Thanne Jhesus seide to hym, Goo, Sathanas; for it is writun, Thou schalt worschipe thi Lord God, and to hym aloone thou shalt serue.
23221	40	4	11	Thanne the feend lafte hym; and lo! aungels camen nyy, and serueden to hym.
23222	40	4	12	But whanne Jhesus hadde herd that Joon was takun, he wente in to Galilee.
23223	40	4	13	And he lefte the citee of Nazareth, and cam, and dwelte in the citee of Cafarnaum, biside the see, in the coostis of Zabulon and Neptalym,
23224	40	4	14	that it shulde be fulfillid, that was seid by Ysaie, the profete, seiynge,
23225	40	4	15	The lond of Sabulon and the lond of Neptalym, the weie of the see ouer Jordan, of Galilee of hethen men,
23226	40	4	16	the puple that walkide in derknessis saye greet liyt, and while men satten in the cuntre of shadewe of deth, liyt aroos to hem.
23227	40	4	17	Fro that tyme Jhesus bigan to preche, and seie, Do ye penaunce, for the kyngdom of heuenes schal come niy.
23228	40	4	18	And Jhesus walkide bisidis the see of Galilee, and saye twei britheren, Symount, that is clepid Petre, and Andrewe, his brothir, castynge nettis in to the see; for thei weren fischeris.
23229	40	4	19	And he seide to hem, Come ye aftir me, and Y shal make you to be maad fisscheris of men.
23230	40	4	20	And anoon thei leften the nettis, and sueden hym.
23231	40	4	21	And he yede forth fro that place, and saie tweyne othere britheren, James of Zebede, and Joon, his brother, in a schip with Zebede, her fadir, amendynge her nettis, and he clepide hem.
23232	40	4	22	And anoon thei leften the nettis and the fadir, and sueden hym.
23233	40	4	23	And Jhesus yede aboute al Galilee, techynge in the synagogis of hem, and prechynge the gospel of the kyngdom, and heelynge euery languor and eche sekenesse among the puple.
23234	40	4	24	And his fame wente in to al Sirie; and thei brouyten to hym alle that weren at male ese, and that weren take with dyuerse languores and turmentis, and hem that hadden feendis, and lunatike men, and men in palesy, and he heelide hem.
23235	40	4	25	And ther sueden hym myche puple of Galile, and of Decapoli, and of Jerusalem, and of Judee, and of biyende Jordan.
23236	40	5	1	And Jhesus, seynge the puple, wente vp in to an hil; and whanne he was set, hise disciplis camen to hym.
23237	40	5	2	And he openyde his mouth, and tauyte hem, and seide,
23238	40	5	3	Blessed ben pore men in spirit, for the kyngdom of heuenes is herne.
23239	40	5	4	Blessid ben mylde men, for thei schulen welde the erthe.
23240	40	5	5	Blessid ben thei that mornen, for thei schulen be coumfortid.
23241	40	5	6	Blessid ben thei that hungren and thristen riytwisnesse, for thei schulen be fulfillid.
23242	40	5	7	Blessid ben merciful men, for thei schulen gete merci.
23243	40	5	8	Blessid ben thei that ben of clene herte, for thei schulen se God.
23244	40	5	9	Blessid ben pesible men, for thei schulen be clepid Goddis children.
23245	40	5	10	Blessid ben thei that suffren persecusioun for riytfulnesse, for the kingdam of heuenes is herne.
23246	40	5	11	`Ye schulen be blessid, whanne men schulen curse you, and schulen pursue you, and shulen seie al yuel ayens you liynge, for me.
23247	40	5	12	Ioie ye, and be ye glad, for youre meede is plenteuouse in heuenes; for so thei han pursued `also profetis that weren bifor you.
23248	40	5	13	Ye ben salt of the erthe; that if the salt vanysche awey, whereynne schal it be saltid? To no thing it is worth ouere, no but that it be cast out, and be defoulid of men.
23249	40	5	14	Ye ben liyt of the world; a citee set on an hil may not be hid;
23250	40	5	15	ne me teendith not a lanterne, and puttith it vndur a busschel, but on a candilstike, that it yyue liyt to alle that ben in the hous.
23251	40	5	16	So schyne youre liyt befor men, that thei se youre goode werkis, and glorifie youre fadir that is in heuenes.
23252	40	5	17	Nil ye deme, that Y cam to vndo the lawe, or the profetis; Y cam not to vndo the lawe, but to fulfille.
23253	40	5	18	Forsothe Y seie to you, til heuene and erthe passe, o lettir or o titel shal not passe fro the lawe, til alle thingis be doon.
23254	40	5	19	Therfor he that brekith oon of these leeste maundementis, and techith thus men, schal be clepid the leste in the rewme of heuenes; `but he that doith, and techith, schal be clepid greet in the kyngdom of heuenes.
23255	40	5	20	And Y seie to you, that but your riytfulnesse be more plenteuouse than of scribis and of Farisees, ye schulen not entre into the kyngdom of heuenes.
23256	40	5	21	Ye han herd that it was seid to elde men, Thou schalt not slee; and he that sleeth, schal be gilti to doom.
23257	40	5	22	But Y seie to you, that ech man that is wrooth to his brothir, schal be gilti to doom; and he that seith to his brother, Fy! schal be gilti to the counseil; but he that seith, Fool, schal be gilti to the fier of helle.
23258	40	5	23	Therfor if thou offrist thi yifte `at the auter, and ther thou bithenkist, that thi brothir hath sum what ayens thee,
23259	40	5	24	leeue there thi yifte bifor the auter, and go first to be recounselid to thi brothir, and thanne thou schalt come, and schalt offre thi yifte.
23260	40	5	25	Be thou consentynge to thin aduersarie soone, while thou art in the weie with hym, lest perauenture thin aduersarie take thee to the domesman, and the domesman take thee to the mynystre, and thou be sent in to prisoun.
23261	40	5	26	Treuli Y seie to thee, thou shalt not go out fro thennus, til thou yelde the last ferthing.
23262	40	5	27	Ye han herd that it was seid to elde men, Thou schalt `do no letcherie.
23263	40	5	28	But Y seie to you, that euery man that seeth a womman for to coueite hir, hath now do letcherie bi hir in his herte.
23264	40	5	29	That if thi riyt iye sclaundre thee, pulle hym out, and caste fro thee; for it spedith to thee, that oon of thi membris perische, than that al thi bodi go in to helle.
23265	40	5	30	And if thi riyt hond sclaundre thee, kitte hym aweye, and caste fro thee; for it spedith to thee that oon of thi membris perische, than that al thi bodi go in to helle.
23266	40	5	31	And it hath be seyd, Who euere leeueth his wijf, yyue he to hir a libel of forsakyng.
23267	40	5	32	But Y seie to you, that euery man that leeueth his wijf, outtakun cause of fornycacioun, makith hir to do letcherie, and he that weddith the forsakun wijf, doith auowtrye.
23268	40	5	33	Eftsoone ye han herd, that it was seid to elde men, Thou schalt not forswere, but thou schalt yelde thin othis to the Lord.
23269	40	5	34	But Y seie to you, that ye swere not `for ony thing; nethir bi heuene, for it is the trone of God;
23270	40	5	35	nether bi the erthe, for it is the stole of his feet; nether bi Jerusalem, for it is the citee of a greet kyng; nether thou shalt not swere bi thin heed,
23271	40	5	36	for thou maist not make oon heere white, ne blacke;
23272	40	5	37	but be youre word, Yhe, yhe; Nay, nay; and that that is more than these, is of yuel.
23273	40	5	38	Ye han herd that it hath be seid, Iye for iye, and tothe for tothe.
23274	40	5	39	But Y seie to you, that ye ayenstonde not an yuel man; but if ony smyte thee in the riyt cheke, schewe to him also the tothir;
23275	40	5	40	and to hym that wole stryue with thee in doom, and take awey thi coote, leeue thou `to him also thi mantil;
23276	40	5	41	and who euer constreyneth thee a thousynde pacis, go thou with hym othir tweyne.
23277	40	5	42	Yyue thou to hym that axith of thee, and turne not awey fro hym that wole borewe of thee.
23278	40	5	43	Ye han herd that it was seid, Thou shalt loue thi neiybore, and hate thin enemye.
23279	40	5	44	But Y seie to you, loue ye youre enemyes, do ye wel to hem that hatiden you, and preye ye for hem that pursuen, and sclaundren you;
23280	40	5	45	that ye be the sones of your fadir that is in heuenes, that makith his sunne to rise vpon goode `and yuele men, and reyneth on iust men and vniuste.
23281	40	5	46	For if ye louen hem that louen you, what mede schulen ye han? whether pupplicans doon not this?
23282	40	5	47	And if ye greten youre britheren oonli, what schulen ye do more? ne doon not hethene men this?
23283	40	5	48	Therfore be ye parfit, as youre heuenli fadir is parfit.
23284	40	6	1	Takith hede, that ye do not youre riytwisnesse bifor men, to be seyn of hem, ellis ye schulen haue no meede at youre fadir that is in heuenes.
23285	40	6	2	Therfore whanne thou doist almes, nyle thou trumpe tofore thee, as ypocritis doon in synagogis and stretis, that thei be worschipid of men; sotheli Y seie to you, they han resseyued her meede.
23286	40	6	3	But whanne thou doist almes, knowe not thi left hond what thi riyt hond doith, that thin almes be in hidils,
23287	40	6	4	and thi fadir that seeth in hiddils, schal quyte thee.
23288	40	6	5	And whanne ye preyen, ye schulen not be as ipocritis, that louen to preye stondynge in synagogis and corneris of stretis, to be seyn of men; treuli Y seie to you, thei han resseyued her meede.
23289	40	6	6	But whanne thou schalt preye, entre in to thi couche, and whanne the dore is schet, preye thi fadir in hidils, and thi fadir that seeth in hidils, schal yelde to thee.
23290	40	6	7	But in preiyng nyle yee speke myche, as hethene men doon, for thei gessen that thei ben herd in her myche speche.
23291	40	6	8	Therfor nyle ye be maad lich to hem, for your fadir woot what is nede to you, bifore that ye axen hym.
23292	40	6	9	And thus ye schulen preye, Oure fadir that art in heuenes, halewid be thi name;
23293	40	6	10	thi kyngdoom come to; be thi wille don `in erthe as in heuene;
23294	40	6	11	yyue to vs this dai oure `breed ouer othir substaunce;
23295	40	6	12	and foryyue to vs oure dettis, as we foryyuen to oure dettouris; and lede vs not in to temptacioun,
23296	40	6	13	but delyuere vs fro yuel.
23297	40	6	14	Amen. For if ye foryyuen to men her synnes, youre heuenli fadir schal foryyue to you youre trespassis.
23298	40	6	15	Sotheli if ye foryyuen not to men, nether youre fadir schal foryyue to you youre synnes.
23299	40	6	16	But whanne ye fasten, nyle ye be maad as ypocritis sorewful, for thei defacen hem silf, to seme fastyng to men; treuli Y seie to you, they han resseyued her meede.
23300	40	6	17	But whanne thou fastist, anoynte thin heed, and waische thi face,
23301	40	6	18	that thou be not seen fastynge to men, but to thi fadir that is in hidlis, and thi fadir that seeth in priuey, shal yelde to thee.
23302	40	6	19	Nile ye tresoure to you tresouris in erthe, where ruste and mouyte destrieth, and where theues deluen out and stelen;
23303	40	6	20	but gadere to you tresouris in heuene, where nether ruste ne mouyte distrieth, and where theues deluen not out, ne stelen.
23304	40	6	21	For where thi tresoure is, there also thin herte is.
23305	40	6	22	The lanterne of thi bodi is thin iye; if thin iye be symple, al thi bodi shal be liytful;
23306	40	6	23	but if thin iye be weiward, al thi bodi shal be derk. If thanne the liyt that is in thee be derknessis, how grete schulen thilk derknessis be?
23307	40	6	24	No man may serue tweyn lordis, for ethir he schal hate `the toon, and loue the tother; ethir he shal susteyne `the toon, and dispise the tothir. Ye moun not serue God and richessis.
23308	40	6	25	Therfor I seie to you, that ye be not bisi to youre lijf, what ye schulen ete; nether to youre bodi, with what ye schulen be clothid. Whether lijf is not more than meete, and the bodie more than cloth?
23309	40	6	26	Biholde ye the foulis of the eire, for thei sowen not, nethir repen, nethir gaderen in to bernes; and youre fadir of heuene fedith hem. Whether ye ben not more worthi than thei?
23310	40	6	27	But who of you thenkynge mai putte to his stature o cubit?
23311	40	6	28	And of clothing what ben ye bisye? Biholde ye the lilies of the feeld, how thei wexen. Thei trauelen not, nether spynnen;
23312	40	6	29	and Y seie to you, Salomon in al his glorie was not keuered as oon of these.
23313	40	6	30	And if God clothith thus the hei of the feeld, that to day is, and to morewe is cast in to an ouen, hou myche more you of litel feith?
23314	40	6	31	Therfor nyle ye be bisi, seiynge, What schulen we ete? or, What schulen we drinke? or, With what thing schulen we be keuered?
23315	40	6	32	For hethene men seken alle these thingis; and youre fadir woot, that ye han nede to alle these thingis.
23316	40	6	33	Therfor seke ye first the kyngdom of God, and his riytfulnesse, and alle these thingis shulen be cast to you.
23317	40	6	34	Therfor nyle ye be bisy in to the morew, for the morew shal be bisi to `hym silf; for it suffisith to the dai his owen malice.
23318	40	7	1	Nile ye deme, `that ye be not demed; for in what doom ye demen,
23319	40	7	2	ye schulen be demed, and in what mesure ye meten, it schal be meten ayen to you.
23320	40	7	3	But what seest thou a litil mote in the iye of thi brother, and seest not a beem in thin owne iye?
23321	40	7	4	Or hou seist thou to thi brothir, Brothir, suffre I schal do out a mote fro thin iye, and lo! a beem is in thin owne iye?
23322	40	7	5	Ipocrite, `do thou out first the beem of thin iye, and thanne thou schalt se to do out the mote of the iye of thi brothir.
23323	40	7	6	Nile ye yyue hooli thing to houndis, nethir caste ye youre margaritis bifore swyne, lest perauenture thei defoulen hem with her feet, and the houndis be turned, and al to-tere you.
23324	40	7	7	Axe ye, and it schal be youun to you; seke ye, and ye schulen fynde; knocke ye, and it schal be openyd to you.
23325	40	7	8	For ech that axith, takith; and he that sekith, fyndith; and it schal be openyd to hym, that knockith.
23326	40	7	9	What man of you is, that if his sone axe hym breed, whethir he wole take hym a stoon?
23327	40	7	10	Or if he axe fische, whether he wole take hym an edder?
23328	40	7	11	Therfor if ye, whanne ye ben yuele men, kunnen yyue good yiftis to youre sones, hou myche more youre fadir that is in heuenes schal yyue good thingis to men that axen hym?
23329	40	7	12	Therfor alle thingis, what euere thingis ye wolen that men do to you, do ye to hem, for this is the lawe and the prophetis.
23330	40	7	13	Entre ye bi the streyt yate; for the yate that ledith to perdicioun is large, and the weie is broode, and there ben many that entren bi it.
23331	40	7	14	Hou streit is the yate, and narwy the weye, that ledith to lijf, and ther ben fewe that fynden it.
23332	40	7	15	Be ye war of fals prophetis, that comen to you in clothingis of scheep, but withynneforth thei ben as wolues of raueyn;
23333	40	7	16	of her fruytis ye schulen knowe hem. Whether men gaderen grapis of thornes, or figus of breris?
23334	40	7	17	So euery good tre makith good fruytis; but an yuel tre makith yuel fruytis.
23335	40	7	18	A good tre may not make yuel fruytis, nethir an yuel tre make good fruytis.
23336	40	7	19	Euery tre that makith not good fruyt, schal be kyt doun, and schal be cast in to the fier.
23337	40	7	20	Therfor of her fruytis ye schulen knowe hem.
23338	40	7	21	Not ech man that seith to me, Lord, Lord, schal entre in to the kyngdom of heuenes; but he that doith the wille of my fadir that is in heuenes, he schal entre in to the kyngdoom of heuenes.
23339	40	7	22	Many schulen seie to me in that dai, Lord, Lord, whether we han not prophesied in thi name, and han caste out feendis in thi name, and han doon many vertues in thi name?
23340	40	7	23	And thanne Y schal knouleche to hem, That Y knewe you neuere; departe awei fro me, ye that worchen wickidnesse.
23341	40	7	24	Therfor ech man that herith these my wordis, and doith hem, schal be maad lijk to a wise man, that hath bildid his hous on a stoon.
23342	40	7	25	And reyn felde doun, and flodis camen, and wyndis blewen, and russchiden `in to that hous; and it felde not doun, for it was foundun on a stoon.
23343	40	7	26	And euery man that herith these my wordis, and doith hem not, is lijk to a fool, that hath bildid his hous on grauel.
23344	40	7	27	And reyn cam doun, and floodis camen, and wyndis blewen, and thei hurliden ayen that hous; and it felde doun, and the fallyng doun therof was greet.
23345	40	7	28	And it was doon, whanne Jhesus hadde endid these wordis, the puple wondride on his techyng;
23346	40	7	29	for he tauyte hem, as he that hadde power, and not as the scribis `of hem, and the Farisees.
23347	40	8	1	But whanne Jhesus was come doun fro the hil, mych puple suede hym.
23348	40	8	2	And loo! a leprouse man cam, and worschipide hym, and seide, Lord, if thou wolt, thou maist make me clene.
23349	40	8	3	And Jhesus helde forth the hoond, and touchide hym, and seide, Y wole, be thou maad cleene. And anoon the lepre of him was clensid.
23350	40	8	4	And Jhesus seide to hym, Se, seie thou to no man; but go, shewe thee to the prestis, and offre the yift that Moyses comaundide, in witnessyng to hem.
23351	40	8	5	And whanne he hadde entrid in to Cafarnaum, `the centurien neiyede to him, and preiede him,
23352	40	8	6	and seide, Lord, my childe lijth in the hous sijk on the palesie, and is yuel turmentid.
23353	40	8	7	And Jhesus seide to him, Y schal come, and schal heele him.
23354	40	8	8	And the centurien answeride, and seide to hym, Lord, Y am not worthi, that thou entre vndur my roof; but oonli seie thou bi word, and my childe shal be heelid.
23355	40	8	9	For whi Y am a man ordeyned vndur power, and haue knyytis vndir me; and Y seie to this, Go, and he goith; and to another, Come, and he cometh; and to my seruaunt, Do this, and he doith it.
23356	40	8	10	And Jhesus herde these thingis, and wondride, and seide to men `that sueden him, Treuli Y seie to you, Y foond not so greet feith in Israel.
23357	40	8	11	And Y seie to you, that many schulen come fro the eest and the west, and schulen reste with Abraham and Ysaac and Jacob in the kyngdom of heuenes;
23358	40	8	12	but the sones of the rewme schulen be cast out in to vtmer derknessis; there schal be wepyng, and grynting of teeth.
23359	40	8	13	And Jhesus seide to the centurioun, Go, and as thou hast bileuyd, be it doon to thee. And the child was heelid fro that hour.
23360	40	8	14	And whanne Jhesus was comun in to the hous of Symount Petre, he say his wyues modir liggynge, and shakun with feueris.
23361	40	8	15	And he touchide hir hoond, and the feuer lefte hir; and she roos, and seruede hem.
23362	40	8	16	And whanne it was euen, thei brouyten to hym manye that hadden deuelis, and he castide out spiritis bi word, and heelide alle that weren yuel at ese;
23363	40	8	17	that it were fulfillid, that was seid by Ysaie, the profete, seiynge, He took oure infirmytees, and bar oure siknessis.
23364	40	8	18	And Jhesus say myche puple aboute him, and bade hise disciplis go ouer the watir.
23365	40	8	19	And a scribe neiyede, and seide to hym, Maistir, Y shal sue thee, whidir euer thou schalt go.
23366	40	8	20	And Jhesus seide to hym, Foxis han dennes, and briddis of heuene han nestis, but mannus sone hath not where `he schal reste his heed.
23367	40	8	21	Anothir of his disciplis seide to him, Lord, suffre me to go first, and birie my fader.
23368	40	8	22	But Jhesus seide to hym, Sue thou me, and lete deed men birie her deede men.
23369	40	8	23	And whanne he was goon vp in to a litil schip, his disciplis sueden hym.
23370	40	8	24	And loo! a greet stiring was maad in the see, so that the schip was hilid with wawes; but he slepte.
23371	40	8	25	And hise disciplis camen to hym, and reysiden hym, and seiden, Lord, saue vs; we perischen.
23372	40	8	26	And Jhesus seide to hem, What ben ye of litil feith agaste? Thanne he roos, and comaundide to the wyndis and the see, and a greet pesibilnesse was maad.
23373	40	8	27	And men wondriden, and seiden, What maner man is he this, for the wyndis and the see obeischen to him?
23374	40	8	28	And whanne Jhesus was comun ouer the watir in to the cuntre of men of Gerasa, twey men metten hym, that hadden deuelis, and camen out of graues, ful woode, so that noo man myyte go bi that weie.
23375	40	8	29	And lo! thei crieden, and seiden, What to vs and to thee, Jhesu, the sone of God? `art thou comun hidir bifore the tyme to turmente vs?
23376	40	8	30	And not fer fro hem was a flocke of many swyne lesewynge.
23377	40	8	31	And the deuelis preyeden hym, and seiden, If thou castist out vs fro hennes, sende vs in to the droue of swyne.
23378	40	8	32	And he seide to hem, Go ye. And thei yeden out, and wenten in to the swyne; and loo! in a greet bire al the droue wente heedlyng in to the see, and thei weren deed in the watris.
23379	40	8	33	And the hirdis fledden awey, and camen in to the citee, and telden alle these thingis, and of hem that hadden the feendis.
23380	40	8	34	And lo! al the citee wente out ayens Jhesu; and whanne thei hadden seyn hym, thei preieden, that he wolde passe fro her coostis.
23381	40	9	1	And Jhesus wente vp in to a boot, and passide ouer the watir, and cam in to his citee.
23382	40	9	2	And lo! thei brouyten to hym a man sike in palesie, liggynge in a bed. And Jhesus saw the feith of hem, and seide to the man sike in palesye, Sone, haue thou trist; thi synnes ben foryouun to thee.
23383	40	9	3	And lo! summe of the scribis seiden withynne hem silf, This blasfemeth.
23384	40	9	4	And whanne Jhesus hadde seyn her thouytis, he seide, Wherto thenken ye yuele thingis in youre hertis?
23385	40	9	5	What is liytere to seye, Thi synnes ben foryouun to thee, ethir `to seie, Rise thou, and walke?
23386	40	9	6	But that ye wite that mannus sone hath power to foryyue synnes in erthe, thanne he seide to the sijk man in palesie, Rise vp; take thi bed, and go in to thin hous.
23387	40	9	7	And he roos, and wente in to his hous.
23388	40	9	8	And the puple seynge dredde, and glorifiede God, that yaf suche power to men.
23389	40	9	9	And whanne Jhesus passide fro thennus, he say a man, Matheu bi name, sittynge in a tolbothe. And he seide to hym, Sue thou me.
23390	40	9	10	And he roos, and folewide hym. And it was don, the while he sat `at the mete in the hous, lo! many pupplicans and synful men camen, and saten `at the mete with Jhesu and hise disciplis.
23391	40	9	11	And Farisees sien, and seiden to hise disciplis, Whi etith youre maister with pupplicans and synful men?
23392	40	9	12	And Jhesus herde, and seide, A leche is not nedeful to men that faren wel, but to men that ben yuel at ese.
23393	40	9	13	But go ye, and lerne what it is, Y wole merci, and not sacrifice; for I cam, not to clepe riytful men, but synful men.
23394	40	9	14	Thanne the disciplis of Joon camen to hym, and seiden, Whi we and Farisees fasten ofte, but thi disciplis fasten not?
23395	40	9	15	And Jhesus seide to hem, Whether the sones of the spouse moun morne, as long as the spouse is with hem? But daies schulen come, whanne the spouse schal be takun a wei fro hem, and thanne thei schulen faste.
23396	40	9	16	And no man putteth a clout of buystous clothe in to an elde clothing; for it doith awey the fulnesse of the cloth, and a wers breking is maad.
23397	40	9	17	Nethir men putten newe wyne in to elde botelis, ellis the botels ben to-broke, and distried, and the wyn sched out. But men putten newe wyne in to newe botels, and bothe ben kept.
23398	40	9	18	Whiles that Jhesus spak thes thingis to hem, lo! a prince cam, and worschipide hym, and seide, Lord, my douyter is now deed; but come thou, and putte thin hond on hir, and she schal lyue.
23399	40	9	19	And Jhesus roos, and `hise disciplis, and sueden hym.
23400	40	9	20	And lo! a womman, that hadde the blodi flux twelue yere, neiyede bihynde, and touchide the hem of his cloth.
23401	40	9	21	For sche seide with ynne hir self, Yif Y touche oonli the cloth of hym, Y schal be saaf.
23402	40	9	22	And Jhesus turnede, and say hir, and seide, Douytir, haue thou trist; thi feith hath maad thee saaf. And the womman was hool fro that our.
23403	40	9	23	And whanne Jhesus cam in to the hous of the prince, and say mynstrallis, and the puple makynge noise,
23404	40	9	24	he seide, Go ye a wei, for the damysel is not deed, but slepith. And thei scornyden hym.
23405	40	9	25	And whanne the folc was put out, he wente in, and helde hir hond; and the damysel roos.
23406	40	9	26	And this fame wente out in to al that loond.
23407	40	9	27	And whanne Jhesus passide fro thennus, twei blynde men criynge sueden hym, and seiden, Thou sone of Dauid, haue merci on vs.
23408	40	9	28	And whanne he cam in to the hous, the blynde men camen to hym; and Jhesus seide to hem, What wolen ye, that I do to you? And thei seiden, Lord, that oure iyen be opened. And Jhesus seide, Bileuen ye, that Y mai do this thing to you? Thei seien to him, Yhe, Lord.
23409	40	9	29	Thanne he touchide her iyen, and seide, Aftir youre feith be it doon to you.
23410	40	9	30	And the iyen of hem were opened. And Jhesus thretenede hem, and seide, Se ye, that no man wite.
23411	40	9	31	But thei yeden out, and diffameden hym thorou al that lond.
23412	40	9	32	And whanne thei weren gon out, loo! thei brouyten to hym a doumbe man, hauynge a deuel.
23413	40	9	33	And whanne the deuel was cast out, the doumb man spak. And the puple wondride, and seide, It hath not be say thus in Israel.
23414	40	9	34	But the Farisees seiden, In the prince of deuelis he castith out deuelis.
23415	40	9	35	And Jhesus wente `aboute alle the `citees and castels, techinge in the synagogis of hem, and prechynge the gospel of the kyngdom, and helynge euery langour and euery sijknesse.
23416	40	9	36	And he siy the puple, and hadde reuthe on hem; for thei weren trauelid, and liggynge as scheep not hauynge a scheepherde.
23417	40	9	37	Thanne he seide to hise disciplis, Sotheli there is myche ripe corn, but fewe werk men.
23418	40	9	38	Therfor preye ye the lord of the ripe corn, that he sende werke men in to his ripe corn.
23419	40	10	1	And whanne his twelue disciplis weren clepid togidere, he yaf to hem powere of vnclene spiritis, to caste hem out of men, and to heele eueri langour, and sijknesse.
23420	40	10	2	And these ben the names of the twelue apostlis; the firste, Symount, that is clepid Petre, and Andrew, his brothir; James of Zebede, and Joon, his brothir; Filip, and Bartholomeu;
23421	40	10	3	Thomas, and Matheu, pupplican; and James Alfey, and Tadee;
23422	40	10	4	Symount Chananee, and Judas Scarioth, that bitrayede Crist.
23423	40	10	5	Jhesus sente these twelue, and comaundide hem, and seide, Go ye not `in to the weie of hethene men, and entre ye not in to the citees of Samaritans;
23424	40	10	6	but rather go ye to the scheep of the hous of Israel, that han perischid.
23425	40	10	7	And go ye, and preche ye, and seie, that the kyngdam of heuenes shal neiye;
23426	40	10	8	heele ye sike men, reise ye deede men, clense ye mesels, caste ye out deuelis; freeli ye han takun, freli yyue ye.
23427	40	10	9	Nyle ye welde gold, nether siluer, ne money in youre girdlis, not a scrippe in the weie,
23428	40	10	10	nether twei cootis, nethir shoon, nether a yerde; for a werkman is worthi his mete.
23429	40	10	11	In to what euere citee or castel ye schulen entre, axe ye who therynne is worthi, and there dwelle ye, til ye go out.
23430	40	10	12	And whanne ye goon in to an hous, `grete ye it, and seyn, Pees to this hous.
23431	40	10	13	And if thilk hous be worthi, youre pees schal come on it; but if that hous be not worthi, youre pees schal turne ayen to you.
23432	40	10	14	And who euere resseyueth not you, nethir herith youre wordis, go ye fro that hous or citee, and sprenge of the dust of youre feet.
23433	40	10	15	Treuly Y seie to you, it shal be more suffrable to the loond of men of Sodom and of Gommor in the dai of iugement, than to thilke citee.
23434	40	10	16	Lo! Y sende you as scheep in the myddil of wolues; therfor be ye sliy as serpentis, and symple as dowues.
23435	40	10	17	But be ye war of men, for thei schulen take you in counseilis, and thei schulen bete you in her synagogis;
23436	40	10	18	and to meyris, or presidentis, and to kyngis, ye schulen be lad for me, in witnessyng to hem, and to the hethen men.
23437	40	10	19	But whanne thei take you, nyle ye thenke, hou or what thing ye schulen speke, for it shal be youun `to you in that our, what ye schulen speke;
23438	40	10	20	for it ben not ye that speken, but the spirit of youre fadir, that spekith in you.
23439	40	10	21	`And the brother shal take the brother in to deeth, and the fader the sone, and sones schulen rise ayens fadir and modir, and schulen turmente hem bi deeth.
23440	40	10	22	And ye schulen be in hate to alle men for my name; but he that shall dwelle stille in to the ende, shal be saaf.
23441	40	10	23	And whanne thei pursuen you in this citee, fle ye in to anothir. Treuli Y seie to you, ye schulen not ende the citees of Israel, to for that mannus sone come.
23442	40	10	24	The disciple is not aboue the maistir, ne the seruaunt aboue hys lord;
23443	40	10	25	it is ynowy to the disciple, that he be as his maistir, and to the seruaunt as his lord. If thei han clepid the hosebonde man Belsabub, hou myche more his houshold meyne?
23444	40	10	26	Therfor drede ye not hem; for no thing is hid, that schal not be shewid; and no thing is priuey, that schal not be wist.
23445	40	10	27	That thing that Y seie to you in derknessis, seie ye in the liyt; and preche ye on housis, that thing that ye heeren in the ere.
23446	40	10	28	And nyle ye drede hem that sleen the bodi; for thei moun not sle the soule; but rather drede ye hym, that mai lese bothe soule and bodi in to helle.
23447	40	10	29	Whether twei sparewis ben not seeld for an halpeny? and oon of hem shal not falle on the erthe with outen youre fadir.
23448	40	10	30	`And alle the heeris of youre heed ben noumbrid. Therfor nyle ye drede; ye ben betere than many sparewis.
23449	40	10	31	Therfor euery man that schal knouleche me bifore men, Y schal knouleche hym bifor my fadir that is in heuenes.
23450	40	10	33	But he that shal denye me bifor men, and I shal denye him bifor my fadir that is in heuenes.
23451	40	10	34	Nile ye deme, that Y cam to sende pees in to erthe; Y cam not to sende pees, but swerd.
23452	40	10	35	For Y cam to departe a man ayens his fadir, and the douytir ayens hir modir, and the sones wijf ayens the housbondis modir;
23453	40	10	36	and the enemyes of a man ben `thei, that ben homeli with him.
23454	40	10	37	He that loueth fadir or modir more than me, is not worthi to me. And he that loueth sone or douyter ouer me, is not worthi to me.
23455	40	10	38	And he that takith not his croos, and sueth me, is not worthi to me.
23456	40	10	39	He that fyndith his lijf, shal lose it; and he that lesith his lijf for me, shal fynde it.
23457	40	10	40	He that resseyueth you, resseyueth me; and he that resseyueth me, resseyueth hym that sente me.
23458	40	10	41	He that resseyueth a prophete in the name of a prophete, shal take the mede of a prophete. And he that resseyueth a iust man in the name of a iust man, schal take the mede of a iust man.
23459	40	10	42	And who euer yyueth drynke to oon of these leeste a cuppe of coolde watir oonli in the name of a disciple, treuli Y seie to you, he shal not leese his mede.
23460	40	11	1	And it was doon, whanne Jhesus hadde endid, he comaundide to hise twelue disciplis, and passide fro thennus to teche and preche in the citees of hem.
23461	40	11	2	But whanne Joon in boondis hadde herd the werkis of Crist, he sente tweyne of hise disciplis,
23462	40	11	3	and seide to him, `Art thou he that schal come, or we abiden another?
23463	40	11	4	And Jhesus answeride, and seide `to hem, Go ye, and telle ayen to Joon tho thingis that ye han herd and seyn.
23464	40	11	5	Blynde men seen, crokid men goon, meselis ben maad clene, deefe men heren, deed men rysen ayen, pore men ben takun to `prechyng of the gospel.
23465	40	11	6	And he is blessid, that shal not be sclaundrid in me.
23466	40	11	7	And whanne thei weren goon awei, Jhesus bigan to seie of Joon to the puple, What thing wenten ye out in to desert to se? a reed wawed with the wynd?
23467	40	11	8	Or what thing wenten ye out to see? a man clothid with softe clothis? Lo! thei that ben clothid with softe clothis ben in the housis of kyngis.
23468	40	11	9	But what thing wenten ye out to se? a prophete? Yhe, Y seie to you, and more than a prophete.
23469	40	11	10	For this is he, of whom it is writun, Lo! Y sende myn aungel bifor thi face, that shal make redi thi weye bifor thee.
23470	40	11	11	Treuli Y seie to you, ther roos noon more than Joon Baptist among the children of wymmen; but he that is lesse in the kyngdom of heuenes, is more than he.
23471	40	11	12	And fro the daies of Joon Baptist til now the kyngdom of heuenes suffrith violence, and violent men rauyschen it.
23472	40	11	13	For alle prophetis and the lawe `til to Joon prophecieden; and if ye wolen resseyue,
23473	40	11	14	he is Elie that is to come.
23474	40	11	15	He that hath eris of heryng, here he.
23475	40	11	16	But to whom schal Y gesse this generacioun lijk? It is lijk to children sittynge in chepyng, that crien to her peeris,
23476	40	11	17	and seien, We han songun to you, and ye han not daunsid; we han morned to you, and ye han not weilid.
23477	40	11	18	For Joon cam nether etynge ne drynkynge, and thei seien, He hath a deuel.
23478	40	11	19	The sone of man cam etynge and drynkynge, and thei seien, Lo! a man a glotoun, and a drinkere of wijne, and a freend of pupplicans and of synful men. And wisdom is iustified of her sones.
23479	40	11	20	Thanne Jhesus bigan to seye repreef to citees, in whiche ful manye vertues of him weren doon, for thei diden not penaunce.
23480	40	11	21	Wo to thee! Corosaym, woo to thee! Bethsaida; for if the vertues that ben doon in you hadden be doon in Tyre and Sidon, sumtyme thei hadden don penaunce in heyre and aische.
23481	40	11	22	Netheles Y seie to you, it schal be lesse peyne to Tire and Sidon in the dai of doom, than to you.
23482	40	11	23	And thou, Cafarnaum, whethir thou schalt be arerid vp in to heuene? Thou shalt go doun in to helle. For if the vertues that ben don in thee, hadden be don in Sodom, perauenture thei schulden haue dwellid `in to this dai.
23483	40	11	24	Netheles Y seie to you, that to the lond of Sodom it schal be `lesse peyne in the dai of doom, than to thee.
23484	40	11	25	In thilke tyme Jhesus answeride, and seide, Y knowleche to thee, fadir, lord of heuene and of erthe, for thou hast hid these thingis fro wijse men, and redi, and hast schewid hem to litle children;
23485	40	11	26	so, fadir, for so it was plesynge tofore thee.
23486	40	11	27	Alle thingis ben youune to me of my fadir; and no man knewe the sone, but the fadir, nethir ony man knewe the fadir, but the sone, and to whom the sone wolde schewe.
23487	40	11	28	Alle ye that traueilen, and ben chargid, come to me, and Y schal fulfille you.
23488	40	11	29	Take ye my yok on you, and lerne ye of me, for Y am mylde and meke in herte; and ye schulen fynde reste to youre soulis.
23489	40	11	30	`For my yok is softe, and my charge liyt.
23490	40	12	1	In that tyme Jhesus wente bi cornes in the sabot day; and hise disciplis hungriden, and bigunnen to plucke the eris of corn, and to ete.
23491	40	12	2	And Fariseis, seynge, seiden to hym, Lo! thi disciplis don that thing that is not leueful to hem to do in sabatis.
23492	40	12	3	And he seide to hem, Whether ye han not red, what Dauid dide, whanne he hungride, and thei that weren with hym?
23493	40	12	4	hou he entride in to the hous of God, and eet looues of proposicioun, whiche looues it was not leueful to hym to ete, nether to hem that weren with hym, but to prestis aloone?
23494	40	12	5	Or whether ye han not red in the lawe, that in sabotis prestis in the temple defoulen the sabotis, and thei ben with oute blame?
23495	40	12	6	And Y seie to you, that here is a gretter than the temple.
23496	40	12	7	And if ye wisten, what it is, Y wole merci, and not sacrifice, ye schulden neuer haue condempned innocentis.
23497	40	12	8	For mannus Sone is lord, yhe, of the sabat.
23498	40	12	9	And whanne he passide fro thennus, he cam in to the synagoge of hem.
23499	40	12	10	And lo! a man that hadde a drye hoond. And thei axiden hym, and seiden, Whether it be leueful to hele in the sabot? that thei schulden acuse hym.
23500	40	12	11	And he seide to hem, What man of you schal be, that hath o scheep, and if it falle in to a diche in the sabotis, whether he shal not holde, and lifte it vp?
23501	40	12	12	How myche more is a man better than a scheep? Therfor it is leueful to do good in the sabatis.
23502	40	12	13	Thanne he seide to the man, Stretche forth thin hoond. And he strauyte forth; and it was restorid to heelthe as the tothir.
23503	40	12	14	And the Farisees wenten out, and maden a counsel ayens hym, hou thei schulden distrie hym.
23504	40	12	15	And Jhesus knewe it, and wente awei fro thennus; and many sueden hym, and he helide hem alle.
23505	40	12	16	And he comaundide to hem, that thei schulden not make hym knowun;
23506	40	12	17	that that thing were fulfillid, that was seid by Isaie, the prophete, seiynge, Lo!
23507	40	12	18	my child, whom Y haue chosun, my derling, in whom it hath wel plesid to my soule; Y shal put my spirit on him, and he shal telle dom to hethen men.
23508	40	12	19	He shal not stryue, ne crye, nethir ony man shal here his voice in stretis.
23509	40	12	20	A brisid rehed he shal not breke, and he schal not quenche smokynge flax, til he caste out doom to victorie;
23510	40	12	21	and hethene men schulen hope in his name.
23511	40	12	22	Thanne a man blynde and doumbe, that hadde a feend, was brouyt to hym; and he helide hym, so that he spak, and say.
23512	40	12	23	And al the puple wondride, and seide, Whether this be the sone of Dauid?
23513	40	12	24	But the Farisees herden, and seiden, He this casteth not out feendis, but in Belsabub, prince of feendis.
23514	40	12	25	And Jhesus, witynge her thouytis, seide to hem, Eche kingdom departid ayens it silf, schal be desolatid, and eche cite, or hous, departid ayens it self, schal not stonde.
23515	40	12	26	And if Satanas castith out Satanas, he is departid ayens him silf; therfor hou schal his kingdom stonde?
23516	40	12	27	And if Y in Belsabub caste out deuelis, in `whom youre sones casten out? Therfor thei schulen be youre domes men.
23517	40	12	28	But if Y in the Spirit of God caste out feendis, thanne the kyngdom of God is comen in to you.
23518	40	12	29	Ethir hou may ony man entre in to the hous of a stronge man, and take awey hise vesselis, but `he first bynde the stronge man, and thanne he schal spuyle his hous?
23519	40	12	30	He that is not with me, is ayens me; and he that gaderith not togidere with me, scaterith abrood.
23520	40	12	31	Therfor I seie to you, al synne and blasfemye shal be foryouun to men, but `the spirit of blasfemye shal not be foryouun.
23521	40	12	32	And who euere seith a word ayens mannus sone, it shal be foryouun to him; but who that seieth a word ayens the Hooli Goost, it shal not be foryouun to hym, nether in this world, ne in `the tothir.
23522	40	12	33	Ethir make ye the tree good, and his fruyt good; ether make ye the tree yuel and his fruyt yuel; for a tree is knowun of the fruyt.
23523	40	12	34	Ye generacioun of eddris, hou moun ye speke goode thingis, whanne ye ben yuele? For the mouth spekith of plente of the herte.
23524	40	12	35	A good man bryngith forth good thingis of good tresoure, and an yuel man bringith forth yuel thingis of yuel tresoure.
23525	40	12	36	And Y seie to you, that of euery idel word, that men speken, thei schulen yelde resoun therof in the dai of doom;
23526	40	12	37	for of thi wordis thou schalt be iustified, and of thi wordis thou shalt be dampned.
23527	40	12	38	Thanne summe of the scribis and Farisees answeriden to hym, and seiden, Mayster, we wolen se a tokne of thee.
23528	40	12	39	Which answeride, and seide to hem, An yuel kynrede and a spouse brekere sekith a tokene, and a tokene shal not be youun to it, but the tokene of Jonas, the prophete.
23529	40	12	40	For as Jonas was in the wombe of a whal thre daies and thre nyytis, so mannus sone shal be in the herte of the erthe thre daies and thre nyytis.
23530	40	12	41	Men of Nynyue schulen rise in doom with this generacioun, and schulen condempne it; for thei diden penaunce in the prechyng of Jonas, and lo! here a gretter than Jonas.
23531	40	12	42	The queene of the south shal rise in doom with this generacioun, and schal condempne it; for she cam fro the eendis of the erthe to here the wisdom of Salomon, and lo! here a gretter than Salomon.
23532	40	12	43	Whanne an vnclene spirit goith out fro a man, he goith bi drie places, `and sekith rest, and fyndith not.
23533	40	12	44	Thanne he seith, Y shal turne ayen in to myn hous, fro whannys Y wente out. And he cometh, and fyndith it voide, and clensid with besyms, and maad faire.
23534	40	12	45	Thanne he goith, and takith with him seuene othere spiritis worse than hym silf; and thei entren, and dwellen there. And the laste thingis of that man ben maad worse than the formere. So it shal be to this worste generacioun.
23535	40	12	46	Yit whil he spak to the puple, lo! his modir and his bretheren stoden withouteforth, sekynge to speke to hym.
23536	40	12	47	And a man seide to hym, Lo! thi modir and thi britheren stonden withouteforth, sekynge thee.
23537	40	12	48	He answeride to the man, that spak to hym, and seide, Who is my modir? and who ben my britheren?
23538	40	12	49	And he helde forth his hoond in to hise disciplis, and seide, Lo! my modir and my bretheren;
23539	40	12	50	for who euer doith the wille of my fadir that is in heuenes, he is my brothir, and sistir, and modir.
23540	40	13	1	In that dai Jhesus yede out of the hous, and sat bisidis the see.
23541	40	13	2	And myche puple was gaderid to hym, so that he wente up in to a boot, and sat; and al the puple stood on the brenke.
23542	40	13	3	And he spac to hem many thingis in parablis, and seide, Lo! he that sowith, yede out to sowe his seed.
23543	40	13	4	And while he sowith, summe seedis felden bisidis the weie, and briddis of the eir camen, and eeten hem.
23544	40	13	5	But othere seedis felden in to stony places, where thei hadden not myche erthe; and anoon thei sprongen vp, for thei hadden not depnesse of erthe.
23545	40	13	6	But whanne the sonne was risun, thei swaliden, and for thei hadden not roote, thei drieden vp.
23546	40	13	7	And other seedis felden among thornes; and thornes woxen vp, and strangeleden hem.
23547	40	13	8	But othere seedis felden in to good lond, and yauen fruyt; summe an hundrid foold, an othir sixti foold, an othir thritti foold.
23548	40	13	9	He that hath eris of heryng, here he.
23549	40	13	10	And the disciplis camen nyy, and seiden to him, Whi spekist thou in parablis to hem?
23550	40	13	11	And he answeride, and seide to hem, `For to you it is youun to knowe the priuytees of the kyngdom of heuenes; but it is not youun to hem.
23551	40	13	12	For it shal be youun to hym that hath, and he shal haue plente; but if a man hath not, also that thing that he hath shal be takun awei fro hym.
23552	40	13	13	Therfor Y speke to hem in parablis, for thei seynge seen not, and thei herynge heren not, nether vndurstonden;
23553	40	13	14	that the prophesie of Ysaie `seiynge be fulfillid `in hem, With heryng ye schulen here, and ye shulen not vndurstonde; and ye seynge schulen se, and ye shulen not se;
23554	40	13	15	for the herte of this puple is greetli fattid, and thei herden heuyli with eeris, and thei han closed her iyen, lest sumtime thei seen with iyen, and with eeris heeren, and vndirstonden in herte, and thei be conuertid, and Y heele hem.
23555	40	13	16	But youre iyen that seen ben blesside, and youre eeris that heren.
23556	40	13	17	Forsothe Y seie to you, that manye profetis and iust men coueitiden to se tho thingis that ye seen, and thei sayn not, and to heere tho thingis that ye heren, and thei herden not.
23557	40	13	18	Therfor here ye the parable of the sowere.
23558	40	13	19	Ech that herith the word of the rewme, and vndirstondith not, the yuel spirit cometh, and rauyschith that that is sowun in his herte; this it is, that is sowun bisidis the weie.
23559	40	13	20	But this that is sowun on the stony loond, this it is, that herith the word of God, and anoon with ioye takith it.
23560	40	13	21	And he hath not roote in hym silf, but is temporal. For whanne tribulacioun and persecucioun is maad for the word, anoon he is sclaundrid.
23561	40	13	22	But he that is sowun in thornes, is this that heerith the word, and the bisynesse of this world, and the fallace of ritchessis strangulith the word, and it is maad with outen fruyt.
23562	40	13	23	But he that is sowun in to good loond, is this that herith the word, and vnderstondeth, and bryngith forth fruyt. And summe makith an hundrid fold, treuli anothir sixti fold, and another thritti fold.
23563	40	13	24	Anothir parable Jhesus puttide forth to hem, and seide, The kyngdom of heuenes is maad lijk to a man, that sewe good seed in his feld.
23564	40	13	25	And whanne men slepten, his enemy cam, and sewe aboue taris in the myddil of whete, and wente awei.
23565	40	13	26	But whanne the erbe was growed, and made fruyt, thanne the taris apperiden.
23566	40	13	27	And the seruauntis of the hosebonde man camen, and seiden to hym, Lord, whether hast thou not sowun good seed in thi feeld? where of thanne hath it taris?
23567	40	13	28	And he seide to hem, An enemy hath do this thing. And the seruauntis seiden to him, `Wolt thou that we goon, and gaderen hem?
23568	40	13	29	And he seide, Nay, lest perauenture ye in gaderynge taris drawen vp with hem the whete bi the roote.
23569	40	13	30	Suffre ye hem bothe to wexe in to repyng tyme; and in the tyme of ripe corne Y shal seie to the reperis, First gadere ye to gidere the taris, and bynde hem to gidere in knytchis to be brent, but gadere ye whete in to my berne.
23570	40	13	31	Another parable Jhesus puttide forth to hem, and seide, The kyngdom of heuenes is lijk to a corn of seneuey, which a man took, and sewe in his feeld.
23571	40	13	32	Which is the leeste of alle seedis, but whanne it hath woxen, it is the moste of alle wortis, and is maad a tre; so that briddis of the eir comen, and dwellen in the bowis therof.
23572	40	13	33	Another parable Jhesus spac to hem, The kyngdom of heuenes is lijk to sour douy, which a womman took, and hidde in thre mesuris of mele, til it were alle sowrid.
23573	40	13	34	Jhesus spac alle thes thingis in parablis to the puple, and he spac not to hem with out parablis, that it schulde be fulfillid,
23574	40	13	35	that is seid bi the prophete, seiynge, Y shal opene my mouth in parablis; Y shal telle out hid thingis fro the makyng of the world.
23575	40	13	36	Thanne he lefte the puple, and cam in to an hous; and hise disciplis camen to him, and seiden, Expowne to vs the parable of taris of the feeld.
23576	40	13	37	Which answeride, and seide, He that sowith good seed is mannus sone;
23577	40	13	38	the feeld is the world; but the good seed, these ben sones of the kyngdom, but taris, these ben yuele children;
23578	40	13	39	the enemye that sowith hem is the feend; and the ripe corn is the endyng of the world, the reperis ben aungels.
23579	40	13	40	Therfor as taris ben gaderid togidere, and ben brent in fier, so it shal be in the endyng of the world.
23580	40	13	41	Mannus sone shal sende hise aungels, and thei schulen gadere fro his rewme alle sclaundris, and hem that doon wickidnesse;
23581	40	13	42	and thei schulen sende hem in to the chymney of fier, there shal be weping and betyng to gidere of teeth.
23582	40	13	43	Thanne iuste men schulen schyne as the sunne, in the rewme of her fadir. He that hath eeris of heryng, here he.
23583	40	13	44	The kyngdom of heuenes is lijk to tresour hid in a feld, which a man that fyndith, hidith; and for ioye of it he goith, and sillith alle thingis that he hath, and bieth thilk feeld.
23584	40	13	45	Eftsoone the kyngdom of heuenes is lijk to a marchaunt, that sechith good margaritis;
23585	40	13	46	but whanne he hath foundun o precious margarite, he wente, and selde alle thingis that he hadde, and bouyte it.
23586	40	13	47	Eft the kyngdom of heuenes is lijk to a nette cast into the see, and that gaderith to gidere of al kynde of fisschis;
23587	40	13	48	which whanne it was ful, thei drowen vp, and seten bi the brenke, and chesen the goode in to her vessels, but the yuel thei kesten out.
23588	40	13	49	So it schal be in the endyng of the world. Aungels schulen go out, and schulen departe yuel men fro the myddil of iuste men.
23589	40	13	50	And thei shulen sende hem in to the chymnei of fier; ther shal be weping and gryntyng of teeth.
23590	40	13	51	Han ye vndirstonde alle these thingis? Thei seien to hym, Yhe.
23591	40	13	52	He seith to hem, Therfor euery wise man of lawe in the kyngdom of heuenes, is lijk to an hosebonde man, that bryngith forth of his tresoure newe thingis and elde.
23592	40	13	53	And it was doon, whanne Jhesus hadde endid these parablis, he passide fro thennus.
23593	40	13	54	And he cam in to his cuntrei, and tauyte hem in her synagogis, so that thei wondriden, and seiden, Fro whennus this wisdam and vertues camen to this?
23594	40	13	55	Whether `is not this the sone of a carpentere? Whether his modir be not seid Marie? and hise britheren, James, and Joseph, and Symount, and Judas? and hise sistris,
23595	40	13	56	whether thei alle ben not among us? Fro whennus thanne `alle thes thingis camen to this?
23596	40	13	57	And so thei weren sclaundrid in hym. But Jhesus seide to hem, A profete is not with oute worschip, but in his owen cuntre, and in his owen hous.
23597	40	13	58	And he dide not there manye vertues, for the vnbileue of hem.
23598	40	14	1	In that tyme Eroude tetrarke, prynce of the fourthe part, herde the fame of Jhesu;
23599	40	14	2	and seide to hise children, This is Joon Baptist, he is rysun fro deeth, and therfor vertues worchen in hym.
23600	40	14	3	For Heroude hadde holde Joon, and bounde hym, and puttide hym `in to prisoun for Herodias, the wijf of his brothir.
23601	40	14	4	For Joon seide to him, It is not leueful to thee to haue hir.
23602	40	14	5	And he willynge to sle hym, dredde the puple; for thei hadden hym as a prophete.
23603	40	14	6	But in the dai of Heroudis birthe, the douytir of Herodias daunside in the myddil, and pleside Heroude.
23604	40	14	7	Wherfor with an ooth he bihiyte to yyue to hir, what euere thing she hadde axid of hym.
23605	40	14	8	And she bifor warned of hir modir, seide, Yif thou to me here the heed of Joon Baptist in a disch.
23606	40	14	9	And the kyng was sorewful, but for the ooth, and for hem that saten to gidere at the mete, he comaundide to be youun.
23607	40	14	10	And he sente, and bihedide Joon in the prisoun.
23608	40	14	11	And his heed was brouyt in a dische, and it was youun to the damysel, and she bar it to hir modir.
23609	40	14	12	And hise disciplis camen, and token his bodi, and birieden it; and thei camen, and tolden to Jhesu.
23610	40	14	13	And whanne Jhesus hadde herd this thing, he wente fro thennus in a boot, in to desert place bisides. And whanne the puple hadde herd, thei folewiden hym on her feet fro citees.
23611	40	14	14	And Jhesus yede out, and sai a greet puple, and hadde reuthe on hem, and heelide the sike men of hem.
23612	40	14	15	But whanne the euentid was com, hise disciplis camen to him, and seiden, The place is desert, and the tyme is now passid; lat the puple go in to townes, to bye hem mete.
23613	40	14	16	Jhesus seide to hem, Thei han not nede to go; yyue ye hem sumwhat to ete.
23614	40	14	17	Thei answeriden, We han not heere, but fyue looues and twei fischis.
23615	40	14	18	And he seide to hem, Brynge ye hem hidur to me.
23616	40	14	19	And whanne he hadde comaundid the puple to sitte to meete on the heye, he took fyue looues and twei fischis, and he bihelde in to heuene, and blesside, and brak, and yaf to hise disciplis; and the disciplis yauen to the puple.
23617	40	14	20	And alle eten, and weren fulfillid. And thei tooken the relifs of brokun gobetis, twelue cofynes ful.
23618	40	14	21	And the noumbre of men that eten was fyue thousynde of men, outakun wymmen and lytle children.
23619	40	14	22	And anoon Jhesus compellide the disciplis to go vp in to a boot, and go bifor hym ouer the see, while he lefte the puple.
23620	40	14	23	And whanne the puple was left, he stiede aloone in to an hil for to preie. But whanne the euenyng was come, he was there aloone.
23621	40	14	24	And the boot in the myddel of the see was schoggid with wawis, for the wynd was contrarie to hem.
23622	40	14	25	But in the fourthe wakyng of the niyt, he cam to hem walkynge aboue the see.
23623	40	14	26	And thei, seynge hym walking on the see, weren disturblid, and seiden, That it is a fantum; and for drede thei crieden.
23624	40	14	27	And anoon Jhesus spac to hem, and seide, Haue ye trust, Y am; nyle ye drede.
23625	40	14	28	And Petre answeride, and seide, Lord, if thou art, comaunde me to come to thee on the watris.
23626	40	14	29	And he seide, Come thou. And Petre yede doun fro the boot, and walkide on the watris to come to Jhesu.
23627	40	14	30	But he siy the wynd strong, and was aferde; and whanne he bigan to drenche, he criede, and seide, Lord, make me saaf.
23628	40	14	31	And anoon Jhesus helde forth his hoond, and took Petre, and seide to hym, Thou of litil feith, whi hast thou doutid?
23629	40	14	32	And whanne he hadde stied in to the boot, the wynd ceessid.
23630	40	14	33	And thei, that weren in the boot, camen, and worschipiden hym, and seiden, Verili, thou art Goddis sone.
23631	40	14	34	And whanne thei hadden passid ouer the see, thei camen in to the loond of Genesar.
23632	40	14	35	And whanne men of that place hadden knowe hym, thei senten in to al that cuntre; and thei brouyten to hym alle that hadden siknesse.
23633	40	14	36	And thei preieden hym, that thei schulden touche the hemme of his clothing; and who euere touchiden weren maad saaf.
23634	40	15	1	Thanne the scribis and the Farisees camen to hym fro Jerusalem, and seiden,
23635	40	15	2	Whi breken thi disciplis the tradiciouns of eldere men? for thei waisschen not her hondis, whanne thei eten breed.
23636	40	15	3	He answeride, and seide to hem, Whi breken ye the maundement of God for youre tradicioun?
23637	40	15	4	For God seide, Honoure thi fadir and thi modir, and he that cursith fadir or modir, die bi deeth.
23638	40	15	5	But ye seien, Who euer seith to fadir or modir, What euere yifte is of me, it schal profite to thee;
23639	40	15	6	and he hath not worschipid his fadir or his modir; and ye han maad the maundement of God voide for youre tradicioun.
23640	40	15	7	Ypocritis, Isaie, the prophete, prophesiede wel of you,
23641	40	15	8	and seide, This puple honourith me with lippis, but her herte is fer fro me;
23642	40	15	9	and thei worschipen me `with outen cause, techynge the doctrines and maundementis of men.
23643	40	15	10	And whanne the puple weren clepid to gidere to hym, he seide to hem, Here ye, and `vndurstonde ye.
23644	40	15	11	That thing that entrith in to the mouth, defoulith not a man; but that thing that cometh out of the mouth, defoulith a man.
23645	40	15	12	Thanne hise disciplis camen, and seiden to hym, Thou knowist, that, if this word be herd, the Farisees ben sclaundrid?
23646	40	15	13	And he answeride, and seide, Eueri plauntyng, that my fadir of heuene hath not plauntid, shal be drawun vp by the roote.
23647	40	15	14	Suffre ye hem; thei ben blynde, and leederis of blynde men. And if a blynd man lede a blynd man, bothe fallen doun in to the diche.
23648	40	15	15	Petre answeride, and seide to hym, Expowne to vs this parable.
23649	40	15	16	And he seide, Yit `ye ben also with oute vndurstondyng?
23650	40	15	17	Vndurstonden ye not, that al thing that entrith in to the mouth, goith in to the wombe, and is sent out in to the goyng awei?
23651	40	15	18	But tho thingis that comen forth fro the mouth, goon out of the herte, and tho thingis defoulen a man.
23652	40	15	19	For of the herte goon out yuele thouytis, mansleyngis, auowtries, fornycaciouns, theftis, fals witnessyngis, blasfemyes.
23653	40	15	20	Thes thingis it ben that defoulen a man; but to ete with hondis not waischun, defoulith not a man.
23654	40	15	21	And Jhesus yede out fro thennus, and wente in to the coostis of Tire and Sidon.
23655	40	15	22	And lo! a womman of Canane yede out of tho coostis, and criede, and seide to him, Lord, the sone of Dauid, haue merci on me; my douyter is yuel traueilid of a feend.
23656	40	15	23	And he answeride not to hir a word. And hise disciplis camen, and preieden hym, and seiden, Leue thou hir, for she crieth aftir vs.
23657	40	15	24	He answeride, and seide, Y am not sent, but to the scheep of the hous of Israel that perischiden.
23658	40	15	25	And she cam, and worschipide hym, and seide, Lord, helpe me.
23659	40	15	26	Which answeride, and seide, It is not good to take the breed of children, and caste to houndis.
23660	40	15	27	And she seide, Yhis, Lord; for whelpis eten of the crummes, that fallen doun fro the bord of her lordis.
23661	40	15	28	Thanne Jhesus answeride, and seide to hir, A! womman, thi feith is greet; be it doon to thee, as thou wolt. And hir douytir was helid fro that hour.
23662	40	15	29	And whanne Jhesus hadde passed fro thennus, he cam bisidis the see of Galilee. And he yede vp in to an hil, and sat there.
23663	40	15	30	And myche puple cam to hym, and hadden with hem doumbe men and crokid, feble and blynde, and many other; and thei castiden doun hem at hise feet. And he helide hem,
23664	40	15	31	so that the puple wondriden seynge doumbe men spekynge, and crokid goynge, blynde men seynge; and thei magnyfieden God of Israel.
23665	40	15	32	And Jhesus, whanne hise disciplis weren clepid to gidere, seide to hem, Y haue reuthe of the puple, for thei han abiden now thre daies with me, and han no thing to ete; and Y wole not leeue hem fastynge, lest thei failen in the weie.
23666	40	15	33	And the disciplis seien to him, Wherof thanne so many looues among vs in desert, to fulfille so greet a puple?
23667	40	15	34	And Jhesus seide to hem, Hou many looues han ye? And thei seiden, Seuene, and a fewe smale fisshis.
23668	40	15	35	And he comaundide to the puple, to sitte to mete on the erthe.
23669	40	15	36	And he took seuene looues and fyue fischis, and dide thankyngis, and brak, and yaf to hise disciplis; and the disciplis yauen to the puple.
23670	40	15	37	And alle eten, and weren fulfillid, and thei token that that was left of relifes, seuene lepis fulle.
23671	40	15	38	And thei that eten weren foure thousynde of men, with outen litle children and wymmen.
23672	40	15	39	And whanne he hadde left the puple, he wente vp in to a boot, and cam in to the coostis of Magedan.
23673	40	16	1	And the Farisees and the Saducees camen to hym temptynge, and preieden hym to schewe hem a tokene fro heuene.
23674	40	16	2	And he answeride, and seide to hem, Whanne the euentid is comun, ye seien, It schal be clere, for heuene is rodi;
23675	40	16	3	and the morewtid, To dai tempest, for heuene schyneth heueli.
23676	40	16	4	Thanne ye kunne deme the face of heuene, but ye moun not wite the tokenes of tymes. An yuel generacioun and auoutresse sekith a tokene; and a tokene schal not be youun to it, but the tokene of Jonas, the profete. And whanne he hadde left hem, he wente forth.
23677	40	16	5	And whanne his disciplis camen ouer the see, thei foryaten to take looues.
23678	40	16	6	And he seide to hem, Biholde ye, and be war of the soure dowy of Farisees and Saducees.
23679	40	16	7	And thei thouyten among hem, and seiden, For we han not take looues.
23680	40	16	8	But Jhesus witynge seide to hem, What thenken ye among you of litel feith, for ye han not looues?
23681	40	16	9	Yit `vndurstonden not ye, nether han mynde of fyue looues in to fyue thousynde of men, and hou many cofyns ye token?
23682	40	16	10	nether of seuene looues in to foure thousynde of men, and hou many lepis ye token?
23683	40	16	11	Whi vndurstonden ye not, for Y seide not to you of breed, Be ye war of the sourdowy of Farisees and of Saducees?
23684	40	16	12	Thanne thei vndurstooden, that he seide not to be war of sourdowy of looues, but of the techyng of Farisees and Saducees.
23685	40	16	13	And Jhesus cam in to the parties of Cesarie of Filip, and axide hise disciplis, and seide, Whom seien men to be mannus sone?
23686	40	16	14	And thei seiden, Summe Joon Baptist; othere Elie; and othere Jeremye, or oon of the prophetis.
23687	40	16	15	Jhesus seide to hem, But whom seien ye me to be?
23688	40	16	16	Symount Petre answeride, and seide, Thou art Crist, the sone of God lyuynge.
23689	40	16	17	Jhesus answeride, and seide to him, Blessid art thou, Symount Bariona; for fleisch and blood schewide not to thee, but my fadir that is in heuenes.
23690	40	16	18	And Y seie to thee, that thou art Petre, and on this stoon Y schal bilde my chirche, and the yatis of helle schulen not haue miyt ayens it.
23691	40	16	19	And to thee Y shal yyue the keies of the kingdom of heuenes; and what euer thou shalt bynde on erthe, schal be boundun also in heuenes; and what euer thou schalt vnbynde on erthe, schal be vnbounden also in heuenes.
23692	40	16	20	Thanne he comaundide to hise disciplis, that thei schulden seie to no man, that he was Crist.
23693	40	16	21	Fro that tyme Jhesus bigan to schewe to hise disciplis, that it bihofte hym go to Jerusalem, and suffre many thingis, of the eldere men, and of scribis, and princis of prestis; and be slayn, and the thridde dai to rise ayen.
23694	40	16	22	And Petre took hym, and bigan to blame him, and seide, Fer be it fro thee, Lord; this thing schal not be to thee.
23695	40	16	23	And he turnede, and seide to Petre, Sathanas, go after me; thou art a sclaundre to me; for thou sauerist not tho thingis that ben of God, but tho thingis that ben of men.
23696	40	16	24	Thanne Jhesus seide to his disciplis, If ony man wole come after me, denye he hym silf, and take his cros, and sue me; for he that wole make his lijf saaf,
23697	40	16	25	shal leese it; and he that schal leese his lijf for me, schal fynde it.
23698	40	16	26	For what profitith it to a man, if he wynne al the world, and suffre peiryng of his soule? or what chaunging schal a man yyue for his soule?
23699	40	16	27	For mannes sone schal come in glorie of his fader, with his aungels, and thanne he schal yelde to ech man after his werkis.
23700	40	16	28	Treuli Y seie to you, `ther ben summe of hem that stonden here, whiche schulen not taste deth, til thei seen mannus sone comynge in his kyngdom.
23701	40	17	1	And after sixe daies Jhesus took Petre, and James, and Joon, his brother, and ledde hem aside in to an hiy hil,
23702	40	17	2	and was turned in to an othir licnesse bifor hem. And his face schone as the sunne; and hise clothis weren maad white as snowe.
23703	40	17	3	And lo! Moises and Elie apperiden to hem, and spaken with hym.
23704	40	17	4	And Petre answeride, and seide to Jhesu, Lord, it is good vs to be here. If thou wolt, make we here thre tabernaclis; to thee oon, to Moises oon, and oon to Elye. Yit the while he spak, lo!
23705	40	17	5	a briyt cloude ouerschadewide hem; and lo! a voice out of the cloude, that seide, This is my dereworth sone, in whom Y haue wel pleside to me; here ye hym.
23706	40	17	6	And the disciplis herden, and felden doun on her faces, and dredden greetli.
23707	40	17	7	And Jhesus cam, and touchide hem, and seide to hem, Rise vp, and nyle ye drede.
23708	40	17	8	And thei liften vp her iyen, and saien no man, but Jhesu aloone.
23709	40	17	9	And as thei camen doun of the hille, Jhesus comaundide to hem, and seide, Seie ye to no man the visioun, til mannus sone rise ayen fro deeth.
23710	40	17	10	And his disciplis axiden hym, and seiden, What thanne seien the scribis, that it bihoueth that Elie come first?
23711	40	17	11	He answeride, and seide to hem, Elie schal come, and he schal restore alle thingis.
23712	40	17	12	And Y seie to you, that Elie is nowe comun, and thei knewen hym not, but thei diden in him what euer thingis thei wolden; and so mannus sone schal suffre of hem.
23713	40	17	13	Thanne the disciplis vndurstoden, that he seide to hem of Joon Baptist.
23714	40	17	14	And whanne he cam to the puple, a man cam to hym, and felde doun on hise knees bifor hym, and seide, Lord, haue merci on my sone; for he is lunatike, and suffrith yuele, for ofte tymes he fallith in to the fier, and ofte tymes in to water.
23715	40	17	15	And Y brouyte hym to thi disciplis, and thei myyten not heele hym.
23716	40	17	16	Jhesus answeride, and seide, A! thou generacion vnbileueful and weiward; hou long schal Y be with you? hou long schal Y suffre you? Brynge ye hym hider to me.
23717	40	17	17	And Jhesus blamede hym, and the deuel wente out fro hym; and the child was heelid fro that our.
23718	40	17	18	Thanne the disciplis camen to Jhesu priueli, and seiden to hym, Whi myyten not we caste hym out?
23719	40	17	19	Jhesus seith to hem, For youre vnbileue. Treuli Y seie to you, if ye han feith, as a corn of seneueye, ye schulen seie to this hil, Passe thou hennus, and it schal passe; and no thing schal be vnpossible to you;
23720	40	17	20	but this kynde is not caste out, but bi preiyng and fastyng.
23721	40	17	21	And whilis thei weren abidynge togidere in Galilee, Jhesus seide to hem, Mannus sone schal be bitraied in to the hondis of men;
23722	40	17	22	and thei schulen sle hym, and the thridde day he schal rise ayen to lijf.
23723	40	17	23	And thei weren ful sori. And whanne thei camen to Cafarnaum, thei that token tribute, camen to Petre, and seiden to hym, Youre maister payeth not tribute?
23724	40	17	24	And he seide, Yhis. And whanne he was comen in to the hous, Jhesus cam bifor hym, and seide, Symount, what semeth to thee? Kyngis of erthe, of whom taken thei tribute? of her sones, ether of aliens?
23725	40	17	25	And he seide, Of aliens. Jhesus seide to hym, Thanne sones ben fre.
23726	40	17	26	But that we sclaundre hem not, go to the see, and caste an hook, and take thilke fisch that first cometh vp; and, whanne his mouth is opened, thou schalt fynde a stater, and yyue for thee and for me.
23727	40	18	1	In that our the disciplis camen to Jhesu, and seiden, Who, gessist thou, is gretter in the kyngdom of heuenes?
23728	40	18	2	And Jhesus clepide a litil child, and putte hym in the myddil of hem;
23729	40	18	3	and seide, Y seie treuthe to you, but ye be turned, and maad as litle children, ye schulen not entre in to the kyngdom of heuenes.
23730	40	18	4	Therfor who euer mekith hym as this litil child, he is gretter in the kyngdom of heuenes.
23731	40	18	5	And he that resseyueth o siche litil child in my name, resseyueth me.
23732	40	18	6	But who so sclaundrith oon of these smale, that bileuen in me, it spedith to hym that a mylnstoon `of assis be hangid in his necke, and he be drenchid in the depnesse of the see.
23733	40	18	7	Woo to the world, for sclaundris; for it is nede that sclaundris come; netheles wo to thilke man bi whom a sclaundre cometh.
23734	40	18	8	And if thin hoond or thi foot sclaundreth thee, kitte it of, and caste awei fro thee. It is betere to thee to entre to lijf feble, ethir crokid, than hauynge tweyne hoondis or twey feet to be sent in to euerlastynge fier.
23735	40	18	9	And if thin iye sclaundre thee, pulle it out, and caste awei fro thee. It is betere to thee with oon iye to entre in to lijf, thanne hauynge tweyn iyen to be sent in to the fier of helle.
23736	40	18	10	Se ye, that ye dispise not oon of these litle. For Y seie to you, that the aungels of hem in heuenes seen euermore the face of my fadir that is in heuenes.
23737	40	18	11	For mannus sone cam to saue that thing that perischide.
23738	40	18	12	What semeth to you? If ther weren to sum man an hundrid scheep, and oon of hem hath errid, whethir he schal not leeue nynti and nyne in desert, and schal go to seche that that erride?
23739	40	18	13	And if it falle that he fynde it, treuli Y seie to you, that he schal haue ioye theron more than on nynti and nyne that erriden not.
23740	40	18	14	So it is not the wille bifor youre fadir that is in heuenes, that oon of these litle perische.
23741	40	18	15	But if thi brother synneth ayens thee, go thou, and repreue hym, bitwixe thee and hym aloone; if he herith thee, thou hast wonnun thi brother.
23742	40	18	16	And if he herith thee not, take with thee oon or tweyne, that euery word stonde in the mouth of tweyne or thre witnessis.
23743	40	18	17	And if he herith not hem, seie thou to the chirche. But if he herith not the chirche, be he as an hethen and a pupplican to thee.
23744	40	18	18	Y seie to you treuli, what euer thingis ye bynden on erthe, tho schulen be boundun also in heuene; and what euer thingis ye vnbynden on erthe, tho schulen be vnboundun also in heuene.
23745	40	18	19	Eftsoone Y seie to you, that if tweyne of you consenten on the erthe, of euery thing what euer thei axen, it schal be don to hem of my fadir that is in heuenes.
23746	40	18	20	For where tweyne or thre ben gaderid in my name, there Y am in the myddil of hem.
23747	40	18	21	Thanne Petre cam to hym, and seide, Lord, how ofte schal my brother synne ayens me, and Y schal foryyue hym?
23748	40	18	22	Whether til seuen tymes? Jhesus seith to hym, Y seie not to thee, til seuene sithis; but til seuenti sithis seuene sithis.
23749	40	18	23	Therfor the kyngdom of heuenes is licned to a kyng, that wolde rekyn with hise seruauntis.
23750	40	18	24	And whanne he bigan to rekene, oon that ouyte ten thousynde talentis, was brouyt to hym.
23751	40	18	25	And whanne he hadde not wherof to yelde, his lord comaundide hym to be seld, and his wijf, and children, and alle thingis that he hadde, and to be paied.
23752	40	18	26	But thilke seruaunt felde doun, and preiede hym, and seide, Haue pacience in me, and Y schal yelde to thee alle thingis.
23753	40	18	27	And the lord hadde merci on that seruaunt, and suffride hym to go, and foryaf to hym the dette.
23754	40	18	28	But thilke seruaunt yede out, and foonde oon of his euen seruauntis, that ouyte hym an hundrid pens; and he helde hym, and stranglide hym, and seide, Yelde that that thou owest.
23755	40	18	29	And his euen seruaunt felle doun, and preyede hym, and seide, Haue pacience in me, and Y schal quyte alle thingis to thee.
23756	40	18	30	But he wolde not; but wente out, and putte hym in to prisoun, til he paiede al the dette.
23757	40	18	31	And hise euen seruauntis, seynge the thingis that weren don, soreweden greetli. And thei camen, and telden to her lord alle the thingis that weren don.
