23758	40	18	32	Thanne his lord clepide hym, and seide to hym, Wickid seruaunt, Y foryaf to thee al the dette, for thou preiedist me.
23759	40	18	33	Therfor whether it bihouede not also thee to haue merci on thin euen seruaunt, as Y hadde merci on thee?
23760	40	18	34	And his lord was wroth, and took hym to turmentouris, til he paiede al the dette.
23761	40	18	35	So my fadir of heuene schal do to you, if ye foryyuen not euery man to his brother, of youre hertes.
23762	40	19	1	And it was don, whanne Jhesus hadde endid these wordis, he passide fro Galilee, and cam in to the coostis of Judee ouer Jordan.
23763	40	19	2	And myche puple suede him, and he heelide hem there.
23764	40	19	3	And Farisees camen to him, temptynge him, and seiden, Whether it be leueful to a man to leeue his wijf, for ony cause?
23765	40	19	4	Which answeride, and seide to hem, Han ye not red, for he that made men at the bigynnyng, made hem male and female?
23766	40	19	5	And he seide, For this thing a man schal leeue fadir and modir, and he schal draw to his wijf; and thei schulen be tweyne in o fleisch.
23767	40	19	6	And so thei ben not now tweyne, but o fleisch. Therfor a man departe not that thing that God hath ioyned.
23768	40	19	7	Thei seien to hym, What thanne comaundide Moises, to yyue a libel of forsakyng, and to leeue of?
23769	40	19	8	And he seide to hem, For Moises, for the hardnesse of youre herte, suffride you leeue youre wyues; but fro the bigynnyng it was not so.
23770	40	19	9	And Y seie to you, that who euer leeueth his wijf, but for fornycacioun, and weddith another, doith letcherie; and he that weddith the forsakun wijf, doith letcherie.
23771	40	19	10	His disciplis seien to him, If the cause of a man with a wijf is so, it spedith not to be weddid.
23772	40	19	11	And he seide to hem, Not alle men taken this word; but to whiche it is youun.
23773	40	19	12	For ther ben geldingis, whiche ben thus born of the modris wombe; and ther ben geldyngis, that ben maad of men; and there ben geldyngis, that han geldid hem silf, for the kyngdom of heuenes. He that may take, `take he.
23774	40	19	13	Thanne litle children weren brouyte to hym, that he schulde putte hondis to hem, and preie.
23775	40	19	14	And the disciplis blamyden hem. But Jhesus seide to hem, Suffre ye that litle children come to me, and nyle ye forbede hem; for of siche is the kyngdom of heuenes.
23776	40	19	15	And whanne he hadde put to hem hondis, he wente fro thennus.
23777	40	19	16	And lo! oon cam, and seide to hym, Good maister, what good schal Y do, that Y haue euerlastynge lijf?
23778	40	19	17	Which seith to hym, What axist thou me of good thing? There is o good God. But if thou wolt entre to lijf, kepe the comaundementis.
23779	40	19	18	He seith to hym, Whiche? And Jhesus seide, Thou schalt not do mansleying, thou schalt not do auowtrie, thou schalt not do thefte, thou schalt not seie fals witnessying;
23780	40	19	19	worschipe thi fadir and thi modir, and, thou schalt loue thi neiybore as thi silf.
23781	40	19	20	The yonge man seith to hym, Y haue kept alle these thingis fro my youthe, what yit failith to me?
23782	40	19	21	Jhesus seith to hym, If thou wolt be perfite, go, and sille alle thingis that thou hast, and yyue to pore men, and thou schalt haue tresoure in heuene; and come, and sue me.
23783	40	19	22	And whanne the yong man hadde herd these wordis, he wente awei sorewful, for he hadde many possessiouns.
23784	40	19	23	And Jhesus seide to hise disciplis, Y seie to you treuthe, for a riche man of hard schal entre in to the kyngdom of heuenes.
23785	40	19	24	And eftsoone Y seie to you, it is liyter a camel to passe thorou a needlis iye, thanne a riche man to entre in to the kyngdom of heuens.
23786	40	19	25	Whanne these thingis weren herd, the disciplis wondriden greetli, and seiden, Who thanne may be saaf?
23787	40	19	26	Jhesus bihelde, and seide to hem, Anentis men this thing is impossible; but anentis God alle thingis ben possible.
23788	40	19	27	Thanne Petre answeride, and seide to hym, Lo! we han forsake alle thingis, and we han suede thee; what thanne schal be to vs?
23789	40	19	28	Jhesus seide to hem, Truli I seie to you, that ye that han forsake alle thingis, and han sued me, in the regeneracioun whanne mannus sone schal sitte in the sete of his maieste, ye schulen sitte on twelue setis, demynge the twelue kynredis of Israel.
23790	40	19	29	And euery man that forsakith hous, britheren or sistren, fadir or modir, wijf ethir children, or feeldis, for my name, he schal take an hundrid foold, and schal welde euerlastynge lijf.
23791	40	19	30	But manye schulen be, the firste the laste, and the laste the firste.
23792	40	20	1	The kyngdom of heuenes is lijc to an housbonde man, that wente out first bi the morewe, to hire werk men in to his vyneyerd.
23793	40	20	2	And whanne the couenaunt was maad with werk men, of a peny for the dai, he sente hem in to his vyneyerd.
23794	40	20	3	And he yede out aboute the thridde our, and say othere stondynge idel in the chepyng.
23795	40	20	4	And he seide to hem, Go ye also in to myn vynyerd, and that that schal be riytful, Y schal yyue to you.
23796	40	20	5	And thei wenten forth. Eftsoones he wente out aboute the sixte our, and the nynthe, and dide in lijk maner.
23797	40	20	6	But aboute the elleuenthe our he wente out, and foond other stondynge; and he seide to hem, What stonden ye idel here al dai?
23798	40	20	7	Thei seien to him, For no man hath hirid vs. He seith to hem, Go ye also in to my vyneyerd.
23799	40	20	8	And whanne euenyng was comun, the lord of the vyneyerd seith to his procuratoure, Clepe the werk men, and yelde to hem her hire, and bigynne thou at the laste til to the firste.
23800	40	20	9	And so whanne thei weren comun, that camen aboute the elleuenthe our, also thei token eueryche of hem a peny.
23801	40	20	10	But the firste camen, and demeden, that thei schulden take more, but thei token ech oon bi hem silf a peny;
23802	40	20	11	and in the takyng grutchiden ayens the hosebonde man, and seiden,
23803	40	20	12	These laste wrouyten oon our, and thou hast maad hem euen to vs, that han born the charge of the dai, and heete?
23804	40	20	13	And he answeride to oon of hem, and seide, Freend, Y do thee noon wrong; whether thou hast not acordid with me for a peny?
23805	40	20	14	Take thou that that is thin, and go; for Y wole yyue to this laste man, as to thee.
23806	40	20	15	Whether it is not leueful to me to do that that Y wole? Whether thin iye is wickid, for Y am good?
23807	40	20	16	So the laste schulen be the firste, and the firste the laste; `for many ben clepid, but fewe ben chosun.
23808	40	20	17	And Jhesus wente vp to Jerusalem, and took hise twelue disciplis in priuetee, and seide to hem, Lo!
23809	40	20	18	we goon vp to Jerusalem, and mannus sone schal be bitakun to princis of prestis, and scribis; and thei schulen condempne him to deeth.
23810	40	20	19	And thei schulen bitake hym to hethene men, for to be scorned, and scourgid, and crucified; and the thridde day he schal rise ayen to lijf.
23811	40	20	20	Thanne the modir of the sones of Zebedee cam to hym with hir sones, onourynge, and axynge sum thing of hym.
23812	40	20	21	And he seide to hir, What wolt thou? She seith to hym, Seie that thes tweyne my sones sitte, oon at thi riythalf, and oon at thi lefthalf, in thi kyngdom.
23813	40	20	22	Jhesus answeride, and seide, Ye witen not what ye axen. Moun ye drynke the cuppe which Y schal drynke? Thei seien to hym, We moun.
23814	40	20	23	He seith to hem, Ye schulen drinke my cuppe; but to sitte at my riythalf or lefthalf, it is not myn to yyue to you; but to whiche it is maad redi of my fadir.
23815	40	20	24	And the ten herynge, hadden indignacioun of the twei britheren.
23816	40	20	25	But Jhesus clepide hem to hym, and seide, Ye witen, that princis of hethene men ben lordis of hem, and thei that ben gretter, vsen power on hem.
23817	40	20	26	It schal not be so among you; but who euer wole be maad gretter among you, be he youre mynystre; and who euer among you wole be the firste, he schal be youre seruaunt.
23818	40	20	28	As mannus sone cam not to be seruyd, but to serue, and to yyue his lijf redempcioun for manye.
23819	40	20	29	And whanne thei yeden out of Jerico, miche puple suede him.
23820	40	20	30	And lo! twei blynde men saten bisydis the weie, and herden that Jhesus passide; and thei crieden, and seiden, Lord, the sone of Dauid, haue merci on vs.
23821	40	20	31	And the puple blamede hem, that thei schulden be stille; and thei crieden the more, and seiden, Lord, the sone of Dauid, haue merci on vs.
23822	40	20	32	And Jhesus stood, and clepide hem, and seide, What wolen ye, that Y do to you?
23823	40	20	33	Thei seien to him, Lord, that oure iyen be opened.
23824	40	20	34	And Jhesus hadde merci on hem, and touchide her iyen; and anoon thei sayen, and sueden him.
23825	40	21	1	And whanne Jhesus cam nyy to Jerusalem, and cam to Bethfage, at the mount of Olyuete, thanne sente he his twei disciplis, and seide to hem,
23826	40	21	2	Go ye in to the castel that is ayens you, and anoon ye schulen fynde an asse tied, and a colt with hir; vntien ye, and brynge to me.
23827	40	21	3	And if ony man seie to you ony thing, seie ye, that the Lord hath nede to hem; and anoon he schal leeue hem.
23828	40	21	4	Al this was doon, that that thing schulde be fulfillid, that was seid bi the prophete, seiynge, Seie ye to the douyter of Syon, Lo!
23829	40	21	5	thi kyng cometh to thee, meke, sittynge on an asse, and a fole of an asse vnder yok.
23830	40	21	6	And the disciplis yeden, and diden as Jhesus comaundide hem.
23831	40	21	7	And thei brouyten an asse, and the fole, and leiden her clothis on hem, and maden hym sitte aboue.
23832	40	21	8	And ful myche puple strewiden her clothis in the weie; othere kittiden braunchis of trees, and strewiden in the weie.
23833	40	21	9	And the puple that wente bifore, and that sueden, crieden, and seiden, Osanna to the sone of Dauid; blessid is he that cometh in the name of the Lord; Osanna in hiy thingis.
23834	40	21	10	And whanne he was entrid in to Jerusalem, al the citee was stirid, and seide, Who is this?
23835	40	21	11	But the puple seide, This is Jhesus, the prophete, of Nazareth of Galilee.
23836	40	21	12	And Jhesus entride in to the temple of God, and castide out of the temple alle that bouyten and solden; and he turnede vpsedoun the bordis of chaungeris, and the chayeris of men that solden culueris.
23837	40	21	13	And he seith to hem, It is writun, Myn hous schal be clepid an hous of preier; but ye han maad it a denne of theues.
23838	40	21	14	And blynde and crokid camen to hym in the temple, and he heelide hem.
23839	40	21	15	But the princis of prestis and scribis, seynge the merueilouse thingis that he dide, and children criynge in the temple, and seiynge, Osanna to the sone of Dauid, hadden indignacioun,
23840	40	21	16	and seiden to hym, Herist thou what these seien? And Jhesus seide to hem, Yhe; whether ye han neuer redde, That of the mouth of yonge children, and of soukynge childryn, thou hast maad perfit heriyng?
23841	40	21	17	And whanne he hadde left hem, he wente forth out of the citee, in to Bethanye; and there he dwelte, and tauyte hem of the kyngdom of God.
23842	40	21	18	But on the morowe, he, turnynge ayen in to the citee, hungride.
23843	40	21	19	And he saye a fige tree bisidis the weie, and cam to it, and foond no thing ther ynne but leeues oneli. And he seide to it, Neuer fruyt come forth of thee, in to with outen eende, And anoon the fige tre was dried vp.
23844	40	21	20	And disciplis `sawen, and wondriden, seiynge, Hou anoon it driede.
23845	40	21	21	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, Treuli Y seie to you, if ye haue feith, and douten not, not oonli ye schulen do of the fige tree, but also if ye seyn to this hil, Take, and caste thee in to the see, it schal be don so.
23846	40	21	22	And alle thingis what euere ye bileuynge schulen axe in preyer, ye schulen take.
23847	40	21	23	And whanne he cam in to the temple, the princis of prestis and elder men of the puple camen to hym that tauyte, and seiden, In what power doist thou these thingis? and who yaf thee this power?
23848	40	21	24	Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, And Y schal axe you o word, the which if ye tellen me, Y schal seie to you, in what power Y do these thingis.
23849	40	21	25	Of whennys was the baptym of Joon; of heuene, or of men? And thei thouyten with ynne hem silf,
23850	40	21	26	seiynge, If we seien of heuene, he schal seie to vs, Whi thanne bileuen ye not to hym? If we seien of men, we dreden the puple, for alle hadden Joon as a prophete.
23851	40	21	27	And thei answeriden to Jhesu, and seiden, We witen not. And he seide to hem, Nether Y seie to you, in what power Y do these thingis.
23852	40	21	28	But what semeth to you? A man hadde twey sones; and he cam to the firste, and seide, Sone, go worche this dai in my vyneyerd.
23853	40	21	29	And he answeride, and seide, Y nyle; but afterward he forthouyte, and wente forth.
23854	40	21	30	But he cam to `the tother, and seide on lijk maner. And he answeride, and seide, Lord, Y go; and he wente not.
23855	40	21	31	Who of the tweyne dide the fadris wille? Thei seien to hym, The firste. Jhesus seith to hem, Treuli Y seie to you, for pupplicans and hooris schulen go bifor you `in to the kyngdom of God.
23856	40	21	32	For Joon cam to you in the weie of riytwisnesse, and ye bileueden not to him; but pupplicans and hooris bileueden to hym. But ye sayn, and hadden no forthenkyng aftir, that ye bileueden to hym.
23857	40	21	33	Here ye another parable. There was an hosebonde man, that plauntide a vynyerd, and heggide it aboute, and dalfe a presour ther ynne, and bildide a tour, and hiride it to erthe tilieris, and wente fer in pilgrimage.
23858	40	21	34	But whanne the tyme of fruytis neiyede, he sente his seruauntis to the erthe tilieris, to take fruytis of it.
23859	40	21	35	And the erthetilieris token his seruauntis, and beeten `the toon, thei slowen another, and thei stonyden another.
23860	40	21	36	Eftsoone he sente othere seruauntis, mo than the firste, and in lijk maner thei diden to hem.
23861	40	21	37	And at the laste he sente his sone to hem, and seide, Thei schulen drede my sone.
23862	40	21	38	But the erthe tilieris, seynge the sone, seiden with ynne hem silf, This is the eire; come ye, sle we hym, and we schulen haue his eritage.
23863	40	21	39	And thei token, and castiden hym out of the vynyerd, and slowen hym.
23864	40	21	40	Therfor whanne the lord of the vyneyerd schal come, what schal he do to thilke erthe tilieris?
23865	40	21	41	Thei seien to hym, He schal leese yuele the yuele men, and he schal sette to hire his vyneyerd to othere erthetilieris, whyche schulen yelde to hym fruyt in her tymes.
23866	40	21	42	Jhesus seith to hem, Redden ye neuer in scripturis, The stoon which bilderis repreueden, this is maad in to the heed of the corner? Of the Lord this thing is don, and it is merueilous bifor oure iyen.
23867	40	21	43	Therfor Y seie to you, that the kyngdom of God schal be takun fro you, and shal be youun to a folc doynge fruytis of it.
23868	40	21	44	And he that schal falle on this stoon, schal be brokun; but on whom it schal falle, it schal al tobrise hym.
23869	40	21	45	And whanne the princes of prestis and Farisees hadden herd hise parablis, thei knewen that he seide of hem.
23870	40	21	46	And thei souyten to holde hym, but thei dredden the puple, for thei hadden hym as a prophete.
23871	40	22	1	And Jhesus answeride, and spak eftsoone in parablis to hem,
23872	40	22	2	and seide, The kyngdom of heuenes is maad lijk to a kyng that made weddyngis to his sone.
23873	40	22	3	And he sente hise seruauntis for to clepe men that weren bode to the weddyngis, and thei wolden not come.
23874	40	22	4	Eftsoone he sente othere seruauntis, and seide, Seie ye to the men that ben bode to the feeste, Lo! Y haue maad redi my meete, my bolis and my volatilis ben slayn, and alle thingis ben redy; come ye to the weddyngis.
23875	40	22	5	But thei dispisiden, and wenten forth, oon in to his toun, anothir to his marchaundise. But othere helden his seruauntis, and turmentiden hem, and slowen.
23876	40	22	7	But the kyng, whanne he hadde herd, was wroth; and he sente hise oostis, and he distruyede tho manquelleris, and brente her citee.
23877	40	22	8	Thanne he seide to hise seruauntis, The weddyngis ben redi, but thei that weren clepid to the feeste, weren not worthi.
23878	40	22	9	Therfor go ye to the endis of weies, and whom euere ye fynden, clepe ye to the weddyngis.
23879	40	22	10	And hise seruauntis yeden out in to weies, and gadriden togider alle that thei founden, good and yuele; and the bridale was fulfillid with men sittynge at the mete.
23880	40	22	11	And the kyng entride, to se men sittynge at the mete; and he siye there a man not clothid with bride cloth.
23881	40	22	12	And he seide to hym, Freend, hou entridist thou hidir with out bride clothis? And he was doumbe.
23882	40	22	13	Thanne the kyng bad hise mynystris, Bynde hym bothe hondis and feet, and sende ye him in to vtmer derknessis; there schal be wepyng and grentyng of teeth.
23883	40	22	14	For many ben clepid, but fewe ben chosun.
23884	40	22	15	Thanne Farisees yeden awei, and token a counsel to take Jhesu in word.
23885	40	22	16	And thei senden to hym her disciplis, with Erodians, and seien, Maister, we witen, that thou art sothefast, and thou techist in treuthe the weie of God, and thou chargist not of ony man, for thou biholdist not the persoone of men.
23886	40	22	17	Therfor seie to vs, what it seemeth to thee. Is it leueful that tribute be youun to the emperoure, ether nay?
23887	40	22	18	And whanne Jhesus hadde knowe the wickidnesse of hem, he seide, Ypocritis, what tempten ye me?
23888	40	22	19	Schewe ye to me the prynte of the money. And thei brouyten to hym a peny.
23889	40	22	20	And Jhesus seide to hem, Whos is this ymage, and the writyng aboue?
23890	40	22	21	Thei seien to hym, The emperouris. Thanne he seide to hem, Therfor yelde ye to the emperoure tho thingis that ben the emperouris, and to God tho thingis that ben of God.
23891	40	22	22	And thei herden, and wondriden; and thei leften hym, and wenten awey.
23892	40	22	23	In that dai Saduceis, that seien there is no risyng ayen to lijf, camen to hym, and axiden him,
23893	40	22	24	and seiden, Mayster, Moises seide, if ony man is deed, not hauynge a sone, that his brother wedde his wijf, and reise seed to his brothir.
23894	40	22	25	And seuen britheren weren at vs; and the firste weddide a wijf, and is deed. And he hadde no seed, and lefte his wijf to his brother;
23895	40	22	26	also the secounde, and the thridde, til to the seuenthe.
23896	40	22	27	But the laste of alle, the woman is deed.
23897	40	22	28	Also in the risyng ayen to lijf, whos wijf of the seuene schal sche be? for alle hadden hir.
23898	40	22	29	Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, Ye erren, `and ye knowen not scripturis, ne the vertu of God.
23899	40	22	30	For in the rysyng ayen to lijf, nether thei schulen wedde, nethir schulen be weddid; but thei ben as the aungels of God in heuene.
23900	40	22	31	And of the risyng ayen of deed men, `han ye not red, that is seid of the Lord, that seith to you,
23901	40	22	32	Y am God of Abraham, and God of Ysaac, and God of Jacob? he is not God of deede men, but of lyuynge men.
23902	40	22	33	And the puple herynge, wondriden in his techynge.
23903	40	22	34	And Fariseis herden that he hadde put silence to Saduceis, and camen togidere.
23904	40	22	35	And oon of hem, a techere of the lawe, axide Jhesu, and temptide him,
23905	40	22	36	Maistir, which is a greet maundement in the lawe?
23906	40	22	37	Jhesus seide to him, Thou schalt loue thi Lord God, of al thin herte, and in al thi soule, and in al thi mynde.
23907	40	22	38	This is the firste and the moste maundement.
23908	40	22	39	And the secounde is lijk to this; Thou schalt loue thi neiyebore as thi silf.
23909	40	22	40	In these twey maundementis hangith al the lawe and the profetis.
23910	40	22	41	And whanne the Farisees weren gederid togidere, Jhesus axide hem,
23911	40	22	42	and seide, What semeth to you of Crist, whos sone is he? Thei seien to hym, Of Dauid.
23912	40	22	43	He seith to hem, Hou thanne Dauid in spirit clepith hym Lord,
23913	40	22	44	and seith, The Lord seide to my Lord, Sitte on my riythalf, til Y putte thin enemyes a stool of thi feet?
23914	40	22	45	Thanne if Dauid clepith hym Lord, hou is he his sone?
23915	40	22	46	And no man miyte answere a word to hym, nethir ony man was hardi fro that day, to axe hym more.
23916	40	23	1	Thanne Jhesus spac to the puple, and to hise disciplis,
23917	40	23	2	and seide, On the chayere of Moises, scribis and Farisees han sete.
23918	40	23	3	Therfor kepe ye, and do ye alle thingis, what euer thingis thei seien to you. But nyle ye do aftir her werkis; for thei seien, and don not.
23919	40	23	4	And thei bynden greuouse chargis, and that moun not be borun, and putten on schuldris of men; but with her fyngur thei wolen not moue hem.
23920	40	23	5	Therfor thei don alle her werkis `that thei be seen of men; for thei drawen abrood her filateries, and magnifien hemmes.
23921	40	23	6	And thei louen the first sittyng placis in soperis, and the first chaieris in synagogis;
23922	40	23	7	and salutaciouns in chepyng, and to be clepid of men maystir.
23923	40	23	8	But nyle ye be clepid maister; for oon is youre maystir, and alle ye ben britheren.
23924	40	23	9	And nyle ye clepe to you a fadir on erthe, for oon is your fadir, that is in heuenes.
23925	40	23	10	Nether be ye clepid maistris, for oon is youre maister, Crist.
23926	40	23	11	He that is grettest among you, schal be youre mynystre.
23927	40	23	12	For he that hieth himself, schal be mekid; and he that mekith hym silf, schal be enhaunsid.
23928	40	23	13	But wo to you, scribis and Farisees, ipocritis, that closen the kyngdom of heuenes bifore men; and ye entren not, nether suffren men entrynge to entre.
23929	40	23	14	Wo to you, scribis and Farisees, ipocritis, that eten the housis of widowis, and preien bi longe preier; for this thing ye schulen take more doom.
23930	40	23	15	Wo to you, scribis and Farisees, ypocritis, that goon aboute the see and the loond, to make o prosilite; and whanne he is maad, ye maken hym a sone of helle, double more than ye ben.
23931	40	23	16	Wo to you, blynde lederis, that seien, Who euer swerith bi the temple of God, it is `no thing; but he that swerith in the gold of the temple, is dettoure.
23932	40	23	17	Ye foolis and blynde, for what is grettere, the gold, or the temple that halewith the gold?
23933	40	23	18	And who euer swerith in the auter, it is no thing; but he that swerith in the yifte that is on the auter, owith.
23934	40	23	19	Blynde men, for what is more, the yifte, or the auter that halewith the yifte?
23935	40	23	20	Therfor he that swerith in the auter, swerith in it, and in alle thingis that ben ther on.
23936	40	23	21	And he that swerith in the temple, swerith in it, and in hym that dwellith in the temple.
23937	40	23	22	And he that swerith in heuene, swerith in the trone of God, and in hym that sittith ther on.
23938	40	23	23	Wo to you, scribis and Farisees, ypocritis, that tithen mynte, anete, and cummyn, and han left tho thingis that ben of more charge of the lawe, doom, and merci, and feith. And it bihofte to do these thingis, and not to leeue tho.
23939	40	23	24	Blynde lederis, clensinge a gnatte, but swolewynge a camel.
23940	40	23	25	Woo to you, scribis and Farisees, ypocritis, that clensen the cuppe and the plater with outforth; but with ynne ye ben ful of raueyne and vnclennesse.
23941	40	23	26	Thou blynde Farisee, clense the cuppe and the plater with ynneforth, that that that is with outforth be maad clene.
23942	40	23	27	Wo to you, scribis and Farisees, ipocritis, that ben lijk to sepulcris whitid, whiche with outforth semen faire to men; but with ynne thei ben fulle of boonus of deed men, and of al filthe.
23943	40	23	28	So ye with outforth semen iust to men; but with ynne ye ben ful of ypocrisy and wickidnesse.
23944	40	23	29	Wo to you, scribis and Farisees, ipocritis, that bilden sepulcris of profetis, and maken faire the birielis of iust men,
23945	40	23	30	and seien, If we hadden be in the daies of oure fadris, we schulden not haue be her felowis in the blood of prophetis.
23946	40	23	31	And so ye ben in witnessyng to you silf, that ye ben the sones of hem that slowen the prophetis.
23947	40	23	32	And fulfille ye the mesure of youre fadris.
23948	40	23	33	Ye eddris, and eddris briddis, hou schulen ye fle fro the doom of helle?
23949	40	23	34	Therfor lo! Y sende to you profetis, and wise men, and scribis; and of hem ye schulen sle and crucifie, and of hem ye schulen scourge in youre sinagogis, and schulen pursue fro cite in to citee;
23950	40	23	35	that al the iust blood come on you, that was sched on the erthe, fro the blood of iust Abel to the blood of Zacarie, the sone of Barachie, whom ye slowen bitwixe the temple and the auter.
23951	40	23	36	Treuli Y seie to you, alle these thingis schulen come on this generacioun.
23952	40	23	37	Jerusalem, Jerusalem, that sleest prophetis, and stoonest hem that ben sent to thee, hou ofte wolde Y gadere togidere thi children, as an henne gaderith togidir her chikenes vndir hir wengis, and thou woldist not.
23953	40	23	38	Lo! youre hous schal be left to you desert.
23954	40	23	39	And Y seie to you, ye schulen not se me fro hennus forth, til ye seien, Blessid is he, that cometh in the name of the Lord.
23955	40	24	1	And Jhesus wente out of the temple; and his disciplis camen to hym, to schewe hym the bildyngis of the temple.
23956	40	24	2	But he answeride, and seide to hem, Seen ye alle these thingis? Treuli Y seie to you, a stoon schal not be left here on a stoon, that ne it schal be destried.
23957	40	24	3	And whanne he satte on the hille of Olyuete, hise disciplis camen to hym priueli, and seiden, Seie vs, whanne these thingis schulen be, and what token of thi comyng, and of the ending of the world.
23958	40	24	4	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, Loke ye, that no man disseyue you.
23959	40	24	5	For many schulen come in my name, and schulen seie, Y am Crist; and thei schulen disseyue manye.
23960	40	24	6	For ye schulen here batels, and opyniouns of batels; se ye that ye be not disturblid; for it byhoueth these thingis to be don, but not yit is the ende.
23961	40	24	7	Folk schal rise togidere ayens folc, and rewme ayens rewme, and pestilences, and hungris, and the erthemouyngis schulen be bi placis;
23962	40	24	8	and alle these ben bigynnyngis of sorewes.
23963	40	24	9	Thanne men schulen bitake you in to tribulacion, and schulen sle you, and ye schulen be in hate to alle folk for my name.
23964	40	24	10	And thanne many schulen be sclaundrid, and bitraye ech other, and thei schulen hate ech other.
23965	40	24	11	And many false prophetis schulen rise, and disseyue manye.
23966	40	24	12	And for wickidnesse schal `be plenteuouse, the charite of manye schal wexe coold;
23967	40	24	13	but he that schal dwelle stable in to the ende, schal be saaf.
23968	40	24	14	And this gospel of the kyngdom schal be prechid in al the world, in witnessyng to al folc;
23969	40	24	15	and thanne the ende schal come. Therfor whanne ye se the abhomynacioun of discomfort, that is seid of Danyel, the prophete, stondynge in the hooli place; he that redith, vndirstonde he;
23970	40	24	16	thanne thei that ben in Judee, fle to the mounteyns; and he that is in the hous roof,
23971	40	24	17	come not doun to take ony thing of his hous; and he that is in the feeld,
23972	40	24	18	turne not ayen to take his coote.
23973	40	24	19	But wo to hem that ben with child, and nurischen in tho daies.
23974	40	24	20	Preye ye, that youre fleyng be not maad in wynter, or in the saboth.
23975	40	24	21	For thanne schal be greet tribulacioun, what maner `was not fro the bigynnyng of the world to now, nether schal be maad.
23976	40	24	22	And but tho daies hadden be abreggide, ech flesch schulde not be maad saaf; but tho daies schulen be maad schort, for the chosun men.
23977	40	24	23	Thanne if ony man seie to you, Lo! here is Crist, or there, nyle ye bileue.
23978	40	24	24	For false Cristis and false prophetis schulen rise, and thei schulen yyue grete tokenes and wondrys; so that also the chosun be led in to erroure, if it may be done.
23979	40	24	25	Lo! Y haue bifor seid to you.
23980	40	24	26	Therfor if thei seie to you, Lo! he is in desert, nyle ye go out; lo! in priuey placis, nyle ye trowe.
23981	40	24	27	For as leit goith out fro the eest, and apperith in to the weste, so schal be also the coming of mannus sone.
23982	40	24	28	Where euer the bodi schal be, also the eglis schulen be gaderid thidur.
23983	40	24	29	And anoon after the tribulacioun of tho daies, the sunne schal be maad derk, and the moone schal not yyue hir liyt, and the sterris schulen falle fro heuene, and the vertues of heuenes schulen be moued.
23984	40	24	30	And thanne the tokene of mannus sone schal appere in heuene, and thanne alle kynredis of the erthe schulen weile; and thei schulen see mannus sone comynge in the cloudis of heuene, with miche vertu and maieste.
23985	40	24	31	And he schal sende hise aungels with a trumpe, and a greet vois; and thei schulen gedere hise chosun fro foure wyndis, fro the hiyest thingis of heuenes to the endis of hem.
23986	40	24	32	And lerne ye the parable of a fige tre. Whanne his braunche is now tendir, and the leeues ben sprongun, ye witen that somer is nyy;
23987	40	24	33	`so and ye whanne ye seen alle these thingis, wite ye that it is nyy, in the yatis.
23988	40	24	34	Treuli Y seie to you, for this generacioun schal not passe, til alle thingis be don;
23989	40	24	35	heuene and erthe schulen passe, but my wordis schulen not passe.
23990	40	24	36	But of thilke dai and our no man wote, nethir aungels of heuenes, but the fadir aloone.
23991	40	24	37	But as it was in the daies of Noe, so schal be the comyng of mannus sone.
23992	40	24	38	For as in the daies bifore the greet flood, thei weren etynge and drynkynge, weddynge and takynge to weddyng, to that dai, that Noe entride in to the schippe;
23993	40	24	39	and thei knewen not, til the greet flood cam, and took alle men, so schal be the comyng of mannus sone.
23994	40	24	40	Thanne tweyne schulen be in o feeld, oon schal be takun, and another left;
23995	40	24	41	twey wymmen schulen be gryndynge in o queerne, oon schal be takun, and `the tother left; tweyn in a bedde, `the toon schal be takun, and the tother left.
23996	40	24	42	Therfor wake ye, for ye witen not in what our the Lord schal come.
23997	40	24	43	But wite ye this, that if the hosebonde man wiste in what our the thefe were to come, certis he wolde wake, and suffre not his hous to be vndurmyned.
23998	40	24	44	And therfor be ye redi, for in what our ye gessen not, mannus sone schal come.
23999	40	24	45	Who gessist thou is a trewe seruaunt and prudent, whom his lord ordeyned on his meynee, to yyue hem mete in tyme?
24000	40	24	46	Blessed is that seruaunt, whom `his lord, whanne he schal come, schal fynde so doynge.
24001	40	24	47	Treuli Y seye to you, for on alle his goodis he schal ordeyne hym.
24002	40	24	48	But if thilke yuel seruaunt seie in his herte, My lord tarieth to come,
24003	40	24	49	and bigynneth to smyte hise euen seruauntis, and ete, and drynke with drunken men;
24004	40	24	50	the lord of that seruaunt schal come in the dai which he hopith not, and in the our that he knowith not,
24005	40	24	50	and schal departe hym, and putte his part with ypocritis; there schal be wepyng, and gryntyng of teeth.
24006	40	25	1	Thanne the kyngdoom of heuenes schal be lijk to ten virgyns, whiche token her laumpis, and wenten out ayens the hosebonde and the wijf;
24007	40	25	2	and fyue of hem weren foolis, and fyue prudent.
24008	40	25	3	But the fyue foolis token her laumpis, and token not oile with hem;
24009	40	25	4	but the prudent token oile in her vessels with the laumpis.
24010	40	25	5	And whilis the hosebonde tariede, alle thei nappiden and slepten.
24011	40	25	6	But at mydnyyt a cryy was maad, Lo! the spouse cometh, go ye oute to mete with him.
24012	40	25	7	Thanne alle tho virgyns risen vp, and araieden her laumpis.
24013	40	25	8	And the foolis seiden to the wise, Yyue ye to vs of youre oile, for oure laumpis ben quenchid.
24014	40	25	9	The prudent answeriden, and seiden, Lest perauenture it suffice not to vs and to you, go ye rather to men that sellen, and bie to you.
24015	40	25	10	And while thei wenten for to bie, the spouse cam; and tho that weren redi, entreden with him to the weddyngis; and the yate was schit.
24016	40	25	11	And at the last the othere virgyns camen, and seiden, Lord, lord, opene to vs.
24017	40	25	12	And he answeride, and seide, Treuli Y seie to you, Y knowe you not.
24018	40	25	13	Therfor wake ye, for ye witen not the dai ne the our.
24019	40	25	14	For as a man that goith in pilgrimage, clepide hise seruauntis, and bitook to hem hise goodis;
24020	40	25	15	and to oon he yaf fyue talentis, and to another tweyne, and to another oon, to ech after his owne vertu; and wente forth anoon.
24021	40	25	16	And he that hadde fyue besauntis, wente forth, and wrouyte in hem, and wan othere fyue.
24022	40	25	17	Also and he that hadde takun tweyne, wan othere tweyne.
24023	40	25	18	But he that hadde takun oon, yede forth, and dalf in to the erthe, and hidde the money of his lord.
24024	40	25	19	But after long tyme, the lord of tho seruauntis cam, and rekenede with hem.
24025	40	25	20	And he that hadde takun fyue besauntis, cam, and brouyte othere fyue, and seide, Lord, thou bytokist to me fyue besauntis, loo! Y haue getun aboue fyue othere.
24026	40	25	21	His lord seide to hym, Wel be thou, good seruaunt and feithful; for on fewe thingis thou hast be trewe, Y schal ordeyne thee on manye thingis; entre thou in to the ioye of thi lord.
24027	40	25	22	And he that hadde takun twey talentis, cam, and seide, Lord, thou bitokist to me twey besauntis; loo!
24028	40	25	23	Y haue wonnen ouer othir tweyne. His lord seide to him, Wel be thou, good seruaunt and trewe; for on fewe thingis thou hast be trewe, Y schal ordeyne thee on many thingis; entre thou in to the ioie of thi lord.
24029	40	25	24	But he that hadde takun o besaunt, cam, and seide, Lord, Y woot that thou art an hard man; thou repist where thou hast not sowe, and thou gederist togidere where thou hast not spred abrood;
24030	40	25	25	and Y dredynge wente, and hidde thi besaunt in the erthe; lo! thou hast that that is thin.
24031	40	25	26	His lord answeride, and seide to hym, Yuel seruaunt and slowe, wistist thou that Y repe where Y sewe not, and gadir to gidere where Y spredde not abrood?
24032	40	25	27	Therfor it bihofte thee to bitake my money to chaungeris, that whanne Y cam, Y schulde resseyue that that is myn with vsuris.
24033	40	25	28	Therfor take awei fro hym the besaunt, and yyue ye to hym that hath ten besauntis.
24034	40	25	29	For to euery man that hath me schal yyue, and he schal encreese; but fro hym that hath not, also that that hym semeth to haue, schal be taken awey fro him.
24035	40	25	30	And caste ye out the vnprofitable seruaunt in to vtmer derknessis; ther schal be wepyng, and gryntyng of teeth.
24036	40	25	31	Whanne mannus sone schal come in his maieste, and alle hise aungels with hym, thanne he schal sitte on the sege of his maieste;
24037	40	25	32	and alle folkis schulen be gaderid bifor hym,
24038	40	25	33	and he schal departe hem atwynne, as a scheeperde departith scheep from kidis; and he schal sette the scheep on his riythalf, and the kidis on the lefthalf.
24039	40	25	34	Thanne the kyng schal seie to hem, that schulen be on his riythalf, Come ye, the blessid of my fadir, take ye in possessioun the kyngdoom maad redi to you fro the makyng of the world.
24040	40	25	35	For Y hungride, and ye yauen me to ete; Y thristide, and ye yauen me to drynke; Y was herboreles, and ye herboriden me;
24041	40	25	36	nakid, and ye hiliden me; sijk, and ye visitiden me; Y was in prisoun, and ye camen to me.
24042	40	25	37	Thanne iust men schulen answere to hym, and seie, Lord, whanne siyen we thee hungry, and we fedden thee; thristi, and we yauen to thee drynk?
24043	40	25	38	and whanne sayn we thee herborles, and we herboreden thee; or nakid, and we hiliden thee?
24044	40	25	39	or whanne sayn we thee sijk, or in prisoun, and we camen to thee?
24045	40	25	40	And the kyng answerynge schal seie to hem, Treuli Y seie to you, as longe as ye diden to oon of these my leeste britheren, ye diden to me.
24046	40	25	41	Thanne the kyng schal seie also to hem, that schulen be on his lefthalf, Departe fro me, ye cursid, in to euerlastynge fijr, that is maad redi to the deuel and hise aungels.
24047	40	25	42	For Y hungride, and ye yauen not me to ete; Y thristide, and ye yauen not me to drynke;
24048	40	25	43	Y was herborles, and ye herberden not me; nakid, and ye keuerden not me; sijk, and in prisoun, and ye visitiden not me.
24049	40	25	44	Thanne and thei schulen answere to hym, and schulen seie, Lord, whanne sayn we thee hungrynge, or thristynge, or herboreles, or nakid, or sijk, or in prisoun, and we serueden not to thee?
24050	40	25	45	Thanne he schal answere to hem, and seie, Treuli Y seie to you, `hou longe ye diden not to oon of these leeste, nether ye diden to me.
24051	40	25	46	And these schulen goo in to euerlastynge turment; but the iust men schulen go in to euerlastynge lijf.
24052	40	26	1	And it was doon, whanne Jhesus hadde endid alle these wordis, he seide to hise disciplis,
24053	40	26	2	Ye witen, that aftir twei daies pask schal be maad, and mannus sone schal be bitakun to be crucified.
24054	40	26	3	Than the princes of prestis and the elder men of the puple were gaderid in to the halle of the prince of prestis, that was seid Cayfas,
24055	40	26	4	and maden a counsel to holde Jhesu with gile, and sle him;
24056	40	26	5	but thei seiden, Not in the haliday, lest perauenture noyse were maad in the puple.
24057	40	26	6	And whanne Jhesus was in Betanye, in the hous of Symount leprous,
24058	40	26	7	a womman that hadde a box of alabastre of precious oynement, cam to hym, and schedde out on the heed of hym restynge.
24059	40	26	8	And disciplis seynge hadden dedeyn, and seiden, Wherto this loss? for it myyte be seld for myche,
24060	40	26	9	and be youun to pore men.
24061	40	26	10	But Jhesus knewe, and seide to hem, What ben ye heuy to this womman? for sche hath wrouyt in me a good werk.
24062	40	26	11	For ye schulen euere haue pore men with you, but ye schulen not algatis haue me.
24063	40	26	12	This womman sendynge this oynement in to my bodi, dide to birie me.
24064	40	26	13	Treuli Y seie to you, where euer this gospel schal be prechid in al the world, it schal be seid, that sche dide this, in mynde of hym.
24065	40	26	14	Thanne oon of the twelue, that was clepid Judas Scarioth, wente forth to the princis of prestis,
24066	40	26	15	and seide to hem, What wolen ye yyue to me, and Y schal bitake hym to you? And thei ordeyneden to hym thretti pans of siluer.
24067	40	26	16	And fro that tyme he souyte oportunyte, to bitraye hym.
24068	40	26	17	And in the firste dai of therf looues the disciplis camen to Jhesu, and seiden, Where wolt thou we make redi to thee, to ete paske?
24069	40	26	18	Jhesus seide, Go ye into the citee to `sum man, and seie to hym, The maistir seith, My tyme is nyy; at thee Y make paske with my disciplis.
24070	40	26	19	And the disciplis diden, as Jhesus comaundide to hem; and thei maden the paske redi.
24071	40	26	20	And whanne euentid was come, he sat to mete with hise twelue disciplis.
24072	40	26	21	And he seide to hem, as thei eten, Treuli Y seie to you, that oon of you schal bitraye me.
24073	40	26	22	And thei ful sori bigunnen ech bi hym silf to seie, Lord, whether `Y am?
24074	40	26	23	And he answeride, and seide, He that puttith with me his hoond in the plater, schal bitraye me.
24075	40	26	24	Forsothe mannus sone goith, as it is writun of hym; but wo to that man, bi whom mannus sone schal be bitrayed; it were good to hym, if that man hadde not be borun.
24076	40	26	25	But Judas that bitraiede hym, answeride, seiynge, Maister, whether `Y am? Jhesus seide to hym, Thou hast seid.
24077	40	26	26	And while thei soupeden, Jhesus took breed, and blesside, and brak, and yaf to hise disciplis, and seide, Take ye, and ete; this is my body.
24078	40	26	27	And he took the cuppe, and dide thankyngis, and yaf to hem,
24079	40	26	28	and seide, Drynke ye alle herof; this is my blood of the newe testament, which schal be sched for many, in to remissioun of synnes.
24080	40	26	29	And Y seie to you, Y schal not drynke fro this tyme, of this fruyt of the vyne, in to that dai whanne Y schal drynke it newe with you, in the kyngdom of my fadir.
24081	40	26	30	And whanne the ympne was seid, thei wenten out in to the mount of Olyuete.
24082	40	26	31	Thanne Jhesus seide to hem, Alle ye schulen suffre sclaundre in me, in this niyt; for it is writun, Y schal smyte the scheeperde, and the scheep of the flok schulen be scaterid.
24083	40	26	32	But aftir that Y schal rise ayen, Y schal go bifore you in to Galilee.
24084	40	26	33	Petre answeride, and seide to hym, Thouy alle schulen be sclaundrid in thee, Y schal neuer be sclaundrid.
24085	40	26	34	Jhesus seide to him, Treuli Y seie to thee, for in this nyyt bifor the cok crowe, thries thou schalt denye me.
24086	40	26	35	Peter seide to him, Yhe, thouy it bihoue that Y die with thee, Y schal not denye thee. Also alle the disciplis seiden.
24087	40	26	36	Thanne Jhesus cam with hem in to a toun, that is seid Jessamanye. And he seide to his disciplis, Sitte ye here, the while Y go thider, and preye.
24088	40	26	37	And whanne he hadde take Peter, and twei sones of Zebedee, he bigan to be heuy and sori.
24089	40	26	38	Thanne he seide to hem, My soule is soreuful to the deeth; abide ye here, and wake ye with me.
24090	40	26	39	And he yede forth a litil, and felde doun on his face, preiynge, and seiynge, My fader, if it is possible, passe this cuppe fro me; netheles not as Y wole, but as thou wolt.
24091	40	26	40	And he cam to his disciplis, and foond hem slepynge. And he seide to Petir, So, whethir ye myyten not oon our wake with me?
24092	40	26	41	Wake ye, and preye ye, that ye entre not in to temptacioun; for the spirit is redi, but the fleisch is sijk.
24093	40	26	42	Eft the secounde tyme he wente, and preyede, seiynge, My fadir, if this cuppe may not passe, but Y drynke hym, thi wille be doon.
24094	40	26	43	And eftsoone he cam, and foond hem slepynge; for her iyen weren heuyed.
24095	40	26	44	And he lefte hem, and wente eftsoone, and preiede the thridde tyme, and seide the same word.
24096	40	26	45	Thanne he cam to his disciplis, and seide to hem, Slepe ye now, and reste ye; loo! the our hath neiyed, and mannus sone schal be takun in to the hondis of synneris;
24097	40	26	46	rise ye, go we; loo! he that schal take me, is nyy.
24098	40	26	47	Yit the while he spak, lo! Judas, oon of the twelue, cam, and with hym a greet cumpeny, with swerdis and battis, sent fro the princis of prestis, and fro the eldre men of the puple.
24099	40	26	48	And he that bitraiede hym, yaf to hem a tokene, and seide, Whom euer Y schal kisse, he it is; holde ye hym.
24100	40	26	49	And anoon he cam to Jhesu, and seid, Haile, maister;
24101	40	26	50	and he kisside hym. And Jhesus seide to hym, Freend, wherto art thou comun? Thanne thei camen niy, and leiden hoondis on Jhesu, and helden hym.
24102	40	26	51	And lo! oon of hem that weren with Jhesu, streiyte out his hoond, and drouy out his swerd; and he smoot the seruaunt of the prince of prestis, and kitte of his ere.
24103	40	26	52	Thanne Jhesus seide to hym, Turne thi swerd in to his place; for alle that taken swerd, schulen perische bi swerd.
24104	40	26	53	Whether gessist thou, that Y may not preie my fadir, and he schal yyue to me now mo than twelue legiouns of aungels?
24105	40	26	54	Hou thanne schulen the scriptures be fulfilled? for so it bihoueth to be doon.
24106	40	26	55	In that our Jhesus seide to the puple, As to a theef ye han gon out, with swerdis and battis, to take me; dai bi dai Y sat among you, and tauyt in the temple, and ye helden me not.
24107	40	26	56	But al this thing was don, that the scripturis of profetis schulden be fulfillid. Thanne alle the disciplis fledden, and leften hym.
24108	40	26	57	And thei helden Jhesu, and ledden hym to Cayfas, the prince of prestis, where the scribis and the Farisees, and the eldre men of the puple weren comun togidere.
24109	40	26	58	But Petir swede him afer, in to the halle of the prince of prestis; and he wente in, and sat with the seruauntis, to se the ende.
24110	40	26	59	And the prince of prestis, and al the counsel souyten fals witnessing ayens Jhesu, that thei schulden take hym to deeth;
24111	40	26	60	and thei founden not, whanne manye false witnessis weren comun. But at the laste, twei false witnessis camen,
24112	40	26	61	and seiden, `This seide, Y may distruye the temple of God, and after the thridde dai bilde it ayen.
24113	40	26	62	And the prince of prestis roos, and seide to hym, Answerist thou no thing to tho thingis, that these witnessen ayens thee?
24114	40	26	63	But Jhesus was stille. And the prince of prestis seide to hym, Y coniure thee bi lyuynge God, that thou seie to vs, if thou art Crist, the sone of God.
24115	40	26	64	Jhesus seide to him, Thou hast seid; netheles Y seie to you, `fro hennus forth ye schulen se mannus sone sittinge at the riythalf of the vertu of God, and comynge in the cloudis of heuene.
24116	40	26	65	Thanne the prince of prestis to-rente his clothis, and seide, He hath blasfemed; what yit han we nede to witnessis? lo! now ye han herd blasfemye; what semeth to you?
24117	40	26	66	And thei answeriden, and seiden, He is gilti of deeth.
24118	40	26	67	Thanne thei speten `in to his face, and smyten hym with buffatis; and othere yauen strokis with the pawme of her hondis in his face,
24119	40	26	68	and seide, Thou Crist, arede to vs, who is he that smoot thee?
24120	40	26	69	And Petir sat with outen in the halle; and a damysel cam to hym, and seide, Thou were with Jhesu of Galilee.
24121	40	26	70	And he denyede bifor alle men, and seide, Y woot not what thou seist.
24122	40	26	71	And whanne he yede out at the yate, another damysel say hym, and seide to hem that weren there, And this was with Jhesu of Nazareth.
24123	40	26	72	And eftsoone he denyede with an ooth, For I knewe not the man.
24124	40	26	73	And a litil aftir, thei that stooden camen, and seiden to Petir, Treuli thou art of hem; for thi speche makith thee knowun.
24125	40	26	74	Thanne he bigan to warie and to swere, that he knewe not the man. And anoon the cok crewe.
24126	40	26	75	And Petir bithouyte on the word of Jhesu, that he hadde seid, Bifore the cok crowe, thries thou schalt denye me. And he yede out, and wepte bitterli.
24127	40	27	1	But whanne the morowtid was comun, alle the princis of prestis, and the eldre men of the puple token counsel ayens Jhesu, that thei schulden take hym to the deeth.
24128	40	27	2	And thei ledden him boundun, and bitoken to Pilat of Pounce, iustice.
24129	40	27	3	Thanne Judas that bitraiede hym, say that he was dampned, he repentide, and brouyte ayen the thretti pans to the princis of prestis, and to the elder men of the puple,
24130	40	27	4	and seide, Y haue synned, bitraiynge riytful blood. And thei seiden, What to vs? bise thee.
24131	40	27	5	And whanne he hadde cast forth the siluer in the temple, he passide forth, and yede, and hongide hym silf with a snare.
24132	40	27	6	And the princis of prestis token the siluer, and seide, It is not leueful to putte it in to the treserie, for it is the prijs of blood.
24133	40	27	7	And whanne thei hadden take counsel, thei bouyten with it a feeld of a potter, in to biryyng of pilgrymys.
24134	40	27	8	Herfor thilke feeld is clepid Acheldemac, that is, a feeld of blood, in to this dai.
24135	40	27	9	Thanne that was fulfillid, that was seid bi the prophete Jeremye, seiynge, And thei han takun thretti pans, the prijs of a man preysid, whom thei preiseden of the children of Israel;
24136	40	27	10	and thei yauen hem in to a feeld of a potter, as the Lord hath ordenyd to me.
24137	40	27	11	And Jhesus stood bifor the domesman; and the iustice axide him, and seide, Art thou king of Jewis?
24138	40	27	12	Jhesus seith to hym, Thou seist. And whanne he was accusid of the princis of prestis, and of the eldere men of the puple, he answeride no thing.
24139	40	27	13	Thanne Pilat seith to him, Herist thou not, hou many witnessyngis thei seien ayens thee?
24140	40	27	14	And he answeride not `to hym ony word, so that the iustice wondride greetli.
24141	40	27	15	But for a solempne dai the iustice was wont to delyuere to the puple oon boundun, whom thei wolden.
24142	40	27	16	And he hadde tho a famous man boundun, that was seid Barrabas.
24143	40	27	17	Therfor Pilate seide to hem, whanne thei weren to gidere, Whom wolen ye, that Y delyuere to you? whether Barabas, or Jhesu, that is seid Crist?
24144	40	27	18	For he wiste, that bi enuye thei bitraieden hym.
24145	40	27	19	And while he sat for domesman, his wijf sente to hym, and seide, No thing to thee and to that iust man; for Y haue suffrid this dai many thingis for hym, bi a visioun.
24146	40	27	20	Forsothe the prince of prestis, and the eldere men counseiliden the puple, that thei schulden axe Barabas, but thei schulden distrye Jhesu.
24147	40	27	21	But the iustice answeride, and seide to hem, Whom of the tweyn wolen ye, that be delyuerit to you? And thei seiden, Barabas.
24148	40	27	22	Pilat seith to hem, What thanne schal Y do of Jhesu, that is seid Crist?
24149	40	27	23	Alle seien, `Be he crucified. The iustice seith to hem, What yuel hath he doon? And thei crieden more, and seiden, Be he crucified.
24150	40	27	24	And Pilat seynge that he profitide no thing, but that the more noyse was maad, took watir, and waischide hise hondis bifor the puple, and seide, Y am giltles of the blood of this riytful man; bise you.
24151	40	27	25	And al the puple answeride, and seide, His blood be on vs, and on oure children.
24152	40	27	26	Thanne he deliuerede to hem Barabas, but he took to hem Jhesu scourgid, to be crucified.
24153	40	27	27	Thanne knyytis of the iustice token Jhesu in the moot halle, and gadriden to hym al the cumpeny `of knyytis.
24154	40	27	28	And thei vnclothiden hym, and diden aboute hym a reed mantil;
24155	40	27	29	and thei foldiden a coroun of thornes, and putten on his heed, and a rehed in his riyt hoond; and thei kneliden bifore hym, and scornyden hym, and seiden, Heil, kyng of Jewis.
24156	40	27	30	And thei speten on hym, and tooken a rehed, and smoot his heed.
24157	40	27	31	And aftir that thei hadden scorned him, thei vnclothiden hym of the mantil, and thei clothiden hym with hise clothis, and ledden hym to `crucifien hym.
24158	40	27	32	And as thei yeden out, thei founden a man of Cirenen comynge fro the toun, Symont bi name; thei constreyneden hym to take his cross.
24159	40	27	33	And thei camen in to a place that is clepid Golgatha, that is, the place of Caluarie.
24160	40	27	34	And thei yauen hym to drynke wyne meynd with galle; and whanne he hadde tastid, he wolde not drynke.
24161	40	27	35	And aftir that thei hadden crucified hym, thei departiden his clothis, and kesten lotte, to fulfille that is seid bi the prophete, seiynge, Thei partiden to hem my clothis, and on my clooth thei kesten lott.
24162	40	27	36	And thei seten, and kepten him;
24163	40	27	37	and setten aboue his heed his cause writun, This is Jhesu of Nazareth, kyng of Jewis.
24164	40	27	38	Thanne twey theues weren crucified with hym, oon on the riythalf, and oon on the lefthalf.
24165	40	27	39	And men that passiden forth blasfemeden hym,
24166	40	27	40	mouynge her heedis, and seiynge, Vath to thee, that distriest the temple of God, and in the thridde dai bildist it ayen; saue thou thi silf; if thou art the sone of God, come doun of the cross.
24167	40	27	41	Also and princis of prestis scornynge, with scribis and elder men,
24168	40	27	42	seiden, He made othere men saaf, he may not make hym silf saaf; if he is kyng of Israel, come he now doun fro the crosse, and we bileuen to hym;
24169	40	27	43	he tristide in God; delyuer he hym now, if he wole; for he seide, That Y am Goddis sone.
24170	40	27	44	And the theues, that weren crucified with hym, vpbreididen hym of the same thing.
24171	40	27	45	But fro the sixte our derknessis weren maad on al the erthe, to the nynthe our.
24172	40	27	46	And aboute the nynthe our Jhesus criede with a greet vois, and seide, Heli, Heli, lamazabatany, that is, My God, my God, whi hast thou forsake me?
24173	40	27	47	And summen that stoden there, and herynge, seiden, This clepith Helye.
24174	40	27	48	And anoon oon of hem rennynge, took and fillide a spounge with vynegre, and puttide on a rehed, and yaf to hym to drynke.
24175	40	27	49	But othir seiden, Suffre thou; se we whether Helie come to deliuer hym.
24176	40	27	50	Forsothe Jhesus eftsoone criede with a greet voyce, and yaf vp the goost.
24177	40	27	51	And lo! the veil of the temple was to-rent in twey parties, fro the hiest to the lowest. And the erthe schoke, and stoonus weren cloue; and birielis weren openyd,
24178	40	27	52	and many bodies of seyntis that hadden slepte, rysen vp.
24179	40	27	53	And thei yeden out of her birielis, and aftir his resurreccioun thei camen in to the holi citee, and apperiden to many.
24180	40	27	54	And the centurien and thei that weren with hym kepinge Jhesu, whanne thei saien the erthe schakynge, and tho thingis that weren doon, thei dredden greetli,
24181	40	27	55	and seiden, Verili this was Goddis sone. And ther weren there many wymmen afer, that sueden Jhesu fro Galilee, and mynystriden to hym.
24182	40	27	56	Among whiche was Marie Magdalene, and Marie, the modir of James, and of Joseph, and the modir of Zebedees sones.
24183	40	27	57	But whanne the euenyng was come, ther cam a riche man of Armathi, Joseph bi name, and he was a disciple of Jhesu.
24184	40	27	58	He wente to Pilat, and axide the bodi of Jhesu.
24185	40	27	59	Thanne Pilat comaundide the bodie to be youun. And whanne the bodi was takun, Joseph lappide it in a clene sendel,
24186	40	27	60	and leide it in his newe biriel, that he hadde hewun in a stoon; and he walewide a greet stoon to the dore of the biriel, and wente awei.
24187	40	27	61	But Marie Maudelene and anothir Marie weren there, sittynge ayens the sepulcre.
24188	40	27	62	And on `the tother dai, that is aftir pask euen, the princis of prestis and the Farisees camen togidere to Pilat,
24189	40	27	63	and seiden, Sir, we han mynde, that thilke giloure seide yit lyuynge, Aftir thre daies Y schal rise ayen to lijf.
24190	40	27	64	Therfor comaunde thou, that the sepulcre be kept in to the thridde dai; lest hise disciplis comen, and stelen hym, and seie to the puple, He hath rise fro deeth; and the laste errour schal be worse than the formere.
24191	40	27	65	Pilat seide to hem, Ye han the kepyng; go ye, kepe ye as ye kunnen.
24192	40	27	66	And thei yeden forth, and kepten the sepulcre, markynge the stoon, with keperis.
24193	40	28	1	But in the euentid of the sabat, that bigynneth to schyne in the firste dai of the woke, Marie Mawdelene cam, and another Marie, to se the sepulcre.
24194	40	28	2	And lo! ther was maad a greet ertheschakyng; for the aungel of the Lord cam doun fro heuene, and neiyede, and turnede awei the stoon, and sat theron.
24195	40	28	3	And his lokyng was as leit, and hise clothis as snowe;
24196	40	28	4	and for drede of hym the keperis weren afeerd, and thei weren maad as deede men.
24197	40	28	5	But the aungel answeride, and seide to the wymmen, Nyle ye drede, for Y woot that ye seken Jhesu, that was crucified;
24198	40	28	6	he is not here, for he is risun, as he seide; come ye, and se ye the place, where the Lord was leid.
24199	40	28	7	And go ye soone, and seie ye to his disciplis, that he is risun. And lo! he schal go bifore you in to Galilee; there ye schulen se hym.
24200	40	28	8	Lo! Y haue biforseid to you. And thei wenten out soone fro the biriels, with drede and greet ioye, rennynge to telle to hise disciplis.
24201	40	28	9	And lo! Jhesus mette hem, and seide, Heile ye. And thei neiyeden, and heelden his feet, and worschipiden him.
24202	40	28	10	Thanne Jhesus seide to hem, Nyle ye drede; go ye, `telle ye to my britheren, that thei go in to Galile; there thei schulen se me.
24203	40	28	11	And whanne thei weren goon, lo! summe of the keperis camen in to the citee, and telden to the princis of prestis alle thingis that weren doon.
24204	40	28	12	And whanne thei weren gaderid togidere with the elder men, and hadden take her counseil, thei yauen to the kniytis miche monei, and seiden, Seie ye,
24205	40	28	13	that hise disciplis camen bi nyyt, and han stolen hym, while ye slepten.
24206	40	28	14	And if this be herd of the iustice, we schulen counseile hym, and make you sikir.
24207	40	28	15	And whanne the monei was takun, thei diden, as thei weren tauyt. And this word is pupplischid among the Jewis, til in to this day.
24208	40	28	16	And the enleuen disciplis wenten in to Galilee, in to an hille, where Jhesus hadde ordeyned to hem.
24209	40	28	17	And thei sayn hym, and worschipiden; but summe of hem doutiden.
24210	40	28	18	And Jhesus cam nyy, and spak to hem, and seide, Al power in heuene and in erthe is youun to me.
24211	40	28	19	Therfor go ye, and teche alle folkis, baptisynge hem in the name of the Fadir, and of the Sone, and of the Hooli Goost;
24212	40	28	20	techynge hem to kepe alle thingis, what euer thingis Y haue comaundid to you; and lo! Y am with you in alle daies, in to the ende of the world.
24213	41	1	1	The bigynnyng of the gospel of Jhesu Crist, the sone of God.
24214	41	1	2	As it is writun in Ysaie, the prophete, Lo! Y sende myn aungel bifor thi face, that schal make thi weie redi bifor thee.
24215	41	1	3	The vois of a crier in desert, Make ye redi the weie of the Lord, make ye hise paththis riyt.
24216	41	1	4	Joon was in desert baptisynge, and prechynge the baptym of penaunce, in to remissioun of synnes.
24217	41	1	5	And al the cuntre of Judee wente out to hym, and alle men of Jerusalem; and thei weren baptisid of hym in the flom Jordan, `and knoulechiden her synnes.
24218	41	1	6	And Joon was clothid with heeris of camels, and a girdil of skyn was about hise leendis; and he ete hony soukis, and wilde hony, and prechide,
24219	41	1	7	and seide, A stronger than Y schal come aftir me, and Y am not worthi to knele doun, and vnlace his schoone.
24220	41	1	8	Y haue baptisid you in watir; but he schal baptise you in the Hooli Goost.
24221	41	1	9	And it was don in tho daies, Jhesus cam fro Nazareth of Galilee, and was baptisid of Joon in Jordan.
24222	41	1	10	And anoon he wente up of the watir, and saye heuenes opened, and the Hooli Goost comynge doun as a culuer, and dwellynge in hym.
24223	41	1	11	And a vois was maad fro heuenes, Thou art my loued sone, in thee Y am plesid.
24224	41	1	12	And anoon the Spirit puttide hym forth in to deseert.
24225	41	1	13	And he was in deseert fourti daies and fourti nyytis, and was temptid of Sathanas, and he was with beestis, and aungels mynystriden to hym.
24226	41	1	14	But aftir that Joon was takun, Jhesus cam in to Galilee, and prechide the gospel of the kyngdoom of God,
24227	41	1	15	and seide, That the tyme is fulfillid, and the kyngdoom of God schal come nyy; do ye penaunce, and bileue ye to the gospel.
24228	41	1	16	And as he passide bisidis the see of Galilee, he say Symount, and Andrew, his brother, castynge her nettis in to the see; for thei weren fisscheris.
24229	41	1	17	And Jhesus seide to hem, Come ye aftir me; Y schal make you to be maad fisscheris of men.
24230	41	1	18	And anoon thei leften the nettis, and sueden hym.
24231	41	1	19	And he yede forth fro thennus a litil, and siy James of Zebedee, and Joon, his brother, in a boot makynge nettis.
24232	41	1	20	And anoon he clepide hem; and thei leften Zebedee, her fadir, in the boot with hiryd seruauntis, and thei suweden hym.
24233	41	1	21	And thei entriden in to Capharnaum, and anoon in the sabatys he yede in to a synagoge, and tauyte hem.
24234	41	1	22	And thei wondriden on his teching; for he tauyte hem, as he that hadde power, and not as scribis.
24235	41	1	23	And in the synagoge of hem was a man in an vnclene spirit, and he criede out,
24236	41	1	24	and seide, What to vs and to thee, thou Jhesu of Nazareth? hast thou come to distrie vs? Y woot that thou art the hooli of God.
24237	41	1	25	And Jhesus thretenede hym, and seide, Wex doumbe, and go out of the man.
24238	41	1	26	And the vnclene spirit debreidynge hym, and criynge with greet vois, wente out fro hym.
24239	41	1	27	And alle men wondriden, so that thei souyten with ynne hem silf, and seiden, What thing is this? what newe doctrine is this? for in power he comaundith to vnclene spiritis, and thei obeyen to hym.
24240	41	1	28	And the fame of hym wente forth anoon in to al the cuntree of Galilee.
24241	41	1	29	And anoon thei yeden out of the synagoge, and camen into the hous of Symount and of Andrewe, with James and Joon.
24242	41	1	30	And the modir of Symountis wijf lay sijk in fyueris; and anoon thei seien to hym of hyr.
24243	41	1	31	And he cam nyy, and areride hir, and whanne he hadde take hir hoond, anoon the feuer lefte hir, and sche seruede hem.
24244	41	1	32	But whanne the euentid was come, and the sonne was gon doun, thei brouyten to hym alle that weren of male ese, and hem that hadden fendis.
24245	41	1	33	And al the citee was gaderid at the yate.
24246	41	1	34	And he heelide many, that hadden dyuerse sijknessis, and he castide out many feendis, and he suffride hem not to speke, for thei knewen hym.
24247	41	1	35	And he roos ful eerli, and yede out, and wente in to a desert place, and preiede there.
24248	41	1	36	And Symount suede hym, and thei that weren with hym.
24249	41	1	37	And whanne thei hadden founde hym, thei seiden to hym, That alle men seken thee.
24250	41	1	38	And he seide to hem, Go we in to the next townes and citees, that Y preche also there, for her to Y cam.
24251	41	1	39	And he prechide in the synagogis of hem, and in al Galilee, and castide out feendis.
24252	41	1	40	And a leprouse man cam to hym, and bisouyte, `and knelide, and seide, If thou wolt, thou maist clense me.
24253	41	1	41	And Jhesus hadde mercy on hym, and streiyte out his hoond, and towchyde hym, and seide to hym, I wole, be thou maad cleene.
24254	41	1	42	And whanne he hadde seide this, anoon the lepre partyde awey fro hym, and he was clensyd.
24255	41	1	43	And Jhesus thretenede hym, and anoon Jhesus putte hym out,
24256	41	1	44	and seyde to hym, Se thou, seye to no man; but go, schewe thee to the pryncys of prestys, and offre for thi clensynge in to wytnessyng to hem, tho thingis that Moyses bad.
24257	41	1	45	And he yede out, and bigan to preche, and publische the word, so that now he myyte not go opynli in to the citee, but be withoutforth in desert placis; and thei camen to hym on alle sidis.
24258	41	2	1	And eft he entride in to Cafarnaum, aftir eiyte daies.
24259	41	2	2	And it was herd, that he was in an hous, and many camen to gidir, so that thei miyten not be in the hous, ne at the yate. And he spak to hem the word.
24260	41	2	3	And there camen to hym men that brouyten a man sijk in palesie, which was borun of foure.
24261	41	2	4	And whanne thei myyten not brynge hym to Jhesu for the puple, thei vnhileden the roof where he was, and openede it, and thei leten doun the bed in which the sijk man in palesie laye.
24262	41	2	5	And whanne Jhesus hadde seyn the feith of hem, he seide to the sijk man in palesie, Sone, thi synnes ben foryouun to thee.
24263	41	2	6	But there weren summe of the scribis sittynge, and thenkynge in her hertis,
24264	41	2	7	What spekith he thus? He blasfemeth; who may foryyue synnes, but God aloone?
24265	41	2	8	And whanne Jhesus hadde knowe this bi the Hooli Goost, that thei thouyten so with ynne hem silf, he seith to hem, What thenken ye these thingis in youre hertis?
24266	41	2	9	What is liyter to seie to the sijk man in palesie, Synnes ben foryouun to thee, or to seie, Ryse, take thi bed, and walke?
24267	41	2	10	But that ye wite that mannus sone hath power in erthe to foryyue synnes, he seide to the sijk man in palesie, Y seie to thee,
24268	41	2	11	ryse vp, take thi bed, and go in to thin hous.
24269	41	2	12	And anoon he roos vp, and whanne he hadde take the bed, he wente bifor alle men, so that alle men wondriden, and onoureden God, and seiden, For we seien neuer so.
24270	41	2	13	And he wente out eftsoone to the see, and al the puple cam to hym; and he tauyte hem.
24271	41	2	14	And whanne he passide, he saiy Leuy `of Alfei sittynge at the tolbothe, and he seide to hym, Sue me. And he roos, and suede hym.
24272	41	2	15	And it was doon, whanne he sat at the mete in his hous, many pupplicans and synful men saten togidere at the mete with Jhesu and hise disciplis; for there weren many that folewiden hym.
24273	41	2	16	And scribis and Farisees seynge, that he eet with pupplicans and synful men, seiden to hise disciplis, Whi etith and drynkith youre maystir with pupplicans and synneris?
24274	41	2	17	Whanne this was herd, Jhesus seide to hem, Hoole men han no nede to a leche, but thei that ben yuel at eese; for Y cam not to clepe iust men, but synneris.
24275	41	2	18	And the disciplis of Joon and the Farisees weren fastynge; and thei camen, and seien to hym, Whi fasten the disciplis of Joon, and the Farisees fasten, but thi disciplis fasten not?
24276	41	2	19	And Jhesus seide to hem, Whether the sones of sposailis moun faste, as longe as the spouse is with hem? As long tyme as thei haue the spouse with hem, thei moun not faste.
24277	41	2	20	But daies schulen come, whanne the spouse schal be takun awei fro hem, and thanne thei schulen faste in tho daies.
24278	41	2	21	No man sewith a patche of newe clooth to an elde clooth, ellis he takith awei the newe patche fro the elde, and a more brekyng is maad.
24279	41	2	22	And no man puttith newe wyn in to elde botelis, ellis the wyn schal breste the botels, and the wyn schal be sched out, and the botels schulen perische. But newe wyn schal be put into newe botels.
24280	41	2	23	And it was doon eftsoones, whanne the Lord walkid in the sabotis bi the cornes, and hise disciplis bigunnen to passe forth, and plucke eeris of the corn.
24281	41	2	24	And the Farisees seiden to hym, Lo! what thi disciplis doon in sabotis, that is not leeueful.
24282	41	2	25	And he seide to hem, Radden ye neuer what Dauid dide, whanne he hadde nede, and he hungride, and thei that weren with hym?
24283	41	2	26	Hou he wente in to the hous of God, vndur Abiathar, prince of prestis, and eete looues of proposicioun, which it was not leeueful to ete, but to preestis aloone, and he yaf to hem that weren with hym.
24284	41	2	27	And he seide to hem, The sabat is maad for man, and not a man for the sabat; and so mannus sone is lord also of the sabat.
24285	41	3	1	And he entride eftsoone in to the synagoge, and there was a man hauynge a drye hoond.
24286	41	3	2	And thei aspieden hym, if he helide in the sabatis, to accuse him.
24287	41	3	3	And he seide to the man that hadde a drie hoond, Rise in to the myddil.
24288	41	3	4	And he seith to hem, Is it leeueful to do wel in the sabatis, ether yuel? to make a soul saaf, ether to leese? And thei weren stille.
24289	41	3	5	And he biheeld hem aboute with wraththe, and hadde sorewe on the blyndnesse of her herte, and seith to the man, Hold forth thin hoond. And he helde forth, and his hoond was restorid to hym.
24290	41	3	6	Sotheli Farisees yeden out anoon, and maden a counsel with Erodians ayens hym, hou thei schulden lese hym.
24291	41	3	7	But Jhesus with hise disciplis wente to the see; and myche puple fro Galilee and Judee suede hym,
24292	41	3	8	and fro Jerusalem, and fro Ydume, and fro biyondis Jordan, and thei that weren aboute Tire and Sidon, a greet multitude, heringe the thingis that he dide, and cam to hym.
24293	41	3	9	And Jhesus seide to hise disciplis, that the boot schulde serue hym, for the puple, lest thei thristen hym;
24294	41	3	10	for he heelide many, so that thei felden fast to hym, to touche hym. And hou many euer hadde syknessis, and vnclene spirits,
24295	41	3	11	whanne thei seyen hym, felden doun to hym, and crieden, seiynge, Thou art the sone of God.
24296	41	3	12	And greetli he manasside hem, that thei schulden not make hym knowun.
24297	41	3	13	And he wente in to an hille, and clepide to hym whom he wolde; and thei camen to hym.
24298	41	3	14	And he made, that there weren twelue with hym, to sende hem to preche.
24299	41	3	15	And he yaf to hem pouwer to heele sijknessis, and to caste out feendis.
24300	41	3	16	And to Symount he yaf a name Petre, and he clepide James of Zebede and Joon,
24301	41	3	17	the brother of James, and he yaf to hem names Boenarges, that is, sones of thundryng.
24302	41	3	18	And he clepide Andrew and Filip, and Bartholomew and Matheu, and Thomas and James Alfey, and Thadee,
24303	41	3	19	and Symount Cananee, and Judas Scarioth, that bitraiede hym.
24304	41	3	20	And thei camen to an hous, and the puple cam togidere eftsoone, so that thei miyten not ete breed.
24305	41	3	21	And whanne his kynnysmen hadden herd, thei wenten out `to holde him; for thei seiden, that he is turned in to woodnesse.
24306	41	3	22	And the scribis that camen doun fro Jerusalem, seiden, That he hath Belsabub, and that in the prince of deuelis he castith out fendis.
24307	41	3	23	And he clepide hem togidir, and he seide to hem in parablis, Hou may Sathanas caste out Sathanas?
24308	41	3	24	And if a rewme be departid ayens it silf, thilke rewme may not stonde.
24309	41	3	25	And if an hous be disparpoilid on it silf, thilke hous may not stonde.
24310	41	3	26	And if Sathanas hath risun ayens hym silf, he is departid, and he schal not mowe stonde, but hath an ende.
24311	41	3	27	No man may go in to a stronge mannus hous, and take awey hise vessels, but he bynde first the stronge man, and thanne he schal spoile his hous.
24312	41	3	28	Treuli Y seie to you, that alle synnes and blasfemyes, bi whiche thei han blasfemed, schulen be foryouun to the sones of men.
24313	41	3	29	But he that blasfemeth ayens the Hooli Goost, hath not remissioun in to with outen ende, but he schal be gilty of euerlastynge trespas.
24314	41	3	30	For thei seiden, He hath an vnclene spirit.
24315	41	3	31	And his modir and britheren camen, and thei stoden withoutforth, and senten to hym, and clepiden hym.
24316	41	3	32	And the puple sat aboute hym; and thei seien to hym, Lo! thi modir and thi britheren with outforth seken thee.
24317	41	3	33	And he answeride to hem, and seide, Who is my modir and my britheren?
24318	41	3	34	And he bihelde thilke that saten aboute hym, and seide, Lo! my modir and my britheren.
24319	41	3	35	For who that doith the wille of God, he is my brothir, and my sistir, and modir.
24320	41	4	1	And eft Jhesus bigan to teche at the see; and myche puple was gaderid to hym, so that he wente in to a boot, and sat in the see, and al the puple was aboute the see on the loond.
24321	41	4	2	And he tauyte hem in parablis many thingis. And he seide to hem in his techyng,
24322	41	4	3	Here ye. Lo! a man sowynge goith out to sowe.
24323	41	4	4	And the while he sowith, summe seed felde aboute the weie, and briddis of heuene camen, and eeten it.
24324	41	4	5	Othere felde doun on stony places, where it had not myche erthe; and anoon it spronge vp, for it had not depnesse of erthe.
24325	41	4	6	And whanne the sunne roos vp, it welewide for heete, and it driede vp, for it hadde no roote.
24326	41	4	7	And othere felde doun in to thornes, and thornes sprongen vp, and strangliden it, and it yaf not fruyt.
24327	41	4	8	And other felde doun in to good loond, and yaf fruyt, springynge vp, and wexynge; and oon brouyte thretti foold, and oon sixti fold, and oon an hundrid fold.
24328	41	4	9	And he seide, He that hath eeris of heryng, here he.
24329	41	4	10	And whanne he was bi hym silf, tho twelue that weren with hym axiden hym to expowne the parable.
24330	41	4	11	And he seide to hem, To you it is youun to knowe the priuete of the kyngdom of God. But to hem that ben with outforth, alle thingis be maad in parablis, that thei seynge se,
24331	41	4	12	and se not, and thei herynge here and vnderstonde not; lest sum tyme thei be conuertid, and synnes be foryouun to hem.
24332	41	4	13	And he seide to hem, Knowe not ye this parable? and hou ye schulen knowe alle parablis?
24333	41	4	14	He that sowith, sowith a word.
24334	41	4	15	But these it ben that ben aboute the weie, where the word is sowun; and whanne thei han herd, anoon cometh Satanas, and takith awei the word that is sowun in her hertis.
24335	41	4	16	And in lijk maner ben these that ben sowun on stony placis, whiche whanne thei han herd the word, anoon thei taken it with ioye;
24336	41	4	17	and thei han not roote in hem silf, but thei ben lastynge a litil tyme; aftirward whanne tribulacioun risith, and persecucioun for the word, anoon thei ben sclaundrid.
24337	41	4	18	And ther ben othir that ben sowun in thornes; these it ben that heren the word,
24338	41	4	19	and disese of the world, and disseit of ritchessis, and othir charge of coueytise entrith, and stranglith the word, and it is maad with out fruyt.
24339	41	4	20	And these it ben that ben sowun on good lond, whiche heren the word, and taken, and maken fruyt, oon thritti fold, oon sixti fold, and oon an hundrid fold.
24340	41	4	21	And he seide to hem, Wher a lanterne cometh, that it be put vndur a buschel, or vndur a bed? nay, but that it be put on a candilstike?
24341	41	4	22	Ther is no thing hid, that schal not be maad opyn; nethir ony thing is pryuey, that schal not come in to opyn.
24342	41	4	23	If ony man haue eeris of heryng, here he.
24343	41	4	24	And he seide to hem, Se ye what ye heren. In what mesure ye meten, it schal be metun to you ayen, and be cast to you.
24344	41	4	25	For it schal be youun to hym that hath, and it schal be takun awei fro him that hath not, also that that he hath.
24345	41	4	26	And he seide, So the kingdom of God is, as if a man caste seede in to the erthe,
24346	41	4	27	and he sleepe, and it rise up niyt and dai, and brynge forth seede, and wexe faste, while he woot not.
24347	41	4	28	For the erthe makith fruyt, first the gras, aftirward the ere, and aftir ful fruyt in the ere.
24348	41	4	29	And whanne of it silf it hath brouyt forth fruyt, anoon he sendith a sikil, for repyng tyme is come.
24349	41	4	30	And he seide, To what thing schulen we likne the kyngdom of God? or to what parable schulen we comparisoun it?
24350	41	4	31	As a corne of seneuei, which whanne it is sowun in the erthe, is lesse than alle seedis that ben in the erthe;
24351	41	4	32	and whanne it is sprongun up, it waxith in to a tre, and is maad gretter than alle erbis; and it makith grete braunchis, so that briddis of heuene moun dwelle vndur the schadewe therof.
24352	41	4	33	And in many suche parablis he spak to hem the word, as thei myyten here;
24353	41	4	34	and he spak not to hem with out parable. But he expownede to hise disciplis alle thingis bi hemsilf.
24354	41	4	35	And he seide to hem in that dai, whanne euenyng was come, Passe we ayenward.
24355	41	4	36	And thei leften the puple, and token hym, so that he was in a boot; and othere bootys weren with hym.
24356	41	4	37	And a greet storm of wynde was maad, and keste wawis in to the boot, so that the boot was ful.
24357	41	4	38	And he was in the hyndir part of the boot, and slepte on a pilewe. And thei reisen hym, and seien to hym, Maistir, perteyneth it not to thee, that we perischen?
24358	41	4	39	And he roos vp, and manasside the wynde, and seide to the see, Be stille, wexe doumbe. And the wynde ceesside, and greet pesiblenesse was maad.
24359	41	4	40	And he seide to hem, What dreden ye? `Ye han no feith yit? And thei dredden with greet drede, and seiden `ech to other, Who, gessist thou, is this? for the wynde and the see obeschen to hym.
24360	41	5	1	And thei camen ouer the see in to the cuntree of Gerasenes.
24361	41	5	2	And aftir that he was goon out of the boot, anoon a man in an vncleene spirit ran out of birielis to hym.
24362	41	5	3	Which man hadde an hous in biriels, and nether with cheynes now myyte ony man bynde hym.
24363	41	5	4	For ofte tymes he was boundun in stockis and chaynes, and he hadde broke the chaynes, and hadde broke the stockis to smale gobetis, and no man myyte make hym tame.
24364	41	5	5	And euermore, nyyt and dai, in birielis and in hillis, he was criynge and betynge hym silf with stoonus.
24365	41	5	6	And he siy Jhesus afer, and ran, and worschipide hym.
24366	41	5	7	And he criede with greet voice, and seide, What to me and to thee, thou Jhesu, the sone of the hiyest God? Y coniure thee bi God, that thou turmente me not.
24367	41	5	8	And Jhesus seide to hym, Thou vnclene spirit, go out fro the man.
24368	41	5	9	And Jhesus axide hym, What is thi name? And he seith to hym, A legioun is my name; for we ben many.
24369	41	5	10	And he preiede Jhesu myche, that he schulde not putte hym out of the cuntrei.
24370	41	5	11	And there was there aboute the hille a greet flok of swyn lesewynge.
24371	41	5	12	And the spiritis preieden Jhesu, and seiden, Sende vs into the swyn, that we entre in to hem.
24372	41	5	13	And anoon Jhesus grauntide to hem. And the vnclene spiritis yeden out, and entriden in to the swyn, and with a greet birre the flocke was cast doun in to the see, a twei thousynde, and thei weren dreynt in the see.
24373	41	5	14	And thei that kepten hem, fledden, and tolden in to the citee, and in to the feeldis; and thei wenten out, to se what was don.
24374	41	5	15	And thei camen to Jhesu, and sayn hym that hadde be trauelid of the feend, syttynge clothid, and of hool mynde; and thei dredden.
24375	41	5	16	And thei that saien, hou it was don to hym that hadde a feend, and of the swyne, telden to hem.
24376	41	5	17	And thei bigunnen to preie hym, that he schulde go a wei fro her coostis.
24377	41	5	18	And whanne he yede up in to a boot, he that was trauelid of the deuel, bigan to preie hym, that he schulde be with hym.
24378	41	5	19	But Jhesus resseyuede hym not, but seide to hym, Go thou in to thin hous to thine, and telle to hem, hou grete thingis the Lord hath don to thee, and hadde merci of thee.
24379	41	5	20	And he wente forth, and bigan to preche in Decapoli, hou grete thingis Jhesus hadde don to hym; and alle men wondriden.
24380	41	5	21	And whanne Jhesus hadde gon vp in to the boot eftsoone ouer the see, myche puple cam togidere to him, and was aboute the see.
24381	41	5	22	And oon of the princis of synagogis, bi name Jayrus, cam, and siy hym, and felde doun at hise feet,
24382	41	5	23	and preyede hym myche, and seide, My douyter is nyy deed; come thou, putte thin hoond on her, that sche be saaf, and lyue.
24383	41	5	24	And he wente forth with hym, and myche puple suede hym, and thruste hym.
24384	41	5	25	And a womman hadde ben in the blodi fluxe twelue yeer,
24385	41	5	26	and hadde resseyued many thingis of ful many lechis, and hadde spendid al hir good, and was nothing amendid, but was rather the wors, whanne sche hadde herd of Jhesu,
24386	41	5	27	sche cam among the puple bihynde, and touchide his cloth.
24387	41	5	28	For sche seide, That if Y touche yhe his cloth, Y schal be saaf.
24388	41	5	29	And anoon the welle of hir blood was dried vp, and sche felide in bodi that sche was heelid of the siknesse.
24389	41	5	30	And anoon Jhesus knewe in hym silf the vertu that was goon out of hym, and turnede to the puple, and seide, Who touchide my clothis?
24390	41	5	31	And hise disciplis seiden to hym, Thou seest the puple thristynge thee, and seist, Who touchide me?
24391	41	5	32	And Jhesus lokide aboute to se hir that hadde don this thing.
