24392	41	5	33	And the womman dredde, and quakide, witynge that it was doon in hir, and cam, and felde doun bifor hym, and seide to hym al the treuthe.
24393	41	5	34	And Jhesus seide to hyr, Douytir, thi feith hath maad thee saaf; go in pees, and he thou hool of thi sijknesse.
24394	41	5	35	Yit while he spak, messangeris camen to the prince of the synagoge, and seien, Thi douytir is deed; what traueilist thou the maistir ferther?
24395	41	5	36	But whanne the word was herd that was seid, Jhesus seide to the prince of the synagoge, Nyle thou drede, oonli bileue thou.
24396	41	5	37	And he took no man to sue hym, but Petir, and James, and Joon, the brother of James.
24397	41	5	38	And thei camen in to the hous of the prince of the synagoge. And he saie noyse, and men wepynge and weilynge myche.
24398	41	5	39	And he yede ynne, and seide to hem, What ben ye troublid, and wepen? The damesel is not deed, but slepith.
24399	41	5	40	And thei scorneden hym. But whanne alle weren put out, he takith the fadir and the modir of the damesel, and hem that weren with hym, and thei entren, where the damysel laye.
24400	41	5	41	And he helde the hoond of the damesel, and seide to hir, Tabita, cumy, that is to seie, Damysel, Y seie to thee, arise.
24401	41	5	42	And anoon the damysel roos, and walkide; and sche was of twelue yeer. And thei weren abaischid with a greet stonying. And he comaundide to hem greetli, that no man schulde wite it.
24402	41	5	43	And he comaundide to yyue hir mete.
24403	41	6	1	And he yede out fro thennus, and wente in to his owne cuntre; and hise disciplis folewiden him.
24404	41	6	2	And whanne the sabat was come, Jhesus bigan to teche in a synagoge. And many herden, and wondriden in his techyng, and seiden, Of whennus to this alle these thingis? and what is the wisdom that is youun to hym, and siche vertues whiche ben maad bi hise hondis?
24405	41	6	3	Whether this is not a carpenter, the sone of Marie, the brother of James and of Joseph and of Judas and of Symount? whether hise sistris ben not here with vs? And thei weren sclaundrid in hym.
24406	41	6	4	And Jhesus seide to hem, That a profete is not without onoure, but in his owne cuntrey, and among his kynne, and in his hous.
24407	41	6	5	And he myyte not do there ony vertu, saue that he helide a fewe sijk men, leiynge on hem hise hoondis.
24408	41	6	6	And he wondride for the vnbileue of hem. And he wente aboute casteles on ech side, and tauyte.
24409	41	6	7	And he clepide togidere twelue, and bigan to sende hem bi two togidere; and yaf to hem power of vnclene spiritis,
24410	41	6	8	and comaundide hem, that thei schulde not take ony thing in the weie, but a yerde oneli, not a scrippe, ne breed, nether money in the girdil,
24411	41	6	9	but schod with sandalies, and that thei schulden not be clothid with twei cootis.
24412	41	6	10	And he seide to hem, Whidur euer ye entren in to an hous, dwelle ye there, til ye goon out fro thennus.
24413	41	6	11	And who euer resseyueth you not, ne herith you, go ye out fro thennus, and schake awei the powdir fro youre feet, in to witnessyng to hem.
24414	41	6	12	And thei yeden forth, and prechiden, that men schulden do penaunce.
24415	41	6	13	And thei castiden out many feendis, and anoyntiden with oyle many sijk men, and thei weren heelid.
24416	41	6	14	And kyng Eroude herde, for his name was maad opyn, and seide, That Joon Baptist hath risen ayen fro deeth, and therfor vertues worchen in hym.
24417	41	6	15	Othir seiden, That it is Helie; but othir seiden, That it is a profete, as oon of profetis.
24418	41	6	16	And whanne this thing was herd, Eroude seide, This Joon, whom Y haue biheedide, is risun ayen fro deeth.
24419	41	6	17	For thilke Eroude sente, and helde Joon, and boond hym in to prisoun, for Erodias, the wijf of Filip, his brothir; for he hadde weddid hir.
24420	41	6	18	For Joon seide to Eroude, It is not leueful to thee, to haue the wijf of thi brothir.
24421	41	6	19	And Erodias leide aspies to hym, and wolde sle hym, and myyte not.
24422	41	6	20	And Eroude dredde Joon, and knewe hym a iust man and hooli, and kepte hym. And Eroude herde hym, and he dide many thingis, and gladli herde hym.
24423	41	6	21	And whanne a couenable dai was fallun, Eroude in his birthdai made a soper to the princis, and tribunes, and to the grettest of Galilee.
24424	41	6	22	And whanne the douyter of thilke Erodias was comun ynne, and daunside, and pleside to Eroude, and also to men that saten at the mete, the kyng seide to the damysel, Axe thou of me what thou wolt, and Y schal yyue to thee.
24425	41	6	23	And he swore to hir, That what euer thou axe, Y schal yyue to thee, thouy it be half my kyngdom.
24426	41	6	24	And whanne sche hadde goon out, sche seide to hir modir, What schal Y axe? And sche seide, The heed of Joon Baptist.
24427	41	6	25	And whanne sche was comun ynne anoon with haast to the kyng, sche axide, and seide, Y wole that anoon thou yyue to me in a dische the heed of Joon Baptist.
24428	41	6	26	And the kyng was sori for the ooth, and for men that saten togidere at the meete he wolde not make hir sori;
24429	41	6	27	but sente a manqueller and comaundide, that Joones heed were brouyt in a dissche. And he bihedide hym in the prisoun,
24430	41	6	28	and brouyte his heed in a disch, and yaf it to the damysel, and the damysel yaf to hir modir.
24431	41	6	29	And whanne this thing was herd, hise disciplis camen, and token his bodi, and leiden it in a biriel.
24432	41	6	30	And the apostlis camen togidere to Jhesu, and telden to hym alle thingis, that thei hadden don, and tauyt.
24433	41	6	31	And he seide to hem, Come ye bi you silf in to a desert place; and reste ye a litil. For there were many that camen, and wenten ayen, and thei hadden not space to ete.
24434	41	6	32	And thei yeden in to a boot, and wenten in to a desert place bi hem silf.
24435	41	6	33	And thei sayn hem go awei, and many knewen, and thei wenten afoote fro alle citees, and runnen thidur, and camen bifor hem.
24436	41	6	34	And Jhesus yede out, and saiy myche puple, and hadde reuth on hem, for thei weren as scheep not hauynge a scheepherd. And he bigan to teche hem many thingis.
24437	41	6	35	And whanne it was forth daies, hise disciplis camen, and seiden, This is a desert place, and the tyme is now passid;
24438	41	6	36	lete hem go in to the nexte townes and villagis, to bie hem meete to ete.
24439	41	6	37	And he answeride, and seide to hem, Yyue ye to hem to ete. And thei seiden to hym, Go we, and bie we looues with two hundrid pens, and we schulen yyue to hem to ete.
24440	41	6	38	And he seith to hem, Hou many looues han ye? Go ye, and se. And whanne thei hadden knowe, thei seien, Fyue, and two fischis.
24441	41	6	39	And he comaundide to hem, that thei schulden make alle men sitte to mete bi cumpanyes, on greene heye.
24442	41	6	40	And thei saten doun bi parties, bi hundridis, and bi fifties.
24443	41	6	41	And whanne he hadde take the fyue looues, and twei fischis, he biheelde in to heuene, and blesside, and brak looues, and yaf to hise disciplis, that thei schulden sette bifor hem. And he departide twei fischis to alle;
24444	41	6	42	and alle eeten, and weren fulfillid.
24445	41	6	43	And thei token the relifs of brokun metis, twelue cofyns ful, and of the fischis.
24446	41	6	44	And thei that eeten, weren fyue thousynde of men.
24447	41	6	45	And anoon he maad hise disciplis to go up in to a boot, to passe bifor hym ouer the se to Bethsaida, the while he lefte the puple.
24448	41	6	46	And whanne he hadde left hem, he wente in to an hille, to preye.
24449	41	6	47	And whanne it was euen, the boot was in the myddil of the see, and he aloone in the loond;
24450	41	6	48	and he say hem trauelynge in rowyng; for the wynde was contrarie to hem. And aboute the fourthe wakynge of the nyyt, he wandride on the see, and cam to hem, and wolde passe hem.
24451	41	6	49	And as thei sayn hym wandrynge on the see, thei gessiden that it weren a fantum, and crieden out;
24452	41	6	50	for alle sayn hym, and thei weren afraied. And anoon he spak with hem, and seide to hem, Triste ye, Y am; nyle ye drede.
24453	41	6	51	And he cam vp to hem in to the boot, and the wynde ceesside. And thei wondriden more `with ynne hem silf;
24454	41	6	52	for thei vndurstoden not of the looues; for her herte was blyndid.
24455	41	6	53	And whanne thei weren passid ouer the see, thei camen in to the lond of Genasareth, and settiden to loond.
24456	41	6	54	And whanne thei weren gon out of the boot, anoon thei knewen hym.
24457	41	6	55	And thei ranne thorou al that cuntre, and bigunnen to brynge sijk men in beddis on eche side, where thei herden that he was.
24458	41	6	56	And whidur euer `he entride in to villagis, ethir in to townes, or in to citees, thei setten sijk men in stretis, and preiden hym, that thei schulden touche namely the hemme of his cloth; and hou many that touchiden hym, weren maad saaf.
24459	41	7	1	And the Farisees and summe of the scribis camen fro Jerusalem togidir to hym.
24460	41	7	2	And whanne thei hadden seen summe of hise disciplis ete breed with vnwaisschen hoondis, thei blameden.
24461	41	7	3	The Farisees and alle the Jewis eten not, but thei waisschen ofte her hoondis, holdynge the tradiciouns of eldere men.
24462	41	7	4	And whanne thei turnen ayen fro chepyng, thei eten not, but thei ben waisschen; and many other thingis ben, `that ben taken `to hem to kepe, wasschyngis of cuppis, and of watir vessels, and of vessels of bras, and of beddis.
24463	41	7	5	And Farisees and scribis axiden hym, and seiden, Whi gon not thi disciplis aftir the tradicioun of eldere men, but with vnwasschen hondis thei eten breed?
24464	41	7	6	And he answeride, and seide to hem, Ysaie prophesiede wel of you, ypocritis, as it is writun, This puple worschipith me with lippis, but her herte is fer fro me;
24465	41	7	7	and in veyn thei worschipen me, techinge the doctrines and the heestis of men.
24466	41	7	8	For ye leeuen the maundement of God, and holden the tradiciouns of men, wasschyngis of watir vessels, and of cuppis; and many othir thingis lijk to these ye doon.
24467	41	7	9	And he seide to hem, Wel ye han maad the maundement of God voide, `to kepe youre tradicioun.
24468	41	7	10	For Moyses seide, Worschipe thi fadir and thi modir; and he that cursith fadir or modir, die he by deeth.
24469	41	7	11	But ye seien, If a man seie to fadir or modir, Corban, that is, What euer yifte is of me, it schal profite to thee;
24470	41	7	12	and ouer ye suffren not hym do ony thing to fadir or modir,
24471	41	7	13	and ye breken the word of God bi youre tradicioun, that ye han youun; and ye don many suche thingis.
24472	41	7	14	And he eftsoone clepide the puple, and seide to hem, Ye alle here me, and vndurstonde.
24473	41	7	15	No thing that is withouten a man, that entrith in to hym, may defoule him; but tho thingis that comen forth of a man, tho it ben that defoulen a man.
24474	41	7	16	If ony man haue eeris of hering, here he.
24475	41	7	17	And whanne he was entrid in to an hous, fro the puple, hise disciplis axiden hym the parable.
24476	41	7	18	And he seide to hem, Ye ben vnwise also. Vndurstonde ye not, that al thing without forth that entreth in to a man, may not defoule hym?
24477	41	7	19	for it hath not entrid in to his herte, but in to the wombe, and bynethe it goith out, purgynge alle metis.
24478	41	7	20	But he seide, The thingis that gon out of a man, tho defoulen a man.
24479	41	7	21	For fro with ynne, of the herte of men comen forth yuel thouytis, auowtries,
24480	41	7	22	fornycaciouns, mansleyingis, theftis, auaricis, wickidnessis, gile, vnchastite, yuel iye, blasfemyes, pride, foli.
24481	41	7	23	Alle these yuels comen forth fro with ynne, and defoulen a man.
24482	41	7	24	And Jhesus roos vp fro thennus, and wente in to the coostis of Tyre and of Sidon. And he yede in to an hous, and wolde that no man wiste; and he myyte not be hid.
24483	41	7	25	For a womman, anoon as sche herd of hym, whos douytir hadde an vnclene spirit, entride, and fel doun at hise feet.
24484	41	7	26	And the womman was hethen, of the generacioun of Sirofenyce. And sche preiede hym, that he wolde caste out a deuel fro hir douyter.
24485	41	7	27	And he seide to hir, Suffre thou, that the children be fulfillid first; for it is not good to take the breed of children, and yyue to houndis.
24486	41	7	28	And sche answeride, and seide to him, Yis, Lord; for litil whelpis eten vndur the bord, of the crummes of children.
24487	41	7	29	And Jhesus seide to hir, Go thou, for this word the feend wente out of thi douytir.
24488	41	7	30	And whanne sche was gon in to hir hous home, sche foonde the damysel ligynge on the bed, and the deuel gon out fro hir.
24489	41	7	31	And eftsoones Jhesus yede out fro the coostis of Tire, and cam thorou Sidon to the see of Galilee, bitwixe the myddil of the coostis of Decapoleos.
24490	41	7	32	And thei bryngen to hym a man deef and doumbe, and preieden hym to leye his hoond on hym.
24491	41	7	33	And he took hym asidis fro the puple, and puttide hise fyngris in to hise eris; and he spetide, and touchide his tonge.
24492	41	7	34	And he bihelde in to heuene, and sorewide with ynne, and seide, Effeta, that is, Be thou openyd.
24493	41	7	35	And anoon hise eris weren openyd, and the boond of his tunge was vnboundun, and he spak riytli.
24494	41	7	36	And he comaundide to hem, that thei schulden seie to no man; but hou myche he comaundide to hem, so myche more thei prechiden,
24495	41	7	37	and bi so myche more thei wondriden, and seiden, He dide wel alle thingis, and he made deef men to here, and doumbe men to speke.
24496	41	8	1	In tho daies eft, whanne myche puple was with Jhesu, and hadden not what thei schulden ete, whanne hise disciplis weren clepid togidir,
24497	41	8	2	he seide to hem, I haue reuth on the puple, for lo! now the thridde dai thei abiden me, and han not what to ete;
24498	41	8	3	and if Y leeue hem fastynge in to her hous, thei schulen faile in the weie; for summe of hem camen fro fer.
24499	41	8	4	And hise disciplis answerden to hym, Wherof schal a man mowe fille hem with looues here in wildirnesse?
24500	41	8	5	And he axide hem, Hou many looues han ye?
24501	41	8	6	Whiche seiden, Seuene. And he comaundide the puple to sitte doun on the erthe. And he took the seuene looues, and dide thankyngis, and brak, and yaf to hise disciplis, that thei schulden sette forth. And thei settiden forth to the puple.
24502	41	8	7	And thei hadden a few smale fischis; and he blesside hem, and comaundide, that thei weren sette forth.
24503	41	8	8	And thei eten, and weren fulfillid; and thei token vp that that lefte of relifs, seuene lepis.
24504	41	8	9	And thei that eeten, weren as foure thousynde of men; and he lefte hem.
24505	41	8	10	And anoon he wente vp in to a boot, with hise disciplis, and cam in to the coostis of Dalmamytha.
24506	41	8	11	And the Farisees wenten out, and bigunnen to dispuyte with hym, and axiden a tokne of hym fro heuene, and temptiden hym.
24507	41	8	12	And he sorewynge `with ynne in spirit, seide, What sekith this generacioun a tokne? Treuli Y seie to you, a tokene schal not be youun to this generacioun.
24508	41	8	13	And he lefte hem, and wente vp eftsoone in to a boot, and wente ouer the see.
24509	41	8	14	And thei foryaten to take breed, and thei hadden not with hem but o loof in the boot.
24510	41	8	15	And he comaundide hem, and seide, Se ye, and `be war of the sowre dowy of Farisees, and of the sowrdowy of Eroude.
24511	41	8	16	And thei thouyten, and seiden oon to anothir, For we han not looues.
24512	41	8	17	And whanne this thing was knowun, Jhesus seide to hem, What thenken ye, for ye han not looues? Yit ye knowun not, ne vndurstonden; yit ye han youre herte blyndid.
24513	41	8	18	Ye hauynge iyen, seen not, and ye hauynge eeris, heren not; nethir ye han mynde,
24514	41	8	19	whanne Y brak fyue looues among fyue thousynde, and hou many cofynes ful of brokun meete `ye tokun vp? Thei seien to hym, Twelue.
24515	41	8	20	Whanne also seuene looues among foure thousynde of men, hou many lepis of brokun mete tokun ye vp?
24516	41	8	21	And thei seien to hym, Seuene. And he seide to hem, Hou vndurstonden ye not yit?
24517	41	8	22	And thei camen to Bethsaida, and thei bryngen to hym a blynde man, and thei preieden hym, that he schulde touche hym.
24518	41	8	23	And whanne he hadde take the blynde mannus hoond, he ledde hym out of the street, and spete in to hise iyen, and sette hise hoondis on hym; and he axide hym, if he saye ony thing.
24519	41	8	24	And he bihelde, and seide, Y se men as trees walkynge.
24520	41	8	25	Aftirward eftsoones he sette hise hondis on hise iyen, and he bigan to see, and he was restorid, so that he saiy cleerli alle thingis.
24521	41	8	26	And he sente hym in to his hous, and seide, Go in to thin hous; and if thou goist in to the streete, seie to no man.
24522	41	8	27	And Jhesus entride and hise disciplis in to the castels of Cesarye of Philip. And in the weie he axide hise disciplis, and seide to hem, Whom seien men that Y am?
24523	41	8	28	Whiche answeriden to hym, and seiden, Summen seien, Joon Baptist; other seien, Heli; and other seien, as oon of the prophetis.
24524	41	8	29	Thanne he seith to hem, But whom seien ye that Y am? Petre answeride, and seide to hym, Thou art Crist.
24525	41	8	30	And he chargide hem, that thei schulden not seie of hym to ony man.
24526	41	8	31	And he bigan to teche hem, that it bihoueth mannus sone to suffre many thingis, and to be repreued of the elder men, and of the hiyest prestis, and the scribis, and to be slayn, and aftir thre dayes, to rise ayen.
24527	41	8	32	And he spak pleynli the word. And Peter took hym, and bigan to blame hym, and seide, Lord, be thou merciful to thee, for this schal not be.
24528	41	8	33	And he turnede, and saiy hise disciplis, and manasside Petir, and seide, Go after me, Satanas; for thou sauerist not tho thingis that ben of God, but tho thingis that ben of men.
24529	41	8	34	And whanne the puple was clepid togidere, with hise disciplis, he seide to hem, If ony man wole come after me, denye he hym silf, and take his cros, and sue he me.
24530	41	8	35	For he that wole make saaf his lijf, schal leese it; and he that leesith his lijf for me, and for the gospel, schal make it saaf.
24531	41	8	36	For what profitith it to a man, if he wynne al the world, and do peiryng to his soule?
24532	41	8	37	or what chaunging schal a man yyue for his soule?
24533	41	8	38	But who that knoulechith me and my wordis in this generacioun avowtresse and synful, also mannus sone schal knouleche him, whanne he schal come in the glorie of his fadir, with his aungels.
24534	41	8	39	And he seide to hem, Treuli Y seie to you, that there ben summen stondynge here, whiche schulen not taste deth, til thei seen the rewme of God comynge in vertu.
24535	41	9	1	And aftir sixe daies Jhesus took Petre, and James, and Joon, and ledde hem bi hem silf aloone in to an hiy hille; and he was transfigurid bifor hem.
24536	41	9	2	And hise clothis weren maad ful schynynge and white as snow, whiche maner white clothis a fuller may not make on erthe.
24537	41	9	3	And Helie with Moises apperide to hem, and thei spaken with Jhesu.
24538	41	9	4	And Petre answeride, and seide to Jhesu, Maister, it is good vs to be here; and make we here thre tabernaclis, oon to thee, oon to Moyses, and oon to Helie.
24539	41	9	5	For he wiste not what he schulde seie; for thei weren agaste bi drede.
24540	41	9	6	And ther was maad a cloude overschadewynge hem; and a vois cam of the cloude, and seide, This is my moost derworth sone, here ye hym.
24541	41	9	7	And anoon thei bihelden aboute, and sayn no more ony man, but Jhesu oonli with hem.
24542	41	9	8	And whanne thei camen doun fro the hille, he comaundide hem, that thei schulden not telle to ony man tho thingis that thei hadden seen, but whanne mannus sone hath risun ayen fro deeth.
24543	41	9	9	And thei helden the word at hem silf, sekynge what this schulde be, whanne he hadde risun ayen fro deth.
24544	41	9	10	And thei axiden hym, and seiden, What thanne seien Farisees and scribis, for it bihoueth `Helie to come first.
24545	41	9	11	And he answeride, and seide to hem, Whanne Helie cometh, he schal first restore alle thingis; and as it is writun of mannus sone, that he suffre many thingis, and be dispisid.
24546	41	9	12	And Y seie to you, that Helie is comun, and thei diden to hym what euer thingis thei wolden, as it is writun of hym.
24547	41	9	13	And he comynge to hise disciplis, saiy a greet cumpany aboute hem, and scribis disputynge with hem.
24548	41	9	14	And anoon al the puple seynge Jhesu, was astonyed, and thei dredden; and thei rennynge gretten hym.
24549	41	9	15	And he axide hem, What disputen ye among you?
24550	41	9	16	And oon of the cumpany answerde, and seide, Mayster, Y haue brouyt to thee my sone, that hath a doumbe spirit; and where euer he takith hym,
24551	41	9	17	he hurtlith hym doun, and he fometh, and betith togidir with teeth, and wexith drye. And Y seide to thi disciplis, that thei schulden caste hym out, and thei myyten not.
24552	41	9	18	And he answeride to hem, and seide, A! thou generacioun out of bileue, hou longe schal Y be among you, hou longe schal Y suffre you? Brynge ye hym to me.
24553	41	9	19	And thei brouyten hym. And whanne he had seyn him, anoon the spirit troublide him; and was throw doun to grounde, and walewide, and fomede.
24554	41	9	20	And he axide his fadir, Hou longe `is it, sith this `hath falle to hym? And he seide, Fro childhode;
24555	41	9	21	and ofte he hath put hym in to fier, and in to watir, to leese hym; but if thou maiste ony thing, helpe vs, and haue merci on vs.
24556	41	9	22	And Jhesus seide to hym, If thou maiste bileue, alle thingis ben possible to man that bileueth.
24557	41	9	23	And anoon the fadir of the child criede with teeris, and seide, Lord, Y bileue; Lord, helpe thou myn vnbileue.
24558	41	9	24	And whanne Jhesus hadde seyn the puple rennynge togidere, he manasside the vnclene spirit, and seide to hym, Thou deef and doumbe spirit, Y comaunde thee, go out fro hym, and entre no more in to hym.
24559	41	9	25	And he criynge, and myche to breidynge him, wente out fro hym; and he was maad as deed, so that many seiden, that he was deed.
24560	41	9	26	And Jhesus helde his hoond, and lifte hym vp; and he roos.
24561	41	9	27	And whanne he hadde entrid in to an hous, hise disciplis axiden hym priueli, Whi myyten not we caste hym out?
24562	41	9	28	And he seide to hem, This kynde in no thing may go out, but in preier and fastyng.
24563	41	9	29	And thei yeden fro thennus, and wente forth in to Galile; and thei wolden not, that ony man wiste.
24564	41	9	30	And he tauyte hise disciplis, and seide to hem, For mannus sone schal be bitrayed in to the hondis of men, and thei schulen sle hym, and he slayn schal ryse ayen on the thridde day.
24565	41	9	31	And thei knewen not the word, and dredden to axe hym.
24566	41	9	32	And thei camen to Cafarnaum. And whanne thei weren in the hous, he axide hem, What tretiden ye in the weie?
24567	41	9	33	And thei weren stille; for thei disputiden among hem in the weie, who of hem schulde be grettest.
24568	41	9	34	And he sat, and clepide the twelue, and seide to hem, If ony man wole be the firste among you, he schal be the laste of alle, and the mynyster of alle.
24569	41	9	35	And he took a child, and sette hym in the myddil of hem; and whanne he hadde biclippid hym, he seide to hem,
24570	41	9	36	Who euer resseyueth oon of such children in my name, he resseyueth me; and who euer resseyueth me, he resseyueth not me aloone, but hym that sente me.
24571	41	9	37	Joon answeride to hym, and seide, Maister, we sayn oon castynge out feendis in thi name, which sueth not vs, and we han forbodun hym.
24572	41	9	38	And Jhesus seide, Nyle ye forbede him; for ther is no man that doith vertu in my name, and may soone speke yuel of me.
24573	41	9	39	He that is not ayens vs, is for vs.
24574	41	9	40	And who euer yyueth you a cuppe of coold water to drynke in my name, for ye ben of Crist, treuli Y seie to you, he schal not leese his mede.
24575	41	9	41	And who euer schal sclaundre oon of these litle that bileuen in me, it were betere to hym that a mylne stoon `of assis were don aboute his necke, and he were cast in to the see.
24576	41	9	42	And if thin hoond sclaundre thee, kitte it awey; it is betere to thee to entre feble in to lijf, than haue two hondis, and go in to helle, in to fier that neuer schal be quenchid,
24577	41	9	43	where the worm of hem dieth not, and the fier is not quenchid.
24578	41	9	44	And if thi foote sclaundre thee, kitte it of; it is betere to thee to entre crokid in to euerlastynge lijf, than haue twei feet, and be sent in to helle of fier, that neuer schal be quenchid,
24579	41	9	45	where the worme of hem dieth not, and the fier is not quenchid.
24580	41	9	46	That if thin iye sclaundre thee, cast it out; it is betere to thee to entre gogil iyed in to the reume of God, than haue twey iyen, and be sent in to helle of fier, where the worme of hem dieth not,
24581	41	9	47	and the fier is not quenchid.
24582	41	9	48	And euery man schal be saltid with fier, and euery slayn sacrifice schal be maad sauery with salt.
24583	41	9	49	Salt is good; if salt be vnsauery, in what thing schulen ye make it sauery? Haue ye salt among you, and haue ye pees among you.
24584	41	10	1	And Jhesus roos vp fro thennus, and cam in to the coostis of Judee ouer Jordan; and eftsoones the puple cam togidere to hym, and as he was wont, eftsoone he tauyte hem.
24585	41	10	2	And the Farisees camen, and axiden hym, Whether it be leueful to a man to leeue his wijf? and thei temptiden hym.
24586	41	10	3	And he answeride, and seide to hem, What comaundide Moises to you?
24587	41	10	4	And thei seiden, Moises suffride to write a libel of forsaking, and to forsake.
24588	41	10	5	`To whiche Jhesus answeride, and seide, For the hardnesse of youre herte Moises wroot to you this comaundement.
24589	41	10	6	But fro the bigynnyng of creature God made hem male and female;
24590	41	10	7	and seide, For this thing a man schal leeue his fadir and modir,
24591	41	10	8	and schal drawe to hys wijf, and thei schulen be tweyne in o flesch. And so now thei ben not tweyne, but o flesch.
24592	41	10	9	Therfor that thing that God ioynede togidere, no man departe.
24593	41	10	10	And eftsoone in the hous hise disciplis axiden hym of the same thing.
24594	41	10	11	And he seide to hem, Who euer leeuith his wijf, and weddith another, he doith auowtri on hir.
24595	41	10	12	And if the wijf leeue hir housebonde, and be weddid to another man, sche doith letcherie.
24596	41	10	13	And thei brouyten to hym litle children, that he schulde touche hem; and the disciplis threteneden the men, that brouyten hem.
24597	41	10	14	And whanne Jhesus hadde seyn hem, he baar heuy, and seide to hem, Suffre ye litle children to come to me, and forbede ye hem not, for of suche is the kyngdom of God.
24598	41	10	15	Treuli Y seie to you, who euer resseyueth not the kyngdom of God as a litil child, he schal not entre in to it.
24599	41	10	16	And he biclippide hem, and leide hise hondis on hem, and blisside hem.
24600	41	10	17	And whanne Jhesus was gon out in the weie, a man ranne bifore, and knelide bifor hym, and preiede hym, and seide, Good maister, what schal Y do, that Y resseyue euerlastynge lijf?
24601	41	10	18	And Jhesus seide to hym, What seist thou, that Y am good? Ther is no man good, but God hym silf.
24602	41	10	19	Thou knowist the comaundementis, do thou noon auowtrie, `sle not, stele not, seie not fals witnessyng, do no fraude, worschipe thi fadir and thi modir.
24603	41	10	20	And he answeride, and seide to hym, Maister, Y haue kept alle these thingis fro my yongthe.
24604	41	10	21	And Jhesus bihelde hym, and louede hym, and seide to hym, O thing faileth to thee; go thou, and sille alle thingis that thou hast, and yyue to pore men, and thou schalt haue tresoure in heuene; and come, sue thou me.
24605	41	10	22	And he was ful sori in the word, and wente awei mornyng, for he hadde many possessiouns.
24606	41	10	23	And Jhesus bihelde aboute, and seide to hise disciplis, Hou hard thei that han ritchessis schulen entre in to the kyngdom of God.
24607	41	10	24	And the disciplis weren astonyed in hise wordis. And Jhesus eftsoone answeride, and seide `to hem, Ye litle children, hou hard it is for men that tristen in ritchessis to entre in to the kyngdom of God.
24608	41	10	25	It is liyter a camele to passe thorou a nedlis iye, than a riche man to entre in to the kyngdom of God.
24609	41	10	26	And thei wondriden more, and seiden among hem silf, And who may be sauyd?
24610	41	10	27	And Jhesus bihelde hem, and seide, Anentis men it is impossible, but not anentis God; for alle thingis ben possible anentis God.
24611	41	10	28	And Petir bigan to seie to hym, Lo! we han left alle thingis, and han sued thee.
24612	41	10	29	Jhesus answeride, and seide, Treuli Y seie to you, ther is no man that leeueth hous, or britheren, or sistris, or fadir, or modir, or children, or feeldis for me and for the gospel,
24613	41	10	30	which schal not take an hundrid fold so myche now in this tyme, housis, and britheren, and sistris, and modris, and children, and feeldis, with persecuciouns, and in the world to comynge euerlastynge lijf.
24614	41	10	31	But many schulen be, the firste the last, and the last the firste.
24615	41	10	32	And thei weren in the weie goynge vp to Jerusalem; and Jhesus wente bifor hem, and thei wondriden, and foleweden, and dredden. And eftsoone Jhesus took the twelue, and bigan to seie to hem, what thingis weren to come to hym.
24616	41	10	33	For lo! we stien to Jerusalem, and mannus sone schal be bitraied to the princis of prestis, and to scribis, and to the eldre men; and thei schulen dampne hym bi deth, and thei schulen take hym to hethene men. And thei schulen scorne hym,
24617	41	10	34	and bispete hym, and bete him; and thei schulen sle hym, and in the thridde dai he schal rise ayen.
24618	41	10	35	And James and Joon, Zebedees sones, camen to hym, and seiden, Maister, we wolen, that what euer we axen, thou do to vs.
24619	41	10	36	And he seide to hem, What wolen ye that Y do to you?
24620	41	10	37	And thei seiden, Graunte to vs, that we sitten `the toon at thi riythalf, and the tother at thi left half, in thi glorie.
24621	41	10	38	And Jhesus seide to hem, Ye witen not what ye axen; moun ye drynke the cuppe, which Y schal drynke, or be waischun with the baptym, in which Y am baptisid?
24622	41	10	39	And thei seiden to hym, We moun. And Jhesus seide to hem, Ye schulen drynke the cuppe that Y drynke, and ye schulen be waschun with the baptym, in which Y am baptisid;
24623	41	10	40	but to sitte at my riythalf or lefthalf is not myn to yyue to you, but to whiche it is maad redi.
24624	41	10	41	And the ten herden, and bigunnen to haue indignacioun of James and Joon.
24625	41	10	42	But Jhesus clepide hem, and seide to hem, Ye witen, that thei that semen to haue prynshode of folkis, ben lordis of hem, and the princes of hem han power of hem.
24626	41	10	43	But it is not so among you, but who euer wole be maad gretter, schal be youre mynyster;
24627	41	10	44	and who euer wole be the firste among you, schal be seruaunt of alle.
24628	41	10	45	For whi mannus sone cam not, that it schulde be mynystrid to hym, but that he schulde mynystre, and yyue his lijf ayenbiyng for manye.
24629	41	10	46	And thei camen to Jerico; and whanne he yede forth fro Jerico, and hise disciplis, and a ful myche puple, Barthymeus, a blynde man, the sone of Thimei, sat bisidis the weie, and beggide.
24630	41	10	47	And whanne he herde, that it is Jhesus of Nazareth, he bigan to crie, and seie, Jhesu, the sone of Dauid, haue merci on me.
24631	41	10	48	And manye thretneden hym, that he schulde be stille; and he criede myche the more, Jhesu, the sone of Dauid, haue merci on me.
24632	41	10	49	And Jhesus stood, and comaundide hym to be clepid; and thei clepen the blynde man, and seien to hym, Be thou of betere herte, rise vp, he clepith thee.
24633	41	10	50	And he castide awei his cloth, and skippide, and cam to hym.
24634	41	10	51	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hym, What wolt thou, that Y schal do to thee? The blynde man seide to hym, Maister, that Y se.
24635	41	10	52	Jhesus seide to hym, Go thou, thi feith hath maad thee saaf. And anoon he saye, and suede hym in the weie.
24636	41	11	1	And whanne Jhesus cam nyy to Jerusalem and to Betanye, to the mount of Olyues, he sendith tweyne of hise disciplis, and seith to hem,
24637	41	11	2	Go ye in to the castel that is ayens you; and anoon as ye entren there ye schulen fynde a colt tied, on which no man hath sete yit; vntie ye, and brynge hym.
24638	41	11	3	And if ony man seye ony thing to you, What doen ye? seie ye, that he is nedeful to the Lord, and anoon he schal leeue hym hidir.
24639	41	11	4	And thei yeden forth, and founden a colt tied bifor the yate with out forth, in the metyng of twei weies; and thei vntieden hym.
24640	41	11	5	And summe of hem that stoden there seiden to hem, What doen ye, vntiynge the colt?
24641	41	11	6	And thei seiden to hem, as Jhesus comaundide hem; and thei leften it to hem.
24642	41	11	7	And thei brouyten the colt to Jhesu, and thei leiden on hym her clothis, and Jhesus sat on hym.
24643	41	11	8	And many strewiden her clothis in the weie, othere men kittiden braunchis fro trees, and strewiden in the weie.
24644	41	11	9	And thei that wenten bifor, and that sueden, crieden, and seiden, Osanna,
24645	41	11	10	blissid is he that cometh in the name of the Lord; blessid be the kyngdom of oure fadir Dauid that is come; Osanna in hiyest thingis.
24646	41	11	11	And he entride in to Jerusalem, in to the temple; and whanne he `hadde seyn al thing aboute, whanne it was eue, he wente out in to Betanye, with the twelue.
24647	41	11	12	And anothir daye, whanne he wente out of Betanye, he hungride.
24648	41	11	13	And whanne he hadde seyn a fige tree afer hauynge leeues, he cam, if happili he schulde fynde ony thing theron; and whanne he cam to it, he foonde no thing, out takun leeues; for it was not tyme of figis.
24649	41	11	14	And Jhesus answeride and seide to it, Now neuer ete ony man fruyt of thee more. And hise disciplis herden;
24650	41	11	15	and thei camen to Jerusalem. And whanne he was entrid in to the temple, he bigan to caste out silleris and biggeris in the temple; and he turnede vpsodoun the bordis of chaungeris, and the chayeris of men that selden culueris;
24651	41	11	16	and he suffride not, that ony man schulde bere a vessel thorou the temple.
24652	41	11	17	And he tauyte hem, and seide, Whether it is not writun, That myn hous schal be clepid the hous of preyng to alle folkis? but ye han maad it a denne of theues.
24653	41	11	18	And whanne this thing was herd, the princis of prestis and scribis souyten hou thei schulden leese hym; for thei dredden hym, for al the puple wondride on his techyng.
24654	41	11	19	And whanne euenyng was come, he wente out of the citee.
24655	41	11	20	And as thei passiden forth eerli, thei sayn the fige tree maad drye fro the rootis.
24656	41	11	21	And Petir bithouyte hym, and seide to hym, Maister, lo! the fige tree, whom thou cursidist, is dried vp.
24657	41	11	22	And Jhesus answeride and seide to hem, Haue ye the feith of God;
24658	41	11	23	treuli Y seie to you, that who euer seith to this hil, Be thou takun, and cast in to the see; and doute not in his herte, but bileueth, that what euer he seie, schal be don, it schal be don to hym.
24659	41	11	24	Therfor Y seie to you, alle thingis what euer thingis ye preynge schulen axe, bileue ye that ye schulen take, and thei schulen come to you.
24660	41	11	25	And whanne ye schulen stonde to preye, foryyue ye, if ye han ony thing ayens ony man, that youre fadir that is in heuenes, foryyue to you youre synnes.
24661	41	11	26	And if ye foryyuen not, nether youre fadir that is in heuenes, schal foryyue to you youre synnes.
24662	41	11	27	And eftsoone thei camen to Jerusalem. And whanne he walkide in the temple, the hiyeste prestis, and scribis, and the elder men camen to hym,
24663	41	11	28	and seyn to hym, In what power doist thou these thingis? or who yaf to thee this power, that thou do these thingis?
24664	41	11	29	Jhesus answeride and seide to hem, And Y schal axe you o word, and answere ye to me, and Y schal seie to you in what power Y do these thingis.
24665	41	11	30	Whether was the baptym of Joon of heuene, or of men? answere ye to me.
24666	41	11	31	And thei thouyten with ynne hem silf, seiynge, If we seien of heuene, he schal seie to vs, Whi thanne bileuen ye not to him;
24667	41	11	32	if we seien of men, we dreden the puple; for alle men hadden Joon, that he was verili a prophete.
24668	41	11	33	And thei answeryden, and seien to Jhesu, We witen neuer. And Jhesu answerde, and seide to hem, Nether Y seie to you, in what power Y do these thingis.
24669	41	12	1	And Jhesus bigan to speke to hem in parablis. A man plauntide a vynyerd, and sette an hegge aboute it, and dalf a lake, and bildide a toure, and hiryde it to tilieris, and wente forth in pilgrimage.
24670	41	12	2	And he sente to the erthe tilieris in tyme a seruaunt, to resseyue of the erthe tilieris of the fruyt of the vynyerd.
24671	41	12	3	And thei token hym, and beeten, and leften hym voide.
24672	41	12	4	And eftsoone he sente to hem anothir seruaunt, and thei woundiden hym in the heed, and turmentiden hym.
24673	41	12	5	And eftsoone he sente another, and thei slowen hym, and othir mo, betynge summe, and sleynge othere.
24674	41	12	6	But yit he hadde a moost derworth sone, and he sente hym last to hem, and seide, Perauenture thei schulen drede my sone.
24675	41	12	7	But the erthetilieris seiden togidere, This is the eire; come ye, sle we hym, and the eritage schal be ourun.
24676	41	12	8	And thei tokun hym, and killiden, and castiden out without the vynyerd.
24677	41	12	9	Thanne what schal the lord of the vynyerd do? He schal come, and lese the tilieris, and yyue the vynyerd to othere.
24678	41	12	10	Whether ye han not red this scripture, The stoon which the bilderis han disspisid, this is maad in to the heed of the corner?
24679	41	12	11	This thing is doon of the Lord, and is wondirful in oure iyen.
24680	41	12	12	And thei souyten to holde hym, and thei dredden the puple; for thei knewen that to hem he seide this parable; and thei leften hym,
24681	41	12	13	and thei wenten awei. And thei senten to hym summe of the Farisees and Erodians, to take hym in word.
24682	41	12	14	Whiche camen, and seien to hym, Maistir, we witen that thou art sothfast, and reckist not of ony man; for nethir thou biholdist in to the face of man, but thou techist the weie of God in treuthe. Is it leeueful that tribute be youun to the emperoure, or we schulen not yyue?
24683	41	12	15	Which witynge her pryuei falsnesse, seide to hem, What tempten ye me? brynge ye to me a peny, that Y se.
24684	41	12	16	And thei brouyten to hym. And he seide to hem, Whos is this ymage, and the writyng? Thei seien to him, The emperouris.
24685	41	12	17	And Jhesus answeride and seide to hem, Thanne yelde ye to the emperour tho thingis that ben of the emperours; and to God tho thingis that ben of God.
24686	41	12	18	And thei wondriden of hym. And Saduces, that seien that ther is no ressurreccioun, camen to hym, and axeden hym,
24687	41	12	19	and seiden, Maister, Moyses wroot to vs, that if the brother of a man were deed, and lefte his wijf, and haue no sones, his brother take his wijf, and reise vp seed to his brother.
24688	41	12	20	Thanne seuene britheren ther weren; and the firste took a wijf, and diede, and lefte no seed.
24689	41	12	21	And the secounde took hir, and he diede, and nether this lefte seed.
24690	41	12	22	And the thridde also. And in lijk manere the seuene token hir, and leften not seed. And the womman the laste of alle `is deed.
24691	41	12	23	Thanne in the resurreccioun, whanne thei schulen rise ayen, whos wijf of these schal sche be? for seuene hadden hir to wijf.
24692	41	12	24	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, Whether ye erren not therfor, that ye knowe not scripturis, nethir the vertu of God?
24693	41	12	25	For whanne thei schulen rise ayen fro deeth, nether thei schulen wedde, nethir schulen be weddid, but thei schulen be as aungels of God in heuenes.
24694	41	12	26	And of deed men, that thei risen ayen, han ye not red in the book of Moises, on the buysch, hou God spak to hym, and seide, Y am God of Abraham, and God of Isaac, and God of Jacob?
24695	41	12	27	He is not God of deed men, but of lyuynge men; therfor ye erren myche.
24696	41	12	28	And oon of the scribis, that hadde herde hem dispuytynge togidir, cam nyy, and saiy that Jhesus had wel answeride hem, and axide hym, which was the firste maundement of alle.
24697	41	12	29	And Jhesus answeride to him, that the firste maundement of alle is, Here thou, Israel, thi Lord God is o God;
24698	41	12	30	and thou schalt loue thi Lord God of al thin herte, and of al thi soule, and of al thi mynde, and of al thi myyt.
24699	41	12	31	This is the firste maundement. And the secounde is lijk to this, Thou schalt loue thi neiybore as thi silf. Ther is noon other maundement gretter than these.
24700	41	12	32	And the scribe seide to hym, Maister, in treuthe thou hast wel seid; for o God is, and ther is noon other, outakun hym;
24701	41	12	33	that he be loued of al the herte, and of al the mynde, and of al the vndurstondynge, and of al the soule, and of al strengthe, and to loue the neiybore as hym silf, is gretter than alle brent offryngis and sacrifices.
24702	41	12	34	And Jhesus seynge that he hadde answerid wiseli, seide to hym, Thou art not fer fro the kyngdom of God.
24703	41	12	35	And thanne no man durste axe hym no more ony thing. And Jhesus answeride and seide, techynge in the temple, Hou seien scribis, that Crist is the sone of Dauid?
24704	41	12	36	For Dauid hym silf seide in the Hooli Goost, the Lord seide to my lord, Sitte on my riythalf, til Y putte thin enemyes the stool of thi feet.
24705	41	12	37	Thanne Dauid hym silf clepith him lord, hou thanne is he his sone? And myche puple gladli herde hym.
24706	41	12	38	And he seide to hem in his techyng, Be ye war of scribis, that wolen wandre in stolis,
24707	41	12	39	and be salutid in chepyng, and sitte in synagogis in the firste chaieris, and the firste sittyng placis in soperis;
24708	41	12	40	whiche deuouren the housis of widewis vndur colour of long preier; thei schulen take the longer doom.
24709	41	12	41	And Jhesus sittynge ayens the tresorie, bihelde hou the puple castide monei in to the tresorie; and many riche men castiden many thingis.
24710	41	12	42	But whanne a pore widewe was comun, sche keste two mynutis, that is, a ferthing.
24711	41	12	43	And he clepide togidere hise disciplis, and seide to hem, Treuli Y seie to you, that this pore widewe keste more thanne alle, that kesten in to the tresorie.
24712	41	12	44	For alle kesten of that thing that thei hadden plente of; but this of her pouert keste alle thingis that sche hadde, al hir lyuelode.
24713	41	13	1	And whanne he wente out of the temple, oon of hise disciplis seide to hym, Maister, biholde, what maner stoonys, and what maner bildyngis.
24714	41	13	2	And Jhesu answeride, and seide to hym, Seest thou alle these grete bildingis? ther schal not be left a stoon on a stoon, which schal not be distried.
24715	41	13	3	And whanne he sat in the mount of Olyues ayens the temple, Petir and James and Joon and Andrew axiden hym bi hem silf,
24716	41	13	4	Seie thou to vs, whanne these thingis schulen be don, and what tokene schal be, whanne alle these thingis schulen bigynne to be endid.
24717	41	13	5	And Jhesus answeride, and bigan to seie to hem, Loke ye, that no man disseyue you;
24718	41	13	6	for manye schulen come in my name, seiynge, That Y am; and thei schulen disseyue manye.
24719	41	13	7	And whanne ye here batels and opynyouns of batels, drede ye not; for it bihoueth these thingis to be doon, but not yit anoon is the ende.
24720	41	13	8	For folk schal rise on folk, and rewme on rewme, and erthe mouyngis and hungur schulen be bi placis; these thingis schulen be bigynnyngis of sorewis.
24721	41	13	9	But se ye you silf, for thei schulen take you in counsels, and ye schulen be betun in synagogis; and ye schulen stonde bifor kyngis and domesmen for me, in witnessyng to hem.
24722	41	13	10	And it bihoueth, that the gospel be first prechid among al folk.
24723	41	13	11	And whanne thei taken you, and leden you forth, nyle ye bifore thenke what ye schulen speke, but speke ye that thing that schal be youun to you in that our; for ye ben not the spekeris, but the Hooli Goost.
24724	41	13	12	For a brother schal bitake the brother in to deth, and the fadir the sone, and sones schulen rise togider ayens fadris and modris, and punysche hem bi deeth.
24725	41	13	13	And ye schulen be in hate to alle men for my name; but he that lastith in to the ende, schal be saaf.
24726	41	13	14	But whanne ye schulen se the abhomynacioun of discoumfort, stondynge where it owith not; he that redith, vndurstonde; thanne thei that be in Judee, fle `in to hillis.
24727	41	13	15	And he that is aboue the roof, come not doun in to the hous, nethir entre he, to take ony thing of his hous;
24728	41	13	16	and he that schal be in the feeld, turne not ayen bihynde to take his cloth.
24729	41	13	17	But wo to hem that ben with child, and norischen in tho daies.
24730	41	13	18	Therfor preye ye, that thei be not don in wyntir.
24731	41	13	19	But thilke daies of tribulacioun schulen be suche, whiche maner weren not fro the bigynnyng of creature, which God hath maad, til now, nethir schulen be.
24732	41	13	20	And but the Lord hadde abredgide tho daies, al fleische hadde not be saaf; but for the chosun whiche he chees, the Lord hath maad schort the daies.
24733	41	13	21	And thanne if ony man seie to you, Lo! here is Crist, lo! there, bileue ye not.
24734	41	13	22	For false Cristis and false prophetis schulen rise, and schulen yyue tokenes and wondris, to disseyue, if it may be don, yhe, hem that be chosun.
24735	41	13	23	Therfor take ye kepe; lo! Y haue bifor seid to you alle thingis.
24736	41	13	24	But in tho daies, aftir that tribulacioun, the sunne schal be maad derk, and the moon schal not yyue hir liyt,
24737	41	13	25	and the sterris of heuene schulen falle doun, and the vertues that ben in heuenes, schulen be moued.
24738	41	13	26	And thanne thei schulen se mannus sone comynge in cloudis of heuene, with greet vertu and glorie.
24739	41	13	27	And thanne he schal sende hise aungelis, and schal geder hise chosun fro the foure wyndis, fro the hiyest thing of erthe til to the hiyest thing of heuene.
24740	41	13	28	But of the fige tree lerne ye the parable. Whanne now his braunche is tendre, and leeues ben sprongun out, ye knowen that somer is nyy.
24741	41	13	29	So whanne ye seen these thingis be don, wite ye, that it is nyy in the doris.
24742	41	13	30	Treuli Y seie to you, that this generacioun schal not passe awei, til alle these thingis be don.
24743	41	13	31	Heuene and erthe schulen passe, but my wordis schulen not passe.
24744	41	13	32	But of that dai or our no man woot, nether aungels in heuene, nether the sone, but the fadir.
24745	41	13	33	Se ye, wake ye, and preie ye; for ye witen not, whanne the tyme is.
24746	41	13	34	For as a man that is gon fer in pilgrimage, lefte his hous, and yaf to his seruauntis power of euery work, and comaundide to the porter, that he wake.
24747	41	13	35	Therfor wake ye, for ye witen not, whanne the lord of the hous cometh, in the euentide, or at mydnyyt, or at cockis crowyng, or in the mornyng;
24748	41	13	36	leste whanne he cometh sodenli, he fynde you slepynge.
24749	41	13	37	Forsothe that that Y seie to you, Y seie to alle, Wake ye.
24750	41	14	1	Pask and the feest of therf looues was after twei daies. And the hiyest preestis and scribis souyten, hou thei schulden holde hym with gile, and sle.
24751	41	14	2	But thei seiden, Not in the feeste dai, lest perauenture a noyse were maad among the puple.
24752	41	14	3	And whanne he was at Betanye, in the hous of Symount leprous, and restide, a womman cam, that hadde a boxe of alabastre of precious oynement spikenard; and whanne the boxe of alabastre was brokun, sche helde it on his heed.
24753	41	14	4	But there weren summe that beren it heuyli with ynne hem silf, and seiden, Wher to is this losse of oynement maad?
24754	41	14	5	For this oynement myyte haue be seld more than for thre hundrid pens, and be youun to pore men. And thei groyneden ayens hir.
24755	41	14	6	But Jhesus seide, Suffre ye hir; what be ye heuy to hir? sche hath wrouyt a good werk in me.
24756	41	14	7	For euermore ye schulen haue pore men with you, and whanne ye wolen, ye moun do wel to hem; but ye schulen not euer more haue me.
24757	41	14	8	Sche dide that that sche hadde; sche cam bifore to anoynte my bodi in to biriyng.
24758	41	14	9	Treuli Y seie to you, where euer this gospel be prechid in al the world, and that that `this womman hath don, schal be told in to mynde of hym.
24759	41	14	10	And Judas Scarioth, oon of the twelue, wente to the hiyest prestis, to bitraye hym to hem.
24760	41	14	11	And thei herden, and ioyeden, and bihiyten to yyue hym money. And he souyt hou he schulde bitraye hym couenabli.
24761	41	14	12	And the firste dai of therf looues, whanne thei offriden pask, the disciplis seyn to hym, Whidir `wilt thou that we go, and make redi to thee, that thou ete the pask?
24762	41	14	13	And he sendith tweyn of hise disciplis, and seith to hem, Go ye in to the citee, and a man berynge a galoun of watir schal meete you; sue ye hym.
24763	41	14	14	And whidur euer he entrith, seie ye to the lord of the hous, That the maister seith, Where is myn etynge place, where Y schal ete pask with my disciplis?
24764	41	14	15	And he schal schewe to you a grete soupyng place arayed, and there make ye redi to vs.
24765	41	14	16	And hise disciplis wenten forth, and camen in to the citee, and founden as he hadde seid to hem; and thei maden redy the pask.
24766	41	14	17	And whanne the euentid was come, he cam with the twelue.
24767	41	14	18	And whanne thei saten `at the mete, and eeten, Jhesus seide, Treuli Y seie to you, that oon of you that etith with me, schal bitray me.
24768	41	14	19	And thei bigunnen to be sori, and to seie to hym, ech bi hem silf, Whether Y?
24769	41	14	20	Which seide to hem, Oon of twelue that puttith the hoond with me in the platere.
24770	41	14	21	And sotheli mannus sone goith, as it is writun of hym; but wo to that man, by whom mannus sone schal be bitrayed. It were good to hym, yf thilke man hadde not be borun.
24771	41	14	22	And while thei eeten, Jhesus took breed, and blessid, and brak, and yaf to hem, and seide, Take ye; this is my bodi.
24772	41	14	23	And whanne he hadde take the cuppe, he dide thankyngis, and yaf to hem, and alle dronken therof.
24773	41	14	24	And he seide to hem, This is my blood of the newe testament, which schal be sched for many.
24774	41	14	25	Treuli Y seye to you, for now Y schal not drynke of this fruyt of vyne, in to that dai whane Y schal drynke it newe in the rewme of God.
24775	41	14	26	And whanne the ympne was seid, thei wenten out in to the hil of Olyues.
24776	41	14	27	And Jhesus seide to hem, Alle ye schulen be sclaundrid in me in this nyyt; for it is writun, Y schal smyte the scheepherde, and the scheep of the flok schulen be disparplid.
24777	41	14	28	But aftir that Y schal rise ayen, Y schal go bifor you in to Galilee.
24778	41	14	29	And Petir seide to hym, Thouy alle schulen be sclaundrid, but not Y.
24779	41	14	30	And Jhesus seide to hym, Treuli Y seie to thee, that to dai bifore that the cok in this niyt crowe twies, thou schalt thries denye me.
24780	41	14	31	But he seide more, Thouy it bihoueth, that Y die togider with thee, Y schal not forsake thee. And in lijk maner alle seiden.
24781	41	14	32	And thei camen in to a place, whos name is Gethsamany. And he seide to hise disciplis, Sitte ye here, while Y preye.
24782	41	14	33	And he took Petir and James and Joon with hym, and bigan to drede, and to be anoyed.
24783	41	14	34	And he seide to hem, My soule is soreweful to the deeth; abide ye here, and wake ye with me.
24784	41	14	35	And whanne he was gon forth a litil, he felde doun on the erthe, and preiede, that if it myyte be, that the our schulde passe fro hym.
24785	41	14	36	And he seide, Abba, fadir, alle thingis ben possible to thee, bere ouer fro me this cuppe; but not that Y wole, but that thou wolt, be don.
24786	41	14	37	And he cam, and foond hem slepynge. And he seide to Petir, Symount, slepist thou? myytist thou not wake with me oon our?
24787	41	14	38	Wake ye, and `preie ye, that ye entre not in to temptacioun; for the spirit is redi, but the fleische is sijk.
24788	41	14	39	And eftsoone he yede, and preiede, and seide the same word;
24789	41	14	40	and turnede ayen eftsoone, and foond hem slepynge; for her iyen weren heuyed. And thei knewen not, what thei schulden answere to hym.
24790	41	14	41	And he cam the thridde tyme, and seide to hem, Slepe ye now, and reste ye; it suffisith. The hour is comun; lo! mannus sone schal be bitraied in to the hondis of synful men.
24791	41	14	42	Rise ye, go we; lo! he that schal bitraye me is nyy.
24792	41	14	43	And yit while he spak, Judas Scarioth, oon of the twelue, cam, and with him miche puple with swerdis and staues, sent fro the hiyest prestis, and the scribis, and fro the eldre men.
24793	41	14	44	And his traytour hadde youun to hem a tokene, and seide, Whom euer Y kisse, he it is; holde ye hym, and lede ye warli.
24794	41	14	45	And whanne he cam, anoon he came to hym, and seide, Maistir; and he kisside hym.
24795	41	14	46	And thei leiden hondis on hym, and helden hym.
24796	41	14	47	But oon of the men that stoden aboute, drowy out a swerd, and smoot the seruaunt of the hiyest preest, and kittide of his eere.
24797	41	14	48	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, As to a theef ye han gon out with swerdis and staues, to take me?
24798	41	14	49	Dai bi dai Y was among you, and tauyte in the temple, and ye helden not me; but that the scripturis be fulfillid.
24799	41	14	50	Thanne alle hise disciplis forsoken hym, and fledden.
24800	41	14	51	But a yong man, clothid with lynnun cloth on the bare, suede hym; and thei helden hym.
24801	41	14	52	And he lefte the lynnyn clothing, and fleiy nakid awei fro hem.
24802	41	14	53	And thei ledden Jhesu to the hiyest preest. And alle the prestis and scribis and eldere men camen togidir.
24803	41	14	54	But Petir suede hym afer in to the halle of the hiyest preest. And he sat with the mynystris, and warmede hym at the fier.
24804	41	14	55	And the hiyest prestis, and al the counsel, souyten witnessyng ayens Jhesu to take hym to the deeth; but thei founden not.
24805	41	14	56	For manye seiden fals witnessyng ayens hym, and the witnessyngis weren not couenable.
24806	41	14	57	And summe risen vp, and baren fals witnessyng ayens hym,
24807	41	14	58	and seiden, For we `han herd hym seiynge, Y schal vndo this temple maad with hondis, and aftir the thridde dai Y schal bilde another not maad with hondis.
24808	41	14	59	And the witnessyng `of hem was not couenable.
24809	41	14	60	And the hiyest prest roos vp in to the myddil, and axide Jhesu, and seide, Answerist thou no thing to tho thingis that ben put ayens thee of these?
24810	41	14	61	But he was stille, and answeride no thing. Eftsoone the hiyest prest axide hym, and seide to hym, Art thou Crist, the sone of the blessid God?
24811	41	14	62	And Jhesus seide to hym, Y am; and ye schulen se mannus sone sittynge on the riythalf of the vertu of God, and comynge in the cloudis of heuene.
24812	41	14	63	And the hiyest preest torente hise clothis, and seide, What yit dissiren we witnessis?
24813	41	14	64	Ye han herd blasfemye. What semeth to you? And thei alle condempneden hym to be gilti of deeth.
24814	41	14	65	And summe bigunnen to bispete hym, `and to hile his face, and to smite hym with buffetis, and seie to hym, Areede thou. And the mynystris beeten hym with strokis.
24815	41	14	66	And whanne Petir was in the halle bynethen, oon of the damesels of the hiyest prest cam.
24816	41	14	67	And whanne sche hadde seyn Petir warmynge hym, sche bihelde hym, and seide, And thou were with Jhesu of Nazareth.
24817	41	14	68	And he denyede, and seide, Nethir Y woot, nethir Y knowe, what thou seist. And he wente without forth bifor the halle; and anoon the cok crewe.
24818	41	14	69	And eftsoone whanne another damesel hadde seyn hym, sche bigan to seye to men that stoden aboute, That this is of hem.
24819	41	14	70	And he eftsoone denyede. And aftir a litil, eftsoone thei that stoden nyy, seiden to Petir, Verili thou art of hem, for thou art of Galilee also.
24820	41	14	71	But he bigan to curse and to swere, For Y knowe not this man, whom ye seien.
24821	41	14	72	And anoon eftsoones the cok crew. And Petir bithouyte on the word that Jhesus hadde seide to hym, Bifor the cok crowe twies, thries thou schalt denye me. And he bigan to wepe.
24822	41	15	1	And anoon in the morewtid the hiyeste prestis maden a counsel with the elder men, and the scribis, and with al the counsel, and bounden Jhesu and ledden, and bitoken hym to Pilat.
24823	41	15	2	And Pilat axide hym, Art thou kynge of Jewis? And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hym, Thou seist.
24824	41	15	3	And the hieste prestis accusiden hym in many thingis.
24825	41	15	4	But Pilat eftsoone axide hym, and seide, Answerist thou no thing? Seest thou in hou many thingis thei accusen thee?
24826	41	15	5	But Jhesus answeride no more, so that Pilat wondride.
24827	41	15	6	But bi the feeste dai he was wont to leeue to hem oon of men boundun, whom euer thei axiden.
24828	41	15	7	And `oon ther was that was seid Barabas, that was boundun with men of dissencioun, that hadden don manslauytir in seducioun.
24829	41	15	8	And whanne the puple was gon vp, he bigan to preie, as he euer more dide to hem.
24830	41	15	9	And Pilat answeride `to hem, and seide, Wolen ye Y leeue to you the kyng of Jewis?
24831	41	15	10	For he wiste, that the hiyeste prestis hadden takun hym bi enuye.
24832	41	15	11	But the bischopis stireden the puple, that he schulde rather leeue to hem Barabas.
24833	41	15	12	And eftsoone Pilat answerde, and seide to hem, What thanne wolen ye that Y schal do to the kyng of Jewis?
24834	41	15	13	And thei eftsoone crieden, Crucifie hym.
24835	41	15	14	But Pilat seide to hem, What yuel hath he don? And thei crieden the more, Crucifie hym.
24836	41	15	15	And Pilat, willynge to make aseeth to the puple, lefte to hem Barabas, and bitok to hem Jhesu, betun with scourgis, to be crucified.
24837	41	15	16	And knyytis ledden hym with ynneforth, in to the porche of the mote halle. And thei clepiden togidir al the cumpany of knyytis,
24838	41	15	17	and clothiden hym with purpur. And thei writhen a coroun of thornes, and puttiden on hym.
24839	41	15	18	And thei bigunnen to grete hym, and seiden, Heile, thou kyng of Jewis.
24840	41	15	19	And thei smyten his heed with a reed, and bispatten hym; and thei kneliden, and worschipiden hym.
24841	41	15	20	And aftir that thei hadden scorned him, thei vnclothiden hym of purpur, and clothiden hym with hise clothis, and ledden out hym, to crucifie hym.
24842	41	15	21	And thei compelliden a man that passide the weie, that cam fro the toun, Symount of Syrenen, the fader of Alisaundir and of Rufe, to bere his cross.
24843	41	15	22	And thei ledden hym in to a place Golgatha, that is to seie, the place of Caluari.
24844	41	15	23	And thei yauen to hym to drynke wyn meddlid with mirre, and he took not.
24845	41	15	24	And thei crucifieden him, and departiden hise clothis, and kesten lot on tho, who schulde take what.
24846	41	15	25	And it was the thridde our, and thei crucifieden hym.
24847	41	15	26	And the titil of his cause was writun, Kyng of Jewis.
24848	41	15	27	And thei crucifien with hym twei theues, oon `at the riythalf and oon at his lefthalf.
24849	41	15	28	And the scripture was fulfillid that seith, And he is ordeyned with wickid men.
24850	41	15	29	And as thei passiden forth, thei blasfemyden hym, mouynge her heedis, and seiynge, Vath! thou that distriest the temple of God, and in `thre daies bildist it ayen;
24851	41	15	30	come adoun fro the crosse, and make thi silf saaf.
24852	41	15	31	Also the hiyeste prestis scorneden hym ech to othir with the scribis, and seiden, He made othir men saaf, he may not saue hym silf.
24853	41	15	32	Crist, kyng of Israel, come doun now fro the cross, that we seen, and bileuen. And thei that weren crucified with hym, dispiseden hym.
24854	41	15	33	And whanne the sixte hour was come, derknessis weren made on al the erthe til in to the nynthe our.
24855	41	15	34	And in the nynthe our Jhesus criede with a greet vois, and seide, Heloy, Heloy, lamasabatany, that is to seie, My God, my God, whi hast thou forsakun me?
24856	41	15	35	And summe of men that stoden aboute herden, and seiden, Lo! he clepith Helye.
24857	41	15	36	And oon ranne, and fillide a spounge with vynegre, and puttide aboute to a reede, and yaf to hym drynke, and seide, Suffre ye, se we, if Helie come to do hym doun.
24858	41	15	37	And Jhesus yaf out a greet cry, and diede.
24859	41	15	38	And the veil of the temple was rent atwo fro the hiyeste to bynethe.
24860	41	15	39	But the centurien that stood forn ayens siy, that he so criynge hadde diede, and seide, Verili, this man was Goddis sone.
24861	41	15	40	And ther weren also wymmen biholdynge fro afer, among whiche was Marie Maudeleyn, and Marie, the modir of James the lesse, and of Joseph, and of Salome.
24862	41	15	41	And whanne Jhesus was in Galilee, thei folewiden hym, and mynystriden to hym, and many othere wymmen, that camen vp togidir with him to Jerusalem.
24863	41	15	42	And whanne euentid was come, for it was the euentid which is bifor the sabat,
24864	41	15	43	Joseph of Armathie, the noble decurioun, cam, and he abood the rewme of God; and booldli he entride to Pilat, and axide the bodi of Jhesu.
24865	41	15	44	But Pilat wondride, if he were now deed.
24866	41	15	45	And whanne the centurion was clepid, he axide hym, if he were deed; and whanne he knewe of the centurion, he grauntide the bodi of Jhesu to Joseph.
24867	41	15	46	And Joseph bouyte lynnen cloth, and took hym doun, and wlappide in the lynnen cloth, and leide hym in a sepulcre that was hewun of a stoon, and walewide a stoon to the dore of the sepulcre.
24868	41	15	47	And Marie Maudeleyne and Marie of Joseph bihelden, where he was leid.
24869	41	16	1	And whanne the sabat was passid, Marie Maudeleyne, and Marie of James, and Salomee bouyten swete smellynge oynementis, to come and to anoynte Jhesu.
24870	41	16	2	And ful eerli in oon of the woke daies, thei camen to the sepulcre, whanne the sunne was risun.
24871	41	16	3	And thei seiden togidere, Who schal meue awey to vs the stoon fro the dore of the sepulcre?
24872	41	16	4	And thei bihelden, and seien the stoon walewid awei, for it was ful greet.
24873	41	16	5	And thei yeden in to the sepulcre, and sayn a yonglyng, hilide with a white stole, sittynge `at the riythalf; and thei weren afeerd.
24874	41	16	6	Which seith to hem, Nyle ye drede; ye seken Jhesu of Nazareth crucified; he is risun, he is not here; lo! the place where thei leiden hym.
24875	41	16	7	But go ye, and seie ye to hise disciplis, and to Petir, that he schal go bifor you in to Galilee; there ye schulen se hym, as he seide to you.
24876	41	16	8	And thei yeden out, and fledden fro the sepulcre; for drede and quakyng had assailed hem, and to no man thei seiden ony thing, for thei dredden.
24877	41	16	9	And Jhesus roos eerli the firste dai of the woke, and apperid firste to Marie Maudeleyne, fro whom he had caste out seuene deuelis.
24878	41	16	10	And sche yede, and tolde to hem that hadden ben with hym, whiche weren weilynge and wepynge.
24879	41	16	11	And thei herynge that he lyuyde, and was seyn of hir, bileueden not.
24880	41	16	12	But after these thingis whanne tweyne of hem wandriden, he was schewid in anothir liknesse to hem goynge in to a toun.
24881	41	16	13	And thei yeden, and telden to the othir, and nether thei bileueden to hem.
24882	41	16	14	But `at the laste, whanne the enleuene disciplis saten at the mete, Jhesus apperide to hem, and repreuede the vnbileue of hem, and the hardnesse of herte, for thei bileueden not to hem, that hadden seyn that he was risun fro deeth.
24883	41	16	15	And he seide to hem, Go ye in to al the world, and preche the gospel to eche creature.
24884	41	16	16	Who that bileueth, and is baptisid, schal be saaf; but he that bileueth not, schal be dampned.
24885	41	16	17	And these tokenes schulen sue hem, that bileuen. In my name thei schulen caste out feendis; thei schulen speke with newe tungis;
24886	41	16	18	thei schulen do awei serpentis; and if thei drynke ony venym, it schal not noye hem. Thei schulen sette her hondis on sijk men, and thei schulen wexe hoole.
24887	41	16	19	And the Lord Jhesu, aftir he hadde spokun to hem, was takun vp in to heuene, and he sittith on the riythalf of God.
24888	41	16	20	And thei yeden forth, and prechiden euery where, for the Lord wrouyte with hem, and confermyde the word with signes folewynge.
24889	42	1	1	Forsothe for manye men enforceden to ordeyne the tellyng of thingis, whiche ben fillid in vs,
24890	42	1	2	as thei that seyn atte the bigynnyng, and weren ministris of the word,
24891	42	1	3	bitaken, it is seen also to me, hauynge alle thingis diligentli bi ordre, to write to thee,
24892	42	1	4	thou best Theofile, that thou knowe the treuthe of tho wordis, of whiche thou art lerned.
24893	42	1	5	In the daies of Eroude, kyng of Judee, ther was a prest, Sakarie bi name, of the sorte of Abia, and his wijf was of the douytris of Aaron, and hir name was Elizabeth.
24894	42	1	6	And bothe weren iust bifor God, goynge in alle the maundementis and iustifiyngis of the Lord, withouten pleynt.
24895	42	1	7	And thei hadden no child, for Elizabeth was bareyn, and bothe weren of grete age in her daies.
24896	42	1	8	And it bifel, that whanne Zacarie schulde do the office of preesthod, in the ordre of his cours tofor God,
24897	42	1	9	aftir the custome of the preesthod, he wente forth bi lot, and entride in to the temple, to encense.
24898	42	1	10	And al the multitude of the puple was with outforth, and preiede in the our of encensyng.
24899	42	1	11	And an aungel of the Lord apperide to hym, and stood on the riythalf of the auter of encense.
24900	42	1	12	And Zacarie seynge was afraied, and drede fel vpon hym.
24901	42	1	13	And the aungel seide to hym, Zacarie, drede thou not; for thi preyer is herd, and Elizabeth, thi wijf, schal bere to thee a sone, and his name schal be clepid Joon.
24902	42	1	14	And ioye and gladyng schal be to thee; and many schulen `haue ioye in his natyuyte.
24903	42	1	15	For he schal be greet bifor the Lord, and he schal not drynke wyn and sidir, and he schal be fulfillid with the Hooli Goost yit of his modir wombe.
24904	42	1	16	And he schal conuerte many of the children of Israel to her Lord God;
24905	42	1	17	and he schal go bifor hym in the spirit and the vertu of Helie; and he schal turne the hertis of the fadris in to the sones, and men out of bileue to the prudence of iust men, to make redi a perfit puple to the Lord.
24906	42	1	18	And Zacarie seide to the aungel, Wherof schal Y wite this? for Y am eld, and my wijf hath gon fer in to hir daies.
24907	42	1	19	And the aungel answeride, and seide to hym, For Y am Gabriel, that stonde niy bifor God; and Y am sent to thee to speke, and to euangelize to thee these thingis.
24908	42	1	20	And lo! thou schalt be doumbe, and thou schalt not mow speke til in to the dai, in which these thingis schulen be don; for thou hast not bileued to my wordis, whiche schulen be fulfillid in her tyme.
24909	42	1	21	And the puple was abidynge Zacarie, and thei wondriden, that he tariede in the temple.
24910	42	1	22	And he yede out, and myyte not speke to hem, and thei knewen that he hadde seyn a visioun in the temple. And he bikenyde to hem, and he dwellide stille doumbe.
24911	42	1	23	And it was don, whanne the daies of his office weren fulfillid, he wente in to his hous.
24912	42	1	24	And aftir these daies Elizabeth, his wijf, conseyuede, and hidde hir fyue monethis, and seide,
24913	42	1	25	For so the Lord dide to me in the daies, in whiche he bihelde, to take awei my repreef among men.
24914	42	1	26	But in the sixte moneth the aungel Gabriel was sent fro God in to a citee of Galilee, whos name was Nazareth,
24915	42	1	27	to a maidyn, weddid to a man, whos name was Joseph, of the hous of Dauid; and the name of the maidun was Marie.
24916	42	1	28	And the aungel entride to hir, and seide, Heil, ful of grace; the Lord be with thee; blessid be thou among wymmen.
24917	42	1	29	And whanne sche hadde herd, sche was troublid in his word, and thouyte what maner salutacioun this was.
24918	42	1	30	And the aungel seide to hir, Ne drede thou not, Marie, for thou hast foundun grace anentis God.
24919	42	1	31	Lo! thou schalt conceyue in wombe, and schalt bere a sone, and thou schalt clepe his name Jhesus.
24920	42	1	32	This schal be greet, and he schal be clepid the sone of the Hiyeste; and the Lord God schal yeue to hym the seete of Dauid, his fadir, and he schal regne in the hous of Jacob with outen ende,
24921	42	1	33	and of his rewme schal be noon ende.
24922	42	1	34	And Marie seide to the aungel, On what maner schal this thing be doon, for Y knowe not man?
24923	42	1	35	And the aungel answeride, and seide to hir, The Hooly Goost schal come fro aboue in to thee, and the vertu of the Hiyeste schal ouerschadewe thee; and therfor that hooli thing that schal be borun of thee, schal be clepid the sone of God.
24924	42	1	36	And lo! Elizabeth, thi cosyn, and sche also hath conceyued a sone in hir eelde, and this moneth is the sixte to hir that is clepid bareyn;
24925	42	1	37	for euery word schal not be inpossible anentis God.
24926	42	1	38	And Marie seide, Lo! the handmaydyn of the Lord; be it don to me aftir thi word. And the aungel departide fro hir.
24927	42	1	39	And Marie roos vp in tho daies, and wente with haaste in to the mounteyns, in to a citee of Judee.
24928	42	1	40	And sche entride in to the hous of Zacarie, and grette Elizabeth.
24929	42	1	41	And it was don, as Elizabeth herde the salutacioun of Marie, the yong child in hir wombe gladide. And Elizabeth was fulfillid with the Hooli Goost,
24930	42	1	42	and criede with a greet vois, and seide, Blessid be thou among wymmen, and blessid be the fruyt of thi wombe.
24931	42	1	43	And whereof is this thing to me, that the modir of my Lord come to me?
24932	42	1	44	For lo! as the voice of thi salutacioun was maad in myn eeris, the yong child gladide in ioye in my wombe.
24933	42	1	45	And blessid be thou, that hast bileued, for thilke thingis that ben seid of the Lord to thee, schulen be parfitli don.
24934	42	1	46	And Marie seide, Mi soule magnyfieth the Lord,
24935	42	1	47	and my spirit hath gladid in God, myn helthe.
24936	42	1	48	For he hath biholdun the mekenesse of his handmaidun.
24937	42	1	49	For lo! of this alle generaciouns schulen seie that Y am blessid. For he that is myyti hath don to me grete thingis, and his name is hooli.
24938	42	1	50	And his mercy is fro kynrede in to kynredes, to men that dreden hym.
24939	42	1	51	He made myyt in his arme, he scaterede proude men with the thouyte of his herte.
24940	42	1	52	He sette doun myyti men fro sete, and enhaunside meke men.
24941	42	1	53	He hath fulfillid hungri men with goodis, and he hath left riche men voide.
24942	42	1	54	He, hauynge mynde of his mercy, took Israel, his child;
24943	42	1	55	as he hath spokun to oure fadris, to Abraham and to his seed, in to worldis.
24944	42	1	56	And Marie dwellide with hir, as it were thre monethis, and turnede ayen in to hir hous.
24945	42	1	57	But the tyme of beryng child was fulfillid to Elizabeth, and sche bare a sone.
24946	42	1	58	And the neiyboris and cosyns of hir herden, that the Lord hadde magnyfied his mercy with hir; and thei thankiden hym.
24947	42	1	59	And it was don in the eiyte dai, thei camen to circumcide the child; and thei clepiden hym Zacarie, bi the name of his fadir.
24948	42	1	60	And his moder answeride, and seide, Nay, but he schal be clepid Joon.
24949	42	1	61	And thei seiden to hir, For no man is in thi kynrede, that is clepid this name.
24950	42	1	62	And thei bikeneden to his fadir, what he wolde that he were clepid.
24951	42	1	63	And he axynge a poyntil, wroot, seiynge, Joon is his name.
24952	42	1	64	And alle men wondriden. And anoon his mouth was openyd, and his tunge, and he spak, and blesside God.
24953	42	1	65	And drede was maad on alle her neiyboris, and alle these wordis weren pupplischid on alle the mounteyns of Judee.
24954	42	1	66	And alle men that herden puttiden in her herte, and seiden, What maner child schal this be? For the hoond of the Lord was with hym.
24955	42	1	67	And Zacarie, his fadir, was fulfillid with the Hooli Goost, and prophesiede,
24956	42	1	68	and seide, Blessid be the Lord God of Israel, for he hath visitid, and maad redempcioun of his puple.
24957	42	1	69	And he hath rerid to vs an horn of heelthe in the hous of Dauid, his child.
24958	42	1	70	As he spak bi the mouth of hise hooli prophetis, that weren fro the world.
24959	42	1	71	Helthe fro oure enemyes, and fro the hoond of alle men that hatiden vs.
24960	42	1	72	To do merci with oure fadris, and to haue mynde of his hooli testament.
24961	42	1	73	The greet ooth that he swoor to Abraham, oure fadir, to yyue hym silf to vs.
24962	42	1	74	That we with out drede delyuered fro the hoond of oure enemyes,
24963	42	1	75	serue to hym, in hoolynesse and riytwisnesse bifor hym in alle oure daies.
24964	42	1	76	And thou, child, schalt be clepid the prophete of the Hiyest; for thou schalt go bifor the face of the Lord, to make redi hise weies.
24965	42	1	77	To yyue scyence of helthe to his puple, in to remyssioun of her synnes;
24966	42	1	78	bi the inwardnesse of the merci of oure God, in the whiche he spryngynge vp fro an hiy hath visitid vs.
24967	42	1	79	To yyue liyt to hem that sitten in derknessis and in schadewe of deeth; to dresse oure feet in to the weie of pees.
24968	42	1	80	And the child wexide, and was coumfortid in spirit, and was in desert placis `til to the dai of his schewing to Israel.
24969	42	2	1	And it was don in tho daies, a maundement wente out fro the emperour August, that al the world schulde be discryued.
24970	42	2	2	This firste discryuyng was maad of Cyryn, iustice of Sirie.
24971	42	2	3	And alle men wenten to make professioun, ech in to his owne citee.
24972	42	2	4	And Joseph wente vp fro Galilee, fro the citee Nazareth, in to Judee, in to a citee of Dauid, that is clepid Bethleem, for that he was of the hous and of the meyne of Dauid,
24973	42	2	5	that he schulde knouleche with Marie, his wijf, that was weddid to hym, and was greet with child.
24974	42	2	6	And it was don, while thei weren there, the daies weren fulfillid, that sche schulde bere child.
24975	42	2	7	And sche bare hir first borun sone, and wlappide hym in clothis, and leide hym in a cratche, for ther was no place to hym in no chaumbir.
24976	42	2	8	And scheepherdis weren in the same cuntre, wakynge and kepynge the watchis of the nyyt on her flok.
24977	42	2	9	And lo! the aungel of the Lord stood bisidis hem, and the cleernesse of God schinede aboute hem; and thei dredden with greet drede.
24978	42	2	10	And the aungel seide to hem, Nyle ye drede; for lo! Y preche to you a greet ioye, that schal be to al puple.
24979	42	2	11	For a sauyoure is borun to dai to you, that is Crist the Lord, in the citee of Dauid.
24980	42	2	12	And this is a tokene to you; ye schulen fynde a yong child wlappid in clothis, and leid in a cratche.
24981	42	2	13	And sudenli ther was maad with the aungel a multitude of heuenli knyythod, heriynge God,
24982	42	2	14	and seiynge, Glorie be in the hiyeste thingis to God, and in erthe pees be to men of good wille.
24983	42	2	15	And it was don, as the `aungelis passiden awei fro hem in to heuene, the scheephirdis spaken togider, and seiden, Go we ouer to Bethleem, and se we this word that is maad, which the Lord hath `maad, and schewide to vs.
24984	42	2	16	And thei hiyynge camen, and founden Marie and Joseph, and the yong child leid in a cratche.
24985	42	2	17	And thei seynge, knewen of the word that was seid to hem of this child.
24986	42	2	18	And alle men that herden wondriden, and of these thingis that weren seid to hem of the scheephirdis.
24987	42	2	19	But Marie kepte alle these wordis, berynge togider in hir herte.
24988	42	2	20	And the scheepherdis turneden ayen, glorifyinge and heriynge God in alle thingis that thei hadden herd and seyn, as it was seid to hem.
24989	42	2	21	And aftir that the eiyte daies weren endid, that the child schulde be circumcided, his name was clepid Jhesus, which was clepid of the aungel, bifor that he was conceyued in the wombe.
24990	42	2	22	And aftir that the daies of the purgacioun of Marie weren fulfillid, aftir Moyses lawe, thei token hym into Jerusalem, to offre hym to the Lord, as it is writun in the lawe of the Lord,
24991	42	2	23	For euery male kynde openynge the wombe, schal be clepid holi to the Lord; and that thei schulen yyue an offryng,
24992	42	2	24	aftir that it is seid in the lawe of the Lord, A peire of turturis, or twei culuer briddis.
24993	42	2	25	And lo! a man was in Jerusalem, whos name was Symeon; and this man was iust and vertuous, and aboode the coumfort of Israel; and the Hooli Goost was in hym.
24994	42	2	26	And he hadde takun an answere of the Hooli Goost, that he schulde not se deeth, but he sawy first the Crist of the Lord.
24995	42	2	27	And he cam in spirit into the temple. And whanne his fadir and modir ledden the child Jhesu to do aftir the custom of the lawe for hym,
24996	42	2	28	he took hym in to hise armes, and he blesside God,
24997	42	2	29	and seide, Lord, now thou leuyst thi seruaunt aftir thi word in pees;
24998	42	2	30	for myn iyen han seyn thin helthe,
24999	42	2	31	which thou hast maad redi bifor the face of alle puplis;
25000	42	2	32	liyt to the schewyng of hethene men, and glorie of thi puple Israel.
25001	42	2	33	And his fadir and his modir weren wondrynge on these thingis, that weren seid of hym.
25002	42	2	34	And Symeon blesside hem, and seide to Marie, his modir, Lo! this is set in to the fallyng doun and in to the risyng ayen of many men in Israel, and in to a tokene, to whom it schal be ayenseid.
25003	42	2	35	And a swerd schal passe thorou thin owne soule, that the thouytis ben schewid of many hertis.
25004	42	2	36	And Anna was a prophetesse, the douytir of Fanuel, of the lynage of Aser. And sche hadde goon forth in many daies, and hadde lyued with hir hosebonde seuene yeer fro hir maydynhode.
25005	42	2	37	And this was a widewe to foure scoor yeer and foure; and sche departide not fro the temple, but seruyde to God nyyt and dai in fastyngis and preieris.
25006	42	2	38	And this cam vpon hem in thilk our, and knoulechide to the Lord, and spak of hym to alle that abiden the redempcioun of Israel.
25007	42	2	39	And as thei hadden ful don alle thingis, aftir the lawe of the Lord, thei turneden ayen in to Galilee, in to her citee Nazareth.
25008	42	2	40	And the child wexe, and was coumfortid, ful of wisdom; and the grace of God was in hym.
25009	42	2	41	And his fadir and modir wenten ech yeer in to Jerusalem, in the solempne dai of pask.
25010	42	2	42	And whanne Jhesus was twelue yeer oold, thei wenten vp to Jerusalem, aftir the custom of the feeste dai.
25011	42	2	43	And whanne the daies weren don, thei turneden ayen; and the child abood in Jerusalem, and his fadir and modir knewen it not.
25012	42	2	44	For thei gessynge that he hadde be in the felowschip, camen a daies iourney, and souyten hym among hise cosyns and hise knouleche.
