25013	42	2	45	And whanne thei founden hym not, thei turneden ayen in to Jerusalem, and souyten hym.
25014	42	2	46	And it bifelle, that aftir the thridde dai thei founden hym in the temple, sittynge in the myddil of the doctours, herynge hem and axynge hem.
25015	42	2	47	And alle men that herden hym, wondriden on the prudence and the answeris of hym.
25016	42	2	48	And thei seyn, and wondriden. And his modir seide to hym, Sone, what hast thou do to vs thus? Lo! thi fadir and Y sorewynge han souyte thee.
25017	42	2	49	And he seide to hem, What is it that ye souyten me? wisten ye not that in tho thingis that ben of my fadir, it behoueth me to be?
25018	42	2	50	And thei vndurstoden not the word, which he spak to hem.
25019	42	2	51	And he cam doun with hem, and cam to Nazareth, and was suget to hem. And his moder kepte togidir alle these wordis, and bare hem in hir herte.
25020	42	2	52	And Jhesus profitide in wisdom, age, and grace, anentis God and men.
25021	42	3	1	In the fiftenthe yeer of the empire of Tiberie, the emperoure, whanne Pilat of Pounce gouernede Judee, and Eroude was prince of Galilee, and Filip, his brothir, was prince of Iturye, and of the cuntre of Tracon, and Lisanye was prince of Abilyn,
25022	42	3	2	vndir the princis of prestis Annas and Caifas, the word of the Lord was maad on Joon, the sone of Zacarie, in desert.
25023	42	3	3	And he cam in to al the cuntre of Jordan, and prechide baptym of penaunce in to remyssioun of synnes.
25024	42	3	4	As it is wrytun in the book of the wordis of Isaye, the prophete, The voice of a crier in desert, Make ye redi the weie of the Lord, make ye hise pathis riyt.
25025	42	3	5	Ech valey schal be fulfillid, and euery hil and litil hil schal be maad lowe; and schrewid thingis schulen ben in to dressid thingis, and scharp thingis in to pleyn weies;
25026	42	3	6	and euery fleisch schal se the heelthe of God.
25027	42	3	7	Therfor he seid to the puple, which wente out to be baptisid of hym, Kyndlyngis of eddris, who schewide to you to fle fro the wraththe to comynge?
25028	42	3	8	Therfor do ye worthi fruytis of penaunce, and bigynne ye not to seie, We han a fadir Abraham; for Y seie to you, that God is myyti to reise of these stoonys the sones of Abraham.
25029	42	3	9	And now an axe is sett to the roote of the tree; and therfor euery tre that makith no good fruyt, schal be kit doun, and schal be cast in to the fier.
25030	42	3	10	And the puple axide hym, and seiden, What thanne schulen we do?
25031	42	3	11	He answeride, and seide to hem, He that hath twei cootis, yyue to hym that hath noon; and he that hath metis, do in lijk maner.
25032	42	3	12	And pupplicans camen to be baptisid; and thei seiden to hym, Maister, what schulen we do?
25033	42	3	13	And he seide to hem, Do ye no thing more, than that that is ordeyned to you.
25034	42	3	14	And knyytis axiden hym, and seiden, What schulen also we do? And he seide to hem, Smyte ye wrongfuli no man, nethir make ye fals chalenge, and be ye apayed with youre sowdis.
25035	42	3	15	Whanne al the puple gesside, and alle men thouyten in her hertis of Joon, lest perauenture he were Crist,
25036	42	3	16	Joon answeride, and seide to alle men, Y baptize you in watir; but a stronger than Y schal come aftir me, of whom Y am not worthi to vnbynde the lace of his schoon; he schal baptize you in the Hooli Goost and fier.
25037	42	3	17	Whos `wynewyng tool in his hond, and he schal purge his floor of corn, and schal gadere the whete in to his berne; but the chaffis he schal brenne with fier vnquenchable.
25038	42	3	18	And many othere thingis also he spak, and prechide to the puple. But Eroude tetrark, whanne he was blamed of Joon for Erodias,
25039	42	3	19	the wijf of his brother, and for alle the yuelis that Eroude dide,
25040	42	3	20	encreside this ouer alle, and schitte Joon in prisoun.
25041	42	3	21	And it was don, whanne al the puple was baptised, and whanne Jhesu was baptised, and preiede, heuene was openyd.
25042	42	3	22	And the Hooli Goost cam doun in bodili licnesse, as a dowue on hym; and a vois was maad fro heuene, Thou art my derworth sone, in thee it hath plesid to me.
25043	42	3	23	And Jhesu hym silf was bigynninge as of thritti yeer, that he was gessid the sone of Joseph, which was of Heli,
25044	42	3	24	which was of Mathath, which was of Leuy, which was of Melchi, that was of Jamne,
25045	42	3	25	that was of Joseph, that was of Matatie, that was of Amos, that was of Naum, that was of Hely, that was of Nagge,
25046	42	3	26	that was of Mathath, that was of Matatie, that was of Semei, that was of Joseph, that was of Juda, that was of Johanna,
25047	42	3	27	that was of Resa, that was of Zorobabel, that was of Salatiel,
25048	42	3	28	that was of Neri, that was of Melchi, that was of Addi, that was of Cosan, that was of Elmadan, that was of Her,
25049	42	3	29	that was of Jhesu, that was of Eleasar, that was of Jorum, that was of Matath,
25050	42	3	30	that was of Leuy, that was of Symeon, that was of Juda, that was of Joseph, that was of Jona, that was of Eliachym,
25051	42	3	31	that was of Melca, that was of Menna, that of Mathatha, that was of Nathan,
25052	42	3	32	that was of Dauid, that was of Jesse, that was of Obeth, that was of Boz, that was of Salmon, that was of Nason,
25053	42	3	33	that was of Amynadab, that was of Aram, that was of Esrom, that was of Fares,
25054	42	3	34	that was of Judas, that was of Jacob, that was of Isaac, that was of Abraham, that was of Tare, that was of Nachor,
25055	42	3	35	that was of Seruth, that was of Ragau, that was of Faleth, that was of Heber,
25056	42	3	36	that was of Sale, that was of Chaynan, that was of Arfaxath, that was of Sem, that was of Noe, that was of Lameth,
25057	42	3	37	that was of Matussale, that was of Enok, that was of Jareth, that was of Malaliel, that was of Cainan, that was of Enos,
25058	42	3	38	that was of Seth, that was of Adam, that was of God.
25059	42	4	1	And Jhesus ful of the Hooli Goost turnede ayen fro Jordan, and was led bi the spirit into desert fourti daies,
25060	42	4	2	and was temptid of the deuel, and eet nothing in tho daies; and whanne tho daies weren endid, he hungride.
25061	42	4	3	And the deuel seide to him, If thou art Goddis sone, seie to this stoon, that it be maad breed.
25062	42	4	4	And Jhesus answeride to hym, It is writun, That a man lyueth not in breed aloone, but in euery word of God.
25063	42	4	5	And the deuel ladde hym in to an hiy hil, and schewide to hym alle the rewmes of the world in a moment of tyme;
25064	42	4	6	and seide to hym, Y schal yyue to thee al this power, and the glorie of hem, for to me thei ben youun, and to whom Y wole, Y yyue hem;
25065	42	4	7	therfor if thou falle doun, and worschipe bifore me, alle thingis schulen be thine.
25066	42	4	8	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hym, It is writun, Thou schalt worschipe thi Lord God, and to hym aloone thou schalt serue.
25067	42	4	9	And he ledde hym in to Jerusalem, and sette hym on the pynacle of the temple, and seide to hym, If thou art Goddis sone, sende thi silf fro hennes doun;
25068	42	4	10	for it is writun, For he hath comaundide to hise aungels of thee, that thei kepe thee in alle thi weies,
25069	42	4	11	and that thei schulen take thee in hondis, lest perauenture thou hirte thi foote at a stoon.
25070	42	4	12	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to him, It is seid, Thou schalt not tempte thi Lord God.
25071	42	4	13	And whanne euery temptacioun was endid, the feend wente a wei fro hym for a tyme.
25072	42	4	14	And Jhesus turnede ayen in the vertu of the spirit in to Galilee, and the fame wente forth of hym thorou al the cuntre.
25073	42	4	15	And he tauyte in the synagogis of hem, and was magnyfied of alle men.
25074	42	4	16	And he cam to Nazareth, where he was norisschid, and entride aftir his custom in the sabat dai in to a synagoge, and roos to reed.
25075	42	4	17	And the book of Ysaye, the prophete, was takun to hym; and as he turnede the book, he foond a place, where it was wrytun,
25076	42	4	18	The Spirit of the Lord on me, for which thing he anoyntide me; he sente me to preche to pore men, to hele contrite men in herte,
25077	42	4	19	and to preche remyssioun to prisoneris, and siyt to blynde men, and to delyuere brokun men in to remissioun; to preche the yeer of the Lord plesaunt, and the dai of yeldyng ayen.
25078	42	4	20	And whanne he hadde closid the book, he yaf ayen to the mynystre, and sat; and the iyen of alle men in the synagoge were biholdynge in to hym.
25079	42	4	21	And he bigan to seie to hem, For in this dai this scripture is fulfillid in youre eeris.
25080	42	4	22	And alle men yauen witnessyng to hym, and wondriden in the wordis of grace, that camen forth of his mouth. And thei seiden, Whether this is not the sone of Joseph?
25081	42	4	23	And he seide to hem, Sotheli ye schulen seie to me this liknesse, Leeche, heele thi silf. The Farisees seiden to Jhesu, Hou grete thingis han we herd don in Cafarnaum, do thou also here in thi cuntre.
25082	42	4	24	And he seide, Treuli Y seie to you, that no profete is resseyued in his owne cuntre.
25083	42	4	25	In treuthe Y seie to you, that many widowis weren in the daies of Elie, the prophete, in Israel, whanne heuene was closid thre yeer and sixe monethis, whanne greet hungur was maad in al the erthe;
25084	42	4	26	and to noon of hem was Elye sent, but in to Sarepta of Sydon, to a widowe.
25085	42	4	27	And many meseles weren in Israel, vndur Helisee, the prophete, and noon of hem was clensid, but Naaman of Sirye.
25086	42	4	28	And alle in the synagoge herynge these thingis, weren fillid with wraththe.
25087	42	4	29	And thei risen vp, and drouen hym out with out the citee, and ledden hym to the cop of the hil on which her citee was bildid, to caste hym doun.
25088	42	4	30	But Jhesus passide, and wente thorou the myddil of hem; and cam doun in to Cafarnaum,
25089	42	4	31	a citee of Galilee, and there he tauyte hem in sabotis.
25090	42	4	32	And thei weren astonyed in his techyng, for his word was in power.
25091	42	4	33	And in her synagoge was a man hauynge an vnclene feend, and he criede with greet vois,
25092	42	4	34	and seide, Suffre, what to vs and to thee, Jhesu of Nazareth? art thou comun to leese vs? Y knowe, that thou art the hooli of God.
25093	42	4	35	And Jhesus blamede hym, and seide, Wexe doumbe, and go out fro hym. And whanne the feend hadde cast hym forth in to the myddil, he wente a wei fro hym, and he noyede hym no thing.
25094	42	4	36	And drede was maad in alle men, and thei spaken togider, and seiden, What is this word, for in power and vertu he comaundith to vnclene spiritis, and thei gon out?
25095	42	4	37	And the fame was pupplischid of him in to ech place of the cuntre.
25096	42	4	38	And Jhesus roos vp fro the synagoge, and entride in to the hous of Symount; and the modir of Symountis wijf was holdun with grete fyueris, and thei preieden hym for hir.
25097	42	4	39	And Jhesus stood ouer hir, and comaundide to the feuer, and it lefte hir; and anoon sche roos vp, and seruede hem.
25098	42	4	40	And whanne the sunne wente doun, alle that hadden sijke men with dyuerse langours, ledden hem to hym; and he sette his hoondis on ech bi `hem silf, and heelide hem.
25099	42	4	41	And feendis wenten out fro manye, and crieden, and seiden, For thou art the sone of God. And he blamede, and suffride hem not to speke, for thei wisten hym, that he was Crist.
25100	42	4	42	And whanne the dai was come, he yede out, and wente in to a desert place; and the puple souyten hym, and thei camen to hym, and thei helden hym, that he schulde not go a wei fro hem.
25101	42	4	43	To whiche he seide, For also to othere citees it bihoueth me to preche the kyngdom of God, for therfor Y am sent.
25102	42	4	44	And he prechide in the synagogis of Galilee.
25103	42	5	1	And it was don, whanne the puple cam fast to Jhesu, to here the word of God, he stood bisidis the pool of Genasereth,
25104	42	5	2	and saiy two bootis stondynge bisidis the pool; and the fischeris weren go doun, and waischiden her nettis.
25105	42	5	3	And he wente vp in to a boot, that was Symoundis, and preiede hym to lede it a litil fro the loond; and he seet, and tauyte the puple out of the boot.
25106	42	5	4	And as he ceesside to speke, he seide to Symount, Lede thou in to the depthe, and slake youre nettis to take fisch.
25107	42	5	5	And Symount answeride, and seide to hym, Comaundoure, we traueliden al the nyyt, and token no thing, but in thi word Y schal leye out the net.
25108	42	5	6	And whanne thei hadden do this thing, thei closiden togidir a greet multitude of fischis; and her net was brokun.
25109	42	5	7	And thei bikenyden to felawis, that weren in anothir boot, that thei schulden come, and helpe hem. And thei camen, and filliden bothe the bootis, so that thei weren almost drenchid.
25110	42	5	8	And whanne Symount Petir saiy this thing, he felde doun to the knees of Jhesu, and seide, Lord, go fro me, for Y am a synful man.
25111	42	5	9	For he was on ech side astonyed, and alle that weren with hym, in the takyng of fischis whiche thei token.
25112	42	5	10	Sotheli in lijk maner James and Joon, the sones of Zebedee, that weren felowis of Symount Petre. And Jhesus seide to Symount, Nyle thou drede; now fro this tyme thou schalt take men.
25113	42	5	11	And whanne the bootis weren led vp to the loond, thei leften alle thingis, and thei sueden hym.
25114	42	5	12	And it was don, whanne he was in oon of the citees, lo! a man ful of lepre; and seynge Jhesu felle doun on his face, and preyede hym, and seide, Lord, if thou wolt, thou maist make me clene.
25115	42	5	13	And Jhesus held forth his hoond, and touchide hym, and seide, Y wole, be thou maad cleene. And anoon the lepre passide awei fro hym.
25116	42	5	14	And Jhesus comaundide to hym, that he schulde seie to no man; But go, schewe thou thee to a preest, and offre for thi clensyng, as Moises bad, in to witnessyng to hem.
25117	42	5	15	And the word walkide aboute the more of hym; and myche puple camen togidere, to here, and to be heelid of her siknessis.
25118	42	5	16	And he wente in to desert, and preiede.
25119	42	5	17	And it was don in oon of the daies, he sat, and tauyte; and there weren Farisees sittynge, and doctouris of the lawe, that camen of eche castel of Galilee, and of Judee, and of Jerusalem; and the vertu of the Lord was to heele sike men.
25120	42	5	18	And lo! men beren in a bed a man that was sijk in the palsye, and thei souyten to bere hym in, and sette bifor hym.
25121	42	5	19	And thei founden not in what partie thei schulden bere hym in, for the puple, `and thei wenten on the roof, and bi the sclattis thei leeten hym doun with the bed, in to the myddil, bifor Jhesus.
25122	42	5	20	And whanne Jhesu saiy the feith of hem, he seide, Man, thi synnes ben foryouun to thee.
25123	42	5	21	And the scribis and Farisees bigunnen to thenke, seiynge, Who is this, that spekith blasfemyes? who may foryyue synnes, but God aloone?
25124	42	5	22	And as Jhesus knewe the thouytis of hem, he answeride, and seide to hem, What thenken ye yuele thingis in youre hertes?
25125	42	5	23	What is liyter to seie, Synnes ben foryouun to thee, or to seie, Rise vp, and walke?
25126	42	5	24	But that ye wite, that mannus sone hath power in erthe to foryyue synnes, he seide to the sijk man in palesie, Y seie to thee, ryse vp, take thi bed, and go in to thin hous.
25127	42	5	25	And anoon he roos vp bifor hem, and took the bed in which he lay, and wente in to his hous, and magnyfiede God.
25128	42	5	26	And greet wondur took alle, and thei magnyfieden God; and thei weren fulfillid with greet drede, and seiden, For we han seyn merueilouse thingis to dai.
25129	42	5	27	And after these thingis Jhesus wente out, and saiy a pupplican, Leuy bi name, sittynge at the tolbothe. And he seide to hym, Sue thou me;
25130	42	5	28	and whanne he hadde left alle thingis, he roos vp, and suede hym.
25131	42	5	29	And Leuy made to hym a greet feeste in his hous; and ther was a greet cumpanye of pupplicans, and of othere that weren with hem, sittynge at the mete.
25132	42	5	30	And Farisees and the scribis of hem grutchiden, and seiden to hise disciplis, Whi eten ye and drynken with pupplicans and synful men?
25133	42	5	31	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, Thei that ben hoole han no nede to a leche, but thei that ben sijke;
25134	42	5	32	for Y cam not to clepe iuste men, but synful men to penaunce.
25135	42	5	33	And thei seiden to hym, Whi the disciplis of Joon fasten ofte, and maken preieris, also and of Farisees, but thine eten and drynken?
25136	42	5	34	To whiche he seide, Whether ye moun make the sones of the spouse to faste, while the spouse is with hem?
25137	42	5	35	But daies schulen come, whanne the spouse schal be takun a wei fro hem, and thanne thei schulen faste in tho daies.
25138	42	5	36	And he seide to hem also a liknesse; For no man takith a pece fro a newe cloth, and puttith it in to an oold clothing; ellis bothe he brekith the newe, and the pece of the newe acordith not to the elde.
25139	42	5	37	And no man puttith newe wyne in to oolde botels; ellis the newe wyn schal breke the botels, and the wyn schal be sched out, and the botels schulen perische.
25140	42	5	38	But newe wyne owith to be put in to newe botels, and bothe ben kept.
25141	42	5	39	And no man drynkynge the elde, wole anoon the newe; for he seith, The olde is the betere.
25142	42	6	1	And it was don in the secounde firste sabat, whanne he passid bi cornes, hise disciplis pluckiden eeris of corn; and thei frotynge with her hondis, eeten.
25143	42	6	2	And summe of the Farisees seiden to hem, What doon ye that, that is not leeueful in the sabotis?
25144	42	6	3	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, Han ye not redde, what Dauith dide, whanne he hungride, and thei that weren with hym;
25145	42	6	4	hou he entride in to the hous of God, and took looues of proposicioun, and eet, and yaf to hem that weren with hem; whiche looues it was not leeueful to eete, but oonli to prestis.
25146	42	6	5	And he seide to hem, For mannus sone is lord, yhe, of the sabat.
25147	42	6	6	And it was don in another sabat, that he entride in to a synagoge, and tauyte. And a man was there, and his riyt hoond was drie.
25148	42	6	7	And the scribis and Farisees aspieden hym, if he wolde heele hym in the sabat, that thei schulden fynde cause, whereof thei schulden accuse hym.
25149	42	6	8	And he wiste the thouytis of hem, and he seide to the man that hadde a drie hoond, Rise vp, and stonde in to the myddil. And he roos, and stood.
25150	42	6	9	And Jhesus seide to hem, Y axe you, if it is leueful to do wel in the sabat, or yuel? to make a soule saaf, or to leese?
25151	42	6	10	And whanne he hadde biholde alle men aboute, he seide to the man, Hold forth thin hoond. And he held forth, and his hond was restorid to helthe.
25152	42	6	11	And thei weren fulfillid with vnwisdom, and spaken togidir, what thei schulden do of Jhesu.
25153	42	6	12	And it was don in tho daies, he wente out in to an hil to preye; and he was al nyyt dwellynge in the preier of God.
25154	42	6	13	And whanne the day was come, he clepide hise disciplis, and chees twelue of hem, whiche he clepide also apostlis;
25155	42	6	14	Symount, whom he clepide Petir, and Andrew, his brothir, James and Joon,
25156	42	6	15	Filip and Bartholomew, Matheu and Thomas, James Alphei, and Symount, that is clepid Zelotes,
25157	42	6	16	Judas of James, and Judas Scarioth, that was traytoure.
25158	42	6	17	And Jhesus cam doun fro the hil with hem, and stood in a feeldi place; and the cumpeny of hise disciplis, and a greet multitude of puple, of al Judee, and Jerusalem, and of the see coostis, and of Tyre and Sidon,
25159	42	6	18	that camen to here hym, and to be heelid of her siknessis; and thei that weren trauelid of vncleene spiritis, weren heelid.
25160	42	6	19	And al puple souyte to touche hym, for vertu wente out of hym, and heelide alle.
25161	42	6	20	And whanne hise iyen weren cast vp in to hise disciplis, he seide, Blessid be ye, `pore men, for the kyngdom of God is youre.
25162	42	6	21	Blessid be ye, that now hungren, for ye schulen be fulfillid. Blessid be ye, that now wepen, for ye schulen leiye.
25163	42	6	22	Ye schulen be blessid, whanne men schulen hate you, and departe you awei, and putte schenschip to you, and cast out youre name as yuel, for mannus sone.
25164	42	6	23	Joye ye in that dai, and be ye glad; for lo! youre meede is myche in heuene; for aftir these thingis the fadris of hem diden to prophetis.
25165	42	6	24	Netheles wo to you, riche men, that han youre coumfort.
25166	42	6	25	Wo to you that ben fulfillid, for ye schulen hungre. Wo to you that now leiyen, for ye schulen morne, and wepe.
25167	42	6	26	Wo to you, whanne alle men schulen blesse you; aftir these thingis the fadris of hem diden to profetis.
25168	42	6	27	But Y seie to you that heren, loue ye youre enemyes, do ye wel to hem that hatiden you;
25169	42	6	28	blesse ye men that cursen you, preye ye for men that defamen you.
25170	42	6	29	And to him that smytith thee on o cheeke, schewe also the tothir; and fro hym that takith awei fro thee a cloth, nyle thou forbede the coote.
25171	42	6	30	And yyue to eche that axith thee, and if a man takith awei tho thingis that ben thine, axe thou not ayen.
25172	42	6	31	And as ye wolen that men do to you, do ye also to hem in lijk maner.
25173	42	6	32	And if ye louen hem that louen you, what thanke is to you? for synful men louen men that louen hem.
25174	42	6	33	And if ye don wel to hem that don wel to you, what grace is to you? synful men don this thing.
25175	42	6	34	And if ye leenen to hem of whiche ye hopen to take ayen, what thanke is to you? for synful men leenen to synful men, to take ayen as myche.
25176	42	6	35	Netheles loue ye youre enemyes, and do ye wel, and leene ye, hopinge no thing therof, and youre mede schal be myche, and ye schulen be the sones of the Heyest, for he is benygne on vnkynde men and yuele men.
25177	42	6	36	Therfor be ye merciful, as youre fadir is merciful.
25178	42	6	37	Nyle ye deme, and ye schulen not be demed. Nyle ye condempne, and ye schulen not be condempned; foryyue ye, and it schal be foryouun to you.
25179	42	6	38	Yyue ye, and it schal be youun to you. Thei schulen yyue in to youre bosum a good mesure, and wel fillid, and schakun togidir, and ouerflowynge; for bi the same mesure, bi whiche ye meeten, it schal be metun `ayen to you.
25180	42	6	39	And he seide to hem a liknesse, Whether the blynde may leede the blynde? ne fallen thei not bothe `in to the diche?
25181	42	6	40	A disciple is not aboue the maistir; but eche schal be perfite, if he be as his maister.
25182	42	6	41	And what seest thou in thi brotheris iye a moot, but thou biholdist not a beem, that is in thin owne iye?
25183	42	6	42	Or hou maist thou seie to thi brother, Brothir, suffre, Y schal caste out the moot of thin iye, and thou biholdist not a beem in thin owne iye? Ipocrite, first take out the beem of thin iye, and thanne thou schalt se to take the moot of thi brotheris iye.
25184	42	6	43	It is not a good tree, that makith yuel fruytis, nether an yuel tree, that makith good fruytis;
25185	42	6	44	for euery tre is knowun of his fruyt. And men gaderen not figus of thornes, nethir men gaderen a grape of a buysche of breris.
25186	42	6	45	A good man of the good tresoure of his herte bryngith forth good thingis, and an yuel man of the yuel tresoure bryngith forth yuel thingis; for of the plente of the herte the mouth spekith.
25187	42	6	46	And what clepen ye me, Lord, Lord, and doon not tho thingis that Y seie.
25188	42	6	47	Eche that cometh to me, and herith my wordis, and doith hem, Y schal schewe to you, to whom he is lijk.
25189	42	6	48	He is lijk to a man that bildith an hous, that diggide deepe, and sette the foundement on a stoon. And whanne greet flood was maad, the flood was hurtlid to that hous, and it miyte not moue it, for it was foundid on a sad stoon.
25190	42	6	49	But he that herith, and doith not, is lijk to a man bildynge his hous on erthe with outen foundement; in to which the flood was hurlid, and anoon it felle doun; and the fallyng doun of that hous was maad greet.
25191	42	7	1	And whanne he hadde fulfillid alle hise wordis in to the eeris of the puple, he entride in to Cafarnaum.
25192	42	7	2	But a seruaunt of a centurien, that was precious to hym, was sijk, and drawynge to the deeth.
25193	42	7	3	And whanne he hadde herd of Jhesu, he sente to hym the eldere men of Jewis, and preiede hym, that he wolde come, and heele his seruaunt.
25194	42	7	4	And whanne thei camen to Jhesu, thei preieden hym bisili, and seiden to hym, For he is worthi, that thou graunte to hym this thing;
25195	42	7	5	for he loueth oure folk, and he bildide to vs a synagoge.
25196	42	7	6	And Jhesus wente with hem. And whanne he was not fer fro the hous, the centurien sente to hym freendis, and seide, Lord, nyle thou be trauelid, for Y am not worthi, that thou entre vnder my roof;
25197	42	7	7	for which thing and Y demede not my silf worthi, that Y come to thee; but seie thou bi word, and my child schal be helid.
25198	42	7	8	For Y am a man ordeyned vndur power, and haue knyytis vndur me; and Y seie to this, Go, and he goith, and to anothir, Come, and he cometh, and to my seruaunt, Do this thing, and he doith.
25199	42	7	9	And whanne this thing was herd, Jhesus wondride; and seide to the puple suynge hym, Treuli Y seie to you, nether in Israel Y foond so greet feith.
25200	42	7	10	And thei that weren sent, turneden ayen home, and founden the seruaunt hool, which was sijk.
25201	42	7	11	And it was don aftirward, Jhesus wente in to a citee, that is clepid Naym, and hise disciplis; and ful greet puple wente with hym.
25202	42	7	12	And whanne he cam nyy to the yate of the citee, lo! the sone of a womman that hadde no mo children, was borun out deed; and this was a widowe; and myche puple of the citee with hir.
25203	42	7	13	And whanne the Lord Jhesu hadde seyn hir, he hadde reuthe on hir, and seide to hir, Nyle thou wepe.
25204	42	7	14	And he cam nyy, and touchide the beere; and thei that baren stoden. And he seide, Yonge man, Y seie to thee, rise vp.
25205	42	7	15	And he that was deed sat vp ayen, and bigan to speke; and he yaf hym to his modir.
25206	42	7	16	And drede took alle men, and thei magnyfieden God, and seiden, For a grete profete is rysun among vs, and, For God hath visitid his puple.
25207	42	7	17	And this word wente out of hym in to al Judee, and in to al the cuntre aboute.
25208	42	7	18	And Joones disciplis toolden hym of alle these thingis.
25209	42	7	19	And Joon clepide tweyn of hise disciplis, and sente hem to Jhesu, and seide, Art thou he that is to come, or abiden we anothir?
25210	42	7	20	And whanne the men cam to hym, thei seiden, Joon Baptist sente vs to thee, and seide, Art thou he that is to come, or we abiden anothir?
25211	42	7	21	And in that our he heelide many men of her sijknessis, and woundis, and yuel spiritis; and he yaf siyt to many blynde men.
25212	42	7	22	And Jhesus answerde, and seide to hem, Go ye ayen, and telle ye to Joon tho thingis that ye han herd and seyn; blynde men seyn, crokid men goen, mesels ben maad cleene, deef men heren, deed men risen ayen, pore men ben takun to prechyng of the gospel.
25213	42	7	23	And he that schal not be sclaundrid in me, is blessid.
25214	42	7	24	And whanne the messangeris of Joon weren go forth, he bigan to seie of Joon to the puple,
25215	42	7	25	What wenten ye out in to desert to se? a reed waggid with the wynd?
25216	42	7	26	But what wenten ye out to se? a man clothid with softe clothis? Lo! thei that ben in precious cloth and in delicis, ben in kyngis housis. But what wenten ye out to se? a profete? Yhe, Y seie to you, and more than a profete.
25217	42	7	27	This is he, of whom it is writun, Lo! Y sende myn aungel bifor thi face, which schal make `thi weie redi bifor thee.
25218	42	7	28	Certis Y seie to you, there is no man more prophete among children of wymmen, than is Joon; but he that is lesse in the kyngdom of heuenes, is more than he.
25219	42	7	29	And al the puple herynge, and pupplicans, that hadden be baptisid with baptym of Joon, iustifieden God;
25220	42	7	30	but the Farisees and the wise men of the lawe, that weren not baptisid of hym, dispisiden the counsel of God ayens hem silf.
25221	42	7	31	And the Lord seide, Therfor to whom schal Y seie `men of this generacioun lijk, and to whom ben thei lijk?
25222	42	7	32	Thei ben lijk to children sittynge in chepyng, and spekynge togider, and seiynge, We han sungun to you with pipis, and ye han not daunsid; we han maad mornyng, and ye han not wept.
25223	42	7	33	For Joon Baptist cam, nethir etynge breed, ne drynkynge wyne, and ye seyen, He hath a feend.
25224	42	7	34	Mannus sone cam etynge and drynkynge, and ye seien, Lo! a man a deuourer, and drynkynge wyne, a frend of pupplicans and of synful men.
25225	42	7	35	And wisdom is iustified of her sones.
25226	42	7	36	But oon of the Farisees preiede Jhesu, that he schulde ete with hym. And he entride in to the hous of the Farise, and sat at the mete.
25227	42	7	37	And lo! a synful womman, that was in the citee, as sche knewe, that Jhesu sat at the mete in the hous of the Farisee, sche brouyte an alabaustre box of oynement;
25228	42	7	38	and sche stood bihynde bysidis hise feet, and bigan to moiste hise feet with teeris, and wipide with the heeris of hir heed, and kiste hise feet, and anoyntide with oynement.
25229	42	7	39	And the Farise seynge, that hadde clepide hym, seide within hym silf, seiynge, If this were a prophete, he schulde wite, who and what maner womman it were that touchith hym, for sche is a synful womman.
25230	42	7	40	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hym, Symount, Y haue sumthing to seie to thee. And he seide, Maistir, seie thou.
25231	42	7	41	And he answeride, Twei dettouris weren to o lener; and oon auyt fyue hundrid pans, and `the other fifti; but whanne thei hadden not wherof `thei schulden yeelde, he foryaf to bothe. Who thanne loueth hym more?
25232	42	7	43	Symount answeride, and seide, Y gesse, that he to whom he foryaf more. And he answeride to hym, Thou hast demyd riytli.
25233	42	7	44	And he turnede to the womman, and seide to Symount, Seest thou this womman? I entride into thin hous, thou yaf no watir to my feet; but this hath moistid my feet with teeris, and wipide with hir heeris.
25234	42	7	45	Thou hast not youun to me a cosse; but this, sithen sche entride, ceesside not to kisse my feet.
25235	42	7	46	Thou anoyntidist not myn heed with oile; but this anoyntide my feet with oynement.
25236	42	7	47	For the which thing Y seie to thee, many synnes ben foryouun to hir, for sche hath loued myche; and to whom is lesse foryouun, he loueth lesse.
25237	42	7	48	And Jhesus seide to hir, Thi synnes ben foryouun to thee.
25238	42	7	49	And thei that saten to gider at the mete, bigunnen to seie with ynne hem silf, Who is this that foryyueth synnes.
25239	42	7	50	But he seide to the womman, Thi feith hath maad thee saaf; go thou in pees.
25240	42	8	1	And it was don aftirward, and Jhesus made iourney bi citees and castels, prechynge and euangelisynge the rewme of God, and twelue with hym;
25241	42	8	2	and sum wymmen that weren heelid of wickid spiritis and sijknessis, Marie, that is clepid Maudeleyn, of whom seuene deuelis wenten out,
25242	42	8	3	and Joone, the wijf of Chuse, the procuratoure of Eroude, and Susanne, and many othir, that mynystriden to hym of her ritchesse.
25243	42	8	4	And whanne myche puple was come togidir, and men hiyeden to hym fro the citees, he seide bi a symylitude,
25244	42	8	5	He that sowith, yede out to sowe his seed. And while he sowith, sum fel bisidis the weie, and was defoulid, and briddis of the eir eten it.
25245	42	8	6	And othir fel on a stoon, and it sprunge vp, and driede, for it hadde not moysture.
25246	42	8	7	And othir fel among thornes, and the thornes sprongen vp togider, and strangliden it.
25247	42	8	8	And othir fel in to good erthe, and it sprungun made an hundrid foold fruyt. He seide these thingis, and criede, He that hath eeris of heryng, here he.
25248	42	8	9	But hise disciplis axiden him, what this parable was.
25249	42	8	10	And he seide to hem, To you it is grauntid to knowe the pryuete of the kyngdom of God; but to othir men in parablis, that thei seynge se not, and thei herynge vndurstonde not.
25250	42	8	11	And this is the parable.
25251	42	8	12	The seed is Goddis word; and thei that ben bisidis the weie, ben these that heren; and aftirward the feend cometh, and takith awei the word fro her herte, lest thei bileuynge be maad saaf.
25252	42	8	13	But thei that fel on a stoon, ben these that whanne thei han herd, resseyuen the word with ioye. And these han not rootis; for at a tyme thei bileuen, and in tyme of temptacioun thei goen awei.
25253	42	8	14	But that that fel among thornes, ben these that herden, and of bisynessis, and ritchessis, and lustis of lijf thei gon forth, and ben stranglid, and bryngen forth no fruyt.
25254	42	8	15	But that that fel in to good erthe, ben these that, in a good herte, and best heren the word, and holdun, and brengen forth fruyt in pacience.
25255	42	8	16	No man lityneth a lanterne, and hilith it with a vessel, or puttith it vndur a bed, but on a candilstike, that men that entren seen liyt.
25256	42	8	17	For ther is no priuei thing, which schal not be openyd, nether hid thing, which schal not be knowun, and come in to open.
25257	42	8	18	Therfor se ye, hou ye heren; for it schal be youun to hym that hath, and who euer hath not, also that that he weneth that he haue, schal be takun awei fro hym.
25258	42	8	19	And his modir and britheren camen to hym; and thei myyten not come to hym for the puple.
25259	42	8	20	And it was teeld to hym, Thi modir and thi britheren stonden with outforth, willynge to se thee.
25260	42	8	21	And he answeride, and seide to hem, My modir and my britheren ben these, that heren the word of God, and doon it.
25261	42	8	22	And it was don in oon of daies, he wente vp in to a boot, and hise disciplis. And he seide to hem, Passe we ouer the see. And thei wenten vp.
25262	42	8	23	And while thei rowiden, he slepte. And a tempest of wynde cam doun in to the watir, and thei weren dryuun hidur and thidur with wawis, and weren in perel.
25263	42	8	24	And thei camen nyy, and reisiden hym, and seiden, Comaundoure, we perischen. And he roos, and blamyde the wynde, and the tempest of the watir; and it ceesside, and pesibilte was maad.
25264	42	8	25	And he seide to hem, Where is youre feith? Which dredynge wondriden, and seiden togidir, Who, gessist thou, is this? for he comaundith to wyndis and to the see, and thei obeien to hym.
25265	42	8	26	And thei rowiden to the cuntree of Gerasenus, that is ayens Galilee.
25266	42	8	27	And whanne he wente out to the loond, a man ran to hym, that hadde a deuel long tyme, and he was not clothid with cloth, nether dwellide in hous, but in sepulcris.
25267	42	8	28	This, whanne he saiy Jhesu, fel doun bifor hym, and he criynge with a greet vois seide, What to me and to thee, Jhesu, the sone of the hiyest God? Y biseche thee, that thou turmente `not me.
25268	42	8	29	For he comaundide the vncleene spirit, that he schulde go out fro the man. For he took hym ofte tymes, and he was boundun with cheynes, and kept in stockis, and, whanne the boondis weren brokun, he was lad of deuelis in to desert.
25269	42	8	30	And Jhesus axide hym, and seide, What name is to thee? And he seide, A legioun; for many deuelis weren entrid in to hym.
25270	42	8	31	And thei preyden hym, that he schulde not comaunde hem, that thei schulden go in to helle.
25271	42	8	32	And there was a flok of many swyne lesewynge in an hil, and thei preieden hym, that he schulde suffre hem to entre in to hem. And he suffride hem.
25272	42	8	33	And so the deuelis wenten out fro the man, and entriden in to the swyne; and with a birre the flok wente heedlyng in to the pool, and was drenchid.
25273	42	8	34	And whanne the hirdis sayn this thing don, thei flowen, and tolden in to the cite, and in to the townes.
25274	42	8	35	And thei yeden out to se that thing that was don. And thei camen to Jhesu, and thei founden the man sittynge clothid, fro whom the deuelis wenten out, and in hool mynde at hise feet; and thei dredden.
25275	42	8	36	And thei that sayn tolden to hem, hou he was maad hool of the legioun.
25276	42	8	37	And al the multitude of the cuntre of Gerasenus preiede hym, that he schulde go fro hem, for thei werun holdun with greet drede. He wente vp in to a boot, and turnede ayen.
25277	42	8	38	And the man of whom the deuelis weren gon out, preide hym, that he schulde be with hym. Jhesus lefte hym,
25278	42	8	39	and seide, Go ayen in to thin hous, and telle hou grete thingis God hath don to thee. And he wente thorow al the cite, and prechide, hou grete thingis Jhesus hadde don to hym.
25279	42	8	40	And it was don, whanne Jhesus was gon ayen, the puple resseyuede hym; for alle weren abidynge hym.
25280	42	8	41	And lo! a man, to whom the name was Jayrus, and he was prynce of a synagoge; and he fel doun at the feet of Jhesu, and preiede hym, that he schulde entre in to his hous,
25281	42	8	42	for he hadde but o douyter `almost of twelue yeer eelde, and sche was deed. And it bifel, the while he wente, he was thrungun of the puple.
25282	42	8	43	And a womman that hadde a flux of blood twelue yeer, and hadde spendid al hir catel in leechis, and sche miyte not be curid of ony,
25283	42	8	44	and sche cam nyy bihynde, and touchide the hem of his cloth, and anoon the fluxe of hir blood ceesside.
25284	42	8	45	And Jhesus seide, Who is that touchide me? And whanne alle men denyeden, Petre seide, and thei that weren with hym, Comaundour, the puple thristen, and disesen thee, and thou seist, Who touchide me?
25285	42	8	46	And Jhesus seide, Summan hath touchid me, for that vertu yede out of me.
25286	42	8	47	And the womman seynge, that it was not hid fro hym, cam tremblynge, and fel doun at hise feet, and for what cause sche hadde touchid hym sche schewide bifor al the puple, and hou anoon sche was helid.
25287	42	8	48	And he seide to hir, Douytir, thi feith hath maad thee saaf; go thou in pees.
25288	42	8	49	And yit while he spak, a man cam fro the prince of the synagoge, and seide to hym, Thi douytir is deed, nyle thou trauel the maister.
25289	42	8	50	And whanne this word was herd, Jhesus answeride to the fadir of the damysel, Nyle thou drede, but bileue thou oonli, and sche schal be saaf.
25290	42	8	51	And whanne he cam to the hous, he suffride no man to entre with hym, but Petir and Joon and James, and the fadir and the modir of the damysel.
25291	42	8	52	And alle wepten, and biweileden hir. And he seide, Nyle ye wepe, for the damysel is not deed, but slepith.
25292	42	8	53	And thei scorneden hym, and wisten that sche was deed.
25293	42	8	54	But he helde hir hoond, and criede, and seide, Damysel, rise vp.
25294	42	8	55	And hir spirit turnede ayen, and sche roos anoon. And he comaundide to yyue to hir to ete.
25295	42	8	56	And hir fadir and modir wondriden greetli; and he comaundide hem, that thei schulden not seie to ony that thing that was don.
25296	42	9	1	And whanne the twelue apostlis weren clepid togidir, Jhesus yaf to hem vertu and power on alle deuelis, and that thei schulden heele sijknessis.
25297	42	9	2	And he sente hem for to preche the kyngdom of God, and to heele sijk men.
25298	42	9	3	And he seide to hem, No thing take ye in the weie, nether yerde, ne scrippe, nether breed, ne money, and nether haue ye two cootis.
25299	42	9	4	And in to what hous that ye entren, dwelle ye there, and go ye not out fro thennus.
25300	42	9	5	And who euer resseyuen not you, go ye out of that citee, and schake ye of the poudir of youre feet in to witnessyng on hem.
25301	42	9	6	And thei yeden forth, and wenten aboute bi castels, prechynge and helynge euery where.
25302	42	9	7	And Eroude tetrak herde alle thingis that weren don of hym, and he doutide,
25303	42	9	8	for that it was seide of sum men, that Joon was risen fro deth; and of summen, that Elie hadde apperid; but of othere, that oon of the elde prophetis was risun.
25304	42	9	9	And Eroude seide, Y haue biheedid Joon; and who is this, of whom Y here siche thingis? And he souyte to se hym.
25305	42	9	10	And the apostlis turneden ayen, and tolden to hym alle thingis that thei hadden don. And he took hem, and wente bisidis in to a desert place, that is Bethsada.
25306	42	9	11	And whanne the puple knewen this, thei folewiden hym. And he resseyuede hem, and spak to hem of the kyngdom of God; and he heelide hem that hadden neede of cure.
25307	42	9	12	And the dai bigan to bowe doun, and the twelue camen, and seiden to hym, Leeue the puple, that thei go, and turne in to castels and townes, that ben aboute, that thei fynde mete, for we ben here in a desert place.
25308	42	9	13	And he seide to hem, Yue ye to hem to ete. And thei seiden, Ther ben not to vs mo than fyue looues and twei fischis, but perauenture that we go, and bie meetis to al this puple.
25309	42	9	14	And the men weren almost fyue thousynde. And he seide to hise disciplis, Make ye hem sitte to mete bi cumpanyes, a fifti to gidir.
25310	42	9	15	And thei diden so, and thei maden alle men sitte to mete.
25311	42	9	16	And whanne he hadde take the fyue looues and twei fischis, he biheeld in to heuene, and blesside hem, and brak, and delide to hise disciplis, that thei schulden sette forth bifor the cumpanyes.
25312	42	9	17	And alle men eeten, and weren fulfillid; and that that lefte to hem of brokun metis was takun vp, twelue cofyns.
25313	42	9	18	And it was don, whanne he was aloone preiynge, hise disciplis weren with hym, and he axide hem, and seide, Whom seien the puple that Y am?
25314	42	9	19	And thei answeriden, and seiden, Joon Baptist, othir seien Elie, and othir seien, o profete of the formere is risun.
25315	42	9	20	And he seide to hem, But who seien ye that Y am? Symount Petir answeride, and seide, The Crist of God.
25316	42	9	21	And he blamynge hem comaundide that thei schulden seie to no man,
25317	42	9	22	and seide these thingis, For it bihoueth mannus sone to suffre many thingis, and to be repreued of the elder men, and of the princis of prestis, and of scribis, and to be slayn, and the thridde dai to rise ayen.
25318	42	9	23	And he seide to alle, If ony wole come aftir me, denye he hym silf, and take he his cross euery dai, and sue he me.
25319	42	9	24	For he that wole make his lijf saaf schal leese it; and he that leesith his lijf for me, schal make it saaf.
25320	42	9	25	And what profitith it to a man, if he wynne al the world, and leese hymsilf, and do peiryng of him silf.
25321	42	9	26	For who so schameth me and my wordis, mannus sone schal schame hym, whanne he cometh in his maieste, and of the fadris, and of the hooli aungels.
25322	42	9	27	And Y seie to you, verily ther ben summe stondynge here, whiche schulen not taste deeth, til thei seen the rewme of God.
25323	42	9	28	And it was don aftir these wordis almest eiyte daies, and he took Petre and James and Joon, and he stiede in to an hil, to preye.
25324	42	9	29	And while he preiede, the licnesse of his cheer was chaungid, and his clothing was whit schynynge.
25325	42	9	30	And lo! two men spaken with hym,
25326	42	9	31	and Moises and Helie weren seen in maieste; and thei sayn his goyng out, which he schulde fulfille in Jerusalem.
25327	42	9	32	And Petre, and thei that weren with hym, weren heuy of sleep, and thei wakynge saien his majeste, and the twey men that stoden with hym.
25328	42	9	33	And it was don, whanne thei departiden fro hym, Petir seide to Jhesu, Comaundour, it is good that we be here, and make we here thre tabernaclis, oon to thee, and oon to Moises, and oon to Elie. And he wiste not what he schulde seie.
25329	42	9	34	But while he spak these thingis, a cloude was maad, and ouerschadewide hem; and thei dredden, whanne thei entriden in to the cloude.
25330	42	9	35	And a vois was maad out of the cloude, and seide, This is my derworth sone, here ye hym.
25331	42	9	36	And while the vois was maad, Jhesu was foundun aloone. And thei weren stille, and to no man seiden in tho daies ouyt of tho thingis, that thei hadden seyn.
25332	42	9	37	But it was doon in the dai suynge, whanne thei camen doun of the hil, myche puple mette hem.
25333	42	9	38	And lo! a man of the cumpany criede, and seide, Maister, Y biseche thee, biholde my sone, for Y haue no mo; and lo!
25334	42	9	39	a spirit takith hym, and sudenli he crieth, and hurtlith doun, and to-drawith hym with fome, and vnneth he goith awei al to-drawynge hym.
25335	42	9	40	And Y preiede thi disciplis, that thei schulden caste hym out, and thei myyten not.
25336	42	9	41	And Jhesus answerde and seide to hem, A! vnfeithful generacioun and weiward, hou long schal Y be at you, and suffre you? brynge hidur thi sone.
25337	42	9	42	And whanne he cam nyy, the deuel hurtlide hym doun, and to-braidide hym. And Jhesus blamyde `the vnclene spirit, and heelide the child, and yeldide him to his fadir.
25338	42	9	43	And alle men wondriden greetli in the gretnesse of God. And whanne alle men wondriden in alle thingis that he dide, he seide to hise disciplis,
25339	42	9	44	Putte ye these wordis in youre hertis, for it is to come, that mannus sone be bitrayed in to the hondis of men.
25340	42	9	45	And thei knewen not this word, and it was hid bifor hem, that thei feeliden it not; and thei dredden to axe hym of this word.
25341	42	9	46	But a thouyt entride in to hem, who of hem schulde be grettest.
25342	42	9	47	And Jhesu, seynge the thouytis of the herte of hem, took a child, and settide hym bisidis hym;
25343	42	9	48	and seide to hem, Who euer resseyueth this child in my name, resseyueth me; and who euer resseyueth me, resseiueth him that sente me; for he that is leest among you alle, is the grettest.
25344	42	9	49	And Joon answeride and seide, Comaundoure, we sayn a man castynge out feendis in thi name, and we han forbedun hym, for he sueth not thee with vs.
25345	42	9	50	And Jhesus seide to hym, Nyle ye forbede, for he that is not ayens vs, is for vs.
25346	42	9	51	And it was don, whanne the daies of his takyng vp weren fulfillid, he settide faste his face, to go to Jerusalem,
25347	42	9	52	and sente messangeris bifor his siyt. And thei yeden, and entriden in to a citee of Samaritans, to make redi to hym.
25348	42	9	53	And thei resseyueden not hym, for the face `was of hym goynge in to Jerusalem.
25349	42	9	54	And whanne James and Joon, hise disciplis, seyn, thei seiden, Lord, wolt thou that we seien, that fier come doun fro heuene, and waste hem?
25350	42	9	55	And he turnede, and blamyde hem, and seide, Ye witen not, whos spiritis ye ben;
25351	42	9	56	for mannus sone cam not to leese mennus soulis, but to saue. And thei wenten in to another castel.
25352	42	9	57	And it was don, whanne thei walkeden in the weie, a man seide to hym, Y schal sue thee, whidur euer thou go.
25353	42	9	58	And Jhesus seide to hym, Foxis han dennes, and briddis of the eir han nestis, but mannus sone hath not where he reste his heed.
25354	42	9	59	And he seide to another, Sue thou me. And he seide, Lord, suffre me first to go, and birie my fadir.
25355	42	9	60	And Jhesus seide to hym, Suffre that deede men birie hir deede men; but go thou, and telle the kyngdom of God.
25356	42	9	61	And another seide, Lord, Y schal sue thee, but first suffre me to leeue `alle thingis that ben at hoom.
25357	42	9	62	And Jhesus seide to hym, No man that puttith his hoond to the plouy, and biholdynge bacward, is able to the rewme of God.
25358	42	10	1	And aftir these thingis the Lord Jhesu ordeynede also othir seuenti and tweyn, and sente hem bi tweyn and tweyn bifor his face in to euery citee and place, whidir he was to come.
25359	42	10	2	And he seide to hem, There is myche ripe corn, and fewe werke men; therfor preie ye the lord of the ripe corn, that he sende werke men in to his ripe corn.
25360	42	10	3	Go ye, lo! Y sende you as lambren among wolues.
25361	42	10	4	Therfor nyle ye bere a sachel, nethir scrippe, nethir schoon, and greete ye no man bi the weie.
25362	42	10	5	In to what hous that ye entren, first seie ye, Pees to this hous.
25363	42	10	6	And if a sone of pees be there, youre pees schal reste on hym; but if noon, it schal turne ayen to you.
25364	42	10	7	And dwelle ye in the same hous, etynge and drynkynge tho thingis that ben at hem; for a werk man is worthi his hire. Nyle ye passe from hous in to hous.
25365	42	10	8	And in to what euer citee ye entren, and thei resseyuen you, ete ye tho thingis that ben set to you;
25366	42	10	9	and heele ye the sijke men that ben in that citee. And seie ye to hem, The kyngdom of God schal neiye in to you.
25367	42	10	10	In to what citee ye entren, and thei resseyuen you not, go ye out in to the streetis of it,
25368	42	10	11	and seie ye, We wipen of ayens you the poudir that cleued to vs of youre citee; netheles wite ye this thing, that the rewme of God schal come nyy.
25369	42	10	12	Y seie to you, that to Sodom it schal be esiere than to that citee in that dai.
25370	42	10	13	Wo to thee, Corosayn; wo to thee, Bethsaida; for if in Tyre and Sidon the vertues hadden be don, whiche han be don in you, sum tyme thei wolden haue sete in heyre and asches, and haue don penaunce.
25371	42	10	14	Netheles to Tire and Sidon it schal be esiere in the doom than to you.
25372	42	10	15	And thou, Cafarnaum, art enhaunsid `til to heuene; thou schalt be drenchid `til in to helle.
25373	42	10	16	He that herith you, herith me; and he that dispisith you, dispisith me; and he that dispisith me, dispisith hym that sente me.
25374	42	10	17	And the two and seuenti disciplis turneden ayen with ioye, and seiden, Lord, also deuelis ben suget to vs in thi name.
25375	42	10	18	And he seide to hem, Y saiy Sathnas fallynge doun fro heuene, as leit.
25376	42	10	19	And lo! Y haue youun to you power to trede on serpentis, and on scorpyouns, and on al the vertu of the enemy, and nothing schal anoye you.
25377	42	10	20	Netheles nyle ye ioye on this thing, that spiritis ben suget to you; but ioye ye, that youre names ben writun in heuenes.
25378	42	10	21	In thilk our he gladide in the Hooli Goost, and seide, Y knouleche to thee, fadir, Lord of heuene and of erthe, for thou hast hid these thingis fro wise men and prudent, and hast schewid hem to smale children. Yhe, fadir, for so it pleside bifor thee.
25379	42	10	22	Alle thingis ben youun to me of my fadir, and no man woot, who is the sone, but the fadir; and who is the fadir, but the sone, and to whom the sone wole schewe.
25380	42	10	23	And he turnede to hise disciplis, and seide, Blessid ben the iyen, that seen tho thingis that ye seen.
25381	42	10	24	For Y seie to you, that many prophetis and kyngis wolden haue seie tho thingis, that ye seen, and thei sayn not; and here tho thingis, that ye heren, and thei herden not.
25382	42	10	25	And lo! a wise man of the lawe ros vp, temptynge hym, and seiynge, Maister, what thing schal Y do to haue euerlastynge lijf?
25383	42	10	26	And he seide to hym, What is writun in the lawe? hou redist thou?
25384	42	10	27	He answeride, and seide, Thou schalt loue thi Lord God of al thin herte, and of al thi soule, and of alle thi strengthis, and of al thi mynde; and thi neiybore as thi silf.
25385	42	10	28	And Jhesus seide to hym, Thou hast answerid riytli; do this thing, and thou schalt lyue.
25386	42	10	29	But he willynge to iustifie hym silf, seide to Jhesu, And who is my neiybore?
25387	42	10	30	And Jhesu biheld, and seide, A man cam doun fro Jerusalem in to Jerico, and fel among theues, and thei robbiden hym, and woundiden hym, and wente awei, and leften the man half alyue.
25388	42	10	31	And it bifel, that a prest cam doun the same weie, and passide forth, whanne he hadde seyn hym.
25389	42	10	32	Also a dekene, whanne he was bisidis the place, and saiy him, passide forth.
25390	42	10	33	But a Samaritan, goynge the weie, cam bisidis hym; and he siy hym, and hadde reuthe on hym;
25391	42	10	34	and cam to hym, and boond togidir hise woundis, and helde in oyle and wynne; and leide hym on his beest, and ledde in to an ostrie, and dide the cure of hym.
25392	42	10	35	And another dai he brouyte forth twey pans, and yaf to the ostiler, and seide, Haue the cure of hym; and what euer thou schalt yyue ouer, Y schal yelde to thee, whanne Y come ayen.
25393	42	10	36	Who of these thre, semeth to thee, was neiybore to hym, that fel among theues?
25394	42	10	37	And he seide, He that dide merci in to hym. And Jhesus seide to hym, Go thou, and do thou on lijk maner.
25395	42	10	38	And it was don, while thei wenten, he entride in to a castel; and a womman, Martha bi name, resseyuede hym in to hir hous.
25396	42	10	39	And to this was a sistir, Marie bi name, which also sat bisidis the feet of the Lord, and herde his word.
25397	42	10	40	But Martha bisiede aboute the ofte seruyce. And sche stood, and seide, Lord, takist thou no kepe, that my sistir hath left me aloone to serue? therfor seie thou to hir, that sche helpe me.
25398	42	10	41	And the Lord answerde, and seide to hir, Martha, Martha, thou art bysi, and art troublid aboute ful many thingis;
25399	42	10	42	but o thing is necessarie.
25400	42	10	43	Marie hath chosun the best part, which schal not be takun awei fro hir.
25401	42	11	1	And it was don, whanne he was preiynge in a place, as he ceesside, oon of hise disciplis seide to hym, Lord, teche vs to preye, as Joon tauyte hise disciplis.
25402	42	11	2	And he seide to hem, Whanne ye preien, seie ye, Fadir, halewid be thi name. Thi kyngdom come to.
25403	42	11	3	Yyue `to vs to dai oure ech daies breed.
25404	42	11	4	And foryyue to vs oure synnes, as we foryyuen to ech man that owith to vs. And lede vs not in to temptacioun.
25405	42	11	5	And he seide to hem, Who of you schal haue a freend, and schal go to hym at mydnyyt, and schal seie to hym, Freend, leene to me thre looues;
25406	42	11	6	for my freend cometh to me fro the weie, and Y haue not what Y schal sette bifor hym.
25407	42	11	7	And he with ynforth answere and seie, Nyle thou be heuy to me; the dore is now schit, and my children ben with me in bed; Y may not rise, and yyue to thee.
25408	42	11	8	And if he schal dwelle stil knockynge, Y seie to you, thouy he schal not rise, and yyue to him, for that that he is his freend, netheles for his contynuel axyng he schal ryse, and yyue to hym, as many as he hath nede to.
25409	42	11	9	And Y seie to you, axe ye, and it schal be youun to you; seke ye, and ye schulen fynde; knocke ye, and it schal be openyd to you.
25410	42	11	10	For ech that axith, takith, and he that sekith, fyndith; and to a man that knockith, it schal be openyd.
25411	42	11	11	Therfor who of you axith his fadir breed, whether he schal yyue hym a stoon? or if he axith fisch, whether he schal yyue hym a serpent for the fisch?
25412	42	11	12	or if he axe an eye, whether he schal a reche hym a scorpioun?
25413	42	11	13	Therfor if ye, whanne ye ben yuel, kunnen yyue good yiftis to youre children, hou myche more youre fadir of heuene schal yyue a good spirit to men that axith him.
25414	42	11	14	And Jhesus was castynge out a feend, and he was doumbe. And whanne he hadde cast out the feend, the doumbe man spak; and the puple wondride.
25415	42	11	15	And sum of hem seiden, In Belsabub, prince of deuelis, he castith out deuelis.
25416	42	11	16	And othir temptinge axiden of hym a tokene fro heuene.
25417	42	11	17	And as he saiy the thouytis of hem, he seide to hem, Euery rewme departid ayens it silf, schal be desolat, and an hous schal falle on an hous.
25418	42	11	18	And if Sathanas be departid ayens hym silf, hou schal his rewme stonde? For ye seien, that Y caste out feendis in Belsabub.
25419	42	11	19	And if Y in Belsabub caste out fendis, in whom casten out youre sones? Therfor thei schulen be youre domesmen.
25420	42	11	20	But if Y caste out fendis in the fyngir of God, thanne the rewme of God is comun among you.
25421	42	11	21	Whanne a strong armed man kepith his hous, alle thingis that he weldith ben in pees.
25422	42	11	22	But if a stronger than he come vpon hym, and ouercome hym, he schal take awei al his armere, in which he tristide, and schal dele abrood his robries.
25423	42	11	23	He that is not with me, is ayens me; and he that gederith not togidir with me, scaterith abrood.
25424	42	11	24	Whanne an vnclene spirit goith out of a man, he wandrith bi drie placis, and sekith reste; and he fyndynge not, seith, Y schal turne ayen in to myn hous, fro whannes Y cam out.
25425	42	11	25	And whanne he cometh, he fyndith it clansid with besyms, and fayre arayed.
25426	42	11	26	Thanne he goith, and takith with hym seuene othere spirits worse than hym silf, and thei entren, and dwellen there. And the laste thingis of that man ben maad worse than the formere.
25427	42	11	27	And it was don, whanne he hadde seid these thingis, a womman of the cumpanye reride hir vois, and seide to hym, Blessid be the wombe that bare thee, and blessid be the tetis that thou hast soken.
25428	42	11	28	And he seide, But yhe blessid be thei, that heren the word of God, and kepen it.
25429	42	11	29	And whanne the puple runnen togidere, he bigan to seie, This generacioun is a weiward generacioun; it sekith a token, and a tokene schal not be youun to it, but the tokene of Jonas, the profete.
25430	42	11	30	For as Jonas was a tokene to men of Nynyue, so mannus sone schal be to this generacioun.
25431	42	11	31	The queen of the south schal rise in doom with men of this generacioun, and schal condempne hem; for sche cam fro the endis of the erthe, for to here the wisdom of Salomon, and lo! here is a gretter than Salomon.
25432	42	11	32	Men of Nynyue schulen rise in doom with this generacioun, and schulen condempne it; for thei diden penaunce in the prechyng of Jonas, and lo! here is a gretter than Jonas.
25433	42	11	33	No man tendith a lanterne, and puttith in hidils, nether vndur a buyschel, but on a candilstike, that thei that goen in, se liyt.
25434	42	11	34	The lanterne of thi bodi is thin iye; if thin iye be symple, al thi bodi schal be liyti; but if it be weyward, al thi bodi schal be derkful.
25435	42	11	35	Therfor se thou, lest the liyt that is in thee, be derknessis.
25436	42	11	36	Therfor if al thi bodi be briyt, and haue no part of derknessis, it schal be al briyt, and as a lanterne of briytnesse it schal yyue liyt to thee.
25437	42	11	37	And whanne he spak, a Farisee preiede him, that he schulde ete with hym. And he entride, and sat to the meete.
25438	42	11	38	And the Farisee bigan to seie, gessynge with ynne hym silf, whi he was not waschen bifor mete.
25439	42	11	39	And the Lord seide to hym, Now ye Farisees clensen that that is with outenforth of the cuppe and the plater; but that thing that is with ynne of you, is ful of raueyn and wickidnesse.
25440	42	11	40	Foolis, whether he that made that that is withoutenforth, made not also that that is with ynne?
25441	42	11	41	Netheles that that is ouer plus, yyue ye almes, and lo! alle thingis ben cleene to you.
25442	42	11	42	But wo to you, Farisees, that tithen mynte, and rue, and ech eerbe, and leeuen doom and the charite of God. For it bihofte to do these thingis, and not leeue tho.
25443	42	11	43	Wo to you, Farisees, that louen the firste chaieris in synagogis, and salutaciouns in chepyng.
25444	42	11	44	Wo to you, that ben as sepulcris, that ben not seyn, and men walkynge aboue witen not.
25445	42	11	45	But oon of the wise men of the lawe answeride, and seide to hym, Maystir, thou seiynge these thingis, also to vs doist dispit.
25446	42	11	46	And he seide, Also wo to you, wise men of lawe, for ye chargen men with birthuns which thei moun not bere, and ye you silf with youre o fyngur touchen not the heuynessis.
25447	42	11	47	Wo to you, that bilden toumbis of profetis; and youre fadris slowen hem.
25448	42	11	48	Treuli ye witnessen, that ye consenten to the werkis of youre fadris; for thei slowen hem, but ye bilden her sepulcris.
25449	42	11	49	Therfor the wisdom of God seide, Y schal sende to hem profetis and apostlis, and of hem thei schulen sle and pursue,
25450	42	11	50	that the blood of alle prophetis, that was sched fro the making of the world, be souyt of this generacioun;
25451	42	11	51	fro the blood of the iust Abel to the blood of Zacharie, that was slayn bitwixe the auter and the hous. So Y seie to you, it schal be souyt of this generacioun.
25452	42	11	52	Wo to you, wise men of the lawe, for ye han takun awei the keye of kunnyng; and ye yow silf entriden not, and ye han forbeden hem that entriden.
25453	42	11	53	And whanne he seide these thingis to hem, the Farisees and wise men of lawe bigunnen greuousli to ayenstonde, and stoppe his mouth of many thingis,
25454	42	11	54	aspiynge hym, and sekynge to take sum thing of his mouth, to accuse hym.
25455	42	12	1	And whanne myche puple stood aboute, so that thei treden ech on othir, he bigan to seie to hise disciplis, Be ye war of the sourdouy of the Farisees, that is ypocrisie.
25456	42	12	2	For no thing is hilid, that schal not be schewid; nether hid, that schal not be wist.
25457	42	12	3	For whi tho thingis that ye han seid in derknessis, schulen be seid in liyt; and that that ye han spokun in eere in the couchis, schal be prechid in roofes.
25458	42	12	4	And Y seie to you, my freendis, be ye not a ferd of hem that sleen the bodie, and aftir these thingis han no more what thei schulen do.
25459	42	12	5	But Y schal schewe to you, whom ye schulen drede; drede ye hym, that aftir he hath slayn, he hath power to sende in to helle. And so Y seie to you, drede ye hym.
25460	42	12	6	Whether fyue sparowis ben not seld for twei halpens; and oon of hem is not in foryetyng bifor God?
25461	42	12	7	But also alle the heeris of youre heed ben noumbrid. Therfor nyle ye drede; ye ben of more prijs than many sparowis.
25462	42	12	8	Treuli Y seie to you, ech man that knoulechith me bifor men, mannus sone schal knouleche hym bifor the aungels of God.
25463	42	12	9	But he that denyeth me bifor men, schal be denyed bifor the aungels of God.
25464	42	12	10	And ech that seith a word ayens mannus sone, it schal be foryouun to hym; but it schal not be foryouun to hym, that blasfemeth ayens the Hooli Goost.
25465	42	12	11	And whanne thei leden you in to synagogis, and to magistratis, and potestatis, nyle ye `be bisie, hou or what ye schulen answere, or what ye schulen seie.
25466	42	12	12	For the Hooli Goost schal teche you in that our, what it bihoueth you to seie.
25467	42	12	13	And oon of the puple seide to hym, Maystir, seie to my brothir, that he departe with me the eritage.
25468	42	12	14	And he seyde to hym, Man, who ordeynede me a domesman, or a departere, on you?
25469	42	12	15	And he seide to hem, Se ye, and be ye war of al coueytice; for the lijf of a man is not in the abundaunce of tho thingis, whiche he weldith.
25470	42	12	16	And he tolde to hem a liknesse, and seide, The feeld of a riche man brouyte forth plenteuouse fruytis.
25471	42	12	17	And he thouyte with ynne hym silf, and seide, What schal Y do, for Y haue not whidur Y schal gadere my fruytis?
25472	42	12	18	And he seith, This thing Y schal do; Y schal throwe doun my bernes, and Y schal make gretter, and thidir Y schal gadir alle thingis that growen to me, and my goodis.
25473	42	12	19	And Y schal seie to my soule, Soule, thou hast many goodis kept in to ful many yeeris; rest thou, ete, drynke, and make feeste.
25474	42	12	20	And God seide to hym, Fool, in this nyyt thei schulen take thi lijf fro thee. And whos schulen tho thingis be, that thou hast arayed?
25475	42	12	21	So is he that tresourith to hym silf, and is not riche in God.
25476	42	12	22	And he seide to hise disciplis, Therfor Y seie to you, nyle ye be bisy to youre lijf, what ye schulen ete, nether to youre bodi, with what ye schulen be clothid.
25477	42	12	23	The lijf is more than mete, and the body more than clothing.
25478	42	12	24	Biholde ye crowis, for thei sowen not, nethir repen, to whiche is no celer, ne berne, and God fedith hem. Hou myche more ye ben of more prijs than thei.
25479	42	12	25	And who of you bithenkynge may put to o cubit to his stature?
25480	42	12	26	Therfor if ye moun not that that is leest, what ben ye bisie of othere thingis?
25481	42	12	27	Biholde ye the lilies of the feeld, hou thei wexen; thei trauelen not, nethir spynnen. And Y seie to you, that nethir Salomon in al his glorie was clothid as oon of these.
25482	42	12	28	And if God clothith thus the hey, that to dai is in the feeld, and to morewe is cast in to an ouen; hou myche more you of litil feith.
25483	42	12	29	And nyle ye seke, what ye schulen ete, or what ye schulen drynke; and nyle ye be reisid an hiy.
25484	42	12	30	For folkis of the world seken alle these thingis; `and your fadir woot, that ye neden alle these thingis.
25485	42	12	31	Netheles seke ye first the kyngdom of God, and alle these thingis schulen be caste to you.
25486	42	12	32	Nile ye, litil flok, drede, for it pleside to youre fadir to yyue you a kyngdom.
25487	42	12	33	Selle ye tho thingis that ye han in possessioun, and yyue ye almes. And make to you sachels that wexen not oolde, tresoure that failith not in heuenes, whidir a theef neiyith not, nether mouyt destruyeth.
25488	42	12	34	For where is thi tresoure, there thin herte schal be.
25489	42	12	35	Be youre leendis gird aboue, and lanternes brennynge in youre hoondis;
25490	42	12	36	and be ye lijk to men that abiden her lord, whanne he schal turne ayen fro the weddyngis, that whanne he schal come, and knocke, anoon thei openen to hym.
25491	42	12	37	Blessid be tho seruauntis, that whanne the lord schal come, he schal fynde wakynge. Treuli Y seie to you, that he schal girde hym silf, and make hem sitte to mete, and he schal go, and serue hem.
25492	42	12	38	And if he come in the secounde wakynge, and if he come in the thridde wakynge, and fynde so, tho seruauntis ben blessid.
25493	42	12	39	And wite ye this thing, for if an hosebonde man wiste, in what our the theef wolde come, sotheli he schulde wake, and not suffre his hous to be myned.
25494	42	12	40	And be ye redi, for in what our ye gessen not, mannus sone schal come.
25495	42	12	41	And Petre seide to hym, Lord, seist thou this parable to vs, or to alle?
25496	42	12	42	And the Lord seide, Who, gessist thou, is a trewe dispendere, and a prudent, whom the lord hath ordeyned on his meyne, to yyue hem in tyme mesure of whete?
25497	42	12	43	Blessid is that seruaunt, that the lord whanne he cometh, schal fynde so doynge.
25498	42	12	44	Verili Y seie to you, that on alle thingis that he weldith, he schal ordeyne hym.
25499	42	12	45	That if that seruaunt seie in his herte, My lord tarieth to come; and bigynne to smyte children, and handmaydenes, and ete, and drynke, and be fulfillid ouer mesure,
25500	42	12	46	the lord of that seruaunt schal come, in the dai that he hopith not, and the our that he woot not; and schal departe hym, and putte his part with vnfeithful men.
25501	42	12	47	But thilke seruaunt that knew the wille of his lord, and made not hym redi, and dide not aftir his wille, schal be betun with many betyngis.
25502	42	12	48	But he that knew not, and dide worthi thingis of strokis, schal be betun with fewe. For to eche man to whom myche is youun, myche schal be axid of hym; and thei schulen axe more of hym, to whom thei bitoken myche.
25503	42	12	49	Y cam to sende fier `in to the erthe, and what wole Y, but that it be kyndlid?
25504	42	12	50	And Y haue to be baptisid with a baptysm, and hou am Y constreyned, til that it be perfitli don?
25505	42	12	51	Wene ye, that Y cam to yyue pees in to erthe? Nay, Y say to you, but departyng.
25506	42	12	52	For fro this tyme ther schulen be fyue departid in oon hous; thre schulen be departid ayens tweyne, and tweyne schulen be departid ayens thre;
25507	42	12	53	the fadir ayens the sone, and the sone ayens the fadir; the modir ayens the douytir, and the douytir ayens the modir; the hosebondis modir ayens the sones wijf, and and the sones wijf ayens hir hosebondis modir.
25508	42	12	54	And he seide also to the puple, Whanne ye seen a cloude risynge fro the sunne goynge doun, anoon ye seien, Reyn cometh; and so it is don.
25509	42	12	55	And whanne ye seen the south blowynge, ye seien, That heete schal be; and it is don.
25510	42	12	56	Ypocritis, ye kunnen preue the face of heuene and of erthe, but hou preuen ye not this tyme.
25511	42	12	57	But what and of you silf ye demen not that that is iust?
25512	42	12	58	But whanne thou goist with thin aduersarie in the weie to the prince, do bisynesse to be delyuerid fro hym; lest perauenture he take thee to the domesman, and the domesman bitake thee to the maistirful axer, and the maistirful axer sende thee in to prisoun.
25513	42	12	59	Y seie to thee, thou schalt not go fro thennus, til thou yelde the laste ferthing.
25514	42	13	1	And sum men weren present in that tyme, that telden to hym of the Galileis, whos blood Pilat myngide with the sacrificis of hem.
25515	42	13	2	And he answeride, and seide to hem, Wenen ye, that these men of Galile weren synneris more than alle Galilees, for thei suffriden siche thingis?
25516	42	13	3	Y seie to you, nay; alle ye schulen perische in lijk manere, but ye han penaunce.
25517	42	13	4	And as tho eiytetene, on which the toure in Siloa fel doun, and slowe hem, gessen ye, for thei weren dettouris more than alle men that dwellen in Jerusalem?
25518	42	13	5	Y seie to you, nai; but also `ye alle schulen perische, if ye doon not penaunce.
25519	42	13	6	And he seide this liknesse, A man hadde a fige tre plauntid in his vynyerd, and he cam sekynge fruyt in it, and foond noon.
25520	42	13	7	And he seide to the tilier of the vynyerd, Lo! thre yeeris ben, sithen Y come sekynge fruyt in this fige tre, and Y fynde noon; therfor kitte it doun, whereto ocupieth it the erthe?
25521	42	13	8	And he answerynge seide to hym, Lord, suffre it also this yeer, the while Y delue aboute it, and Y schal donge it;
25522	42	13	9	if it schal make fruyt, if nay, in tyme comynge thou schalt kitte it doun.
25523	42	13	10	And he was techinge in her synagoge in the sabatis.
25524	42	13	11	And lo! a womman, that hadde a spirit of sijknesse eiytene yeeris, and was crokid, and `nethir ony maner myyte loke vpward.
25525	42	13	12	Whom whanne Jhesus hadde seyn, he clepide to hym, and seide to hir, Womman, thou art delyuerid of thi sijknesse.
25526	42	13	13	And he settide on hir his hoondis, and anoon sche stood upriyt, and glorifiede God.
25527	42	13	14	And the prince of the synagoge answerde, hauynge dedeyn for Jhesus hadde heelid in the sabat; and he seide to the puple, Ther ben sixe dayes, in whiche it bihoueth to worche; therfor come ye in these, and `be ye heelid, and not in the daie of sabat.
25528	42	13	15	But the Lord answeride to hym, and seide, Ypocrite, whether ech of you vntieth not in the sabat his oxe, or asse, fro the cratche, and ledith to watir?
25529	42	13	16	Bihofte it not this douytir of Abraham, whom Satanas hath boundun, lo! eiytetene yeeris, to be vnboundun of this boond in the dai of the sabat?
25530	42	13	17	And whanne he seide these thingis, alle hise aduersaries weren aschamed, and al the puple ioiede in alle thingis, that weren gloriousli don of hym.
25531	42	13	18	Therfor he seide, To what thing is the kyngdom of God lijk? and to what thing schal Y gesse it to be lijk?
25532	42	13	19	It is lijk to a corn of seneuey, which a man took, and cast in to his yerd; and it wax, and was maad in to a greet tree, and foulis of the eire restiden in the braunchis therof.
25533	42	13	20	And eft soone he seide, To what thing schal Y gesse the kyngdom of God lijk?
25534	42	13	21	It is lijk to sourdouy, that a womman took, and hidde it `in to thre mesuris of mele, til al were sourid.
25535	42	13	22	And he wente bi citees and castels, techynge and makynge a iourney in to Jerusalem.
25536	42	13	23	And a man seide to hym, Lord, if there ben fewe, that ben saued? And he seide to hem,
25537	42	13	24	Stryue ye to entre bi the streite yate; for Y seie to you, many seken to entre, and thei schulen not mowe.
25538	42	13	25	For whanne the hosebonde man is entrid, and the dore is closid, ye schulen bigynne to stonde with out forth, and knocke at the dore, and seie, Lord, opyn to vs. And he schal answere, and seie to you, Y knowe you not, of whennus ye ben.
25539	42	13	26	Thanne ye schulen bigynne to seye, We han etun bifor thee and drunkun, and in oure streetis thou hast tauyt.
25540	42	13	27	And he schal seie to you, Y know you not, of whennus ye ben; go awei fro me, alle ye worcheris of wickidnesse.
25541	42	13	28	There schal be wepyng and gruntyng of teeth, whanne ye schulen se Abraham, and Isaac, and Jacob, and alle the prophetis in the kyngdom of God; and you to be put out.
25542	42	13	29	And thei schulen come fro the eest and west, and fro the north and south, and schulen sitte `at the mete in the rewme of God.
25543	42	13	30	And lo! thei that weren the firste, ben the laste; and thei that weren the laste, ben the firste.
25544	42	13	31	In that day sum of the Farisees camen nyy, and seiden to hym, Go out, and go fro hennus, for Eroude wole sle thee.
25545	42	13	32	And he seide to hem, Go ye, and seie to that foxe, Lo! Y caste out feendis, and Y make perfitli heelthis, to dai and to morew, and the thridde dai Y am endid.
25546	42	13	33	Netheles it bihoueth me to dai, and to morewe, and the dai that sueth, to walke; for it fallith not a profete to perische out of Jerusalem.
25547	42	13	34	Jerusalem, Jerusalem, that sleest profetis, and stonest hem that ben sent to thee, hou ofte wolde Y gadre togider thi sones, as a brid gaderith his nest vndur fethris, and thou woldist not.
25548	42	13	35	Lo! youre hous schal be left to you desert. And Y seie to you, that ye schulen not se me, til it come, whanne ye schulen seie, Blessid is he, that cometh in the name of the Lord.
25549	42	14	1	And it was don, whanne he hadde entrid in to the hous of a prince of Farisees, in the sabat, to ete breed, thei aspieden hym.
25550	42	14	2	And lo! a man sijk in the dropesie was bifor hym.
25551	42	14	3	And Jhesus answerynge spak to the wise men of lawe, and to the Farisees, and seide, Whethir it is leeueful to heele in the sabat?
25552	42	14	4	And thei helden pees. And Jhesus took, and heelide hym, and let hym go.
25553	42	14	5	And he answeride to hem, and seide, Whos asse or oxe of you schal falle in to a pit, and `he schal not anoon drawe hym out in the dai of the sabat?
25554	42	14	6	And thei myyten not answere to hym to these thingis.
25555	42	14	7	He seide also a parable to men bodun to a feeste, and biheld hou thei chesen the first sittyng placis, and seide to hem,
25556	42	14	8	Whanne thou art bodun to bridalis, sitte not `at the mete in the firste place; lest perauenture a worthier than thou be bodun of hym,
25557	42	14	9	and lest he come that clepide thee and hym, and seie to thee, Yyue place to this, and thanne thou schalt bigynne with schame to holde the lowest place.
25558	42	14	10	But whanne thou art bedun to a feste, go, and sitte doun in the laste place, that whanne he cometh, that bad thee to the feeste, he seie to thee, Freend, come hiyer. Thanne worschip schal be to thee, bifor men that sitten at the mete.
25559	42	14	11	For ech that enhaunsith hym, schal be lowid; and he that meketh hym, schal be hiyed.
25560	42	14	12	And he seide to hym, that hadde bodun hym to the feeste, Whanne thou makist a mete, or a soper, nyle thou clepe thi freendis, nether thi britheren, nethir cosyns, nethir neiyboris, ne riche men; lest perauenture thei bidde thee ayen to the feeste, and it be yolde ayen to thee.
25561	42	14	13	But whanne thou makist a feeste, clepe pore men,
25562	42	14	14	feble, crokid, and blynde, and thou schalt be blessid; for thei han not wherof to yelde thee, for it schal be yoldun to thee in the risyng ayen of iust men.
25563	42	14	15	And whanne oon of hem that saten togider at the mete hadde herd these thingis, he seide to hym, Blessid is he, that schal ete breed in the rewme of God.
25564	42	14	16	And he seide to hym, A man made a greet soper, and clepide many.
25565	42	14	17	And he sent his seruaunt in the our of soper, to seie to men that weren bodun to the feeste, that thei schulden come, for now alle thingis ben redi.
25566	42	14	18	And alle bigunnen togidir to excusen hem. The firste seide, Y haue bouyt a toun, and Y haue nede to go out, and se it; Y preye thee, haue me excusid.
25567	42	14	19	And the tother seide, Y haue bouyt fyue yockis of oxun, and Y go to preue hem; Y preye thee, haue me excusid.
25568	42	14	20	And an othir seide, Y haue weddid a wijf; and therfor Y may not come.
25569	42	14	21	And the seruaunt turnede ayen, and tolde these thingis to his lord. Thanne the hosebonde man was wrooth, and seide to his seruaunt, Go out swithe in to the grete stretis and smal stretis of the citee, and brynge ynne hidir pore men, and feble, blynde, and crokid.
25570	42	14	22	And the seruaunt seide, Lord, it is don, as thou hast comaundid, and yit there is a void place.
25571	42	14	23	And the lord seide to the seruaunt, Go out in to weies and heggis, and constreine men to entre, that myn hous be fulfillid.
25572	42	14	24	For Y seie to you, that noon of tho men that ben clepid, schal taaste my soper.
25573	42	14	25	And myche puple wenten with hym; and he turnede, and seide to hem,
25574	42	14	26	If ony man cometh to me, and hatith not his fadir, and modir, and wijf, and sones, and britheren, and sistris, and yit his owne lijf, he may not be my disciple.
25575	42	14	27	And he that berith not his cross, and cometh aftir me, may not be my disciple.
25576	42	14	28	For who of you willynge to bilde a toure, whether he `first sitte not, and countith the spensis that ben nedeful, if he haue to perfourme?
25577	42	14	29	Lest aftir that he hath set the foundement, and mowe not perfourme, alle that seen, bigynnen to scorne hym, and seie, For this man bigan to bilde,
25578	42	14	30	and myyte not make an ende.
25579	42	14	31	Or what kyng that wole go to do a bataile ayens anothir kyng, whether he sittith not first, and bithenkith, if he may with ten thousynde go ayens hym that cometh ayens hym with twenti thousynde?
25580	42	14	32	Ellis yit while he is afer, he sendynge a messanger, preieth tho thingis that ben of pees.
25581	42	14	33	So therfor ech of you, that forsakith not alle thingis that he hath, may not be my disciple.
25582	42	14	34	Salt is good; but if salt vanysche, in what thing schal it be sauerid?
25583	42	14	35	Nethir in erthe, nethir in donghille it is profitable, but it schal be cast out. He that hath eeris of herynge, here he.
25584	42	15	1	And pupplicans and synful men weren neiyynge to him, to here hym.
25585	42	15	2	And the Farisees and scribis grutchiden, seiynge, For this resseyueth synful men, and etith with hem.
25586	42	15	3	And he spak to hem this parable,
25587	42	15	4	and seide, What man of you that hath an hundrith scheep, and if he hath lost oon of hem, whethir he leeueth not nynti and nyne in desert, and goith to it that perischide, til he fynde it?
25588	42	15	5	And whanne he hath foundun it, he ioieth, and leyith it on hise schuldris; and he cometh hoom,
25589	42	15	6	and clepith togidir hise freendis and neiyboris, and seith to hem, Be ye glad with me, for Y haue founde my scheep, that hadde perischid.
25590	42	15	7	And Y seie to you, so ioye schal be in heuene on o synful man doynge penaunce, more than on nynti and nyne iuste, that han no nede to penaunce.
25591	42	15	8	Or what womman hauynge ten besauntis, and if sche hath lost oo besaunt, whether sche teendith not a lanterne, and turneth vpsodoun the hows, and sekith diligentli, til that sche fynde it?
25592	42	15	9	And whanne sche hath foundun, sche clepith togidir freendis and neiyboris, and seith, Be ye glad with me, for Y haue founde the besaunt, that Y hadde lost.
25593	42	15	10	So Y seie to you, ioye schal be bifor aungels of God on o synful man doynge penaunce.
