25594	42	15	11	And he seide, A man hadde twei sones;
25595	42	15	12	and the yonger of hem seide to the fadir, Fadir, yyue me the porcioun of catel, that fallith to me. And he departide to hem the catel.
25596	42	15	13	And not aftir many daies, whanne alle thingis weren gederid togider, the yonger sone wente forth in pilgrymage in to a fer cuntre; and there he wastide hise goodis in lyuynge lecherously.
25597	42	15	14	And aftir that he hadde endid alle thingis, a strong hungre was maad in that cuntre, and he bigan to haue nede.
25598	42	15	15	And he wente, and drouy hym to oon of the citeseyns of that cuntre. And he sente hym in to his toun, to fede swyn.
25599	42	15	16	And he coueitide to fille his wombe of the coddis that the hoggis eeten, and no man yaf hym.
25600	42	15	17	And he turnede ayen to hym silf, and seide, Hou many hirid men in my fadir hous han plente of looues; and Y perische here thorouy hungir.
25601	42	15	18	Y schal rise vp, and go to my fadir, and Y schal seie to hym, Fadir, Y haue synned in to heuene, and bifor thee;
25602	42	15	19	and now Y am not worthi to be clepid thi sone, make me as oon of thin hirid men.
25603	42	15	20	And he roos vp, and cam to his fadir. And whanne he was yit afer, his fadir saiy hym, and was stirrid bi mercy. And he ran, and fel on his necke, and kisside hym.
25604	42	15	21	And the sone seide to hym, Fadir, Y haue synned in to heuene, and bifor thee; and now Y am not worthi to be clepid thi sone.
25605	42	15	22	And the fadir seide to hise seruauntis, Swithe brynge ye forth the firste stoole, and clothe ye hym, and yyue ye a ryng in his hoond,
25606	42	15	23	and schoon on hise feet; and brynge ye a fat calf, and sle ye, and ete we, and make we feeste.
25607	42	15	24	For this my sone was deed, and hath lyued ayen; he perischid, and is foundun. And alle men bigunnen to ete.
25608	42	15	25	But his eldere sone was in the feeld; and whanne he cam, and neiyede to the hous, he herde a symfonye and a croude.
25609	42	15	26	And he clepide oon of the seruauntis, and axide, what these thingis weren.
25610	42	15	27	And he seide to hym, Thi brother is comun, and thi fadir slewe a fat calf, for he resseyuede hym saaf.
25611	42	15	28	And he was wrooth, and wolde not come in. Therfor his fadir wente out, and bigan to preye hym.
25612	42	15	29	And he answerde to his fadir, and seide, Lo! so many yeeris Y serue thee, and Y neuer brak thi comaundement; and thou neuer yaf to me a kidde, that Y with my freendis schulde haue ete.
25613	42	15	30	But aftir that this thi sone, that hath deuourid his substaunce with horis, cam, thou hast slayn to hym a fat calf.
25614	42	15	31	And he seide to hym, Sone, thou art euer more with me, and alle my thingis ben thine.
25615	42	15	32	But it bihofte for to make feeste, and to haue ioye; for this thi brother was deed, and lyuede ayen; he perischide, and is foundun.
25616	42	16	1	He seide also to hise disciplis, Ther was a riche man, that hadde a baili; and this was defamed to him, as he hadde wastid his goodis.
25617	42	16	2	And he clepide hym, and seide to hym, What here Y this thing of thee? yelde reckynyng of thi baili, for thou miyte not now be baili.
25618	42	16	3	And the baili seide with ynne him silf, What schal Y do, for my lord takith awei fro me the baili? delfe mai Y not, I schame to begge.
25619	42	16	4	Y woot what Y schal do, that whanne Y am remeued fro the baili, thei resseyue me in to her hous.
25620	42	16	5	Therfor whanne alle the dettours of his lord weren clepid togider, he seide to the firste, Hou myche owist thou to my lord?
25621	42	16	6	And he seide, An hundrid barelis of oyle. And he seide to hym, Take thi caucioun, and sitte soone, and write fifti.
25622	42	16	7	Aftirward he seide to another, And hou myche owist thou? Which answerde, An hundrid coris of whete. And he seide to hym, Take thi lettris, and write foure scoore.
25623	42	16	8	And the lord preiside the baili of wickydnesse, for he hadde do prudentli; for the sones of this world ben more prudent in her generacioun than the sones of liyt.
25624	42	16	9	And Y seie to you, make ye to you freendis of the ritchesse of wickidnesse, that whanne ye schulen fayle, thei resseyue you in to euerlastynge tabernaclis.
25625	42	16	10	He that is trewe in the leeste thing, is trewe also in the more; and he that is wickid in a litil thing, is wickid also in the more.
25626	42	16	11	Therfor if ye weren not trewe in the wickid thing of ritchesse, who schal bitake to you that that is verry?
25627	42	16	12	And if ye weren not trewe in othere mennus thing, who schal yyue to you that that is youre?
25628	42	16	13	No seruaunt may serue to twei lordis; for ether he schal hate `the toon, and loue the tothir; ethir he schal drawe to `the toon, and schal dispise the tothir. Ye moun not serue to God and to ritchesse.
25629	42	16	14	But the Farisees, that weren coueytous, herden alle these thingis, and thei scorneden hym.
25630	42	16	15	And he seide to hem, Ye it ben, that iustifien you bifor men; but God hath knowun youre hertis, for that that is hiy to men, is abhomynacioun bifor God.
25631	42	16	16	The lawe and prophetis til to Joon; fro that tyme the rewme of God is euangelisid, and ech man doith violence in to it.
25632	42	16	17	Forsothe it is liyter heuene and erthe to passe, than that o titil falle fro the lawe.
25633	42	16	18	Euery man that forsakith his wijf, and weddith an other, doith letcherie; and he that weddith the wijf forsakun of the hosebonde, doith auowtrie.
25634	42	16	19	There was a riche man, and was clothid in purpur, and whit silk, and eete euery dai schynyngli.
25635	42	16	20	And there was a begger, Lazarus bi name, that lai at his yate ful of bilis,
25636	42	16	21	and coueitide to be fulfillid of the crummes, that fellen doun fro the riche mannus boord, and no man yaf to hym; but houndis camen, and lickiden hise bilis.
25637	42	16	22	And it was don, that the begger diede, and was borun of aungels in to Abrahams bosum.
25638	42	16	23	And the riche man was deed also, and was biried in helle. And he reiside hise iyen, whanne he was in turmentis, and say Abraham afer, and Lazarus in his bosum.
25639	42	16	24	And he criede, and seide, Fadir Abraham, haue merci on me, and sende Lazarus, that he dippe the ende of his fyngur in watir, to kele my tunge; for Y am turmentid in this flawme.
25640	42	16	25	And Abraham seide to hym, Sone, haue mynde, for thou hast resseyued good thingis in thi lijf, and Lazarus also yuel thingis; but he is now coumfortid, and thou art turmentid.
25641	42	16	26	And in alle these thingis a greet derk place is stablischid betwixe vs and you; that thei that wolen fro hennus passe to you, moun not, nethir fro thennus passe ouer hidur.
25642	42	16	27	And he seide, Thanne Y preie thee, fadir, that thou sende hym in to the hous of my fadir.
25643	42	16	28	For Y haue fyue britheren, that he witnesse to hem, lest also thei come in to this place of turmentis.
25644	42	16	29	And Abraham seide to him, Thei han Moyses and the prophetis; here thei hem.
25645	42	16	30	And he seide, Nay, fadir Abraham, but if ony of deed men go to hem, thei schulen do penaunce.
25646	42	16	31	And he seide to hym, If thei heren not Moises and prophetis, nethir if ony of deed men rise ayen, thei schulen bileue to hym.
25647	42	17	1	And Jhesu seide to hise disciplis, It is impossible that sclaundris come not; but wo to that man, bi whom thei comen.
25648	42	17	2	It is more profitable to him, if a mylne stoon be put aboute his necke, and he be cast in to the see, than that he sclaundre oon of these litle.
25649	42	17	3	Take ye hede you silf; if thi brothir hath synned ayens thee, blame hym; and if he do penaunce, foryyue hym.
25650	42	17	4	And if seuene sithis in the dai he do synne ayens thee, and seuene sithis in the dai he be conuertid to thee, and seie, It forthenkith me, foryyue thou hym.
25651	42	17	5	And the apostlis seiden to the Lord, Encrese to vs feith.
25652	42	17	6	And the Lord seide, If ye han feith as the corn of seneuei, ye schulen seie to this more tre, Be thou drawun vp bi the rote, and be ouerplauntid in to the see, and it schal obeie to you.
25653	42	17	7	But who of you hath a seruaunt erynge, or lesewynge oxis, which seith to hym, whanne he turneth ayen fro the feeld, Anoon go, and sitte to mete;
25654	42	17	8	and seith not to hym, Make redi, that Y soupe, and girde thee, and serue me, while Y ete and drynke, and aftir this thou schalt ete and drynke;
25655	42	17	9	whether he hath grace to that seruaunt, for he dide that that he comaundide hym?
25656	42	17	10	Nay, Y gesse. So ye, whanne ye han don alle thingis that ben comaundid to you, seie ye, We ben vnprofitable seruauntis, we han do that that we ouyten to do.
25657	42	17	11	And it was do, the while Jhesus wente in to Jerusalem, he passide thorou the myddis of Samarie, and Galilee.
25658	42	17	12	And whanne he entride in to a castel, ten leprouse men camen ayens hym, whiche stoden afer,
25659	42	17	13	and reiseden her voys, and seiden, Jhesu, comaundoure, haue merci on vs.
25660	42	17	14	And as he say hem, he seide, Go ye, `schewe ye you to the prestis. And it was don, the while thei wenten, thei weren clensid.
25661	42	17	15	And oon of hem, as he saiy that he was clensid, wente ayen, magnifiynge God with grete vois.
25662	42	17	16	And he fel doun on the face bifore hise feet, and dide thankyngis; and this was a Samaritan.
25663	42	17	17	And Jhesus answerde, and seide, Whether ten ben not clensid, and where ben the nyne?
25664	42	17	18	There is noon foundun, that turnede ayen, and yaf glorie to God, but this alien.
25665	42	17	19	And he seide to hym, Rise vp, go thou; for thi feith hath maad thee saaf.
25666	42	17	20	And he was axid of Farisees, whanne the rewme of God cometh. And he answerde to hem, and seide, The rewme of God cometh not with aspiyng,
25667	42	17	21	nether thei schulen seie, Lo! here, or lo there; for lo! the rewme of God is with ynne you.
25668	42	17	22	And he seide to hise disciplis, Daies schulen come, whanne ye schulen desire to se o dai of mannus sone, and ye schulen not se.
25669	42	17	23	And thei schulen seie to you, Lo! here, and lo there. Nyle ye go, nether sue ye;
25670	42	17	24	for as leyt schynynge from vndur heuene schyneth in to tho thingis that ben vndur heuene, so schal mannus sone be in his dai.
25671	42	17	25	But first it bihoueth hym to suffre many thingis, and to be repreued of this generacioun.
25672	42	17	26	And as it was doon in the daies of Noe, so it schal be in the daies of mannys sone.
25673	42	17	27	Thei eeten and drunkun, weddiden wyues, and weren youun to weddyngis, til in to the dai in the whych Noe entride in to the schip; and the greet flood cam, and loste alle.
25674	42	17	28	Also as it was don in the daies of Loth, thei eeten and drunkun, bouyten and seelden, plauntiden and bildiden; but the dai that Loth wente out of Sodome,
25675	42	17	29	the Lord reynede fier and brymstoon fro heuene, and loste alle.
25676	42	17	30	Lijk this thing it schal be, in what dai mannys sone schal be schewid.
25677	42	17	31	In that our he that is in the roof, and his vessels in the hous, come he not doun to take hem awei; and he that schal be in the feeld, also turne not ayen bihynde.
25678	42	17	32	Be ye myndeful of the wijf of Loth.
25679	42	17	33	Who euer seketh to make his lijf saaf, schal leese it; and who euer leesith it, schal quykene it.
25680	42	17	34	But Y seie to you, in that nyyt twei schulen be in o bed, oon schal be takun, and the tothir forsakun;
25681	42	17	35	twei wymmen schulen be gryndynge togidir, `the toon schal be takun, and `the tother forsakun; twei in a feeld, `the toon schal be takun, and `the tother left.
25682	42	17	36	Thei answeren, and seien to hym, Where, Lord?
25683	42	17	37	Which seide to hym, Where euer the bodi schal be, thidur schulen be gaderid togidere also the eglis.
25684	42	18	1	And he seide to hem also a parable, that it bihoueth to preye euer more, and not faile;
25685	42	18	2	and seide, There was a iuge in a citee, that dredde not God, nether schamede of men.
25686	42	18	3	And a widowe was in that citee, and sche cam to hym, and seide, Venge me of myn aduersarie;
25687	42	18	4	and he wolde not longe tyme. But aftir these thingis he seide with ynne hym silf, Thouy Y drede not God, and schame not of man,
25688	42	18	5	netheles for this widewe is heuy to me, Y schal venge hir; lest at the laste sche comynge condempne me.
25689	42	18	6	And the Lord seide, Here ye, what the domesman of wickidnesse seith;
25690	42	18	7	and whether God schal not do veniaunce of hise chosun, criynge to hym dai and nyyt, and schal haue pacience in hem?
25691	42	18	8	Sotheli Y seie to you, for soone he schal do veniaunce of hem. Netheles gessist thou, that mannus sone comynge schal fynde feith in erthe?
25692	42	18	9	And he seide also to sum men, that tristiden in hem silf, as thei weren riytful, and dispiseden othere, this parable,
25693	42	18	10	seiynge, Twei men wenten vp in to the temple to preye; the toon a Farisee, and the tother a pupplican.
25694	42	18	11	And the Farisee stood, and preiede bi hym silf these thingis, and seide, God, Y do thankyngis to thee, for Y am not as other men, raueinouris, vniust, auoutreris, as also this pupplican;
25695	42	18	12	Y faste twies in the woke, Y yyue tithis of alle thingis that Y haue in possessioun.
25696	42	18	13	And the pupplican stood afer, and wolde nether reise hise iyen to heuene, but smoot his brest, and seide, God be merciful to me, synnere.
25697	42	18	14	Treuli Y seie to you, this yede doun in to his hous, and was iustified fro the other. For ech that enhaunsith hym, schal be maad low, and he that mekith hym, schal be enhaunsid.
25698	42	18	15	And thei brouyten to hym yonge children, that he schulde touche hem; and whanne the disciplis saien this thing, thei blameden hem.
25699	42	18	16	But Jhesus clepide togider hem, and seide, Suffre ye children to come to me, and nyle ye forbede hem, for of siche is the kyngdom of heuenes.
25700	42	18	17	Treuli Y seie to you, who euer schal not take the kyngdom of God as a child, he schal not entre in to it.
25701	42	18	18	And a prince axide hym, and seide, Goode maister, in what thing doynge schal Y weilde euerlastynge lijf?
25702	42	18	19	And Jhesus seide to hym, What seist thou me good? No man is good, but God aloone.
25703	42	18	20	Thou knowist the comaundementis, Thou schalt not sle, Thou schalt not do letcherie, Thou schalt not do theft, Thou schalt not seie fals witnessyng, Worschipe thi fadir and thi modir.
25704	42	18	21	Which seide, Y haue kept alle these thingis fro my yongthe.
25705	42	18	22	And whanne this thing was herd, Jhesus seide to hym, Yit o thing failith `to thee; sille thou alle thingis that thou hast, and yyue to pore men, and thou schalt haue tresour in heuene; and come, and sue thou me.
25706	42	18	23	Whanne these thingis weren herd, he was soreful, for he was ful ryche.
25707	42	18	24	And Jhesus seynge hym maad sorie, seide, How hard thei that han money schulen entre in to the kyngdom of God;
25708	42	18	25	for it is liyter a camel to passe thorou a nedlis iye, than a riche man to entre in to the kyngdom of God.
25709	42	18	26	And thei that herden these thingis seiden, Who may be maad saaf?
25710	42	18	27	And he seide to hem, Tho thingis that ben impossible anentis men, ben possible anentis God.
25711	42	18	28	But Petir seide, Lo! we han left alle thingis, and han sued thee.
25712	42	18	29	And he seide to hym, Treuli Y seie to you, there is no man that schal forsake hous, or fadir, modir, or britheren, or wijf, or children, or feeldis, for the rewme of God,
25713	42	18	30	and schal not resseyue many mo thingis in this tyme, and in the world to comynge euerlastynge lijf.
25714	42	18	31	And Jhesus took hise twelue disciplis, and seide to hem, Lo! we gon vp to Jerusalem, and alle thingis schulen be endid, that ben writun bi the prophetis of mannus sone.
25715	42	18	32	For he schal be bitraied to hethen men, and he schal be scorned, and scourgid, and bispat;
25716	42	18	33	and aftir that thei han scourgid, thei schulen sle hym, and the thridde dai he schal rise ayen.
25717	42	18	34	And thei vndurstoden no thing of these; and this word was hid fro hem, and thei vndurstoden not tho thingis that weren seid.
25718	42	18	35	But it was don, whanne Jhesus cam nyy to Jerico, a blynde man sat bisidis the weie, and beggide.
25719	42	18	36	And whanne he herde the puple passynge, he axide, what this was.
25720	42	18	37	And thei seiden to hym, that Jhesus of Nazareth passide.
25721	42	18	38	And he criede, and seide, Jhesu, the sone of Dauyd, haue mercy on me.
25722	42	18	39	And thei that wenten bifor blamyden hym, that he schulde be stille; but he criede myche the more, Thou sone of Dauid, haue mercy on me.
25723	42	18	40	And Jhesus stood, and comaundide hym to be brouyt forth to hym. And whanne he cam nyy, he axide hym,
25724	42	18	41	and seide, What wolt thou that Y schal do to thee? And he seide, Lord, that Y se.
25725	42	18	42	And Jhesus seide to hym, Biholde; thi feith hath maad thee saaf.
25726	42	18	43	And anoon he say, and suede hym, and magnyfiede God. And al the puple, as it say, yaf heriyng to God.
25727	42	19	1	And Jhesus `goynge yn, walkide thorou Jericho.
25728	42	19	2	And lo! a man, Sache bi name, and this was a prince of pupplicans, and he was riche.
25729	42	19	3	And he souyte to se Jhesu, who he was, and he myyte not, for the puple, for he was litil in stature.
25730	42	19	4	And he ran bifore, and stiyede in to a sicomoure tree, to se hym; for he was to passe fro thennus.
25731	42	19	5	And Jhesus biheld vp, whanne he cam to the place, and saiy hym, and seide to hym, Sache, haste thee, and come doun, for to dai Y mot dwelle in thin hous.
25732	42	19	6	And he hiyynge cam doun, and ioiynge resseyuede hym.
25733	42	19	7	And whanne alle men sayn, thei grutchiden seiynge, For he hadde turned to a synful man.
25734	42	19	8	But Sache stood, and seide to the Lord, Lo! Lord, Y yyue the half of my good to pore men; and if Y haue ony thing defraudid ony man, Y yelde foure so myche.
25735	42	19	9	Jhesus seith to hym, For to dai heelthe is maad to this hous, for that he is Abrahams sone;
25736	42	19	10	for mannus sone cam to seke, and make saaf that thing that perischide.
25737	42	19	11	Whanne thei herden these thingis, he addide, and seide a parable, for that he was nyy Jerusalem, `and for thei gessiden, that anoon the kyngdom of God schulde be schewid.
25738	42	19	12	Therfor he seide, A worthi man wente in to a fer cuntre, to take to hym a kyngdom, and to turne ayen.
25739	42	19	13	And whanne hise ten seruauntis weren clepid, he yaf to hem ten besauntis; and seide to hem, Chaffare ye, til Y come.
25740	42	19	14	But hise citeseyns hatiden hym, and senten a messanger aftir hym, and seiden, We wolen not, that he regne on vs.
25741	42	19	15	And it was don, that he turnede ayen, whan he hadde take the kyngdom; and he comaundide hise seruauntis to be clepid, to whiche he hadde yyue monei, to wite, hou myche ech hadde wonne bi chaffaryng.
25742	42	19	16	And the firste cam, and seide, Lord, thi besaunt hath wonne ten besauntis.
25743	42	19	17	He seide to hym, Wel be, thou good seruaunt; for in litil thing thou hast be trewe, thou schalt be hauynge power on ten citees.
25744	42	19	18	And the tother cam, and seide, Lord, thi besaunt hath maad fyue besauntis.
25745	42	19	19	And to this he seide, And be thou on fyue citees.
25746	42	19	20	And the thridde cam, and seide, Lord, lo! thi besaunt, that Y hadde, put vp in a sudarie.
25747	42	19	21	For Y dredde thee, for thou art `a sterne man; thou takist awey that that thou settidist not, and thou repist that that thou hast not sowun.
25748	42	19	22	He seith to hym, Wickid seruaunt, of thi mouth Y deme thee. Wistist thou, that Y am `a sterne man, takynge awei that thing that Y settide not, and repyng ethat thing that Y sewe not?
25749	42	19	23	and whi hast thou not youun my money to the bord, and Y comynge schulde haue axid it with vsuris?
25750	42	19	24	And he seide to men stondynge nyy, Take ye awei fro hym the besaunt, and yyue ye to hym that hath ten beyauntis:
25751	42	19	25	And thei seiden to hym, Lord, he hath ten besauntis.
25752	42	19	26	And Y seie to you, to ech man that hath, it schal be youun, and he schal encreese; but fro him that hath not, also that thing that he hath, schal be takun of hym.
25753	42	19	27	Netheles brynge ye hidur tho myn enemyes, that wolden not that Y regnede on hem, and sle ye bifor me.
25754	42	19	28	And whanne these thingis weren seid, he wente bifore, and yede vp to Jerusalem.
25755	42	19	29	And it was don, whanne Jhesus cam nyy to Bethfage and Betanye, at the mount, that is clepid of Olyuete, he sente hise twei disciplis, and seide,
25756	42	19	30	Go ye in to the castel, that is ayens you; in to which as ye entren, ye schulen fynde a colt of an asse tied, on which neuer man sat; vntye ye hym, and brynge ye to me.
25757	42	19	31	And if ony man axe you, whi ye vntien, thus ye schulen seie to hym, For the Lord desirith his werk.
25758	42	19	32	And thei that weren sent, wenten forth, and fonden as he seide to hem, a colt stondynge.
25759	42	19	33	And whanne thei vntieden the colt, the lordis of hym seiden to hem, What vntien ye the colt?
25760	42	19	34	And thei seiden, For the Lord hath nede to hym.
25761	42	19	35	And thei ledden hym to Jhesu; and thei castynge her clothis on the colt, setten Jhesu on hym.
25762	42	19	36	And whanne he wente, thei strowiden her clothis in the weie.
25763	42	19	37	And whanne he cam nyy to the comyng doun of the mount of Olyuete, al the puple that cam doun bygunnen to ioye, and to herie God with greet vois on alle the vertues, that thei hadden sayn,
25764	42	19	38	and seiden, Blessid be the king, that cometh in the name of the Lord; pees in heuene, and glorie in hiye thingis.
25765	42	19	39	And sum of the Farisees of the puple seiden to hym, Maister, blame thi disciplis.
25766	42	19	40	And he seide to hem, Y seie to you, for if these ben stille, stoonus schulen crye.
25767	42	19	41	And whanne he neiyede, `he seiy the citee,
25768	42	19	42	and wepte on it, and seide, For if thou haddist knowun, thou schuldist wepe also; for in this dai the thingis ben in pees to thee, but now thei ben hid fro thin iyen.
25769	42	19	43	But daies schulen come in thee, and thin enemyes schulen enuyroun thee with a pale, and thei schulen go aboute thee, and make thee streit on alle sidis,
25770	42	19	44	and caste thee doun to the erthe, and thi sones that ben in thee; and thei schulen not leeue in thee a stoon on a stoon, for thou hast not knowun the tyme of thi visitacioun.
25771	42	19	45	And he entride in to the temple, and bigan to caste out men sellynge ther inne and biynge,
25772	42	19	46	and seide to hem, It is writun, That myn hous is an hous of preyer, but ye han maad it a den of theues.
25773	42	19	47	And he was techynge euerydai in the temple. And the princis of prestis, and the scribis, and the princis of the puple souyten to lese hym;
25774	42	19	48	and thei founden not, what thei schulden do to hym, for al the puple was ocupied, and herde hym.
25775	42	20	1	And it was don in oon of the daies, whanne he tauyte the puple in the temple, and prechide the gospel, the princis of preestis and scribis camen togidere with the elder men;
25776	42	20	2	and thei seiden to hym, Seie to vs, in what power thou doist these thingis, or who is he that yaf to thee this power?
25777	42	20	3	And Jhesus answeride, and seide to hem, And Y schal axe you o word; answere ye to me.
25778	42	20	4	Was the baptym of Joon of heuene, or of men?
25779	42	20	5	And thei thouyten with ynne hem silf, seiynge, For if we seien, Of heuene, he schal seie, Whi thanne bileuen ye not to hym?
25780	42	20	6	and if we seien, Of men, al the puple schal stoone vs; for thei ben certeyn, that Joon is a prophete.
25781	42	20	7	And thei answeriden, that thei knewen not, of whennus it was.
25782	42	20	8	And Jhesus seide to hem, Nether Y seie to you, in what power Y do these thingis.
25783	42	20	9	And he bigan to seie to the puple this parable. A man plauntide a vynyerd, and hiride it to tilieris; and he was in pilgrimage longe tyme.
25784	42	20	10	And in the tyme of gaderynge of grapis, he sente a seruaunt to the tilieris, that thei schulden yyue to hym of the fruyt of the vynyerd; whiche beten hym, and leten hym go voide.
25785	42	20	11	And he thouyte yit to sende another seruaunt; and thei beten this, and turmentiden hym sore, and leten hym go.
25786	42	20	12	And he thouyte yit to sende the thridde, and hym also thei woundiden, and castiden out.
25787	42	20	13	And the lord of the vyneyerd seide, What schal Y do? Y schal sende my dereworthe sone; perauenture, whanne thei seen hym, thei schulen drede.
25788	42	20	14	And whanne the tilieris sayn hym, thei thouyten with ynne hem silf, and seiden, This is the eire, sle we hym, that the eritage be oure.
25789	42	20	15	And thei castiden hym out of the vyneyerd, and killiden hym. What schal thanne the lord of the vyneyerd do to hem?
25790	42	20	16	He schal come, and distruye these tilieris, and yyue the vyneyerd to othere. And whanne this thing was herd, thei seiden to hym, God forbede.
25791	42	20	17	But he bihelde hem, and seide, What thanne is this that is writun, The stoon which men bildynge repreueden, this is maad in to the heed of the corner?
25792	42	20	18	Ech that schal falle on that stoon, schal be to-brisid, but on whom it schal falle, it schal al to-breke him.
25793	42	20	19	And the princis of prestis, and scribis, souyten to leye on hym hoondis in that our, and thei dredden the puple; for thei knewen that to hem he seide this liknesse.
25794	42	20	20	And thei aspieden, and senten aspieris, that feyneden hem iust, that thei schulden take hym in word, and bitaak hym to the `power of the prince, and to the power of the iustice.
25795	42	20	21	And thei axiden hym, and seiden, Maister, we witen, that riytli thou seist and techist; and thou takist not the persoone of man, but thou techist in treuthe the weie of God.
25796	42	20	22	Is it leueful to vs to yyue tribute to the emperoure, or nay?
25797	42	20	23	And he biheld the disseit of hem, and seide to hem, What tempten ye me?
25798	42	20	24	Shewe ye to me a peny; whos ymage and superscripcioun hath it? Thei answerden, and seiden to hym, The emperouris.
25799	42	20	25	And he seide to hem, Yelde ye therfor to the emperoure tho thingis that ben the emperours, and tho thingis that ben of God, to God.
25800	42	20	26	And thei myyten not repreue his word bifor the puple; and thei wondriden in his answere, and heelden pees.
25801	42	20	27	Summe of the Saduceis, that denyeden the ayenrisyng fro deeth to lijf, camen, and axiden hym,
25802	42	20	28	and seiden, Maister, Moises wroot to vs, if the brother of ony man haue a wijf, and be deed, and he was with outen eiris, that his brothir take his wijf, and reise seed to his brother.
25803	42	20	29	And so there weren seuene britheren. The firste took a wijf, and is deed with outen eiris;
25804	42	20	30	and the brothir suynge took hir, and he is deed with outen sone;
25805	42	20	31	and the thridde took hir; also and alle seuene, and leften not seed, but ben deed;
25806	42	20	32	and the laste of alle the womman is deed.
25807	42	20	33	Therfor in the `risyng ayen, whos wijf of hem schal sche be? for seuene hadden hir to wijf.
25808	42	20	34	And Jhesus seide to hem, Sones of this world wedden, and ben youun to weddyngis;
25809	42	20	35	but thei that schulen be had worthi of that world, and of the `risyng ayen fro deeth, nethir ben wedded,
25810	42	20	36	nethir wedden wyues, nethir schulen mowe die more; for thei ben euen with aungels, and ben the sones of God, sithen thei ben the sones of `risyng ayen fro deeth.
25811	42	20	37	And that deed men risen ayen, also Moises schewide bisidis the busch, as he seith, The Lord God of Abraham, and God of Ysaac, and God of Jacob.
25812	42	20	38	And God is not of deed men, but of lyuynge men; for alle men lyuen to hym.
25813	42	20	39	And summe of scribis answeringe, seiden, Maistir, thou hast wel seid.
25814	42	20	40	And thei dursten no more axe hym ony thing.
25815	42	20	41	But he seide to hem, How seien men, Crist to be the sone of Dauid,
25816	42	20	42	and Dauid hym silf seith in the book of Salmes, The Lord seide to my lord, Sitte thou on my riythalf,
25817	42	20	43	til that Y putte thin enemyes a stool of thi feet?
25818	42	20	44	Therfor Dauid clepith hym lord, and hou is he his sone?
25819	42	20	45	And in heryng of al the puple, he seide to hise disciplis,
25820	42	20	46	Be ye war of scribis, that wolen wandre in stolis, and louen salutaciouns in chepyng, and the firste chaieris in synagogis, and the firste sittynge placis in feestis;
25821	42	20	47	that deuouren the housis of widewis, and feynen long preiyng; these schulen take the more dampnacioun.
25822	42	21	1	And he biheeld, and saye tho riche men, that casten her yiftis in to the treserie;
25823	42	21	2	but he saye also a litil pore widewe castynge twei ferthingis.
25824	42	21	3	And he seide, Treuli Y seie to you, that this pore widewe keste more than alle men.
25825	42	21	4	For whi alle these of thing that was plenteuouse to hem casten in to the yiftis of God; but this widewe of that thing that failide to hir, caste al hir liflode, that sche hadde.
25826	42	21	5	And whanne sum men seiden of the temple, that it was apparailid with gode stoonus and yiftis,
25827	42	21	6	he seide, These thingis that ye seen, daies schulen come, in whiche a stoon schal not be left on a stoon, which schal not be destried.
25828	42	21	7	And thei axiden hym, and seiden, Comaundour, whanne schulen these thingis be? and what tokne schal be, whanne thei schulen bigynne to be don?
25829	42	21	8	And he seide, Se ye, that ye be not disseyued; for many schulen come in my name, seiynge, For Y am, and the tyme schal neiye; therfor nyle ye go aftir hem.
25830	42	21	9	And whanne ye schulen here batailis and stryues with ynne, nyle ye be aferd; it bihoueth first these thingis to be don, but not yit anoon is an ende.
25831	42	21	10	Thanne he seide to hem, Folk schal rise ayens folk, and rewme ayens rewme;
25832	42	21	11	grete mouyngis of erthe schulen be bi placis, and pestilencis, and hungris, and dredis fro heuene, and grete tokenes schulen be.
25833	42	21	12	But bifore alle these thingis thei schulen sette her hoondis on you, and schulen pursue, bitakynge in to synagogis and kepyngis, drawynge to kyngis and to iusticis, for my name;
25834	42	21	13	but it schal falle to you in to witnessyng.
25835	42	21	14	Therfor putte ye in youre hertis, not to thenke bifore, hou ye schulen answere; for Y schal yyue to you mouth and wisdom,
25836	42	21	15	to whiche alle youre aduersaries schulen not mowe ayenstonde, and ayenseie.
25837	42	21	16	And ye schulen be takun of fadir, and modir, and britheren, and cosyns, and freendis, and bi deeth thei schulen turmente of you;
25838	42	21	17	and ye schulen be in haate to alle men for my name.
25839	42	21	18	And an heere of youre heed schal not perische;
25840	42	21	19	in youre pacience ye schulen welde youre soulis.
25841	42	21	20	But whanne ye schulen se Jerusalem ben enuyround with an oost, thanne wite ye, that the desolacioun of it schal neiye.
25842	42	21	21	Thanne thei that ben in Judee, fle to the mountans; and thei that ben in the mydil of it, gon awei; and thei that ben in the cuntreis, entre not in to it.
25843	42	21	22	For these ben daies of veniaunce, that alle thingis that ben writun, be fulfillid.
25844	42	21	23	And wo to hem, that ben with child, and norischen in tho daies; for a greet diseese schal be on the erthe, and wraththe to this puple.
25845	42	21	24	And thei schulen falle bi the scharpnesse of swerd, and thei schulen be led prisoneris in to alle folkis; and Jerusalem schal be defoulid of hethene men, til the tymes of naciouns be fulfillid.
25846	42	21	25	And tokenes schulen be in the sunne, and the mone, and in the sterris; and in the erthe ouerleiyng of folkis, for confusioun of sown of the see and of floodis;
25847	42	21	26	for men schulen wexe drye for drede and abidyng that schulen come to al the world; for vertues of heuenes schulen be mouyd.
25848	42	21	27	And thanne thei schulen se mannys sone comynge in a cloude, with greet power and maieste.
25849	42	21	28	And whanne these thingis bigynnen to be maad, biholde ye, and reise ye youre heedis, for youre redempcioun neiyeth.
25850	42	21	29	And he seide to hem a liknesse, Se ye the fige tre, and alle trees,
25851	42	21	30	whanne thei bryngen forth now of hem silf fruyt, ye witen that somer is nyy;
25852	42	21	31	so ye, whanne ye seen these thingis to be don, wite ye, that the kyngdom of God is nyy.
25853	42	21	32	Treuli Y seie to you, that this generacioun schal not passe, til alle thingis be don.
25854	42	21	33	Heuene and erthe schulen passe, but my wordis schulen not passe.
25855	42	21	34	But take ye heede to you silf, lest perauenture youre hertis be greuyd with glotony, and drunkenesse, and bisynessis of this lijf, and thilke dai come sodein on you; for as a snare it schal come on alle men,
25856	42	21	35	that sitten on the face of al erthe.
25857	42	21	36	Therfor wake ye, preiynge in ech tyme, that ye be hadde worthi to fle alle these thingis that ben to come, and to stonde bifor mannus sone.
25858	42	21	37	And in daies he was techynge in the temple, but in nyytis he yede out, and dwellide in the mount, that is clepid of Olyuet.
25859	42	21	38	And al the puple roos eerli, to come to hym in the temple, and to here hym.
25860	42	22	1	And the halidai of therf looues, that is seid pask, neiyede.
25861	42	22	2	And the princis of preestis and the scribis souyten, hou thei schulden sle Jhesu, but thei dredden the puple.
25862	42	22	3	And Sathanas entride in to Judas, that was clepid Scarioth, oon of the twelue.
25863	42	22	4	And he wente, and spak with the princis of preestis, and with the magistratis, hou he schulde bitray hym to hem.
25864	42	22	5	And thei ioyeden, and maden couenaunt to yyue hym money.
25865	42	22	6	And he bihiyte, and he souyte oportunyte, to bitraye hym, with outen puple.
25866	42	22	7	But the daies of therf looues camen, in whiche it was neede, that the sacrifice of pask were slayn.
25867	42	22	8	And he sente Petre and Joon, and seide, Go ye, and make ye redi to vs the pask, that we ete.
25868	42	22	9	And thei seiden, Where wolt thou, that we make redi?
25869	42	22	10	And he seide to hem, Lo! whanne ye schulen entre in to the citee, a man berynge a vessel of watir schal meete you; sue ye hym in to the hous, in to which he entrith.
25870	42	22	11	And ye schulen seie to the hosebonde man of the hous, The maister seith to thee, Where is a chaumbre, where Y schal ete the pask with my disciplis?
25871	42	22	12	And he schal schewe to you a greet soupyng place strewid, and there make ye redi.
25872	42	22	13	And thei yeden, and founden as he seide to hem, and thei maden redi the pask.
25873	42	22	14	And whanne the our was come, he sat to the mete, and the twelue apostlis with hym.
25874	42	22	15	And he seide to hem, With desier Y haue desirid to ete with you this pask, bifor that Y suffre;
25875	42	22	16	for Y seie to you, that fro this tyme Y schal not ete it, til it be fulfillid in the rewme of God.
25876	42	22	17	And whanne he hadde take the cuppe, he dide gracis, and seide, Take ye, and departe ye among you;
25877	42	22	18	for Y seie to you, that Y schal not drynke of the kynde of this vyne, til the rewme of God come.
25878	42	22	19	And whanne he hadde take breed, he dide thankyngis, and brak, and yaf to hem, and seide, This is my bodi, that schal be youun for you; do ye this thing in mynde of me.
25879	42	22	20	He took also the cuppe, aftir that he hadde soupid, and seide, This cuppe is the newe testament in my blood, that schal be sched for you.
25880	42	22	21	Netheles lo! the hoond of hym that bitraieth me, is with me at the table.
25881	42	22	22	And mannus sone goith, `aftir that it is determyned; netheles wo to that man, bi whom he schal be bitraied.
25882	42	22	23	And thei bigunnen to seke among hem, who it was of hem, that was to do this thing.
25883	42	22	24	And strijf was maad among hem, which of hem schulde be seyn to be grettest.
25884	42	22	25	But he seide to hem, Kyngis of hethen men ben lordis of hem, and thei that han power on hem ben clepid good doeris, but ye not so;
25885	42	22	26	but he that is grettest among you, be maad as yongere, and he that is bifor goere, as a seruaunt.
25886	42	22	27	For who is gretter, he that sittith at the mete, or he that mynystrith? whether not he that sittith at the mete? And Y am in the myddil of you, as he that mynystrith.
25887	42	22	28	And ye ben, that han dwellid with me in my temptaciouns; and Y dispose to you,
25888	42	22	29	as my fadir hath disposid to me,
25889	42	22	30	a rewme, that ye ete and drynke on my boord in my rewme, and sitte on trones, and deme the twelue kynredis of Israel.
25890	42	22	31	And the Lord seide to Symount, Symount, lo, Satanas hath axid you, that he schulde ridile as whete; but Y haue preyede for thee,
25891	42	22	32	that thi feith faile not; and thou sum tyme conuertid, conferme thi britheren.
25892	42	22	33	Which seide to hym, Lord, Y am redi to go in to prisoun and in to deeth with thee.
25893	42	22	34	And he seide, Y seie to thee, Petir, the cok schal not crowe to dai, til thou thries forsake that thou knowist me.
25894	42	22	35	And he seide to hem, Whanne Y sente you with outen sachel, and scrippe, and schone, whether ony thing failide to you?
25895	42	22	36	And thei seiden, No thing. Therfor he seide to hem, But now he that hath a sachel, take also and a scrippe; and he that hath noon, selle his coote, and bigge a swerd.
25896	42	22	37	For Y seie to you, that yit it bihoueth that thing that is writun to be fulfillid in me, And he is arettid with wickid men; for tho thingis that ben of me han ende.
25897	42	22	38	And thei seiden, Lord, lo! twei swerdis here. And he seide to hem, It is ynowy.
25898	42	22	39	And he yede out, and wente aftir the custom in to the hille of Olyues; and the disciplis sueden hym.
25899	42	22	40	And whanne he cam to the place, he seide to hem, Preye ye, lest ye entren in to temptacioun.
25900	42	22	41	And he was taken awei fro hem, so myche as is a stonys cast; and he knelide,
25901	42	22	42	and preyede, and seide, Fadir, if thou wolt, do awei this cuppe fro me; netheles not my wille be don, but thin.
25902	42	22	43	And an aungel apperide to hym fro heuene, and coumfortide hym. And he was maad in agonye, and preyede the lenger;
25903	42	22	44	and his swot was maad as dropis of blood rennynge doun in to the erthe.
25904	42	22	45	And whanne he was rysun fro preier, and was comun to hise disciplis, he foond hem slepynge for heuynesse.
25905	42	22	46	And he seide to hem, What slepen ye? Rise ye, and preye ye, that ye entre not in to temptacioun.
25906	42	22	47	Yit while he spak, lo! a company, and he that was clepid Judas, oon of the twelue, wente bifor hem; and he cam to Jhesu, to kisse hym.
25907	42	22	48	And Jhesus seide to hym, Judas, `with a coss `thou bytrayest `mannys sone.
25908	42	22	49	And thei that weren aboute hym, and sayn that that was to come, seiden to hym, Lord, whether we smyten with swerd?
25909	42	22	50	And oon of hem smoot the seruaunt of the prince of preestis, and kittide of his riyt eere.
25910	42	22	51	But Jhesus answerde, and seide, Suffre ye til hidir. And whanne he hadde touchid his eere, he heelide hym.
25911	42	22	52	And Jhesus seide to hem, that camen to hym, the princis of preestis, and maiestratis of the temple, and eldre men, As to a theef ye han gon out with swerdis and staues?
25912	42	22	53	Whanne Y was ech dai with you in the temple, ye streiyten not out hondis in to me; but this is youre our, and the power of derknessis.
25913	42	22	54	And thei token him, and ledden to the hous of the prince of prestis; and Petir suede hym afer.
25914	42	22	55	And whanne a fier was kyndelid in the myddil of the greet hous, and thei saten aboute, Petir was in the myddil of hem.
25915	42	22	56	Whom whanne a damysel hadde seyn sittynge `at the liyt, and hadde biholdun hym, sche seide, And this was with hym.
25916	42	22	57	And he denyede hym, and seide, Womman, Y knowe hym not.
25917	42	22	58	And aftir a litil another man siy hym, and seide, And thou art of hem. But Petir seide, A! man, Y am not.
25918	42	22	59	And whanne a space was maad as of on our, another affermyd, and seide, Treuli this was with hym; for also he is of Galilee.
25919	42	22	60	And Petir seide, Man, Y noot what thou seist. And anoon yit while he spak, the cok crewe.
25920	42	22	61	And the Lord turnede ayen, and bihelde Petre; and Petre hadde mynde on the word of Jhesu, as he hadde seid, For bifor that the cok crowe, thries thou schalt denye me.
25921	42	22	62	And Petre yede out, and wepte bittirli.
25922	42	22	63	And the men that helden hym scorneden hym, and smyten hym.
25923	42	22	64	And thei blynfelden hym, and smyten his face, and axiden hym, and seiden, Arede, thou Crist, to vs, who is he that smoot thee?
25924	42	22	65	Also thei blasfemynge seiden ayens hym many other thingis.
25925	42	22	66	And as the day was come, the eldre men of the puple, and the princis of prestis, and the scribis camen togidir, and ledden hym in to her councel,
25926	42	22	67	and seiden, If thou art Crist, seie to vs.
25927	42	22	68	And he seide to hem, If Y seie to you, ye schulen not bileue to me; and if Y axe, ye schulen not answere to me, nethir ye schulen delyuere me.
25928	42	22	69	But aftir this tyme mannys sone schal be sittynge on the riyt half of the vertu of God.
25929	42	22	70	Therfor alle seiden, Thanne art thou the sone of God? And he seide, Ye seien that Y am.
25930	42	22	71	And thei seiden, What yit desiren we witnessyng? for we vs silf han herd of his mouth.
25931	42	23	1	And al the multitude of hem arysen, and ledden hym to Pilat.
25932	42	23	2	And thei bigunnen to accuse hym, and seiden, We han foundun this turnynge vpsodoun oure folk, and forbedynge tributis to be youun to the emperour, and seiynge that hym silf is Crist and kyng.
25933	42	23	3	And Pilat axide hym, and seide, Art thou kyng of Jewis? And he answeride, and seide, Thou seist.
25934	42	23	4	And Pilat seide to the princis of prestis, and to the puple, Y fynde no thing of cause in this man.
25935	42	23	5	And thei woxen stronger, and seiden, He moueth the puple, techynge thorou al Judee, bigynnynge fro Galile til hidir.
25936	42	23	6	And Pilat herynge Galile axide, if he were a man of Galile.
25937	42	23	7	And whanne he knewe that he was of the powere of Eroude, he sente hym to Eroude; which was at Jerusalem in tho daies.
25938	42	23	8	And whanne Eroude siy Jhesu, he ioyede ful myche; for long tyme he coueitide to se hym, for he herde many thingis of hym, and hopide to see sum tokene `to be don of hym.
25939	42	23	9	And he axide hym in many wordis; and he answeride no thing to hym.
25940	42	23	10	And the princis of preestis and the scribis stoden, stidfastli accusynge hym.
25941	42	23	11	But Eroude with his oost dispiside hym, and scornede hym, and clothide with a white cloth, and sente hym ayen to Pilat.
25942	42	23	12	And Eroude and Pilat weren maad freendis fro that dai; for bifor thei weren enemyes togidre.
25943	42	23	13	And Pilat clepide togider the princis of prestis and the maiestratis of the puple, and seide to hem,
25944	42	23	14	Ye han brouyt to me this man, as turnynge awey the puple, and lo! Y axynge bifor you fynde no cause in this man of these thingis, in whiche ye accusen hym;
25945	42	23	15	nether Eroude, for he hath sent hym ayen to vs, and lo! no thing worthi of deth is don to hym.
25946	42	23	16	And therfor Y schal amende hym, and delyuere hym.
25947	42	23	17	But he moste nede delyuer to hem oon bi the feest dai.
25948	42	23	18	And al the puple criede togidir, and seide, Do `awei hym, and delyuer to vs Barabas;
25949	42	23	19	which was sent `in to prisoun for disturblyng maad in the cite, and for mansleynge.
25950	42	23	20	And eftsoone Pilat spak to hem, and wolde delyuer Jhesu.
25951	42	23	21	And thei vndurcrieden, and seiden, Crucifie, crucifie hym.
25952	42	23	22	And the thridde tyme he seide to hem, For what yuel hath this don? Y fynde no cause of deeth in hym; therfor Y schal chastise hym, and Y schal delyuer.
25953	42	23	23	And thei contynueden with greet voicis axynge, that he schulde be crucified; and the voicis of hem woxen stronge.
25954	42	23	24	And Pilat demyde her axyng to be don.
25955	42	23	25	And he delyueride to hem hym, that for mansleyng and sedicioun was sent in to prisoun, whom thei axiden; but he bitook Jhesu to her wille.
25956	42	23	26	And whanne thei ledden hym, thei token a man, Symon of Syrenen, comynge fro the toun, and thei leiden on hym the cross to bere aftir Jhesu.
25957	42	23	27	And there suede hym myche puple, and wymmen that weiliden, and bymorneden hym.
25958	42	23	28	And Jhesus turnede to hem, and seide, Douytris of Jerusalem, nyle ye wepe on me, but wepe ye on youre silf and on youre sones.
25959	42	23	29	For lo! daies schulen come, in whiche it schal be seid, Blessid be bareyn wymmen, and wombis that han not borun children, and the tetis that han not youun souke.
25960	42	23	30	Thanne thei schulen bigynne to seie to mounteyns, Falle ye doun on vs, and to smale hillis, Keuere ye vs.
25961	42	23	31	For if in a greene tre thei don these thingis, what schal be don in a drie?
25962	42	23	32	Also othere twei wickid men weren led with hym, to be slayn.
25963	42	23	33	And `aftir that thei camen in to a place, that is clepid of Caluerie, there thei crucifieden hym, and the theues, oon on the riyt half, and `the tother on the left half.
25964	42	23	34	But Jhesus seide, Fadir, foryyue hem, for thei witen not what thei doon.
25965	42	23	35	And thei departiden his clothis, and kesten lottis. And the puple stood abidynge; and the princis scorneden hym with hem, and seiden, Othere men he maad saaf; make he hym silf saaf, if this be Crist, the chosun of God.
25966	42	23	36	And the knyytis neiyeden, and scorneden hym, and profreden vynegre to hym,
25967	42	23	37	and seiden, If thou art king of Jewis, make thee saaf.
25968	42	23	38	And the superscripcioun was writun ouer hym with Greke lettris, and of Latyn, and of Ebreu, This is the kyng of Jewis.
25969	42	23	39	And oon of these theues that hangiden, blasfemyde hym, and seide, If thou art Crist, make thi silf saaf and vs.
25970	42	23	40	But `the tothir answerynge, blamyde hym, and seide, Nether thou dredist God, that art in the same dampnacioun?
25971	42	23	41	And treuli we iustli, for we han resseiued worthi thingis to werkis; but this dide no thing of yuel.
25972	42	23	42	And he seide to Jhesu, Lord, haue mynde of me, whanne thou comest `in to thi kyngdom.
25973	42	23	43	And Jhesus seide to hym, Treuli Y seie to thee, this dai thou schalt be with me in paradise.
25974	42	23	44	And it was almest the sixte our, and derknessis weren maad in al the erthe `in to the nynthe our.
25975	42	23	45	And the sun was maad derk, and the veile of the temple was to-rent atwo.
25976	42	23	46	And Jhesus criynge with a greet vois, seide, Fadir, in to thin hoondis Y bitake my spirit. And he seiynge these thingis, yaf vp the goost.
25977	42	23	47	And the centurien seynge that thing that was don, glorifiede God, and seide, Verili this man was iust.
25978	42	23	48	And al the puple of hem that weren there togidir at this spectacle, and sayn tho thingis that weren don, smyten her brestis, and turneden ayen.
25979	42	23	49	But alle his knowun stoden afer, and wymmen that sueden hym fro Galile, seynge these thingis.
25980	42	23	50	And lo! a man, Joseph bi name, of Aramathie, a cite of Judee, that was a decurien, a good man and a iust,
25981	42	23	51	this man concentide not to the counseil and to the dedis of hem; and he abood the kyngdom of God.
25982	42	23	52	This Joseph cam to Pilat, and axide the bodi of Jhesu,
25983	42	23	53	and took it doun, and wlappide it in a cleene lynen cloth, and leide hym in a graue hewun, in which not yit ony man hadde be leid.
25984	42	23	54	And the dai was the euen of the halidai, and the sabat bigan to schyne.
25985	42	23	55	And the wymmen suynge, that camen with hym fro Galile, sayn the graue, and hou his bodi was leid.
25986	42	23	56	And thei turneden ayen, and maden redi swete smellynge spicis, and oynementis; but in the sabat thei restiden, aftir the comaundement.
25987	42	24	1	But in o dai of the woke ful eerli thei camen to the graue, and brouyten swete smellynge spices, that thei hadden arayed.
25988	42	24	2	And thei founden the stoon turned awei fro the graue.
25989	42	24	3	And thei yeden in, and founden not the bodi of the Lord Jhesu.
25990	42	24	4	And it was don, the while thei weren astonyed in thouyt of this thing, lo! twei men stoden bisidis hem in schynynge cloth.
25991	42	24	5	And whanne thei dredden, and boweden her semblaunt in to the erthe, thei seiden to hem, What seken ye hym that lyueth with deed men?
25992	42	24	6	He is not here, but is risun. Haue ye mynde, hou he spak to you, whanne he was yit in Galile,
25993	42	24	7	and seide, For it bihoueth mannys sone to be bitakun in to the hondis of synful men, and to be crucified, and the thridde dai to rise ayen.
25994	42	24	8	And thei bithouyten on hise wordis.
25995	42	24	9	And thei yeden ayen fro the graue, and telden alle these thingis to the enleuene, and to alle othir.
25996	42	24	10	And ther was Marie Mawdeleyn, and Joone, and Marie of James, and other wymmen that weren with hem, that seiden to apostlis these thingis.
25997	42	24	11	And these wordis weren seyn bifor hem as madnesse, and thei bileueden not to hem.
25998	42	24	12	But Petir roos vp, and ran to the graue; and he bowide doun, and say the lynen clothis liynge aloone. And he wente bi him silf, wondrynge on that that was don.
25999	42	24	13	And lo! tweyne of hem wenten in that dai in to a castel, that was fro Jerusalem the space of sixti furlongis, bi name Emaws.
26000	42	24	14	And thei spaken togidir of alle these thingis that haddun bifallun.
26001	42	24	15	And it was don, the while thei talkiden, and souyten bi hem silf, Jhesus hym silf neiyede, and wente with hem.
26002	42	24	16	But her iyen weren holdun, that thei knewen him not.
26003	42	24	17	And he seide to hem, What ben these wordis, that ye speken togidir wandrynge, and ye ben sorewful?
26004	42	24	18	And oon, whos name was Cleofas, answerde, and seide, Thou thi silf art a pilgrym in Jerusalem, and hast thou not knowun, what thingis ben don in it in these daies?
26005	42	24	19	To whom he seide, What thingis? And thei seiden to hym, Of Jhesu of Nazareth, that was a man prophete, myyti in werk and word bifor God and al the puple;
26006	42	24	20	and hou the heiyest preestis of oure princis bitoken hym in to dampnacioun of deeth, and crucifieden hym.
26007	42	24	21	But we hopiden, that he schulde haue ayenbouyt Israel. And now on alle these thingis the thridde dai is to dai, that these thingis weren don.
26008	42	24	22	But also summe wymmen of ouris maden vs afered, whiche bifor dai weren at the graue; and whanne his bodi was not foundun,
26009	42	24	23	thei camen, and seiden, that thei syen also a siyt of aungels, whiche seien, that he lyueth.
26010	42	24	24	And summe of oure wenten to the graue, and thei founden so as the wymmen seiden, but thei founden not hym.
26011	42	24	25	And he seide to hem, A! foolis, and slowe of herte to bileue in alle thingis that the prophetis han spokun.
26012	42	24	26	Whethir it bihofte not Crist to suffre these thingis, and so to entre in to his glorie?
26013	42	24	27	And he bigan at Moises and at alle the prophetis, and declaride to hem in alle scripturis, that weren of hym.
26014	42	24	28	And thei camen nyy the castel, whidur thei wenten. And he made countenaunce that he wolde go ferthere.
26015	42	24	29	And thei constreyneden hym, and seiden, Dwelle with vs, for it drawith to nyyt, and the dai is now bowid doun.
26016	42	24	30	And he entride with hem. And it was don, while he sat at the mete with hem, he took breed, and blesside, and brak, and took to hem.
26017	42	24	31	And the iyen of hem weren openyd, and thei knewen hym; and he vanyschide fro her iyen.
26018	42	24	32	And thei seiden togidir, Whether oure herte was not brennynge in vs, while he spak in the weie, and openyde to vs scripturis?
26019	42	24	33	And thei risen vp in the same our, and wenten ayen in to Jerusalem, and founden the enleuene gaderid togidir, and hem that weren with hem,
26020	42	24	34	seiynge, That the Lord is risun verrili, and apperide to Symount.
26021	42	24	35	And thei tolden what thingis weren don in the weie, and hou thei knewen hym in brekyng of breed.
26022	42	24	36	And the while thei spaken these thingis, Jhesus stood in the myddil of hem, and seide to hem, Pees to you; Y am, nyle ye drede.
26023	42	24	37	But thei weren affraied and agast, and gessiden hem to se a spirit.
26024	42	24	38	And he seide to hem, What ben ye troblid, and thouytis comen vp in to youre hertis?
26025	42	24	39	Se ye my hoondis and my feet, for Y my silf am. Fele ye, and se ye; for a spirit hath not fleisch and boonys, as ye seen that Y haue.
26026	42	24	40	And whanne he hadde seid this thing, he schewide hoondis and feet to hem.
26027	42	24	41	And yit while thei bileueden not, and wondriden for ioye, he seide, Han ye here ony thing that schal be etun?
26028	42	24	42	And thei proferden hym a part of a fisch rostid, and an hony combe.
26029	42	24	43	And whanne he hadde etun bifore hem, he took that that lefte, and yaf to hem;
26030	42	24	44	and seide `to hem, These ben the wordis that Y spak to you, whanne Y was yit with you; for it is nede that alle thingis ben fulfillid, that ben writun in the lawe of Moises, and in prophetis, and in salmes, of me.
26031	42	24	45	Thanne he openyde to hem wit, that thei schulden vnderstonde scripturis.
26032	42	24	46	And he seide to hem, For thus it is writun, and thus it bihofte Crist to suffre, and ryse ayen fro deeth in the thridde dai;
26033	42	24	47	and penaunce and remyssioun of synnes to be prechid in his name `in to alle folkis, bigynnynge at Jerusalem.
26034	42	24	48	And ye ben witnessis of these thingis.
26035	42	24	49	And Y schal sende the biheest of my fadir in to you; but sitte ye in the citee, til that ye be clothid with vertu from an hiy.
26036	42	24	50	And he ledde hem forth in to Betanye, and whanne his hondis weren lift vp, he blesside hem.
26037	42	24	51	And it was don, the while he blesside hem, he departide fro hem, and was borun in to heuene.
26038	42	24	52	And thei worschipiden, and wenten ayen in to Jerusalem with greet ioye,
26039	42	24	53	and weren euermore in the temple, heriynge and blessynge God.
26040	43	1	1	In the bigynnyng was the word, and the word was at God, and God was the word.
26041	43	1	2	This was in the bigynnyng at God.
26042	43	1	3	Alle thingis weren maad bi hym, and withouten hym was maad no thing, that thing that was maad.
26043	43	1	4	In hym was lijf, and the lijf was the liyt of men; and the liyt schyneth in derknessis,
26044	43	1	5	and derknessis comprehendiden not it.
26045	43	1	6	A man was sent fro God, to whom the name was Joon.
26046	43	1	7	This man cam in to witnessyng, that he schulde bere witnessing of the liyt, that alle men schulden bileue bi hym.
26047	43	1	8	He was not the liyt, but that he schulde bere witnessing of the liyt.
26048	43	1	9	There was a very liyt, which liytneth ech man that cometh in to this world.
26049	43	1	10	He was in the world, and the world was maad bi hym, and the world knew hym not.
26050	43	1	11	He cam in to his owne thingis, and hise resseyueden hym not.
26051	43	1	12	But hou many euer resseyueden hym, he yaf to hem power to be maad the sones of God, to hem that bileueden in his name; the whiche not of bloodis,
26052	43	1	13	nether of the wille of fleische, nether of the wille of man, but ben borun of God.
26053	43	1	14	And the word was maad man, and dwellyde among vs, and we han seyn the glorie of hym, as the glorie of the `oon bigetun sone of the fadir, ful of grace and of treuthe.
26054	43	1	15	Joon berith witnessyng of hym, and crieth, and seith, This is, whom Y seide, He that schal come aftir me, is maad bifore me, for he was tofor me;
26055	43	1	16	and of the plente of hym we alle han takun, and grace for grace.
26056	43	1	17	For the lawe was youun bi Moises; but grace and treuthe `is maad bi Jhesu Crist.
26057	43	1	18	No man sai euer God, no but the `oon bigetun sone, that is in the bosum of the fadir, he hath teld out.
26058	43	1	19	And this is the witnessyng of Joon, whanne Jewis senten fro Jerusalem prestis and dekenes to hym, that thei schulden axe hym, Who art thou?
26059	43	1	20	He knoulechide, and denyede not, and he knoulechide, For Y am not Crist.
26060	43	1	21	And thei axiden hym, What thanne? Art thou Elie? And he seide, Y am not. Art thou a profete? And he answeride, Nay.
26061	43	1	22	Therfor thei seiden to hym, Who art thou? that we yyue an answere to these that senten vs. What seist thou of thi silf?
26062	43	1	23	He seide, Y am a vois of a crier in deseert, Dresse ye the weie of the Lord, as Ysaie, the prophete, seide.
26063	43	1	24	And thei that weren sent, weren of the Fariseis.
26064	43	1	25	And thei axiden hym, and seiden to hym, What thanne baptisist thou, if thou art not Crist, nether Elie, nether a profete?
26065	43	1	26	Joon answeride to hem, and seide, Y baptise in watir, but in the myddil of you hath stonde oon, that ye knowen not;
26066	43	1	27	he it is, that schal come aftir me, that was maad bifor me, of whom Y am not worthi to louse the thwong of his schoo.
26067	43	1	28	These thingis weren don in Bethanye biyende Jordan, where Joon was baptisyng.
26068	43	1	29	Anothir day Joon say Jhesu comynge to hym, and he seide, Lo! the lomb of God; lo! he that doith awei the synnes of the world.
26069	43	1	30	This is he, that Y seide of, Aftir me is comun a man, which was maad bifor me; for he was rather than Y.
26070	43	1	31	And Y knew hym not, but that he be schewid in Israel, therfor Y cam baptisynge in watir.
26071	43	1	32	And Joon bar witnessyng, and seide, That Y saiy the spirit comynge doun as a culuer fro heuene, and dwellide on hym.
26072	43	1	33	And Y knew hym not; but he that sente me to baptise in watir, seide to me, On whom thou seest the Spirit comynge doun, and dwellynge on hym, this is he, that baptisith in the Hooli Goost.
26073	43	1	34	And Y say, and bar witnessyng, that this is the sone of God.
26074	43	1	35	Anothir dai Joon stood, and tweyne of hise disciplis;
26075	43	1	36	and he biheeld Jhesu walkinge, and seith, Lo! the lomb of God.
26076	43	1	37	And twei disciplis herden hym spekynge,
26077	43	1	38	and folewiden Jhesu. And Jhesu turnede, and say hem suynge hym, and seith to hem, What seken ye? And thei seiden to hym, Rabi, that is to seie, Maistir, where dwellist thou?
26078	43	1	39	And he seith to hem, Come ye, and se. And thei camen, and sayn where he dwellide; and dwelten with hym that dai. And it was as the tenthe our.
26079	43	1	40	And Andrewe, the brother of Symount Petir, was oon of the tweyne, that herden of Joon, and hadden sued hym.
26080	43	1	41	This foond first his brother Symount, and he seide to him, We han foundun Messias, that is to seie, Crist; and he ledde him to Jhesu.
26081	43	1	42	And Jhesus bihelde hym, and seide, Thou art Symount, the sone of Johanna; thou schalt be clepid Cefas, that is to seie, Petre.
26082	43	1	43	And on the morewe he wolde go out in to Galilee, and he foond Filip; and he seith to hym, Sue thou me.
26083	43	1	44	Filip was of Bethsaida, the citee of Andrew and of Petre.
26084	43	1	45	Filip foond Nathanael, and seide to hym, We han foundun Jhesu, the sone of Joseph, of Nazareth, whom Moyses wroot in the lawe and profetis.
26085	43	1	46	And Nathanael seide to hym, Of Nazareth may sum good thing be?
26086	43	1	47	Filip seide to hym, Come, and se. Jhesus siy Nathanael comynge to hym, and seide to hym, Lo! verili a man of Israel, in whom is no gile.
26087	43	1	48	Nathanael seide to hym, Wherof hast thou knowun me? Jhesus `answerde, and seide to hym, Bifor that Filip clepide thee, whanne thou were vndur the fige tree, Y saiy thee. Nathanael answerde to hym,
26088	43	1	49	`and seide, Rabi, thou art the sone of God, thou art kyng of Israel.
26089	43	1	50	Jhesus answerde, and seide to hym, For Y seide to thee, Y sawy thee vndur the fige tre, thou bileuest; thou schalt se more than these thingis.
26090	43	1	51	And he seide to hem, Treuli, treuli, Y seie to you, ye schulen se heuene opened, and the aungels of God stiynge vp and comynge doun on mannys sone.
26091	43	2	1	And the thridde dai weddyngis weren maad in the Cane of Galilee; and the modir of Jhesu was there.
26092	43	2	2	And Jhesus was clepid, and hise disciplis, to the weddyngis.
26093	43	2	3	And whanne wijn failide, the modir of Jhesu seide to hym, Thei han not wijn.
26094	43	2	4	And Jhesus seith to hir, What to me and to thee, womman? myn our cam not yit.
26095	43	2	5	His modir seith to the mynystris, What euere thing he seie to you, do ye.
26096	43	2	6	And there weren set `sixe stonun cannes, aftir the clensyng of the Jewis, holdynge ech tweyne ether thre metretis.
26097	43	2	7	And Jhesus seith to hem, Fille ye the pottis with watir. And thei filliden hem, vp to the mouth.
26098	43	2	8	And Jhesus seide to hem, Drawe ye now, and bere ye to the architriclyn. And thei baren.
26099	43	2	9	And whanne the architriclyn hadde tastid the watir maad wiyn, and wiste not wherof it was, but the mynystris wisten that drowen the watir, the architriclyn clepith the spouse,
26100	43	2	10	and seith to hym, Ech man settith first good wiyn, and whanne men ben fulfillid, thanne that that is worse; but thou hast kept the good wiyn `in to this tyme.
26101	43	2	11	Jhesus dide this the bigynnyng of signes in the Cane of Galilee, and schewide his glorie; and hise disciplis bileueden in hym.
26102	43	2	12	Aftir these thingis he cam doun to Cafarnaum, and his modir, and hise britheren, and hise disciplis; and thei dwelliden `there not many daies.
26103	43	2	13	And the pask of Jewis was nyy, and Jhesus wente vp to Jerusalem.
26104	43	2	14	And he foond in the temple men sillynge oxun, and scheep, and culueris, and chaungeris sittynge.
26105	43	2	15	And whanne he hadde maad as it were a scourge of smale cordis, he droof out alle of the temple, and oxun, and scheep; and he schedde the money of chaungeris, and turnede vpsedoun the boordis.
26106	43	2	16	And he seide to hem that selden culueris, Take awei fro hennus these thingis, and nyle ye make the hous of my fadir an hous of marchaundise.
26107	43	2	17	And hise disciplis hadden mynde, for it was writun, The feruent loue of thin hous hath etun me.
26108	43	2	18	Therfor the Jewis answeriden, and seiden to hym, What token schewist thou to vs, that thou doist these thingis?
26109	43	2	19	Jhesus answerde, and seide to hem, Vndo ye this temple, and in thre daies Y schal reise it.
26110	43	2	20	Therfor the Jewis seiden to hym, In fourti and sixe yeer this temple was bildid, and schalt thou in thre daies reise it?
26111	43	2	21	But he seide of the temple of his bodi.
26112	43	2	22	Therfor whanne he was risun fro deeth, hise disciplis hadden mynde, that he seide these thingis of his bodi; and thei bileueden to the scripture, and to the word that Jhesus seide.
26113	43	2	23	And whanne Jhesus was at Jerusalem in pask, in the feeste dai, many bileueden in his name, seynge his signes that he dide.
26114	43	2	24	But Jhesus trowide not hym silf to hem, for he knewe alle men;
26115	43	2	25	and for it was not nede to hym, that ony man schulde bere witnessyng, for he wiste, what was in man.
26116	43	3	1	And there was a man of the Farisees, Nychodeme bi name, a prince of the Jewis.
26117	43	3	2	And he cam to Jhesu bi niyt, and seide to hym, Rabi, we witen, that thou art comun fro God maister; for no man may do these signes, that thou doist, but God be with hym.
26118	43	3	3	Jhesus answerde, and seide to hym, Treuli, treuli, Y seie to thee, but a man be borun ayen, he may not se the kyngdom of God.
26119	43	3	4	Nychodeme seide to hym, Hou may a man be borun, whanne he is eeld? whether he may entre ayen in to his modris wombe, and be borun ayen?
26120	43	3	5	Jhesus answeride, Treuli, treuli, Y seie to thee, but a man be borun ayen of watir, and of the Hooli Goost, he may not entre in to the kyngdom of God.
26121	43	3	6	`That that is borun of the fleisch, is fleisch; and `that that is borun of spirit, is spirit.
26122	43	3	7	Wondre thou not, for Y seide to thee, It bihoueth you to be borun ayen.
26123	43	3	8	The spirit brethith where he wole, and thou herist his vois, but thou wost not, fro whennus he cometh, ne whidir he goith; so is ech man that is borun of the spirit.
26124	43	3	9	Nychodeme answeride, and seide to hym, Hou moun these thingis be don?
26125	43	3	10	Jhesus answeride, and seide to hym, Thou art a maister in Israel, and knowist not these thingis?
26126	43	3	11	Treuli, treuli, Y seie to thee, for we speken that that we witen, and we witnessen that that we han seyn, and ye taken not oure witnessyng.
26127	43	3	12	If Y haue seid to you ertheli thingis, and ye bileuen not, hou if Y seie to you heueneli thingis, schulen ye bileue?
26128	43	3	13	And no man stieth in to heuene, but he that cam doun fro heuene, mannys sone that is in heuene.
26129	43	3	14	And as Moises areride a serpent in desert, so it bihoueth mannys sone to be reisid,
26130	43	3	15	that ech man that bileueth in hym, perische not, but haue euerlastynge lijf.
26131	43	3	16	For God louede so the world, that he yaf his `oon bigetun sone, that ech man that bileueth in him perische not, but haue euerlastynge lijf.
26132	43	3	17	For God sente not his sone in to the world, that he iuge the world, but that the world be saued bi him.
26133	43	3	18	He that bileueth in hym, is not demed; but he that bileueth not, is now demed, for he bileueth not in the name of the `oon bigetun sone of God.
26134	43	3	19	And this is the dom, for liyt cam in to the world, and men loueden more derknessis than liyt; for her werkes weren yuele.
26135	43	3	20	For ech man that doith yuele, hatith the liyt; and he cometh not to the liyt, that hise werkis be not repreued.
26136	43	3	21	But he that doith treuthe, cometh to the liyt, that hise werkis be schewid, that thei ben don in God.
26137	43	3	22	Aftir these thingis Jhesus cam, and hise disciplis, in to the loond of Judee, and there he dwellide with hem, and baptiside.
26138	43	3	23	And Joon was baptisinge in Ennon, bisidis Salym, for many watris weren there; and thei camen, and weren baptisid.
26139	43	3	24	And Joon was not yit sent in to prisoun.
26140	43	3	25	Therfor a questioun was maad of Jonys disciplis with the Jewis, of the purificacioun.
26141	43	3	26	And thei camen to Joon, and seiden `to hym, Maister, he that was with thee biyonde Jordan, to whom thou hast borun witnessyng, lo! he baptisith, and alle men comen to hym.
26142	43	3	27	Joon answerde, and seide, A man may not take ony thing, but it be youun to hym fro heuene.
26143	43	3	28	Ye you silf beren witnessyng to me, that Y seide, Y am not Crist, but that Y am sent bifore hym.
26144	43	3	29	He that hath a wijf, is the hosebonde; but the freend of the spouse that stondith, and herith hym, ioieth with ioye, for the vois of the spouse. Therfor in this thing my ioye is fulfillid.
26145	43	3	30	It bihoueth hym to wexe, but me to be maad lesse.
26146	43	3	31	He that cam from aboue, is aboue alle; he that is of the erthe, spekith of the erthe; he that cometh from heuene, is aboue alle.
26147	43	3	32	And he witnessith that thing that he hath seie, and herde, and no man takith his witnessing.
26148	43	3	33	But he that takith his witnessyng, hath confermyd that God is sothefast.
26149	43	3	34	But he whom God hath sent, spekith the wordis of God; for not to mesure God yyueth the spirit.
26150	43	3	35	The fadir loueth the sone, and he hath youun alle thingis in his hoond.
26151	43	3	36	He that bileueth in the sone, hath euerlastynge lijf; but he that is vnbileueful to the sone, schal not se euerlastynge lijf, but the wraththe of God dwellith on hym.
26152	43	4	1	Therfor as Jhesu knew, that the Farisees herden, that Jhesu makith and baptisith mo disciplis than Joon,
26153	43	4	2	thouy Jhesus baptiside not, but hise disciplis, he lefte Judee,
26154	43	4	3	and wente ayen in to Galilee.
26155	43	4	4	And it bihofte hym to passe bi Samarie.
26156	43	4	5	Therfor Jhesus cam in to a citee of Samarie, that is seid Sicar, bisidis the place, that Jacob yaf to Joseph, his sone.
26157	43	4	6	And the welle of Jacob was there; and Jhesus was weri of the iourney, and sat thus vpon the welle. And the our was, as it were the sixte.
26158	43	4	7	And a womman cam fro Samarie, to drawe watir. And Jhesus seith to hir, Yyue me drynk.
26159	43	4	8	And hise disciplis weren gon in to the citee, to bie mete.
26160	43	4	9	Therfor thilke womman of Samarie seith to him, Hou thou, `whanne thou art a Jewe, axist of me drynk, that am a womman of Samarie? for Jewis vsiden not to dele with Samaritans.
26161	43	4	10	Jhesus answerde, and seide to hir, If thou wistist the yifte of God, and who `he is, that seith to thee, Yyue me drynk, thou perauenture woldist haue axid of hym, and he schulde haue youun to thee quyk watir.
26162	43	4	11	The womman seith to him, Sire, thou hast not where ynne to drawe, and the pit is deep; wherof thanne hast thou quik watir?
26163	43	4	12	Whethir thou art grettere than oure fadir Jacob, that yaf to vs the pit? and he drank therof, and hise sones, and hise beestis.
26164	43	4	13	Jhesus answerde, and seide to hir, Eche man that drynkith of this watir, schal thirste efte soone; but he that drynkith of the watir that Y schal yyue hym, schal not thirste with outen ende; but the watir that Y schal yyue hym,
26165	43	4	14	schal be maad in hym a welle `of watir, spryngynge vp in to euerlastynge lijf.
26166	43	4	15	The womman seith to hym, Sire, yyue me this watir, that Y thirste not, nether come hidur to drawe.
26167	43	4	16	Jhesus seith to hir, Go, clepe thin hosebonde, and come hidir.
26168	43	4	17	The womman answerde, and seide, Y haue noon hosebonde. Jhesus seith to hir, Thou seidist wel, That Y haue noon hosebonde;
26169	43	4	18	for thou hast hadde fyue hosebondis, and he that thou hast, is not thin hosebonde. This thing thou seidist sotheli.
26170	43	4	19	The womman seith to hym, Lord, Y se, that thou art a prophete.
26171	43	4	20	Oure fadris worschipiden in this hil, and ye seien, that at Jerusalem is a place, where it bihoueth to worschipe.
26172	43	4	21	Jhesus seith to hir, Womman, bileue thou to me, for the our schal come, whanne nether in this hil, nethir in Jerusalem, ye schulen worschipe the fadir.
26173	43	4	22	Ye worschipen that ye knowen not; we worschipen that that we knowen; for helthe is of the Jewis.
26174	43	4	23	But the tyme is comun, and now it is, whanne trewe worschiperis schulen worschipe the fadir in spirit and treuthe; for also the fadir sekith suche, that worschipen hym.
26175	43	4	24	God is a spirit, and it bihoueth hem that worschipen hym, to worschipe in spirit and treuthe.
26176	43	4	25	The womman seith to hym, Y woot that Messias is comun, that is seid Crist; therfor whanne he cometh, he schal telle vs alle thingis.
26177	43	4	26	Jhesus seith to hir, Y am he, that spekith with thee.
26178	43	4	27	And anoon hise disciplis camen, and wondriden, that he spak with the womman; netheles no man seide to hym, What sekist thou, or, What spekist thou with hir?
26179	43	4	28	Therfor the womman lefte hir watir pot, and wente in to the citee, and seide to tho men,
26180	43	4	29	Come ye, and se ye a man, that seide to me alle thingis that Y haue don; whether he be Crist?
26181	43	4	30	And thei wenten out of the citee, and camen to hym.
26182	43	4	31	In the mene while hise disciplis preieden hym, and seiden, Maistir, ete.
26183	43	4	32	But he seide to hem, Y haue mete to ete, that ye knowen not.
26184	43	4	33	Therfor disciplis seiden togidir, Whether ony man hath brouyt him mete to ete?
26185	43	4	34	Jhesus seith to hem, My mete is, that Y do the wille of hym that sente me, that Y perfourme the werk of hym.
26186	43	4	35	Whether ye seien not, that yit foure monethis ben, and rype corn cometh? Lo! Y seie to you, lifte vp youre iyen, and se ye the feeldis, for now thei ben white to repe.
26187	43	4	36	And he that repith takith hire, and gaderith fruyt in to euerlastynge lijf; that bothe he that sowith, and he that repith, haue ioye togidere.
26188	43	4	37	In this thing is the word trewe, for anothir is that sowith, and anothir that repith.
26189	43	4	38	Y sente you to repe, that that ye `haue not trauelid; `othere men han trauelid, and ye han entrid `in to her trauels.
26190	43	4	39	And of that citee many Samaritans bileueden in hym, for the word of the womman, that bare witnessyng, That he seide to me alle thingis that Y haue don.
26191	43	4	40	Therfor whanne Samaritans camen to hym, thei preieden hym to dwelle there; and he dwelte there twey daies.
26192	43	4	41	And many mo bileueden for his word,
26193	43	4	42	and seiden to the womman, That now not for thi speche we bileuen; for we han herd, and we witen, that this is verili the sauyour of the world.
26194	43	4	43	And aftir twei daies he wente out fro thennus, and wente in to Galilee.
26195	43	4	44	And he bar witnessyng, that a profete in his owne cuntre hath noon onour.
26196	43	4	45	Therfor whanne he cam in to Galilee, men of Galilee resseyueden hym, whanne thei hadden seyn alle thingis that he hadde don in Jerusalem in the feeste dai; for also thei hadden comun to the feeste dai.
26197	43	4	46	Therfor he cam eftsoone in to the Cane of Galile, where he made the watir wiyn. And `a litil kyng was, whos sone was sijk at Cafarnaum.
26198	43	4	47	Whanne this hadde herd, that Jhesu schulde come fro Judee in to Galilee, he wente to hym, and preiede hym, that he schulde come doun, and heele his sone; for he bigan to die.
26199	43	4	48	Therfor Jhesus seide to him, But ye se tokenes and grete wondris, ye bileuen not.
26200	43	4	49	The litil kyng seith to hym, Lord, come doun, bifor that my sone die.
26201	43	4	50	Jhesus seith to hym, Go, thi sone lyueth. The man bileuede to the word, that Jhesus seide to hym, and he wente.
26202	43	4	51	And now whanne he cam doun, the seruauntis camen ayens hym, and telden to hym, and seiden, That his sone lyuede.
26203	43	4	52	And he axide of hem the our, in which he was amendid. And thei seiden to hym, For yistirdai in the seuenthe our the feuer lefte him.
26204	43	4	53	Therfor the fadir knewe, that thilke our it was, in which Jhesus seide to hym, Thi sone lyueth; and he bileuede, and al his hous.
26205	43	4	54	Jhesus dide eft this secounde tokene, whanne he cam fro Judee in to Galilee.
26206	43	5	1	Aftir these thingis ther was a feeste dai of Jewis, and Jhesus wente vp to Jerusalem.
26207	43	5	2	And in Jerusalem is a waissynge place, that in Ebrew is named Bethsaida, and hath fyue porchis.
26208	43	5	3	In these lay a greet multitude of sike men, blynde, crokid, and drie, abidynge the mouyng of the watir.
26209	43	5	4	For the aungel `of the Lord cam doun certeyne tymes in to the watir, and the watir was moued; and he that first cam doun in to the sisterne, aftir the mouynge of the watir, was maad hool of what euer sijknesse he was holdun.
26210	43	5	5	And a man was there, hauynge eiyte and thritti yeer in his sikenesse.
26211	43	5	6	And whanne Jhesus hadde seyn hym liggynge, and hadde knowun, that he hadde myche tyme, he seith to hym, Wolt thou be maad hool?
26212	43	5	7	The sijk man answerde to hym, Lord, Y haue no man, that whanne the watir is moued, to putte me `in to the cisterne; for the while Y come, anothir goith doun bifor me.
26213	43	5	8	Jhesus seith to hym, Rise vp, take thi bed, and go.
26214	43	5	9	And anoon the man was maad hool, and took vp his bed, and wente forth. And it was sabat in that dai.
26215	43	5	10	Therfor the Jewis seiden to him that was maad hool, It is sabat, it is not leueful to thee, to take awei thi bed.
26216	43	5	11	He answeride to hem, He that made me hool, seide to me, Take thi bed, and go.
26217	43	5	12	Therfor thei axiden him, What man `is that, that seide to thee, Take vp thi bed, and go?
26218	43	5	13	But he that was maad hool, wiste not who it was. And Jhesus bowide awei fro the puple, that was set in the place.
26219	43	5	14	Aftirward Jhesus foond hym in the temple, and seide to hym, Lo! thou art maad hool; now nyle thou do synne, lest any worse thing bifalle to thee.
26220	43	5	15	Thilke man wente, and telde to the Jewis, that it was Jhesu that made hym hool.
26221	43	5	16	Therfor the Jewis pursueden Jhesu, for he dide this thing in the sabat.
26222	43	5	17	And Jhesus answeride to hem, My fadir worchith til now, and Y worche.
26223	43	5	18	Therfor the Jewis souyten more to sle hym, for not oneli he brak the sabat, but he seide that God was his fadir, and made hym euene to God.
26224	43	5	19	Therfor Jhesus answerde, and seide to hem, Treuli, treuli, Y seye to you, the sone may not of hym silf do ony thing, but that thing that he seeth the fadir doynge; for what euere thingis he doith, the sone doith in lijk maner tho thingis.
26225	43	5	20	For the fadir loueth the sone, and schewith to hym alle thingis that he doith; and he schal schewe to hym grettere werkis than these, that ye wondren.
26226	43	5	21	For as the fadir reisith deed men, and quykeneth, so the sone quykeneth whom he wole.
26227	43	5	22	For nethir the fadir iugith ony man, but hath youun ech doom to the sone,
26228	43	5	23	that alle men onoure the sone, as thei onouren the fadir. He that onourith not the sone, onourith not the fadir that sente hym.
26229	43	5	24	Treuli, treuli, Y seie to you, that he that herith my word, and bileueth to hym that sente me, hath euerlastynge lijf, and he cometh not in to doom, but passith fro deeth in to lijf.
26230	43	5	25	Treuli, treuli Y seie to you, for the our cometh, and now it is, whanne deed men schulen here the vois of `Goddis sone, and thei that heren, schulen lyue.
26231	43	5	26	For as the fadir hath lijf in hym silf, so he yaf to the sone, to haue lijf in him silf;
26232	43	5	27	and he yaf to hym power to make doom, for he is mannys sone.
26233	43	5	28	Nyle ye wondre this, for the our cometh, in which alle men that ben in birielis, schulen here the voice of Goddis sone.
26234	43	5	29	And thei that han do goode thingis, schulen go in to ayenrisyng of lijf; but thei that han done yuele thingis, in to ayenrisyng of doom.
26235	43	5	30	Y may no thing do of my silf, but as Y here, Y deme, and my doom is iust, for Y seke not my wille, but the wille of the fadir that sente me.
26236	43	5	31	If Y bere witnessing of my silf, my witnessyng is not trewe;
26237	43	5	32	another is that berith witnessyng of me, and Y woot that his witnessyng is trewe, that he berith of me.
26238	43	5	33	Ye senten to Joon, and he bar witnessyng to treuthe.
26239	43	5	34	But Y take not witnessyng of man; but Y seie these thingis, that ye be saaf.
26240	43	5	35	He was a lanterne brennynge and schynynge; but ye wolden glade at an our in his liyt.
26241	43	5	36	But Y haue more witnessyng than Joon, for the werkis that my fadir yaf to me to perfourme hem, thilke werkis that Y do beren witnessyng of me, that the fadir sente me.
26242	43	5	37	And the fadir that sente me, he bar witnessyng of me. Nether ye herden euere his vois, nether ye seien his licnesse.
26243	43	5	38	And ye han not his word dwellynge in you; for ye byleuen not to hym, whom he sente.
26244	43	5	39	Seke ye scripturis, in which ye gessen to haue euerlastynge lijf; and tho it ben, that beren witnessyng of me.
26245	43	5	40	And ye wolen not come to me, that ye haue lijf.
26246	43	5	41	Y take not clerenesse of men;
26247	43	5	42	but Y haue knowun you, that ye han not the loue of God in you.
