27456	44	15	22	Thanne it pleside to the apostlis, and to the eldre men, with al the chirche, to chees men of hem, and sende to Antioche, with Poul and Barnabas, Judas, that was named Barsabas, and Silas, the firste men among britheren;
27457	44	15	23	and wroten bi the hondis of hem, Apostlis and eldre britheren to hem that ben at Antioche, and Sirie, and Silice, britheren of hethen men, greting.
27458	44	15	24	For we herden that summe wenten out fro vs, and trobliden you with wordis, and turneden vpsodoun youre soulis, to whiche men we comaundiden not,
27459	44	15	25	it pleside to vs gaderid in to oon, to chese men, and sende to you, with oure most dereworthe Barnabas and Poul,
27460	44	15	26	men that yauen her lyues for the name of oure Lord Jhesu Crist.
27461	44	15	27	Therfor we senten Judas and Silas, and thei schulen telle the same thingis to you bi wordis.
27462	44	15	28	For it is seyn to the Hooly Goost and to vs, to putte to you no thing more of charge, than these nedeful thingis,
27463	44	15	29	that ye absteyne you fro the offrid thingis of maumetis, and blood stranglid, and fornicacioun. Fro whiche ye kepinge you, schulen do wel. Fare ye wel.
27464	44	15	30	Therfor thei weren let go, and camen doun to Antioche; and whanne the multitude was gaderid, thei token the epistle;
27465	44	15	31	which whanne thei hadden red, thei ioyden on the coumfort.
27466	44	15	32	And Judas and Silas and thei, for thei weren prophetis, coumfortiden britheren, and confermyden with ful many wordis.
27467	44	15	33	But aftir that thei hadden be there a lytil while, thei weren let go of britheren with pees, to hem that hadden sent hem.
27468	44	15	34	But it was seyn to Silas, to dwelle there; and Judas wente aloone to Jerusalem.
27469	44	15	35	And Poul and Barnabas dwelten at Antioche, techinge and prechinge the word of the Lord, with othere manye.
27470	44	15	36	But after summe daies, Poul seide to Barnabas, Turne we ayen, and visite britheren bi alle citees, in whiche we han prechid the word of the Lord, hou thei han hem.
27471	44	15	37	And Barnabas wolde take with hym Joon, that was named Marcus.
27472	44	15	38	But Poul preiede him, that he that departide fro hem fro Pamfilie, and wente not with hem in to the werk, schulde not be resseyued.
27473	44	15	39	And dissencioun was maad, so that thei departiden a twynny. And Barnabas took Mark, and cam bi boot to Cipre.
27474	44	15	40	And Poul chees Silas, and wente forth fro the britheren, and was bitakun to the grace of God.
27475	44	15	41	And he wente bi Sirie and Silice, and confermyde the chirche, comaundinge to kepe the heestis of apostlis and eldre men.
27476	44	16	1	And he cam in to Derben and Listram. And lo! a disciple was there, bi name Timothe, the sone of a Jewesse cristen, and of the fadir hethen.
27477	44	16	2	And britheren that weren in Listris and Iconye, yeldiden good witnessing to hym.
27478	44	16	3	And Poul wolde that this man schulde go forth with him, and he took, and circumsidide hym, for Jewis that weren in the places. For alle wisten, that his fadir was hethen.
27479	44	16	4	Whanne thei passiden bi citees, thei bitoken to hem to kepe the techingis, that weren demyd of apostlis and eldre men, that weren at Jerusalem.
27480	44	16	5	And the chirches weren confermed in feith, and encreseden in noumbre eche dai.
27481	44	16	6	And thei passiden Frigie, and the cuntre of Galathi, and weren forbedun of the Hooli Goost to speke the word of God in Asie.
27482	44	16	7	And whanne thei camen in to Mysie, thei assaieden to go in to Bithynye, and the spirit of Jhesu suffride not hem.
27483	44	16	8	But whanne thei hadden passid bi Mysie, thei camen doun to Troade;
27484	44	16	9	and a visioun `bi nyyt was schewid to Poul. But a man of Macedonye that stoode, preiede hym, and seide, Go thou in to Macedonye, and helpe vs.
27485	44	16	10	And as he hadde sei the visioun, anoon we souyten to go forth in to Macedonye, and weren maad certeyn, that God hadde clepid vs to preche to hem.
27486	44	16	11	And we yeden bi schip fro Troade, and camen to Samatrachia with streiyt cours; and the dai suynge to Neapolis;
27487	44	16	12	and fro thennus to Filippis, that is the firste part of Macedonye, the citee colonye. And we weren in this citee summe daies, and spaken togidere.
27488	44	16	13	And in the dai of sabotis we wenten forth with out the yate bisidis the flood, where preier semyde to be; and we saten, and spaken to wymmen that camen togidere.
27489	44	16	14	And a womman, Lidda bi name, a purpuresse of the cite of Tiatirens, worschipinge God, herde; whos herte the Lord openyde to yyue tente to these thingis, that weren seid of Poul.
27490	44	16	15	And whanne sche was baptisid and hir hous, sche preyede, and seide, If ye han demyd that Y am feithful to the Lord, entre ye in to myn hous, and dwelle.
27491	44	16	16	And sche constreynede vs. And it was don, whanne we yeden to preier, that a damysel that hadde a spirit of diuynacioun, mette vs, which yaf greet wynnyng to her lordis in dyuynynge.
27492	44	16	17	This suede Poul and vs, and criede, and seide, These men ben seruauntis of the hiy God, that tellen to you the weie of helthe.
27493	44	16	18	And this sche dide in many daies. And Poul sorewide, and turnede, and seide to the spirit, Y comaunde thee in the name of Jhesu Crist, that thou go out of hir.
27494	44	16	19	And he wente out in the same our. And the lordis of hir siyen, that the hope of her wynnyng wente awei, and thei token Poul and Silas, and ledden in to the `dom place, to the princis.
27495	44	16	20	And thei brouyten hem to the magistratis, and seiden, These men disturblen oure citee,
27496	44	16	21	for thei ben Jewis, and schewen a custom, which it is not leueful to vs to resseyue, nether do, sithen we ben Romayns.
27497	44	16	22	And the puple `and magistratis runnen ayens hem, and when thei hadden to-rente the cootis of hem, thei comaundiden hem to be betun with yerdis.
27498	44	16	23	And whanne thei hadden youun to hem many woundis, thei senten hem into prisoun, and comaundiden to the kepere, that he schulde kepe hem diligentli.
27499	44	16	24	And whanne he hadde take siche a precept, he putte hem into the ynnere prisoun, and streynede the feet of hem in a tre.
27500	44	16	25	And at mydniyt Poul and Silas worschipide, and heriden God; and thei that weren in kepyng herden hem.
27501	44	16	26	And sudenli a greet erthe mouyng was maad, so that the foundementis of the prisoun weren moued. And anoon alle the doris weren openyd, and the boondis of alle weren lousid.
27502	44	16	27	And the kepere of the prisoun was awakid, and siy the yatis `of the prisoun openyd, and with a swerd drawun out he wolde haue slawe hym silf, and gesside that the men that weren boundun, hadden fled.
27503	44	16	28	But Poul criede with a greet vois, and seide, Do thou noon harm to thi silf, for alle we ben here.
27504	44	16	29	And he axide liyt, and entride, and tremblide, and felle doun to Poul and to Silas at her feet.
27505	44	16	30	And he brouyte hem with out forth, and seide, Lordis, what bihoueth me to do, that Y be maad saaf?
27506	44	16	31	And thei seiden, Bileue thou in the Lord Jhesu, and thou schalt be saaf, and thin hous.
27507	44	16	32	And thei spaken to hym the word of the Lord, with alle that weren in his hous.
27508	44	16	33	And he took hem in the ilke our of the niyt, and waschide her woundis. And he was baptisid, and al his hous anoon.
27509	44	16	34	And whanne he hadde led hem in to his hous, he settide to hem a boord. And he was glad with al his hous, and bileuede to God.
27510	44	16	35	And whanne dai was come, the magistratis senten catchepollis, and seiden, Delyuere thou tho men.
27511	44	16	36	And the kepere of the prisoun telde these wordis to Poul, That the magistratis han sent, that ye be delyuered; now therfor go ye out, and go ye in pees.
27512	44	16	37	And Poul seide to hem, Thei senten vs men of Rome in to prisoun, that weren betun openli and vndampned, and now priueli thei bringen vs out; not so, but come thei hem silf, and delyuere vs out.
27513	44	16	38	And the catchepollis telden these wordis to the magistratis; and thei dredden, for thei herden that thei weren Romayns.
27514	44	16	39	And thei camen, and bisechiden hem, and thei brouyten hem out, and preieden, that thei schulden go out of the citee.
27515	44	16	40	And thei yeden out of the prisoun, and entriden to Lidie. And whanne thei siyen britheren, thei coumfortiden hem, and yeden forth.
27516	44	17	1	And whanne thei hadden passid bi Amfipolis and Appollonye, thei camen to Thessolonyk, where was a synagoge of Jewis.
27517	44	17	2	And bi custom Poul entride to hem, and bi thre sabatis he declaride to hem of scripturis,
27518	44	17	3	and openyde, and schewide that it bihofte Crist to suffre, and rise ayen fro deth, and that this is Jhesus Crist, whom Y telle to you.
27519	44	17	4	And summe of hem bileueden, and weren ioyned to Poul and to Silas; and a greet multitude of hethene men worschipide God, and noble wymmen not a fewe.
27520	44	17	5	But the Jewis hadden enuye, and token of the comyn puple summe yuele men, and whanne thei hadden maad a cumpenye, thei moueden the citee. And thei camen to Jasouns hous, and souyten hem to brynge forth among the puple.
27521	44	17	6	And whanne thei founden hem not, thei drowen Jasoun and summe britheren to the princis of the citee, and crieden, That these it ben, that mouen the world, and hidir thei camen,
27522	44	17	7	whiche Jason resseyuede. And these alle don ayens the maundementis of the emperour, and seien, that Jhesu is anothir king.
27523	44	17	8	And thei moueden the puple, and the princis of the citee, herynge these thingis.
27524	44	17	9	And whanne satisfaccioun was takun of Jason, and of othere, thei leten Poul and Silas go.
27525	44	17	10	And anoon bi niyt britheren leten Silas go in to Beroan. And whanne thei camen thidur, thei entriden in to the synagoge of the Jewis.
27526	44	17	11	But these weren the worthier of hem that ben at Thessolonik, whiche resseyueden the word with al desire, eche dai sekinge scripturis, if these thingis hadden hem so.
27527	44	17	12	And manye of hem bileueden and of hethen wymmen onest and men not a fewe.
27528	44	17	13	But whanne the Jewis in Tessalonyk hadden knowe, that also at Bero the word of God was prechid of Poul, thei camen thidir, mouynge and disturblynge the multitude.
27529	44	17	14	And tho anoon britheren delyuerden Poul, that he schulde go to the see; but Sylas and Tymothe dwelten there.
27530	44	17	15	And thei that ledden forth Poul, ledden hym to Atenes. And whanne thei hadden take maundement of him to Silas and to Tymothe, that ful hiyyngli thei schulden come to hym, thei wenten forth.
27531	44	17	16	And while Poul abood hem at Atenys, his spirit was moued in him, for he saiy the citee youun to ydolatrie.
27532	44	17	17	Therfor he disputide in the synagoge with the Jewis, and with men that worschipiden God, and in the dom place, by alle daies to hem that herden.
27533	44	17	18	And summe Epeicureis, and Stoisens, and filosofris disputiden with hym. And summe seiden, What wole this sowere of wordis seie? And othere seiden, He semeth to be a tellere of newe fendis; for he telde to hem Jhesu, and the ayenrisyng.
27534	44	17	19	And thei token, and ledden hym to Ariopage, and seide, Moun we wite, what is this newe doctryne, that is seid of thee?
27535	44	17	20	For thou bringist ynne summe newe thingis to oure eeris; therfor we wolen wite, what these thingis wolen be.
27536	44	17	21	For alle men of Athenys and comlingis herborid yauen tent to noon other thing, but ether to seie, ethir to here, sum newe thing.
27537	44	17	22	And Poul stood in the myddil of Ariopage, and seide, Men of Athenys, bi alle thingis Y se you as veyn worschipers.
27538	44	17	23	For Y passide, and siy youre maumetis, and foond an auter, in which was writun, To the vnknowun God. Therfor which thing ye vnknowynge worschipen, this thing Y schew to you.
27539	44	17	24	God that made the world and alle thingis that ben in it, this, for he is Lord of heuene and of erthe, dwellith not in templis maad with hoond,
27540	44	17	25	nethir is worschipid bi mannus hoondis, nether hath nede of ony thing, for he yyueth lijf to alle men, and brethinge, and alle thingis;
27541	44	17	26	and made of oon al the kinde of men to enhabite on al the face of the erthe, determynynge tymes ordeyned, and termes of the dwellynge of hem,
27542	44	17	27	to seke God, if perauenture thei felen hym, ether fynden, thouy he be not fer fro eche of you.
27543	44	17	28	For in hym we lyuen, and mouen, and ben. As also summe of youre poetis seiden, And we ben also the kynde of hym.
27544	44	17	29	Therfor sithen we ben the kynde of God, we schulen not deme, that godli thing is lijk gold, and siluer, ethir stoon, ethir to grauyng of craft and thouyt of man.
27545	44	17	30	For God dispisith the tymes of this vnkunnyng, and now schewith to men, that alle euery where doon penaunce; for that he hath ordeyned a dai,
27546	44	17	31	in which he schal deme the world in equite, in a man in which he ordeynede, and yaf feith to alle men, and reiside hym fro deth.
27547	44	17	32	And whanne thei hadden herd the ayenrysing of deed men, summe scorneden, and summe seiden, We schulen here thee eft of this thing.
27548	44	17	33	So Poul wente out of the myddil of hem.
27549	44	17	34	But summen drowen to hym, and bileueden. Among whiche Dynyse Aropagite was, and a womman, bi name Damaris, and othere men with hem.
27550	44	18	1	Aftir these thingis Poul yede out of Atenes, and cam to Corinthie.
27551	44	18	2	And he fonde a man, a Jewe, Aquila bi name, of Ponte bi kynde, that late cam from Ytalie, and Priscille, his wijf, for that Claudius comaundide alle Jewis to departe fro Rome; and he cam to hem.
27552	44	18	3	And for he was of the same craft, he dwellide with hem, and wrouyte; and thei weren of roopmakeris craft.
27553	44	18	4	And he disputide in the synagoge bi ech sabat, puttynge among the name of the Lord Jhesu; and he counselide Jewis and Grekis.
27554	44	18	5	And whanne Silas and Tymothe camen fro Macedonye, Poul yaf bisynesse to the word, and witnesside to the Jewis, that Jhesu is Crist.
27555	44	18	6	But whanne thei ayenseiden and blasfemyden, he schoke awei hise clothis, and seide to hem, Youre blood be on youre heed; Y schal be clene from hennus forth, and schal go to hethene men.
27556	44	18	7	And he passide fro thennus, and entride in to the hous of a iust man, Tite bi name, that worschipide God, whos hous was ioyned to the synagoge.
27557	44	18	8	And Crispe, prince of the synagoge, bileuede to the Lord, with al his hous. And many of the Corinthies herden, and bileueden, and weren cristened.
27558	44	18	9	And the Lord seide bi nyyt to Poul bi a visioun, Nyle thou drede, but speke, and be not stille;
27559	44	18	10	for Y am with thee, and no man schal be put to thee to noye thee, for myche puple is to me in this citee.
27560	44	18	11	And he dwellide there a yeer and sixe monethis, techinge among hem the word of God.
27561	44	18	12	But whanne Gallion was proconsul of Acaye, Jewis risen vp with oo wille ayens Poul, and ledden hym to the doom,
27562	44	18	13	and seiden, Ayens the lawe this counselith men to worschipe God.
27563	44	18	14	And whanne Poul bigan to opene his mouth, Gallion seide to the Jewis, If there were ony wickid thing, ether yuel trespas, ye Jewis, riytli Y schulde suffre you;
27564	44	18	15	but if questiouns ben of the word, and of names of youre lawe, bisee you silf; Y wole not be domesman of these thingis.
27565	44	18	16	And he droof hem fro the doom place.
27566	44	18	17	And alle token Sostenes, prince of the synagoge, and smoten him bifor the doom place; and no thing of these was to charge to Gallion.
27567	44	18	18	And whanne Poul hadde abidun many daies, he seide fare wel to britheren, and bi boot cam to Syrie. And Priscille and Aquila camen with hym, whiche hadden clippid his heed in Tencris; for he had a vow.
27568	44	18	19	And he cam to Effesie, and there he lefte hem; and he yede in to the synagoge, and disputide with Jewis.
27569	44	18	20	And whanne thei preieden, that he schulde dwelle more time,
27570	44	18	21	he consentide not, but he made `fare wel, and seide, Eft Y schal turne ayen to you, if God wole; and he wente forth fro Effesi.
27571	44	18	22	And he cam doun to Cesarie, and he yede vp, and grette the chirche, and cam doun to Antiochie.
27572	44	18	23	And whanne he hadde dwellide there sumwhat of time, he wente forth, walkinge bi rewe thorou the cuntrei of Galathie, and Frigie, and confermyde alle the disciplis.
27573	44	18	24	But a Jewe, Apollo bi name, a man of Alisaundre of kinde, a man eloquent, cam to Effesie; and he was myyti in scripturis.
27574	44	18	25	This man was tauyt the weie of the Lord, and was feruent in spirit, and spak, and tauyte diligentli tho thingis that weren of Jhesu, and knew oonli the baptym of Joon.
27575	44	18	26	And this man bigan to do tristili in the synagoge. Whom whanne Priscille and Aquila herden, thei token hym, and more diligentli expowneden to hym the weie of the Lord.
27576	44	18	27	And whanne he wolde go to Acaie, britheren excitiden, and wroten to the disciplis, that thei schulden resseyue hym; which whanne he cam, yaf myche to hem that bileueden.
27577	44	18	28	For he greetli ouercam Jewis, and schewide opynli bi scripturis, that Jhesu is Crist.
27578	44	19	1	And it bifelle, whanne Apollo was at Corinthi, that Poul whanne he hadde go the hiyer coostis, he cam to Efesie, and foond summe of disciplis.
27579	44	19	2	And he seide to hem, Whethir ye that bileuen han resseyued the Hooli Goost? And thei seiden to hym, But nether `han we herd, if the Hooli Goost is.
27580	44	19	3	And he seide, Therfor in what thing ben ye baptisid? And thei seiden, In the baptym of Joon.
27581	44	19	4	And Poul seide, Joon baptiside the puple in baptym of penaunce, and tauyte, that thei schulden bileue in hym that was to comynge `after hym, that is, in Jhesu.
27582	44	19	5	Whanne thei herden these thingis, thei weren baptisid in the name of the Lord Jhesu.
27583	44	19	6	And whanne Poul hadde leid on hem his hoondis, the Hooli Goost cam in hem, and thei spaken with langagis, and profecieden.
27584	44	19	7	And alle weren almest twelue men.
27585	44	19	8	And he yede in to the synagoge, and spak with trist thre monethis, disputinge and tretinge of the kingdom of God.
27586	44	19	9	But whanne summe weren hardid, and bileueden not, and cursiden the weie of the Lord bifor the multitude, he yede awei fro hem, and departide the disciplis, and disputide in the scole of a myyti man eche dai.
27587	44	19	10	This was doon bi twei yeeris, so that alle that dwelliden in Asie herden the word of the Lord, Jewis and hethene men.
27588	44	19	11	And God dide vertues not smale bi the hoond of Poul,
27589	44	19	12	so that on sijk men the sudaries weren borun fro his bodye, and sijknessis departiden fro hem, and wickid spiritis wenten out.
27590	44	19	13	But also summe of the Jewis exorsisists yeden aboute, and assaieden to clepe the name of the Lord Jhesu Crist on hem that hadden yuele spiritis, and seiden, Y coniure you bi Jhesu, whom Poul prechith.
27591	44	19	14	And ther weren seuene sones of a Jewe, Steuen, a prince of preestis, that diden this thing.
27592	44	19	15	But the yuel spirit answeride, and seide to hem, Y knowe Jhesu, and Y knowe Poul; but who ben ye?
27593	44	19	16	And the man in which was the worste deuel, lippide on hem, and hadde victorie of bothe, and was stronge ayens hem, that thei nakid and woundid fledden awei fro that hous.
27594	44	19	17	And this thing was maad knowun to alle the Jewis and to hethene men, that dwelliden at Effesie; and drede felle doun on hem alle, and thei magnyfieden the name of the Lord Jhesu.
27595	44	19	18	And many men bileueden, and camen, knowlechinge and tellynge her dedis.
27596	44	19	19	And manye of them that sueden curiouse thingis, brouyten togidere bookis, and brenneden hem bifor alle men; and whanne the prices of tho weren acountid, thei founden monei of fifti thousynd pens;
27597	44	19	20	so strongli the word of God wexide, and was confermyd.
27598	44	19	21	And whanne these thingis weren fillid, Poul purposide in spirit, aftir that Macedony was passid and Acaie, to go to Jerusalem, and seide, For aftir that Y schal be there, it bihoueth me `to se also Rome.
27599	44	19	22	And he sente in to Macedonye twey men, that mynystriden to hym, Tymothe, and Eraste, and he dwellide for a tyme in Asie.
27600	44	19	23	And a greet troubling was maad in that dai, of the weie of the Lord.
27601	44	19	24	For a man, Demetrie bi name, a worcher in siluer, makide siluer housis to Diane, and yaf to crafti men myche wynnyng;
27602	44	19	25	which he clepide togidere `hem that weren suche maner werkmen, and seide, Men, ye witen that of this craft wynnyng is to vs;
27603	44	19	26	and ye seen and heren, that this Poul counseilith and turneth awei myche puple, not oonli of Effesie, but almest of al Asie, and seith, that thei ben not goddis, that ben maad with hoondis.
27604	44	19	27	And not oonli this part schal be in perel to vs, to come in to repreef, but also the temple of the greet Dian schal be acountid in to nouyt; yhe, and the maieste of hir schal bigynne to be destried, whom al Asie and the world worschipith.
27605	44	19	28	Whanne these thingis weren herd, thei weren fillid with ire, and crieden, and seiden, Greet is the Dian of Effesians.
27606	44	19	29	And the citee was fillid with confusioun, and thei maden an asaut with oon wille in to the teaatre, and tooken Gayus and Aristark, men of Macedonye, felawis of Poul.
27607	44	19	30	And whanne Poul would haue entrid in to the peple, the disciplis suffriden not.
27608	44	19	31	And also summe of the princis of Asie, that weren hise freendis, senten to him. and preieden, that he schulde not yyue hym silf in to the teatre.
27609	44	19	32	And othere men crieden othir thing; for the chirche was confusid, and many wisten not for what cause thei weren come togidere.
27610	44	19	33	But of the puple thei drowen awei oon Alisaundre, while Jewis puttiden hym forth. And Alisaundre axide with his hoond silence, and wolde yelde a resoun to the puple.
27611	44	19	34	And as thei knewen that he was a Jew, o vois of alle men was maad, criynge as bi tweyn ouris, Greet Dian of Effesians.
27612	44	19	35	And whanne the scribe hadde ceessid the puple, he seide, Men of Effesie, what man is he, that knowith not, that the citee of Effesians is the worschipere of greet Dian, and of the child of Jubiter?
27613	44	19	36	Therfor whanne it may not be ayenseid to these thingis, it behoueth you to be ceessid, and to do no thing folili;
27614	44	19	37	for ye han brouyt these men, nethir sacrilegeris, nethir blasfemynge youre goddesse.
27615	44	19	38	That if Demetrie, and the werk men that ben with hym, han cause ayens ony man, there ben courtis, and domes, and iugis; accusen thei eche other.
27616	44	19	39	If ye seken ouyt of ony othir thing, it may be assoylid in the lawful chirche.
27617	44	19	40	For whi we ben in perel to be repreuyd of this daies dissencioun, sithen no man is gilti, of whom we moun yelde resoun of this rennyng togidre. And whanne he hadde seid this thing, he lete the puple go.
27618	44	20	1	And aftir the noise ceesside, Poul clepide the disciplis, and monestide hem, and seide fare wel; and he wente forth, to go in to Macedonye.
27619	44	20	2	And whanne he hadde walkid bi tho coostis, and hadde monestid hem bi many wordis, he cam to Greece.
27620	44	20	3	Where whanne he hadde be thre monethis, the Jewis leiden aspies for hym, that was to saile in to Sirie; and he hadde counsel to turne ayen bi Macedonye.
27621	44	20	4	And Sosipater of Pirri Boroense folowide hym; of Thessolonycenses, Astirak, and Secoundus, and Gayus Derbeus, and Tymothe; and Asians, Titicus and Trofimus.
27622	44	20	5	These for thei wenten bifore, aboden vs at Troade.
27623	44	20	6	For we schippiden aftir the daies of therf looues fro Filippis, and cam to hem at Troade in fyue daies, where we dwelten seuene daies.
27624	44	20	7	And in the first dai of the woke, whanne we camen to breke breed, Poul disputide with hem, and schulde go forth in the morew;
27625	44	20	8	and he drow along the sermoun til in to mydnyyt. And many laumpes weren in the soler, where we weren gaderyd togidir.
27626	44	20	9	And a yong man, Euticus bi name, sat on the wyndowe, whanne he was fallun in to an heuy sleep, while Poul disputide long, al slepynge he felle doun fro the thridde stage; and he was takun vp, and was brouyt deed.
27627	44	20	10	To whom whanne Poul cam doun, he lay on hym, and biclippide, and seide, Nyle ye be troblid; for his soule is in hym.
27628	44	20	11	And he wente vp, and brak breed, and eete, and spak ynowy vnto the dai; and so he wente forth.
27629	44	20	12	And thei brouyten the childe alyue, and thei weren coumfortid greetli.
27630	44	20	13	And we wenten vp in to a schip, and schippiden in to Asson, to take Poul fro thennus; for so he hadde disposid to make iourney bi loond.
27631	44	20	14	And whanne he foond vs in Asson, we token hym, and camen to Mitilene.
27632	44	20	15	And fro thennus we schippiden in the dai suynge, and we camen ayens Chyum, and another dai we hauenyden at Samum, and in the dai suynge we camen to Mylete.
27633	44	20	16	And Poul purposide to schip ouer to Efesi, lest ony tariyng were maad to hym in Asie; for he hiyede, if it were possible to hym, that he schulde be in the dai of Pentecost at Jerusalem.
27634	44	20	17	Fro Mylete he sente to Effesi, and clepide the grettest men of birthe of the chirche.
27635	44	20	18	And whanne thei camen to hym, and weren togidir, he seide to hem, Ye witen fro the firste dai, in which Y cam in to Asie, hou with you bi eche tyme Y was,
27636	44	20	19	seruynge to the Lord with al mekenesse, and mildnesse, and teeris, and temptaciouns, that felden to me of aspiyngis of Jewis;
27637	44	20	20	hou Y withdrowe not of profitable thingis to you, that Y telde not to you, and tauyte you opynli, and bi housis;
27638	44	20	21	and Y witnesside to Jewis and to hethene men penaunce in to God, and feith in to oure Lord Jhesu Crist.
27639	44	20	22	And now lo! Y am boundun in spirit, and go in to Jerusalem; and Y knowe not what thingis schulen come to me in it,
27640	44	20	23	but that the Hooli Goost `bi alle citees witnessith to me, and seith, that boondis and tribulaciouns at Jerusalem abiden me.
27641	44	20	24	But Y drede no thing of these, nether Y make my lijf preciousere than my silf, so that Y end my cours, and the mynysterie of the word, which Y resseyuede of the Lord Jhesu, to witnesse the gospel of the grace of God.
27642	44	20	25	And `now lo! Y woot, that ye schulen no more se my face, alle ye bi whiche Y passide, prechynge the kingdom of God.
27643	44	20	26	Wherfor Y witnesse to you this day, that Y am cleen of the blood of alle men.
27644	44	20	27	For Y fley not awey, that Y telde not to you al the counsel of God.
27645	44	20	28	Take ye tente to you, and to al the flocke, in which the Hooli Goost hath set you bischops, to reule the chirche of God, which he purchaside with his blood.
27646	44	20	29	Y woot, that aftir my departyng, rauyschinge wolues schulen entre in to you, `and spare not the flok;
27647	44	20	30	and men spekinge schrewid thingis schulen rise of you silf, that thei leden awei disciplis aftir hem.
27648	44	20	31	For which thing wake ye, holdinge in mynde that bi thre yeer nyyt and dai Y ceesside not with teeris monestinge ech of you.
27649	44	20	32	And now Y bitake you to God and to the word of his grace, that is myyti to edifie and yyue eritage in alle that ben maad hooli.
27650	44	20	33	And of no man Y coueitide siluer, and gold, ether cloth, as you silf witen;
27651	44	20	34	for to tho thingis that weren nedeful to me, and to these that ben with me, these hoondis mynystriden.
27652	44	20	35	Alle these thingis Y schewide to you, for so it bihoueth men trauelinge to resseyue sike men, and to haue mynde of the `word of the Lord Jhesu; for he seide, It is more blesful to yyue, than to resseyue.
27653	44	20	36	And whanne he hadde seid these thingis, he knelide, and he preiede with alle hem.
27654	44	20	37	And greet weping of alle men was maad; and thei felden on the necke of Poul, and kissiden hym,
27655	44	20	38	and sorewiden moost in the word that he seide, for thei schulen no more se his face. And thei ledden hym to the schip.
27656	44	21	1	And whanne it was don, that we schulden seile, and weren passid awei fro hem, with streiyt cours we camen to Choum, and the day suynge to Rodis, and fro thennus to Patiram, and fro thennus to Myram.
27657	44	21	2	And whanne we founden a schip passinge ouer to Fenyce, we wenten vp in to it, and sailden forth.
27658	44	21	3	And whanne we apperiden to Cipre, we leften it at the left half, and seiliden in to Sirie, and camen to Tire. For there the schip schulde be vnchargid.
27659	44	21	4	And whanne we foundun disciplis, we dwelliden there seuene daies; whiche seiden bi spirit to Poul, that he schulde not go vp to Jerusalem.
27660	44	21	5	And whanne the daies weren fillid, we yeden forth, and alle men with wyues and children ledden forth vs with outen the citee; and we kneliden in the see brenke, and we preieden.
27661	44	21	6	And whanne we hadden maad fare wel togidre, we wenten vp into the schip; and thei turneden ayen in to her owne places.
27662	44	21	7	And whanne the schip sailinge was fillid fro Tire, we camen doun to Tolamayda, and whanne we hadden gret wel the britheren, we dwelliden o dai at hem.
27663	44	21	8	And another dai we yeden forth, and camen to Cesarie. And we entriden in to the hous of Filip euangelist, that was oon of the seuene, and dwelliden at hym.
27664	44	21	9	And to hym weren foure douytris, virgyns, that profecieden.
27665	44	21	10	And whanne we dwelliden there bi summe daies, a profete, Agabus bi name, cam ouer fro Judee.
27666	44	21	11	This whanne he cam to vs, took the girdil of Poul, and boond togidere hise feet and hoondis, and seide, The Hooli Goost seith these thingis, Thus Jewis schulen bynde in Jerusalem the man, whos is this girdil; and thei schulen bytake into hethene mennys hoondis.
27667	44	21	12	Which thing whanne we herden, we preieden, and thei that weren of that place, that he schulde not go vp to Jerusalem.
27668	44	21	13	Thanne Poul answeride, and seide, What doen ye, wepinge and turmentinge myn herte? For Y am redi, not oonli to be boundun, but also to die in Jerusalem for the name of the Lord Jhesu.
27669	44	21	14	And whanne we myyten not counseile hym, we weren stille, and seiden, The wille of the Lord be don.
27670	44	21	15	And aftir these daies we weren maad redi, and wenten vp to Jerusalem.
27671	44	21	16	And summe of the disciplis camen with vs fro Cesarie, and ledden with hem a man, Jason of Cipre, an elde disciple, at whom we schulden be herborid.
27672	44	21	17	And whanne we camen to Jerusalem, britheren resseyueden vs wilfulli.
27673	44	21	18	And in the dai suynge Poul entride with vs to James, and alle the eldre men weren gaderid.
27674	44	21	19	Whiche whanne he hadde gret, he telde bi alle thingis, what God hadde doon in hethene men, bi the mynysterie of hym.
27675	44	21	20	And whanne thei herden, thei magnyfiden God, and seiden to hym, Brothir, thou seest how many thousyndis ben in Jewis, that han bileued to God, and alle ben loueris of the lawe.
27676	44	21	21	And thei herden of thee, that thou techist departing fro Moises of thilk Jewis that ben bi hethene men, that seien, that thei owen not circumcide her sones, nether owen to entre by custom.
27677	44	21	22	Therfor what is? It bihoueth that the multitude come togidre; for thei schulen here, that thou art come.
27678	44	21	23	Therfor do thou this thing, that we seien to thee. Ther ben to vs foure men, that han a vow on hem.
27679	44	21	24	Take thou these men, and halowe thee with hem; honge on hem, that thei schaue her heedis; and that alle men wite, that the thingis that thei herden of thee ben false, but that thou walkist, and thi silf kepist the lawe.
27680	44	21	25	But of these that bileueden of hethene men, we writen, demynge that thei absteyne hem fro thing offrid to idols, and fro blood, and also fro stranglid thing, and fro fornicacioun.
27681	44	21	26	Thanne Poul took the men, and in the dai suynge he was purified with hem, and entride in to the temple, and schewide the filling of daies of purifying, til the offring was offrid for ech of hem.
27682	44	21	27	And whanne seuene daies weren endid, the Jewis that weren of Asie, whanne thei saien him in the temple, stiriden al the puple, and leyden hondis on hym,
27683	44	21	28	and crieden, Men of Israel, helpe ye vs. This is the man, that ayens the puple and the lawe and this place techith euery where alle men, more ouer and hath led hethene men in to the temple, and hath defoulid this hooli place.
27684	44	21	29	For thei seyen Trofimus of Effesi in the citee with hym, whom thei gessiden that Poul hadde brouyt in to the temple.
27685	44	21	30	And al the citee was moued, and a rennyng togider of the puple was maad. And thei token Poul, and drowen him out of the temple; and anoon the yatis weren closid.
27686	44	21	31	And whanne thei souyten to sle hym, it was teld to the tribune of the cumpany of knyytis, that al Jerusalem is confoundid.
27687	44	21	32	Which anoon took knyytis, and centuriens, and ran to hem. And whanne thei hadden seen the tribune, and the knyytis, thei ceessiden to smyte Poul.
27688	44	21	33	Thanne the tribune cam, and cauyte hym, and comaundide, that he were boundun with twei cheynes; and axide, who he was, and what he hadde don.
27689	44	21	34	But othere crieden other thing among the puple. And whanne he miyte `knowe no certeyn thing for the noise, he comaundide hym to be led in to the castels.
27690	44	21	35	And whanne Poul cam to the grees, it bifel that he was borun of kniytis, for strengthe of the puple.
27691	44	21	36	For the multitude of the puple suede hym, and criede, Take hym awei.
27692	44	21	37	And whanne Poul bigan to be led in to the castels, he seide to the tribune, Whether it is leueful `to me, to speke ony thing to thee?
27693	44	21	38	And he seide, Kanst thou Greek? Whether thou art not the Egipcian, which bifor these daies mouedist a noise, and leddist out in to desert foure thousynde of men, mensleeris?
27694	44	21	39	And Poul seide to hym, For Y am a Jew, of Tharse of Cilicie, a citeseyn, which citee is not vnknowun. And Y preye thee, suffre me to speke to the puple.
27695	44	21	40	And whanne he suffride, Poul stood in the grees, and bikenede with the hoond to the puple. And whanne a greet silence was maad, he spak in Ebrew tunge, and seide,
27696	44	22	1	Britheren and fadris, here ye what resoun Y yelde now to you.
27697	44	22	2	And whanne sum herden that in Ebrew tunge he spak to hem, thei yauen the more silence.
27698	44	22	3	And he seide, Y am a man a Jew, borun at Tharse of Cilicie, nurischid and in this citee bisidis the feet of Gamaliel, tauyt bi the treuthe of fadris lawe, a louyere of the lawe, as also ye alle ben to dai.
27699	44	22	4	And Y pursuede this weie til to the deth, byndynge and bitakinge `in to holdis men and wymmen,
27700	44	22	5	as the prince of prestis yeldith witnessyng to me, and alle the grettest in birth. Of whom also Y took pistlis to britheren, and wente to Damask, to bring fro thennys men boundun in to Jerusalem, that thei schulden be peyned.
27701	44	22	6	And it was don, while Y yede, and neiyede to Damask, at myddai sudeynli fro heuene a greet plente of liyt schoon aboute me.
27702	44	22	7	And Y felde doun to the erthe, and herde a voice fro heuene, seiynge to me, Saul, Saul, what pursuest thou me? It is hard to thee to kike ayens the pricke.
27703	44	22	8	And Y answeride, Who art thou, Lord? And he seide to me, Y am Jhesu of Nazareth, whom thou pursuest.
27704	44	22	9	And thei that weren with me sien but the liyt, but thei herden not the vois of hym, that spak with me.
27705	44	22	10	And Y seide, Lord, what schal Y do? And the Lord seide to me, Rise thou, and go to Damask; and there it schal be seid to thee, of alle thingis which it bihoueth thee to do.
27706	44	22	11	And whanne Y saye not, for the clerete of that liyt, Y was led bi the hond of felowis, and Y cam to Damask.
27707	44	22	12	And a man, Ananye, that bi the lawe hadde wytnessyng of alle Jewis dwellinge in Damask,
27708	44	22	13	cam to me, and stood niy, and seide to me, Saul, brother, biholde. And Y in the same our biheelde in to hym.
27709	44	22	14	And he seide, God of oure fadris hath bifor ordeyned thee, that thou schuldist knowe the wille of him, and schuldist se the riytful man, and here the vois of his mouth.
27710	44	22	15	For thou schalt be his witnesse to alle men, of tho thingis that thou hast seyn and herd.
27711	44	22	16	And now, what dwellist thou? Rise vp, and be baptisid, and waische awei thi synnes, bi the name of hym clepid to help.
27712	44	22	17	And it was don to me, as Y turnede ayen in to Jerusalem, and preyede in the temple, that Y was maad in rauysching of soule,
27713	44	22	18	and Y siy him seiynge to me, Hiye thou, and go out faste of Jerusalem, for thei schulen not resseyue thi witnessing of me.
27714	44	22	19	And Y seide, Lord, thei witen, that Y was closing togidir `in to prisoun, and betinge bi synagogis hem that bileueden `in to thee.
27715	44	22	20	And whanne the blood of Steuene, thi witnesse, was sched out, Y stood niy, and consentide, and kept the clothis of men that slowen hym.
27716	44	22	21	And he seide to me, Go thou, for Y schal sende thee fer to naciouns.
27717	44	22	22	And thei herden him til this word; and thei reiseden her vois, and seiden, Take awei fro the erthe siche a maner man; for it is not leueful, that he lyue.
27718	44	22	23	And whanne thei crieden, and kesten awei her clothis, and threwen dust in to the eir,
27719	44	22	24	the tribune comaundide hym to be led in to castels, and to be betun with scourgis, and to be turmentid, that he wiste, for what cause thei crieden so to him.
27720	44	22	25	And whanne thei hadden boundun hym with cordis, Poul seide to a centurien stondinge niy to hym, Whether it is leueful to you, to scourge a Romayn, and vndampned?
27721	44	22	26	And whanne this thing was herd, the centurien wente to the tribune, and telde to hym, and seide, What art thou to doynge? for this man is a citeseyn of Rome.
27722	44	22	27	And the tribune cam niy, and seide to hym, Seie thou to me, whether thou art a Romayn?
27723	44	22	28	And he seide, Yhe. And the tribune answeride, Y with myche summe gat this fredom. And Poul seide, And Y was borun a citeseyn of Rome.
27724	44	22	29	Therfor anoon thei that schulden haue turmentid hym, departiden awei fro hym. And the tribune dredde, aftir that he wiste, that he was a citeseyn of Rome, and for he hadde boundun hym.
27725	44	22	30	But in the dai suynge he wolde wite more diligentli, for what cause he were accusid of the Jewis, and vnbounde hym, and comaundide prestis and al the counsel to come togidir. And he brouyte forth Poul, and sette hym among hem.
27726	44	23	1	And Poul bihelde in to the counsel, and seide, Britheren, Y with al good conscience haue lyued bifore God, `til in to this dai.
27727	44	23	2	And Anany, prince of prestis, comaundide to men that stoden nyy hym, that thei schulden smyte his mouth.
27728	44	23	3	Thanne Poul seide to hym, Thou whitid wal, God smyte thee; thou sittist, and demest me bi the lawe, and ayens the law thou comaundist me to be smytun.
27729	44	23	4	And thei that stoden niy, seiden, Cursist thou the hiyest prest of God?
27730	44	23	5	And Poul seide, Britheren, Y wiste not, that he is prince of preestis; for it is writun, Thou schalt not curse the prince of thi puple.
27731	44	23	6	But Poul wiste, that o parti was of Saduceis, and the othere of Fariseis; and he criede in the counsel, Britheren, Y am a Farisee, the sone of Farisees; Y am demyd of the hope and of the ayen rising of deed men.
27732	44	23	7	And whanne he hadde seid this thing, dissencioun was maad bitwixe the Fariseis and the Saduceis, and the multitude was departid.
27733	44	23	8	For Saduceis seien, that no `rysing ayen of deed men is, nether aungel, nether spirit; but Fariseis knowlechen euer eithir.
27734	44	23	9	And a greet cry was maad. And summe of Farisees rosen vp, and fouyten, seiynge, We fynden no thing of yuel in this man; what if a spirit, ether an aungel spak to hym?
27735	44	23	10	And whanne greet discencioun was maad, the tribune dredde, lest Poul schulde be to-drawun of hem; and he comaundide knyytis to go doun, and to take hym fro the myddil of hem, and to lede hym in to castels.
27736	44	23	11	And in the niyt suynge the Lord stood niy to hym, and seide, Be thou stidfast; for as thou hast witnessid of me in Jerusalem, so it bihoueth thee to witnesse also at Rome.
27737	44	23	12	And whanne the dai was come, summe of the Jewis gaderiden hem, and maden `avow, and seiden, that thei schulden nether eete, ne drinke, til thei slowen Poul.
27738	44	23	13	And there weren mo than fourti men, that maden this sweryng togider.
27739	44	23	14	And thei wenten to the princis of prestis, and eldre men, and seiden, With deuocioun we han a vowid, that we schulen not taste ony thing, til we sleen Poul.
27740	44	23	15	Now therfor make ye knowun to the tribune, with the counsel, that he bringe hym forth to you, as if ye schulden knowe sum thing more certeynli of hym; and we ben redi to sle hym, bifor that he come.
27741	44	23	16	And whanne the sone of Poulis sister hadde herd the aspies, he cam, and entride in to the castels, and telde to Poul.
27742	44	23	17	And Poul clepide to hym oon of the centuriens, and seide, Lede this yonge man to the tribune, for he hath sum thing to schewe to hym.
27743	44	23	18	And he took hym, and ledde to the tribune, and seide, Poul, that is boundun, preide me to lede to thee this yonge man, that hath sum thing to speke to thee.
27744	44	23	19	And the tribune took his hoond, and wente with hym asidis half, and axide hym, What thing is it, that thou hast to schewe to me?
27745	44	23	20	And he seide, The Jewis ben acordid to preye thee, that to morewe thou brynge forth Poul in to the counsel, as if thei schulden enquere sum thing more certeynli of hym.
27746	44	23	21	But bileue thou not to hem; for mo than fourti men of hem aspien hym, which han a vowid, that thei schulen not eete nether drynke, til thei sleen hym; and now thei ben redi, abidinge thi biheest.
27747	44	23	22	Therfor the tribune lefte the yonge man, and comaundide, that he schulde speke to no man, that he hadde maad these thingis knowun to hym.
27748	44	23	23	And he clepide togidre twei centuriens, and he seide to hem, Make ye redi twei hundrid knyytis, that thei go to Cesarie, and horse men seuenti, and spere men twey hundrid, fro the thridde our of the nyyt.
27749	44	23	24	And make ye redy an hors, for Poul to ride on, to lede hym saaf to Felix, the presydent.
27750	44	23	25	For the tribune dredde, lest the Jewis wolden take hym bi the weie, and sle hym, and aftirward he miyte be chalengid, as he hadde take money.
27751	44	23	26	And wroot hym `a pistle, conteynynge these thingis. Claudius Lisias to the beste Felix, president, heelthe.
27752	44	23	27	This man that was take of the Jewis, and bigan to be slayn, Y cam vpon hem with myn oost, and delyuerede hym fro hem, whanne Y knewe that he was a Romayn.
27753	44	23	28	And Y wolde wite the cause, which thei puttiden ayens hym; and Y ledde hym to the counsel of hem.
27754	44	23	29	And Y foond, that he was accusid of questiouns of her lawe, but he hadde no cryme worthi the deth, ethir boondis.
27755	44	23	30	And whanne it was teeld me of the aspies, that thei arayden for hym, Y sente hym to thee, and Y warnede also the accuseris, that thei seie at thee. Fare wel.
27756	44	23	31	And so the knyytis, as thei weren comaundid, token Poul, and ledde hym bi nyyt into Antipatriden.
27757	44	23	32	And in the dai suynge, whanne the horsmen weren left, that schulden go with hym, thei turneden ayen to the castels.
27758	44	23	33	And whanne thei camen to Cesarie, thei token the pistle to the president, and thei setten also Poul byfore him.
27759	44	23	34	And whanne he hadde red, and axide, of what prouynce he was, and knewe that he was of Cilicie,
27760	44	23	35	Y schal here thee, he seide, whanne thin accuseris comen. And he comaundide hym to be kept in the moot halle of Eroude.
27761	44	24	1	And aftir fyue daies, Ananye, prince of preestis, cam doun with summe eldere men, and Terculle, a feir speker, which wenten to the precident ayens Poul.
27762	44	24	2	And whanne Poul was somened, Terculle bigan to accuse hym, and seide, Whanne in myche pees we doon bi thee, and many thingis ben amendid bi thi wisdom, euere more and euery where,
27763	44	24	3	thou best Felix, we han resseyued with al doyng of thankingis.
27764	44	24	4	But lest Y tarie thee lengere, Y preie thee, schortly here vs for thi mekenesse.
27765	44	24	5	We han foundun this wickid man stirynge dissencioun to alle Jewis in al the world, and auctour of dissencioun of the secte of Nazarenus; and he also enforside to defoule the temple;
27766	44	24	6	whom also we token, and wolden deme, after oure lawe.
27767	44	24	7	But Lisias, the trybune, cam with greet strengthe aboue, and delyuerede hym fro oure hoondis;
27768	44	24	8	and comaundide hise accuseris to come to thee, of whom thou demynge, maist knowe of alle these thingis, of whiche we accusen hym.
27769	44	24	9	And Jewis putten to, and seiden, that these thingis hadden hem so.
27770	44	24	10	And Poul answeride, whanne the president grauntide hym to seie, Of mony yeeris Y knowe thee, that thou art domesman `to this folk, and Y schal do ynowy for me with good resoun.
27771	44	24	11	For thou maist knowe, for to me ben not more than twelue daies, sithen Y cam vp to worschipe in Jerusalem;
27772	44	24	12	and nether in the temple thei founden me disputinge with ony man, nether makynge concours of puple, nether in synagogis, nether in citee;
27773	44	24	13	nether thei moun preue to thee, of the whiche thingis thei now accusen me.
27774	44	24	14	But Y knowleche to thee this thing, that aftir the secte which thei seien eresie, so Y serue to God the fadir, `and Y bileue to alle thingis that ben writun in the lawe and profetis; and Y haue hope in God,
27775	44	24	15	whiche also thei hem silf abiden, the ayenrisyng `to comynge of iust men and wickid.
27776	44	24	16	In this thing Y studie with outen hirtyng, to haue concience to God, and to men euermore.
27777	44	24	17	But after many yeeris, Y cam to do almes dedis to my folc, and offryngis, and auowis;
27778	44	24	18	in whiche thei founden me purified in the temple, not with company, nether with noise. And thei cauyten me, and thei crieden, and seiden, Take awei oure enemye.
27779	44	24	19	And summe Jewis of Asie, whiche it behofte to be now present at thee, and accuse, if thei hadden ony thing ayens me,
27780	44	24	20	ether these hem silf seie, if thei founden in me ony thing of wickidnesse, sithen Y stonde `in the counsel,
27781	44	24	21	but oneli of this vois, by which Y criede stondynge among hem, For of the ayenrisyng of deed men Y am demyd this dai of you.
27782	44	24	22	Sothely Felix delayede hem, and knewe moost certeynli of the weie, and seide, Whanne Lisias, the tribune, schal come doun, Y schal here you.
27783	44	24	23	And he comaundide to a centurien to kepe hym, and that he hadde reste, nethir to forbede ony man to mynystre of his owne thingis to him.
27784	44	24	24	And after summe dayes Felix cam, with Drussille his wijf, that was a Jewesse, and clepide Poul, and herde of him the feith that is in Crist Jhesu.
27785	44	24	25	And while he disputide of riytwisnesse, and chastite, and of dom to comynge, Felix was maad tremblinge, and answerde, That perteneth now, go; but in tyme couenable Y schal clepe thee.
27786	44	24	26	Also he hopide, that money schulde be youun to hym of Poul; for which thing eft he clepide hym, and spak with hym.
27787	44	24	27	And whanne twei yeeris weren fillid, Felix took a successoure, Porcius Festus; and Felix wolde yyue grace to Jewis, and lefte Poul boundun.
27788	44	25	1	Therfor whanne Festus cam in to the prouynce, aftir the thridde dai he wente vp to Jerusalem fro Cesarie.
27789	44	25	2	And the princis of prestis, and the worthieste of the Jewis wenten to hym ayens Poul, and preieden hym,
27790	44	25	3	and axiden grace ayens hym, that he schulde comaunde hym to be led to Jerusalem; and thei settiden aspies to sle hym in the weie.
27791	44	25	4	But Festus answerde, that Poul schulde be kept in Cesarie; sotheli that he hym silf schulde procede more auisili. Therfor he seide, Thei that in you ben myyti,
27792	44	25	5	come doun togidere; and if ony crime is in the man, accuse thei hym.
27793	44	25	6	And he dwellede among hem no more than eiyte ether ten daies, and cam doun to Cesarie; and the tother dai he sat for domesman, and comaundide Poul to be brouyt.
27794	44	25	7	And whanne he was brouyt forth, Jewis stoden aboute hym, whiche camen doun fro Jerusalem, puttynge ayens hym many and greuouse causis, whiche thei miyten not preue.
27795	44	25	8	For Poul yeldide resoun in alle thingis, That nether ayens the lawe of Jewis, nether ayens the temple, nether ayens the emperoure, Y synnede ony thing.
27796	44	25	9	But Festus wolde do grace to the Jewis, and answeride to Poul, and seide, Wolt thou gon vp to Jerusalem, and there be demyd of these thingis bifore me?
27797	44	25	10	And Poul seide, At the domplace of the emperour Y stonde, where it bihoueth me to be demed. Y haue not noied the Jewis, as thou knowist wel.
27798	44	25	11	For if Y haue noyed, ether don ony thing worthi deth, Y forsake not to die; but if no thing of tho is, that thei accusen me, no man may yyue me to hem. Y appele to the emperour.
27799	44	25	12	Thanne Festus spak with the counsel, and answerde, To the emperoure thou hast appelid, to the emperoure thou schalt go.
27800	44	25	13	And whanne summe daies weren passid, Agrippa kyng, and Beronyce camen doun to Cesarie, to welcome Festus.
27801	44	25	14	And whanne thei dwelliden there many daies, Festus schewide to the king of Poul, and seide, A man is left boundun of Felix,
27802	44	25	15	of which, whanne Y was at Jerusalem, princis of preestis and the eldre men of Jewis camen to me, and axiden dampnacioun ayens hym.
27803	44	25	16	To whiche Y answeride, That it is not custom to Romayns, to dampne ony man, bifore that he that is accusid haue hise accuseris present, and take place of defending, to putte awei the crymes, that ben putte ayens hym.
27804	44	25	17	Therfor whanne thei camen togidere hidir, withouten ony delaye, in the dai suynge Y sat for domesman, and comaundide the man to be brouyt.
27805	44	25	18	And whanne hise accuseris stoden, thei seiden no cause, of whiche thingis Y hadde suspicioun of yuel.
27806	44	25	19	But thei hadden ayens hym summe questiouns of her veyn worschiping, and of oon Jhesu deed, whom Poul affermyde to lyue.
27807	44	25	20	And Y doutide of siche maner questioun, and seide, Whether he wolde go to Jerusalem, and ther be demyd of these thingis?
27808	44	25	21	But for Poul appelide, that he schulde be kept to the knowing of the emperoure, Y comaundide him to be kept, til Y sende hym to the emperoure.
27809	44	25	22	And Agrippa seide to Festus, Y my silf wolde here the man. And he seide, To morew thou schalt here hym.
27810	44	25	23	And on the tother day, whanne Agrippa and Beronyce camen with greet desire, and entriden in to the auditorie, with tribunes and the principal men of the citee, whanne Festus bad, Poul was brouyt.
27811	44	25	24	And Festus seide, King Agrippa, and alle men that ben with vs, ye seen this man, of which al the multitude of Jewis preyede me at Jerusalem, and axide, and criede, that he schulde lyue no lenger.
27812	44	25	25	But Y foond, that he hadde don no thing worthi of deth; and Y deme to sende hym to the emperoure, for he appelide this thing.
27813	44	25	26	Of which man Y haue not certeyne, what thing Y schal write to the lord. For which thing Y brouyte hym to you, and moost to thee, thou king Agrippa, that whanne axing is maad, Y haue what Y schal write.
27814	44	25	27	For it is seyn to me with out resoun, to sende a boundun man, and not to signifie the cause of hym.
27815	44	26	1	And Agrippa seide to Poul, It is suffrid to thee, to speke for thi silf. Thanne Poul helde forth the hoond, and bigan to yelde resoun.
27816	44	26	2	Of alle thingis, in whiche Y am accusid of the Jewis, thou king Agrippa, Y gesse me blessid at thee, whanne Y schal defende me this dai;
27817	44	26	3	moost for thou knowist alle thingis that ben among Jewis, customes and questiouns. For which thing, Y biseche, here me pacientli.
27818	44	26	4	For alle Jewis that bifor knewen me fro the bigynnyng, knewen my lijf fro yongthe; that fro the bigynnyng was in my folc in Jerusalem,
27819	44	26	5	if thei wolen bere witnessing, that bi the moost certeyn sect of oure religioun, Y lyuede a Farisee.
27820	44	26	6	And now for the hope of repromyssioun, that is maad to oure fadris of God, Y stonde suget in dom;
27821	44	26	7	in which hope oure twelue lynagis seruynge niyt and dai hopen to come; of which hope, sir king, Y am accusid of the Jewis.
27822	44	26	8	What vnbileueful thing is demed at you, if God reisith deed men?
27823	44	26	9	And sotheli Y gesside, that Y ouyte do many contrarie thingis ayens the name of Jhesu Nazarene.
27824	44	26	10	Which thing also Y dide in Jerusalem, and Y encloside manye of the seyntis in prisoun, whanne Y hadde take powere of the princis of preestis. And whanne thei weren slayn, Y brouyte the sentence.
27825	44	26	11	And bi alle synagogis ofte Y punyschide hem, and constreynede to blasfeme; and more Y wex wood ayens hem, and pursuede in to alien citees.
27826	44	26	12	In whiche, the while Y wente to Damask, with power and suffring of princis of preestis,
27827	44	26	13	at myddai, in the weie Y say, sir king, that fro heuene liyt schynede aboute me, passing the schynyng of the sunne, and aboute hem that weren togidir with me.
27828	44	26	14	And whanne we alle hadden falle doun in to the erthe, Y herde a vois seiynge to me in Ebrew tunge, Saul, Saul, what pursuest thou me? it is hard to thee, to kicke ayens the pricke.
27829	44	26	15	And Y seide, Who art thou, Lord? And the Lord seide, Y am Jhesus, whom thou pursuest.
27830	44	26	16	But rise vp, and stoond on thi feet. For whi to this thing Y apperide to thee, that Y ordeyne thee mynystre and witnesse of tho thingis that thou hast seyn, and of tho in whiche Y schal schewe to thee.
27831	44	26	17	And Y schal delyuere thee fro puplis and folkis, to whiche now Y sende thee,
27832	44	26	18	to opene the iyen of hem, that thei ben conuertid fro derknesse to liyt, and fro power of Sathnas to God, that thei take remyssioun of synnes, and part among seyntis, bi feith that is in me.
27833	44	26	19	Wherfor, sir kyng Agrippa, Y was not vnbileueful to the heuenli visioun;
27834	44	26	20	but Y tolde to hem that been at Damask first, and at Jerusalem, and bi al the cuntre of Judee, and to hethene men, that thei schulden do penaunce, and be conuertid to God, and do worthi werkis of penaunce.
27835	44	26	21	For this cause Jewis token me, whanne Y was in the temple, to sle me.
27836	44	26	22	But Y was holpun bi the helpe of God in to this dai, and stonde, witnessinge to lesse and to more. And Y seye no thing ellis than whiche thingis the prophetis and Moises spaken that schulen come,
27837	44	26	23	if Crist is to suffre, if he is the firste of the ayenrising of deed men, that schal schewe liyt to the puple and to hethene men.
27838	44	26	24	Whanne he spak these thingis, and yeldide resoun, Festus seide with greet vois, Poul, thou maddist; many lettris turnen thee to woodnesse.
27839	44	26	25	And Poul seide, Y madde not, thou beste Festus, but Y speke out the wordis of treuthe and of sobernesse.
27840	44	26	26	For also the king, to whom Y speke stidfastli, woot of these thingis; for Y deme, that no thing of these is hid fro hym; for nether in a cornere was ouyt of these thingis don.
27841	44	26	27	Bileuest thou, king Agrippa, `to prophetis? Y woot that thou bileuest.
27842	44	26	28	And Agrippa seide to Poul, In litil thing thou counseilist me to be maad a cristen man.
27843	44	26	29	And Poul seide, Y desire anentis God, bothe in litil and in greet, not oneli thee, but alle these that heren to dai, to be maad sich as Y am, outakun these boondis.
27844	44	26	30	And the kyng roos vp, and the president, and Beronyce, and thei that saten niy to hem.
27845	44	26	31	And whanne thei wenten awei, thei spaken togider, and seiden, That this man hath not don ony thing worthi deth, nether boondis.
27846	44	26	32	And Agrippa seide to Festus, This man miyt be delyuerid, if he hadde not appelid to the emperour.
27847	44	27	1	But as it was demed hym to schippe into Ytalie, thei bitoken Poul with othere kepers to a centurien, bi name Julius, of the cumpeny of knyytis of the emperoure.
27848	44	27	2	And we wenten vp in to the schip of Adrymetis, and bigunnen to seile, and weren borun aboute the placis of Asie, while Aristark of Macedonye, Tessalonycence, dwellide stille with vs.
27849	44	27	3	And in the dai suynge, we camen to Sydon; and Julius tretyde curteisli Poul, and suffride to go to frendis, and do his nedis.
27850	44	27	4	And whanne we remouede fro thennus, we vndurseiliden to Cipre, for that wyndis weren contrarie.
27851	44	27	5	And we seiliden in the see of Silicie and Pamfilie, and camen to Listris, that is Licie.
27852	44	27	6	And there the centurien foond a schip of Alisaundre, seilinge in to Ytalie, and puttide vs ouer in to it.
27853	44	27	7	And whanne in many daies we seilden slowli, and vnnethe camen ayens Guydum, for the winde lettide vs, we seiliden to Crete, bisidis Salomona.
27854	44	27	8	And vnnethe we seilden bisidis, and camen into a place, that is clepid of good hauen, to whom the cite Tessala was niy.
27855	44	27	9	And whanne miche time was passid, and whanne seiling thanne was not sikir, for that fasting was passid, Poul coumfortide hem,
27856	44	27	10	and seide to hem, Men, Y se that seiling bigynneth to be with wrong and myche harm, not oonli of charge and of the schip, but also of oure lyues.
27857	44	27	11	But the centurien bileuede more to the gouernour, and to the lord of the schip, thanne to these thingis that weren seid of Poul.
27858	44	27	12	And whanne the hauene was not able to dwelle in wynter, ful many ordeyneden counsel to seile fro thennus, if on ony maner thei miyten come to Fenyce, to dwelle in wynter at the hauene of Crete, which biholdith to Affrik, and to Corum.
27859	44	27	13	And whanne the south blew, thei gessiden hem to holde purpos; and whanne thei hadden removed fro Asson, thei seiliden to Crete.
27860	44	27	14	And not aftir miche, the wynde Tifonyk, that is clepid north eest, was ayens it.
27861	44	27	15	And whanne the schip was rauyschid, and myyte not enforse ayens the wynde, whanne the schip was youun to the blowynges of the wynde, we weren borun with cours into an ile,
27862	44	27	16	that is clepid Canda; and vnethe we miyten gete a litil boot.
27863	44	27	17	And whanne this was takun vp, thei vsiden helpis, girdinge togidere the schippe; and dredden, lest thei schulden falle into sondi placis. And whanne the vessel was vndur set, so thei weren borun.
27864	44	27	18	And for we weren throwun with strong tempest, in the dai suynge thei maden casting out.
27865	44	27	19	And the thridde dai with her hoondis thei castiden awei the instrumentis of the schip.
27866	44	27	20	And whanne the sunne nether the sterris weren seie bi many daies, and tempest not a litil neiyede, now al the hope of oure helthe was don awei.
27867	44	27	21	And whanne myche fasting hadde be, thanne Poul stood in the myddil of hem, and seide, A! men, it bihofte, whanne ye herden me, not to haue take awei the schip fro Crete, and gete this wronge and casting out.
27868	44	27	22	And now Y counsel you to be of good coumfort, for los of no persoone of you schal be, outakun of the schip.
27869	44	27	23	For an aungel of God, whos Y am, and to whom Y serue, stood niy to me in this niyt, and seide, Poul, drede thou not;
27870	44	27	24	it bihoueth thee to stonde bifore the emperour. And lo! God hath youun to thee alle that ben in the schip with thee.
27871	44	27	25	For which thing, ye men, be ye of good coumfort; for Y bileue to my God, that so it schal be, as it is seid to me.
27872	44	27	26	And it bihoueth vs to come into sum yle.
27873	44	27	27	But aftirward that in the fourtenthe dai the niyt cam on vs seilinge in the stony see, aboute mydniyt the schipmen supposiden sum cuntre to appere to hem.
27874	44	27	28	And thei kesten doun a plommet, and founden twenti pasis of depnesse. And aftir a litil thei weren departid fro thennus, and foundun fiftene pasis.
27875	44	27	29	And thei dredden, lest we schulden haue fallun in to scharp placis; and fro the last parti of the schip thei senten foure ankeris, and desiriden that the dai hadde be come.
27876	44	27	30	And whanne the schipmen souyten to fle fro the schip, whanne thei hadden sent a litil boot in to the see, vndur colour as thei schulden bigynne to stretche forth the ankeris fro the formere part of the schip,
27877	44	27	31	Poul seide to the centurien and to the knyytis, But these dwellen in the schip, ye moun not be maad saaf.
27878	44	27	32	Thanne knyytis kittiden awei the cordis of the litil boot, and suffriden it to falle awei.
27879	44	27	33	And whanne the dai was come, Poul preiede alle men to take mete, and seide, The fourtenthe dai this dai ye `abiden, and dwellen fastinge, and taken no thing.
27880	44	27	34	Wherfor Y preie you to take mete, for youre helthe; for of noon of you the heer of the heed schal perische.
27881	44	27	35	And whanne he hadde seid these thingis, Poul took breed, and dide thankyngis to God in the siyt of alle men; and whanne he hadde brokun, he bigan to eete.
27882	44	27	36	And alle weren maad of betere coumfort, and thei token mete.
27883	44	27	37	And we weren alle men in the schip, two hundrid seuenti and sexe.
27884	44	27	38	And thei weren fillid with mete, and dischargiden the schip, and castiden whete in to the see.
27885	44	27	39	And whanne the dai was comun, thei knewen no lond; and thei bihelden an hauene that hadde a watir bank, in to which thei thouyten, if thei miyten, to bringe vp the schip.
27886	44	27	40	And whanne thei hadden take vp the ankeris, thei bitoken hem to the see, and slakiden togidir the ioyntours of gouernails. And with a litil seil lift vp, bi blowyng of the wynde thei wenten to the bank.
27887	44	27	41	And whanne we felden into a place of grauel gon al aboute with the see, thei hurtliden the schip. And whanne the formere part was fitchid, it dwellide vnmouable, and the last part was brokun of strengthe of the see.
27888	44	27	42	And counsel of the kniytis was, to sle men that weren in warde, lest ony schulde ascape, whanne he hadde swymmed out.
27889	44	27	43	But the centurien wolde kepe Poul, and forbede it to be don. And he comaundide hem that miyte swymme, to go in to the see, and scape, and go out to the loond.
27890	44	27	44	And thei baren summe othere on boordis, summe on tho thingis that weren of the schip. And so it was don, that alle men ascapiden to the lond.
27891	44	28	1	And whanne we hadden ascapid, thanne we knewen that the ile was clepid Militene. And the hethene men diden to vs not litil curtesie.
27892	44	28	2	And whanne a fier was kyndelid, thei refreschiden vs alle, for the reyn that cam, and the coold.
27893	44	28	3	But whanne Poul hadde gederid `a quantite of kittingis of vines, and leide on the fier, an edder sche cam forth fro the heete, and took hym bi the hoond.
27894	44	28	4	And whanne the hethene men of the ile siyen the beest hangynge in his hoond, thei seiden togidir, For this man is a manquellere; and whanne he scapide fro the see, Goddis veniaunce suffrith hym not to lyue in erthe.
27895	44	28	5	But he schoke awei the beest in to the fier, and hadde noon harm.
27896	44	28	6	And thei gessiden that he schulde be turned `in to swellyng, and falle doun sudenli, and die. But whanne thei abiden longe, and sien that no thing of yuel was don in him, thei turneden hem togider, and seiden, that he was God.
27897	44	28	7	And in tho placis weren maners of the prince of the ile, Puplius bi name, which resseyuede vs bi thre daies benygnli, and foond vs.
27898	44	28	8	And it bifel, that the fader of Pupplius lai trauelid with fyueris and blodi flux. To whom Poul entride, and whanne he hadde preied, and leid his hondis on hym, he helide hym.
27899	44	28	9	And whanne this thing was don, alle that in the ile hadden sijknesses, camen, and weren heelid.
27900	44	28	10	Which also onouriden vs in many worschipis, and puttiden what thingis weren necessarie to vs, whanne we schippiden.
27901	44	28	11	And after thre monethis we schippiden in a schip of Alisaundre, that hadde wyntrid in the ile, to which was an excellent singne of Castours.
27902	44	28	12	And whanne we camen to Siracusan, we dwelliden there thre daies.
27903	44	28	13	Fro thennus we seiliden aboute, and camen to Regyum; and aftir oo dai, while the south blew, in the secounde dai we camen to Puteolos.
27904	44	28	14	Where whanne we founden britheren, we weren preied to dwelle there anentis hem seuene daies. And so we camen to Rome.
27905	44	28	15	And fro thennus whanne britheren hadden herd, thei camen to vs to the cheping of Appius, and to the Thre tauernes.
27906	44	28	16	And whanne Poul hadde seyn hem, he dide thankyngis to God, and took trist. And whanne `we camen to Rome, it was suffrid to Poul to dwelle bi hym silf, with a kniyt kepinge him.
27907	44	28	17	And after the thridde dai, he clepide togidir the worthieste of the Jewis. And whanne thei camen, he seide to hem, Britheren, Y dide no thing ayens the puple ether custom of fadris, and Y was boundun at Jerusalem, and was bitakun in to the hondis of Romayns.
27908	44	28	18	And whanne thei hadden axid of me, wolden haue delyuerid me, for that no cause of deth was in me.
27909	44	28	19	But for Jewis ayenseiden, Y was constreyned to appele to the emperour; not as hauynge ony thing to accuse my puple.
27910	44	28	20	Therfor for this cause Y preiede to se you, and speke to you; for for the hope of Israel Y am gird aboute with this chayne.
27911	44	28	21	And thei seiden to hym, Nether we han resseyued lettris of thee fro Judee, nether ony of britheren comynge schewide, ether spak ony yuel thing of thee.
27912	44	28	22	But we preyen to here of thee, what thingis thou felist; for of this sect it is knowun to vs, that euerywhere me ayenseith it.
27913	44	28	23	And whanne thei hadden ordeined a dai to hym, many men camen to hym in to the in. To whiche he expownede, witnessinge the kyngdom `of God, and counseilide hem of Jhesu, of the lawe of Moyses, and profetis, for the morewe til to euentid.
27914	44	28	24	And summe bileueden to these thingis that weren seid of Poul, summe bileueden not.
27915	44	28	25	And whanne thei weren not consentinge togidir, thei departiden. And Poul seide o word, For the Hooli Goost spak wel bi Ysaye, the profete, to oure fadris,
27916	44	28	26	and seide, Go thou to this puple, and seie to hem, With eere ye schulen here, and ye schulen not vndirstonde; and ye seynge schulen se, and ye schulen not biholde.
27917	44	28	27	For the herte of this puple is greetli fattid, and with eeris thei herden heuyli, and thei closiden togider her iyen, lest perauenture thei se with iyen, and with eeris here, and bi herte vndurstonde, and be conuertid, and Y hele hem.
27918	44	28	28	Therfor be it knowun to you, that this helthe of God is sent to hethen men, and thei schulen here.
27919	44	28	29	And whanne he hadde seid these thingis, Jewis wenten out fro hym, and hadden myche questioun, ethir musyng, among hem silf.
27920	44	28	30	And he dwellide ful twei yeer in his hirid place; and he resseyuede alle that entryden to hym,
27921	44	28	31	and prechide the kingdom of God, and tauyte tho thingis that ben of the Lord Jhesu Crist, with al trist, with out forbedyng. Amen.
27922	45	1	1	Poul, the seruaunt of Jhesu Crist, clepid an apostle, departid in to the gospel of God;
27923	45	1	2	which he hadde bihote tofore bi his profetis in holi scripturis of his sone,
27924	45	1	3	which is maad to hym of the seed of Dauid bi the flesch,
27925	45	1	4	and he was bifor ordeyned the sone of God in vertu, bi the spirit of halewyng of the ayenrisyng of deed men, of Jhesu Crist oure Lord,
27926	45	1	5	bi whom we han resseyued grace and the office of apostle, to obeie to the feith in alle folkis for his name,
27927	45	1	6	among whiche ye ben also clepid of Jhesu Crist,
27928	45	1	7	to alle that ben at Rome, derlyngis of God, and clepid hooli, grace to you, and pees of God oure fadir, and of the Lord Jhesu Crist.
27929	45	1	8	First Y do thankyngis to my God, bi Jhesu Crist, for alle you, for youre feith is schewid in al the world.
27930	45	1	9	For God is a witnesse to me, to whom Y serue in my spirit, in the gospel of his sone,
27931	45	1	10	that with outen ceessyng Y make mynde of you euere in my preieris, and biseche, if in ony maner sum tyme Y haue a spedi weie in the wille of God to come to you.
27932	45	1	11	For Y desire to se you, to parten sumwhat of spiritual grace,
27933	45	1	12	that ye be confermyd, that is, to be coumfortid togidere in you, bi feith that is bothe youre and myn togidere.
27934	45	1	13	And, britheren, Y nyle, that ye vnknowun, that ofte Y purposide to come to you, and Y am lett to this tyme, that Y haue sum fruyt in you, as in othere folkis.
27935	45	1	14	To Grekis and to barberyns, to wise men and to vnwise men,
27936	45	1	15	Y am dettour, so that that is in me is redi to preche the gospel also to you that ben at Rome.
27937	45	1	16	For Y schame not the gospel, for it is the vertu of God in to heelthe to ech man that bileueth, to the Jew first, and to the Greke.
27938	45	1	17	For the riytwisnesse of God is schewid in it, of feith in to feith,
27939	45	1	18	as it is writun, For a iust man lyueth of feith. For the wraththe of God is schewid fro heuene on al vnpite and wickidnesse of tho men, that withholden the treuthe of God in vnriytwisnes.
27940	45	1	19	For that thing of God that is knowun, is schewid to hem, for God hath schewid to hem.
27941	45	1	20	For the vnuysible thingis of hym, that ben vndurstondun, ben biholdun of the creature of the world, bi tho thingis that ben maad, yhe, and the euerlastynge vertu of hym and the godhed, so that thei mowe not be excusid.
27942	45	1	21	For whanne thei hadden knowe God, thei glorifieden hym not as God, nether diden thankyngis; but thei vanyschiden in her thouyts, and the vnwise herte of hem was derkid.
27943	45	1	22	For thei `seiynge that hem silf weren wise, thei weren maad foolis.
27944	45	1	23	And thei chaungiden the glorie of `God vncorruptible in to the licnesse of an ymage of a deedli man, and of briddis, and of foure footid beestis, and of serpentis.
27945	45	1	24	For which thing God bitook hem in to the desiris of her herte, in to vnclennesse, that thei punysche with wrongis her bodies in hem silf.
27946	45	1	25	The whiche chaungiden the treuthe of God in to leesyng, and herieden and serueden a creature rathere than to the creatoure, that is blessid in to worldis of worldis.
27947	45	1	26	Amen. Therfor God bitook hem in to passiouns of schenschipe. For the wymmen of hem chaungiden the kyndli vss in to that vss that is ayens kynde.
27948	45	1	27	Also the men forsoken the kyndli vss of womman, and brenneden in her desiris togidere, and men in to men wrouyten filthehed, and resseyueden in to hem silf the meede that bihofte of her errour.
27949	45	1	28	And as thei preueden that thei hadden not God in knowyng, God bitook hem in to a repreuable wit, that thei do tho thingis that ben not couenable; that thei ben fulfillid with al wickidnesse,
27950	45	1	29	malice, fornycacioun, coueitise, weiwardnesse, ful of enuye, mansleyngis, strijf, gile, yuel wille, preuy bacbiteris, detractouris,
27951	45	1	30	hateful to God, debateris, proude, and hiy ouer mesure, fynderis of yuele thingis, not obeschynge to fadir and modir,
27952	45	1	31	vnwise, vnmanerli, withouten loue, withouten boond of pees, with outen merci.
27953	45	1	32	The whiche whanne thei hadden knowe the riytwisnesse of God, vndirstoden not, that thei that don siche thingis ben worthi the deth, not oneli thei that don tho thingis, but also thei that consenten to the doeris.
27954	45	2	1	Wherfor thou art vnexcusable, ech man that demest, for in what thing thou demest anothir man, thou condempnest thi silf; for thou doist the same thingis whiche thou demest.
27955	45	2	2	And we witen, that the doom of God is aftir treuthe ayens hem, that don siche thingis.
27956	45	2	3	But gessist thou, man, that demest hem that doen siche thingis, and thou doist tho thingis, that thou schalt ascape the doom of God?
27957	45	2	4	Whether `dispisist thou the richessis of his goodnesse, and the pacience, and the long abidyng? Knowist thou not, that the benygnyte of God ledith thee to forthenkyng?
27958	45	2	5	But aftir thin hardnesse and vnrepentaunt herte, thou tresorist to thee wraththe in the dai of wraththe and of schewyng of the riytful doom of God,
27959	45	2	6	that schal yelde to ech man aftir his werkis;
27960	45	2	7	sotheli to hem that ben bi pacience of good werk, glorie, and onour, and vncorrupcioun, to hem that seken euerlastynge lijf;
27961	45	2	8	but to hem that ben of strijf, and that assenten not to treuthe, but bileuen to wickidnesse, wraththe and indignacioun, tribulacioun and angwisch,
27962	45	2	9	in to ech soule of man that worchith yuel, to the Jew first, and to the Greke;
27963	45	2	10	but glorie, and honour, and pees, to ech man that worchith good thing, to the Jew first, and to the Greke.
27964	45	2	11	For accepcioun of persones is not anentis God.
27965	45	2	12	For who euere han synned without the lawe, schulen perische withouten the lawe; and who euere han synned in the lawe, thei schulen be demyd bi the lawe.
27966	45	2	13	For the hereris of lawe ben not iust anentis God, but the doeris of the lawe schulen be maad iust.
27967	45	2	14	For whanne hethene men that han not lawe, don kyndli tho thingis that ben of the lawe, thei not hauynge suche manere lawe, ben lawe to hem silf,
27968	45	2	15	that schewen the werk of the lawe writun in her hertis. For the conscience of hem yeldith to hem a witnessyng bytwixe hem silf of thouytis that ben accusynge or defendynge,
27969	45	2	16	in the dai whanne God schal deme the priuy thingis of men aftir my gospel, bi Jhesu Crist.
27970	45	2	17	But if thou art named a Jew, and restist in the lawe, and hast glorie in God,
27971	45	2	18	and hast knowe his wille, and thou lerud bi lawe preuest the more profitable thingis,
27972	45	2	19	and tristist thi silf to be a ledere of blynde men, the liyt of hem that ben in derknessis,
27973	45	2	20	a techere of vnwise men, a maistir of yonge children, that hast the foorme of kunnyng and of treuthe in the lawe;
27974	45	2	21	what thanne techist thou another, and techist not thi silf? Thou that prechist that me schal not stele, stelist?
27975	45	2	22	Thou that techist that me schal `do no letcherie, doist letcherie? Thou that wlatist maumetis, doist sacrilegie?
27976	45	2	23	Thou that hast glorie in the lawe, vnworschipist God bi brekyng of the lawe?
27977	45	2	24	For the name of God is blasfemed bi you among hethene men, as is writun.
27978	45	2	25	For circumcisioun profitith, if thou kepe the lawe; but if thou be a trespassour ayens the lawe, thi circumsicioun is maad prepucie.
27979	45	2	26	Therfor if prepucie kepe the riytwisnessis of the lawe, whethir his prepucie schal not be arettid in to circumcisioun?
27980	45	2	27	And the prepucie of kynde that fulfillith the lawe, schal deme thee, that bi lettre and circumcisioun art trespassour ayens the lawe.
27981	45	2	28	For he that is in opene is not a Jew, nether it is circumsicioun that is openli in the fleisch;
27982	45	2	29	but he that is a Jew in hid, and the circumcisioun of herte, in spirit, not bi the lettre, whos preisyng is not of men, but of God.
27983	45	3	1	What thanne is more to a Jew, or what profit of circumcisioun?
27984	45	3	2	Myche bi al wise; first, for the spekyngis of God `weren bitakun to hem.
27985	45	3	3	And what if summe of hem bileueden not? Whethir the vnbileue of hem hath auoidid the feith of God?
27986	45	3	4	God forbede. For God is sothefast, but ech man a liere; as it is writun, That thou be iustified in thi wordis, and ouercome, whanne thou art demed.
27987	45	3	5	But if oure wickidnesse comende the riytwisnesse of God, what shulen we seie? Whether God is wickid, that bryngith in wraththe?
27988	45	3	6	Aftir man Y seie. God forbede. Ellis hou schal God deme this world?
27989	45	3	7	For if the treuthe of God hath aboundid in my lessyng, in to the glorie of hym, what yit am Y demed as a synner?
27990	45	3	8	And not as we ben blasfemed, and as summen seien that we seien, Do we yuele thingis, that gode thingis come. Whos dampnacioun is iust.
27991	45	3	9	What thanne? Passen we hem? Nay; for we han schewid bi skile, that alle bothe Jewis and Grekis ben vndur synne,
27992	45	3	10	as it is writun, For ther is no man iust;
27993	45	3	11	ther is no man vndurstondynge, nethir sekynge God.
27994	45	3	12	Alle bowiden a wey, togidere thei ben maad vnprofitable; ther is noon that doith good thing, there is noon `til to oon.
27995	45	3	13	The throte of hem is an opyn sepulcre; with her tungis thei diden gilefuli; the venym of snakis is vndur her lippis.
27996	45	3	14	The mouth of whiche is ful of cursyng and bitternesse;
27997	45	3	15	the feet of hem ben swifte to schede blood.
27998	45	3	16	Sorewe and cursidnesse ben in the weies of hem, and thei knewen not the weie of pees;
27999	45	3	17	[]
28000	45	3	18	the drede of God is not bifor her iyen.
28001	45	3	19	And we witen, that what euere thingis the lawe spekith, it spekith to hem that ben in the lawe, that ech mouth be stoppid, and ech world be maad suget to God.
28002	45	3	20	For of the werkis of the lawe ech fleisch schal not be iustified bifor hym; for bi the lawe ther is knowyng of synne.
28003	45	3	21	But now with outen the lawe the riytwisnesse of God is schewid, that is witnessid of the lawe and the profetis.
28004	45	3	22	And the riytwisnesse of God is bi the feith of Jhesu Crist in to alle men and on alle men that bileuen in hym; for ther is no departyng.
28005	45	3	23	For alle men synneden, and han nede to the glorie of God;
28006	45	3	24	and ben iustified freli bi his grace, bi the ayenbiyng that is in `Crist Jhesu.
28007	45	3	25	Whom God ordeynede foryyuer, bi feith in his blood, to the schewyng of his riytwisnesse, for remyssioun of biforgoynge synnes,
28008	45	3	26	in the beryng up of God, to the schewyng of his riytwisnesse in this tyme, that he be iust, and iustifyynge hym that is of the feith of Jhesu Crist.
28009	45	3	27	Where thanne is thi gloriyng? It is excludid. Bi what lawe? Of dedis doyng? Nay, but by the lawe of feith.
28010	45	3	28	For we demen a man to be iustified bi the feith, with outen werkis of the lawe.
28011	45	3	29	Whethir of Jewis is God oneli? Whether he is not also of hethene men? Yhis, and of hethene men.
28012	45	3	30	For `oon God is, that iustefieth circumcisioun bi feith, and prepucie bi feith.
28013	45	3	31	Distruye we therfor the lawe bi the feith? God forbede; but we stablischen the lawe.
28014	45	4	1	What thanne schulen we seie, that Abraham oure fadir aftir the flesch foond?
28015	45	4	2	For if Abraham is iustified of werkis of the lawe, he hath glorie, but not anentis God.
28016	45	4	3	For what seith the scripture? Abraham bileued to God, and it was arettid to him to riytwisnesse.
28017	45	4	4	And to hym that worchith mede is not arettid bi grace, but bi dette.
