29948	58	1	3	Which whanne also he is the briytnesse of glorie, and figure of his substaunce, and berith alle thingis bi word of his vertu, he makith purgacioun of synnes, and syttith on the riythalf of the maieste in heuenes;
29949	58	1	4	and so myche is maad betere than aungels, bi hou myche he hath eneritid a more dyuerse name bifor hem.
29950	58	1	5	For to whiche of the aungels seide God ony tyme, Thou art my sone, Y haue gendrid thee to dai? And eftsoone, Y schal be to hym in to a fadir, and he schal be to me in to a sone?
29951	58	1	6	And whanne eftsoone he bryngith in the firste bigetun sone in to the world, he seith, And alle the aungels of God worschipe hym.
29952	58	1	7	But he seith to aungels, He that makith hise aungels spiritis, and hise mynystris flawme of fier.
29953	58	1	8	But to the sone he seith, God, thi trone is in to the world of world; a yerde of equite is the yerde of thi rewme;
29954	58	1	9	thou hast louyd riytwisnesse, and hatidist wickidnesse; therfor the God, thi God, anoyntide thee with oile of ioye, more than thi felowis.
29955	58	1	10	And, Thou, Lord, in the bigynnyng foundidist the erthe, and heuenes ben werkis of thin hondis; thei schulen perische,
29956	58	1	11	but thou schalt perfitli dwelle; and alle schulen wexe elde as a cloth, and thou schalt chaunge hem as a cloth,
29957	58	1	12	and thei schulen be chaungid. But thou art the same thi silf, and thi yeeris schulen not faile.
29958	58	1	13	But to whiche of the aungels seide God at ony tyme, Sitte thou on my riythalf, till Y putte thin enemyes a stool of thi feet?
29959	58	1	14	Whether thei alle ben not seruynge spiritis, sente to seruen for hem that taken the eritage of heelthe?
29960	58	2	1	Therfor more plenteuousli it bihoueth vs to kepe tho thingis, that we han herd, lest perauenture we fleten awei.
29961	58	2	2	For if the ilke word that was seid bi aungels, was maad sad, and ech brekyng of the lawe and vnobedience took iust retribucioun of meede,
29962	58	2	3	hou schulen we ascape, if we despisen so greet an heelthe? Which, whanne it hadde takun bigynnyng to be teld out by the Lord, of hem that herden is confermyd in to vs.
29963	58	2	4	For God witnesside to gidere bi myraclis, and wondris, and grete merueilis, and dyuerse vertues, and departyngis of the Hooli Goost, bi his wille.
29964	58	2	5	But not to aungels God sugetide the world that is to comynge, of which we speken.
29965	58	2	6	But sum man witnesside in a place, and seide, What thing is man, that thou art myndeful of hym, or mannus sone, for thou visitist hym?
29966	58	2	7	Thou hast maad hym a litil lesse than aungels; thou hast corowned hym with glorie and onour; and thou hast ordeyned him on the werkis of thin hondis.
29967	58	2	8	Thou hast maad alle thingis suget vndur hise feet. And in that that he sugetide alle thingis to hym, he lefte no thing vnsuget to him. But now we seen not yit alle thingis suget to hym;
29968	58	2	9	but we seen hym that was maad a litil lesse than aungels, Jhesu, for the passioun of deth crowned with glorie and onour, that he thorouy grace of God schulde taste deth for alle men.
29969	58	2	10	For it bisemede hym, for whom alle thingis, and bi whom `alle thingis weren maad, which hadde brouyt many sones into glorie, and was auctour of the heelthe of hem, that he hadde an ende bi passioun.
29970	58	2	11	For he that halewith, and thei that ben halewid, ben alle of oon; for which cause he is not schamed to clepe hem britheren,
29971	58	2	12	seiynge, Y schal telle thi name to my britheren; in the myddil of the chirche Y schal herie thee.
29972	58	2	13	And eftsoone, Y schal be tristnynge in to hym; and eftsoone, Lo! Y and my children, whiche God yaf to me.
29973	58	2	14	Therfor for children comyneden to fleisch and blood, and he also took part of the same, that bi deth he schulde destrie hym that hadde lordschipe of deth, that is to seie, the deuel,
29974	58	2	15	and that he schulde delyuere hem that bi drede of deth, `bi al lijf weren boundun to seruage.
29975	58	2	16	And he took neuere aungelis, but he took the seed of Abraham.
29976	58	2	17	Wherfor he ouyte to be likned to britheren bi alle thingis, that he schulde be maad merciful and a feithful bischop to God, that he schulde be merciful to the trespassis of the puple.
29977	58	2	18	For in that thing in which he suffride, and was temptid, he is miyti to helpe also hem that ben temptid.
29978	58	3	1	Therfor, hooli britheren, and parceneris of heuenli cleping, biholde ye the apostle and the bischop of oure confessioun, Jhesu,
29979	58	3	2	which is trewe to hym that made hym, as also Moises in al the hous of hym.
29980	58	3	3	But this byschop is had worthi of more glorie than Moises, bi as myche as he hath more honour of the hous, that made the hous.
29981	58	3	4	For ech hous is maad of sum man; he that made alle thingis of nouyt is God.
29982	58	3	5	And Moises was trewe in al his hous, as a seruaunt, in to witnessyng of tho thingis that weren to be seid;
29983	58	3	6	but Crist as a sone in his hous. Which hous we ben, if we holden sad trist and glorie of hope in to the ende.
29984	58	3	7	Wherfor as the Hooli Goost seith, To dai, if ye han herd his vois, nyle ye hardne youre hertis,
29985	58	3	8	as in wraththing, lijk the dai of temptacioun in desert;
29986	58	3	9	where youre fadris temptiden me, and preueden, and siyen my werkis fourti yeeris.
29987	58	3	10	Wherfor Y was wrooth to this generacioun, and Y seide, Euere more thei erren in herte, for thei knewen not my weies;
29988	58	3	11	to whiche Y swore in my wraththe, thei schulen not entre in to my reste.
29989	58	3	12	Britheren, se ye, lest perauenture in ony of you be an yuel herte of vnbileue, to departe fro the lyuynge God.
29990	58	3	13	But moneste you silf bi alle daies, the while to dai is named, that noon of you be hardned bi fallas of synne.
29991	58	3	14	For we ben maad parceneris of Crist, if netheles we holden the bigynnyng of his substaunce sad in to the ende.
29992	58	3	15	While it is seid, to dai, if ye han herd the vois of hym, nyle ye hardne youre hertis, as in that wraththing.
29993	58	3	16	For summen heringe wraththiden, but not alle thei that wenten out of Egipt bi Moises.
29994	58	3	17	But to whiche was he wraththid fourti yeeris? Whether not to hem that synneden, whos careyns weren cast doun in desert?
29995	58	3	18	And to whiche swoor he, that thei schulden not entre in to the reste of hym, not but to hem that weren vnbileueful?
29996	58	3	19	And we seen, that thei myyten not entre in to the reste of hym for vnbileue.
29997	58	4	1	Therfor drede we, lest perauenture while the biheest of entryng in to his reste is left, that ony of vs be gessid to be awei.
29998	58	4	2	For it is told also to vs, as to hem. And the word that was herd profitide not to hem, not meynd to feith of tho thingis that thei herden.
29999	58	4	3	For we that han bileued, schulen entre in to reste, as he seide, As Y swoor in my wraththe, thei schulen not entre in to my reste. And whanne the werkis weren maad perfit at the ordynaunce of the world,
30000	58	4	4	he seide thus in a place of the seuenthe dai, And God restide in the seuenthe dai from alle hise werkis.
30001	58	4	5	And in this place eftsoone, Thei schulen not entre in to my reste.
30002	58	4	6	Therfor for it sueth, that summen schulen entre in to it, and thei to whiche it was teld to bifor, entriden not for her vnbileue.
30003	58	4	7	Eftsoone he termyneth sum dai, and seith in Dauith, To dai, aftir so myche tyme of tyme, as it is biforseid, To dai if ye han herd his vois, nyle ye hardne youre hertis.
30004	58	4	8	For if Jhesus hadde youun reste to hem, he schulde neuere speke of othere aftir this dai.
30005	58	4	9	Therfor the sabat is left to the puple of God.
30006	58	4	10	For he that is entrid in to his reste, restide of hise werkis, as also God of hise.
30007	58	4	11	Therfor haste we to entre in to that reste, that no man falle in to the same ensaumple of vnbileue. For the word of God is quyk,
30008	58	4	12	and spedi in worching, and more able to perse than any tweyne eggid swerd, and stretchith forth to the departynge of the soule and of the spirit, and of the ioynturis and merewis, and demere of thouytis, and of intentis and hertis.
30009	58	4	13	And no creature is vnuisible in the siyt of God. For alle thingis ben nakid and opyn to hise iyen, to whom a word to vs.
30010	58	4	14	Therfor we that han a greet bischop, that perside heuenes, Jhesu, the sone of God, holde we the knoulechyng of oure hope.
30011	58	4	15	For we han not a bischop, that may not haue compassioun on oure infirmytees, but was temptid bi alle thingis bi lycnesse, with oute synne.
30012	58	4	16	Therfor go we with trist to the trone of his grace, that we gete merci, and fynde grace in couenable help.
30013	58	5	1	For ech bischop takun of men, is ordeyned for men in these thingis `that ben to God, that he offre yiftis and sacrifices for synnes.
30014	58	5	2	Which may togidere sorewe with hem, that beth vnkunnynge and erren; for also he is enuyrounned with infirmytee.
30015	58	5	3	And therfor he owith, as for the puple, so also for hym silf, to offre for synnes.
30016	58	5	4	Nethir ony man taketh to hym onour, but he that is clepid of God, as Aaron was.
30017	58	5	5	So Crist clarifiede not hym silf, that he were bischop, but he that spak to hym, Thou art my sone, to dai Y gendride thee.
30018	58	5	6	As `in anothere place he seith, Thou art a prest with outen ende, aftir the ordre of Melchisedech.
30019	58	5	7	Which in the daies of his fleisch offride, with greet cry and teeris, preieris and bisechingis to hym that myyte make hym saaf fro deth, and was herd for his reuerence.
30020	58	5	8	And whanne he was Goddis sone, he lernyde obedience of these thingis that be suffride;
30021	58	5	9	and he brouyt to the ende is maad cause of euerlastinge heelthe to alle that obeischen to hym, and is clepid of God a bischop,
30022	58	5	10	bi the ordre of Melchisedech.
30023	58	5	11	Of whom ther is to vs a greet word for to seie, and able to be expowned, for ye ben maad feble to here.
30024	58	5	12	For whanne ye ouyten to be maistris for tyme, eftsoone ye neden that ye be tauyt, whiche ben the lettris of the bigynnyng of Goddis wordis. And ye ben maad thilke, to whiche is nede of mylk, and not sad mete.
30025	58	5	13	For ech that is parcenere of mylk, is with out part of the word of riytwisnesse, for he is a litil child.
30026	58	5	14	But of perfit men is sad mete, of hem that for custom han wittis exercisid to discrecioun of good and of yuel.
30027	58	6	1	Therfor we bringinge in a word of the bigynnyng of Crist, be we borun to the perfeccioun of hym, not eftsoone leggynge the foundement of penaunce fro deed werkis, and of the feith to God, and of teching of baptimys,
30028	58	6	2	and of leiynge on of hondis, and of risyng ayen of deed men, and of the euerlastinge doom.
30029	58	6	3	And this thing we schulen do, if God schal suffre.
30030	58	6	4	But it is impossible, that thei that ben onys liytned, and `han tastid also an heuenly yifte, and ben maad parceneris of the Hooli Goost,
30031	58	6	5	and netheles han tastid the good word of God, and the vertues of the world to comynge, and ben slidun fer awei,
30032	58	6	6	that thei be renewid eftsoone to penaunce. Whiche eftsones crucifien to hem silf the sone of God, and han to scorn.
30033	58	6	7	For the erthe that drinkith reyn ofte comynge on it, and bringith forth couenable erbe to hem of whiche it is tilid, takith blessing of God.
30034	58	6	8	But that that is bringinge forth thornes and breris, is repreuable, and next to curs, whos endyng schal be in to brennyng.
30035	58	6	9	But, ye moost dereworthe, we tristen of you betere thingis, and neer to helthe, thouy we speken so.
30036	58	6	10	For God is not vniust, that he foryete youre werk and loue, whiche ye han schewid in his name; for ye han mynystrid to seyntis, `and mynistren.
30037	58	6	11	And we coueiten that ech of you schewe the same bisynesse to the fillyng of hope in to the ende;
30038	58	6	12	that ye be not maad slowe, but also sueris of hem, whiche bi feith and pacience schulen enherite the biheestis.
30039	58	6	13	For God bihetinge to Abraham, for he hadde noon grettere, bi whom he schulde swere, swoor bi hym silf,
30040	58	6	14	and seide, Y blessinge schal blesse thee, and Y multipliynge schal multiplie thee;
30041	58	6	15	and so he long abidinge hadde the biheeste.
30042	58	6	16	For men sweren bi a grettere than hem silf, and the ende of al her ple is an ooth to confirmacioun.
30043	58	6	17	In which thing God willynge to schewe plenteuouslier to the eiris of his biheest the sadnesse of his counsel,
30044	58	6	18	puttide bitwixe an ooth, that bi twey thingis vnmeuable, bi whiche it is impossible that God lie, we han a strengeste solace, `we that fleen togidere to holde the hope that is put forth to vs.
30045	58	6	19	Which hope as an ankir we han sikir to the soule, and sad, and goynge in to the ynnere thingis of hiding;
30046	58	6	20	where the bifore goere, Jhesus, that is maad bischop with outen ende bi the ordre of Melchisedech, entride for vs.
30047	58	7	1	And this Melchisedech, king of Salem, and preest of the hiyeste God, which mette with Abraham, as he turnede ayen fro the sleyng of kyngis, and blesside hym;
30048	58	7	2	to whom also Abraham departide tithis of alle thingis; first he is seid king of riytwisnesse, and aftirward kyng of Salem, that is to seie, king of pees,
30049	58	7	3	with out fadir, with out modir, with out genologie, nether hauynge bigynnyng of daies, nether ende of lijf; and he is lickened to the sone of God, and dwellith preest with outen ende.
30050	58	7	4	But biholde ye how greet is this, to whom Abraham the patriark yaf tithis of the beste thingis.
30051	58	7	5	For men of the sones of Leuy takinge presthod han maundement to take tithis of the puple, bi the lawe, that is to seie, of her britheren, thouy also thei wenten out of the leendis of Abraham.
30052	58	7	6	But he whos generacioun is not noumbrid in hem, took tithis of Abraham; and he blesside this Abraham, which hadde repromyssiouns.
30053	58	7	7	With outen ony ayenseiyng, that that is lesse, is blessid of the betere.
30054	58	7	8	And heere deedli men taken tithis; but there he berith witnessyng, that he lyueth.
30055	58	7	9	And that it be seid so, bi Abraham also Leuy, that took tithis, was tithid; and yit he was in his fadris leendis,
30056	58	7	10	whanne Melchisedech mette with hym.
30057	58	7	11	Therfor if perfeccioun was bi the preesthood of Leuy, for vndur hym the puple took the lawe, what yit was it nedeful, another preest to rise, bi the ordre of Melchisedech, and not to be seid bi the ordre of Aaron?
30058	58	7	12	For whi whanne the preesthod is translatid, it is nede that also translacioun of the lawe be maad.
30059	58	7	13	But he in whom these thingis ben seid, is of another lynage, of which no man was preest to the auter.
30060	58	7	14	For it is opyn, that oure Lord is borun of Juda, in which lynage Moises spak no thing of preestis.
30061	58	7	15	And more yit it is knowun, if bi the ordre of Melchisedech another preest is risun vp;
30062	58	7	16	which is not maad bi the lawe of fleischli maundement, but bi vertu of lijf that may not be vndon.
30063	58	7	17	For he witnessith, That thou art a preest with outen ende, bi the ordre of Melchisedech;
30064	58	7	18	that repreuyng of the maundement bifor goynge is maad, for the vnsadnesse and vnprofit of it.
30065	58	7	19	For whi the lawe brouyt no thing to perfeccioun, but there is a bringing in of a betere hope, bi which we neiyen to God.
30066	58	7	20	And hou greet it is, not with out sweryng; but the othere ben maad preestis with outen an ooth;
30067	58	7	21	but this preest with an ooth, bi hym that seide `to hym, The Lord swoor, and it schal not rewe hym, Thou art a preest with outen ende, bi the ordre of Melchisedech;
30068	58	7	22	in so myche Jhesus is maad biheetere of the betere testament.
30069	58	7	23	And the othere weren maad manye preestis, `therfor for thei weren forbedun bi deth to dwelle stille;
30070	58	7	24	but this, for he dwellith with outen ende, hath an euerlastynge preesthod.
30071	58	7	25	Wherfor also he may saue with outen ende, comynge nyy bi hym silf to God, and euermore lyueth to preye for vs.
30072	58	7	26	For it bisemyde that sich a man were a bischop to vs, hooli, innocent, vndefoulid, clene, departid fro synful men, and maad hiyere than heuenes;
30073	58	7	27	which hath not nede ech dai, as prestis, first for hise owne giltis to offre sacrifices, and aftirward for the puple; for he dide this thing in offringe hym silf onys.
30074	58	7	28	And the lawe ordeynede men prestis hauynge sijknesse; but the word of swering, which is after the lawe, ordeynede the sone perfit with outen ende.
30075	58	8	1	But a capitle on tho thingis that ben seid. We han siche a bischop, that sat in the riythalf of the seete of greetnesse in heuenes,
30076	58	8	2	the mynystre of seyntis, and of the veri tabernacle, that God made, and not man.
30077	58	8	3	For ech bischop is ordeyned to offre yiftis and sacrificis; wherfor it is nede, that also this bischop haue sum thing that he schal offre.
30078	58	8	4	Therfor if he were on erthe, he were no preest, whanne ther weren that schulden offre yiftis bi the lawe,
30079	58	8	5	whiche seruen to the saumpler and schadewe of heueneli thingis. As it was answerid to Moises, whanne he schulde ende the tabernacle, Se, he seide, make thou alle thingis bi the saumpler, that is schewid to thee in the mount.
30080	58	8	6	But now he hath getun a betere mynysterie, bi so myche as he is a mediatour of a betere testament, which is confermyd with betere biheestis.
30081	58	8	7	For if the ilke firste hadde lackid blame, the place of the secounde schulde not haue be souyt.
30082	58	8	8	For he repreuynge hem seith, Lo! daies comen, seith the Lord, and Y schal make perfit a newe testament on the hous of Israel, and on the hous of Juda;
30083	58	8	9	not lijk the testament that Y made to her fadris, `in the dai in which Y cauyte her hond, that Y schulde lede hem out of the loond of Egipt; for thei dwelliden not perfitli in my testament, and Y haue dispisid hem, seith the Lord.
30084	58	8	10	But this is the testament, which Y schal dispose to the hous of Israel aftir tho daies, seith the Lord, in yyuynge my lawis in to the soulis of hem, and in to the hertis of hem I schal aboue write hem; and Y schal be to hem in to a God, and they schulen be to me in to a puple.
30085	58	8	11	And ech man schal not teche his neiyebore, and ech man his brother, seiynge, Knowe thou the Lord; for alle men schulen knowe me, fro the lesse to the more of hem.
30086	58	8	12	For Y schal be merciful to the wickidnesse of hem, and now Y schal not bithenke on the synnes of hem.
30087	58	8	13	But in seiynge a newe, the formere wexide eeld; and that that is of many daies, and wexith eeld, is nyy the deeth.
30088	58	9	1	And the former testament hadde iustefiyngis of worschip, and hooli thing duringe for a tyme.
30089	58	9	2	For the tabernacle was maad first, in which weren candilstikis, and boord, and setting forth of looues, which is seid hooli.
30090	58	9	3	And after the veil, the secounde tabernacle, that is seid sancta sanctorum, that is, hooli of hooli thingis;
30091	58	9	4	hauynge a goldun cenrer, and the arke of the testament, keuered aboute on ech side with gold, in which was a pot of gold hauynge manna, and the yerde of Aaron that florischide, and the tablis of the testament;
30092	58	9	5	on whiche thingis weren cherubyns of glorie, ouerschadewinge the propiciatorie; of whiche thingis it is not now to seie bi alle.
30093	58	9	6	But whanne these weren maad thus togidere, preestis entriden eueremore in the formere tabernacle, doynge the offices of sacrifices; but in the secounde tabernacle,
30094	58	9	7	the bischop entride onys in the yeer, not without blood, which he offride for his ignoraunce and the puplis.
30095	58	9	8	For the Hooli Goost signefiede this thing, that not yit the weie of seyntis was openyd, while the formere tabernacle hadde staat.
30096	58	9	9	Which parable is of this present tyme, bi which also yiftis and sacrifices ben offrid, whiche moun not make a man seruynge perfit bi conscience, oneli in metis,
30097	58	9	10	and drynkis, and dyuerse waischingis, and riytwisnessis of fleisch, that weren sett to the tyme of correccioun.
30098	58	9	11	But Crist beynge a bischop of goodis to comynge, entride bi a largere and perfitere tabernacle, not maad bi hoond, that is to seye,
30099	58	9	12	not of this makyng, nether bi blood of goot buckis, or of calues, but bi his owne blood, entride onys in to the hooli thingis, that weren foundun bi an euerlastinge redempcioun.
30100	58	9	13	For if the blood of gootbuckis, and of boolis, and the aische of a cow calf spreynd, halewith vnclene men to the clensing of fleisch,
30101	58	9	14	hou myche more the blood of Crist, which bi the Hooli Goost offride hym silf vnwemmyd to God, schal clense oure conscience fro deed werkis, to serue God that lyueth?
30102	58	9	15	And therfor he is a mediatour of the newe testament, that bi deth fallinge bitwixe, in to redempcioun of tho trespassyngis that weren vndur the formere testament, thei that ben clepid take the biheest of euerlastinge eritage.
30103	58	9	16	For where a testament is, it is nede, that the deth of the testament makere come bitwixe.
30104	58	9	17	For a testament is confermed in deed men; ellis it is not worthe, while he lyueth, that made the testament.
30105	58	9	18	Wherfor nether the firste testament was halewid without blood.
30106	58	9	19	For whanne ech maundement of the lawe was red of Moises to al the puple, he took the blood of calues, and of buckis of geet, with watir, and reed wolle, and ysope, and bispreynde bothe thilke book and al the puple,
30107	58	9	20	and seide, This is the blood of the testament, that God comaundide to you.
30108	58	9	21	Also he spreynde with blood the tabernacle, and alle the vessels of the seruyce in lijk maner.
30109	58	9	22	And almest alle thingis ben clensid in blood bi the lawe; and without scheding of blood remyssioun of synnes is not maad.
30110	58	9	23	Therfor it is nede, that the saumpleris of heuenli thingis be clensid with these thingis; but thilke heuenli thingis with betere sacrificis than these.
30111	58	9	24	For Jhesus entride not in to hooli thingis maad bi hoondis, that ben saumpleris of very thingis, but in to heuene it silf, that he appere now to the cheer of God for vs; nether that he offre him silf ofte,
30112	58	9	25	as the bischop entride in to hooli thingis bi alle yeeris in alien blood,
30113	58	9	26	ellis it bihofte hym to suffre ofte fro the bigynnyng of the world; but now onys in the ending of worldis, to distruccioun of synne bi his sacrifice he apperide.
30114	58	9	27	And as it is ordeynede to men,
30115	58	9	28	onys to die, but aftir this is the dom, so Crist was offrid onys, to auoyde the synnes of many men; the secounde tyme he schal appere with outen synne to men that abiden him in to heelthe.
30116	58	10	1	For the lawe hauinge a schadewe of good thingis `that ben to come, not the ilke image of thingis, mai neuer make men neiyinge perfit bi the ilke same sacrifices, which thei offren without ceessing bi alle yeeris;
30117	58	10	2	ellis thei schulden haue ceessid to be offrid, for as myche as the worschiperis clensid onys, hadden not ferthermore conscience of synne.
30118	58	10	3	But in hem mynde of synnes is maad bi alle yeris.
30119	58	10	4	For it is impossible that synnes be doon awei bi blood of boolis, and of buckis of geet.
30120	58	10	5	Therfor he entrynge in to the world, seith, Thou woldist not sacrifice and offryng; but thou hast schapun a bodi to me;
30121	58	10	6	brent sacrificis also for synne plesiden not to thee.
30122	58	10	7	Thanne Y seide, Lo! Y come; in the bigynnyng of the book it is writun of me, that Y do thi wille, God.
30123	58	10	8	He seiynge bifor, That thou woldist not sacrificis, and offringis, and brent sacrifices for synne, ne tho thingis ben plesaunt to thee, whiche ben offrid bi the lawe,
30124	58	10	9	thanne Y seide, Lo! Y come, that Y do thi wille, God. He doith awei the firste, that he make stidfast the secounde.
30125	58	10	10	In which wille we ben halewid bi the offring of the bodi of Crist Jhesu onys.
30126	58	10	11	And ech prest is redi mynystrynge ech dai, and ofte tymes offringe the same sacrifices, whiche moun neuere do awei synnes.
30127	58	10	12	But this man offringe o sacrifice for synnes, for euere more sittith in the riythalf of God the fadir;
30128	58	10	13	fro thennus forth abidinge, til hise enemyes ben put a stool of hise feet.
30129	58	10	14	For bi oon offring he made perfit for euere halewid men.
30130	58	10	15	And the Hooli Goost witnessith to vs; for aftir that he seide, This is the testament,
30131	58	10	16	which Y schal witnesse to hem after tho daies, the Lord seith, in yyuynge my lawes in the hertis of hem, and in the soulis of hem Y schal aboue write hem;
30132	58	10	17	and now Y schal no more thenke on the synnes and the wickidnessis of hem.
30133	58	10	18	And where remyssioun of these is, now is ther noon offring for synne.
30134	58	10	19	Therfor, britheren, hauynge trist in to the entring of hooli thingis in the blood of Crist,
30135	58	10	20	which halewide to vs a newe weie, and lyuynge bi the hiling, that is to seie,
30136	58	10	21	his fleisch, and we hauynge the greet preest on the hous of God,
30137	58	10	22	neiye we with very herte in the plente of feith; and be oure hertis spreined fro an yuel conscience, and oure bodies waischun with clene watir,
30138	58	10	23	and holde we the confessioun of oure hope, bowinge to no side; for he is trewe that hath made the biheeste.
30139	58	10	24	And biholde we togidere in the stiring of charite and of good werkis; not forsakinge oure gadering togidere,
30140	58	10	25	as it is of custom to sum men, but coumfortinge, and bi so myche the more, bi hou myche ye seen the dai neiyynge.
30141	58	10	26	Forwhi now a sacrifice for synnes is not left to vs, that synnen wilfuli, aftir that we han take the knowyng of treuthe.
30142	58	10	27	Forwhi sum abiding of the dom is dreedful, and the suyng of fier, which schal waste aduersaries.
30143	58	10	28	Who that brekith Moises lawe, dieth withouten ony merci, bi tweine or thre witnessis;
30144	58	10	29	hou myche more gessen ye, that he disserueth worse turmentis, which defouleth the sone of God, and holdith the blood of the testament pollut, in which he is halewid, and doith dispit to the spirit of grace?
30145	58	10	30	For we knowen him that seide, To me veniaunce, and Y schal yelde. And eft, For the Lord schal deme his puple.
30146	58	10	31	It is ferdful to falle in to the hondis of God lyuynge.
30147	58	10	32	And haue ye mynde on the formere daies, in which ye weren liytned, and suffriden greet strijf of passiouns.
30148	58	10	33	And in the `tothir ye weren maad a spectacle bi schenschipis and tribulaciouns; in an othir ye weren maad felowis of men lyuynge so.
30149	58	10	34	For also to boundun men ye hadden compassioun, and ye resseyueden with ioye the robbyng of youre goodis, knowinge that ye han a betere and a dwellinge substaunce.
30150	58	10	35	Therfor nyle ye leese youre trist, which hath greet rewarding.
30151	58	10	36	For pacience is nedeful to you, that ye do the wille of God, and bringe ayen the biheest.
30152	58	10	37	For yit a litil, and he that is to comynge schal come, and he schal not tarie.
30153	58	10	38	For my iust man lyueth of feith; that if he withdrawith hym silf, he schal not plese to my soule.
30154	58	10	39	But we ben not the sones of withdrawing awei in to perdicioun, but of feith in to getynge of soule.
30155	58	11	1	But feith is the substaunce of thingis that ben to be hopid, and an argument of thingis not apperynge.
30156	58	11	2	And in this feith elde men han gete witnessyng.
30157	58	11	3	Bi feith we vndurstonden that the worldis weren maad bi Goddis word, that visible thingis weren maad of vnuysible thingis.
30158	58	11	4	Bi feith Abel offride a myche more sacrifice than Caym to God, bi which he gat witnessyng to be iust, for God bar witnessyng to hise yiftis; and bi that feith he deed spekith yit.
30159	58	11	5	Bi feith Ennok was translatid, that he schulde not se deth; and he was not foundun, for the Lord translatide him. For bifore translacioun he hadde witnessing that he pleside God.
30160	58	11	6	And it is impossible to plese God without feith. For it bihoueth that a man comynge to God, bileue that he is, and that he is rewardere to men that seken hym.
30161	58	11	7	Bi feith Noe dredde, thorouy answere takun of these thingis that yit weren not seyn, and schapide a schip in to the helthe of his hous; bi which he dampnede the world, and is ordeyned eir of riytwisnesse, which is bi feith.
30162	58	11	8	By feith he that is clepid Abraham, obeiede to go out in to a place, whiche he schulde take in to eritage; and he wente out, not witinge whidur he schulde go.
30163	58	11	9	Bi feith he dwelte in the loond of biheest, as in an alien loond, dwellynge in litle housis with Ysaac and Jacob, euene heiris of the same biheest.
30164	58	11	10	For he abood a citee hauynge foundementis, whos crafti man and maker is God.
30165	58	11	11	Bi feith also the ilke Sara bareyn, took vertu in consceyuyng of seed, yhe, ayen the tyme of age; for sche bileuede hym trewe, that hadde bihiyte.
30166	58	11	12	For which thing of oon, and yit nyy deed, ther ben borun as sterris of heuene in multitude, and as grauel that is at the see side out of noumbre.
30167	58	11	13	Bi feith alle these ben deed, whanne the biheestis weren not takun, but thei bihelden hem afer, and gretynge hem wel, and knoulechide that thei weren pilgryms, and herboryd men on the erthe.
30168	58	11	14	And thei that sayn these thingis, signifien that thei sechen a cuntre.
30169	58	11	15	`If thei hadden hadde mynde of the ilke, of which thei wenten out, thei hadden tyme of turnyng ayen;
30170	58	11	16	but now thei desiren a betere, that is to seie, heuenli. Therfor God is not confoundid to be clepid the God of hem; for he made redi to hem a citee.
30171	58	11	17	Bi feith Abraham offride Ysaac, whanne he was temptid; and he offride the oon bigetun, whych had takun the biheestis;
30172	58	11	18	to whom it was seid, For in Ysaac the seed schal be clepid to thee.
30173	58	11	19	For he demyde, that God is myyti to reise hym, yhe, fro deth; wherfor he took hym also in to a parable.
30174	58	11	20	Bi feith also of thingis to comynge, Ysaac blesside Jacob and Esau.
30175	58	11	21	Bi feith Jacob diynge blesside alle the sones of Joseph, and onouride the hiynesse of his yerde.
30176	58	11	22	Bi feith Joseph dyynge hadde mynde of the passyng forth of the children of Israel, and comaundide of hise boonys.
30177	58	11	23	Bi feith Moyses borun, was hid thre monethis of his fadir and modir, for that thei seiyen the yonge child fair; and thei dredden not the maundement of the king.
30178	58	11	24	Bi feith Moises was maad greet, and denyede that he was the sone of Faraos douytir,
30179	58	11	25	and chees more to be turmentid with the puple of God, than to haue myrthe of temporal synne;
30180	58	11	26	demynge the repreef of Crist more richessis than the tresours of Egipcians; for he bihelde in to the rewarding.
30181	58	11	27	Bi feith he forsook Egipt, and dredde not the hardynesse of the king; for he abood, as seinge hym that was vnuysible.
30182	58	11	28	Bi feith he halewide pask, and the scheding out of blood, that he that distriede the firste thingis of Egipcians, schulde not touche hem.
30183	58	11	29	Bi feith thei passiden the reed see, as bi drye lond, which thing Egipcians asaiynge weren deuourid.
30184	58	11	30	Bi feith the wallis of Jerico felden doun, bi cumpassyng of seuene daies.
30185	58	11	31	Bi feith Raab hoor resseyuede the aspieris with pees, and perischide not with vnbileueful men.
30186	58	11	32	And what yit schal Y seie? For tyme schal faile to me tellynge of Gedeon, Barak, Sampson, Jepte, Dauid, and Samuel, and of othere prophetis;
30187	58	11	33	whiche bi feith ouercamen rewmes, wrouyten riytwisnesse, gaten repromyssiouns; thei stoppiden the mouthis of liouns,
30188	58	11	34	thei quenchiden the feersnesse of fier, thei dryueden awei the egge of swerd, thei coueriden of sijknesse, thei weren maad strong in batel, thei turneden the oostis of aliens.
30189	58	11	35	Wymmen resseyueden her deed children fro deth to lijf; but othere weren holdun forth, not takinge redempcioun, that thei schulden fynde a betere ayenrising.
30190	58	11	36	And othere asaieden scornyngis and betingis, more ouer and boondis and prisouns.
30191	58	11	37	Thei weren stoned, thei weren sawid, thei weren temptid, thei weren deed in sleyng of swerd. Thei wenten aboute in broc skynnes, and in skynnes of geet, nedi, angwischid, turmentid;
30192	58	11	38	to whiche the world was not worthi. Thei erriden in wildernessis, in mounteynes and dennes, and caues of the erthe.
30193	58	11	39	And alle these, preued bi witnessing of feith, token not repromyssioun;
30194	58	11	40	for God purueiede sum betere thing for vs, that thei schulden not be maad perfit with outen vs.
30195	58	12	1	Therfor we that han so greet a cloude of witnessis put to, do we awei al charge, and synne stondinge aboute vs, and bi pacience renne we to the batel purposid to vs,
30196	58	12	2	biholdinge in to the makere of feith, and the perfit endere, Jhesu; which whanne ioye was purposid to hym, he suffride the cros, and dispiside confusioun, and sittith on the riythalf of the seet of God.
30197	58	12	3	And bithenke ye on hym that suffride siche `ayen seiynge of synful men ayens hym silf, that ye be not maad wery, failinge in youre soulis.
30198	58	12	4	For ye ayenstoden not yit `til to blood, fiytyng ayens synne.
30199	58	12	5	And ye han foryet the coumfort that spekith to you as to sones, and seith, My sone, nyle thou dispise the teching of the Lord, nether be thou maad weri, the while thou art chastisid of hym.
30200	58	12	6	For the Lord chastisith hym that he loueth; he betith euery sone that he resseyueth.
30201	58	12	7	Abide ye stille in chastising; God proferith hym to you as to sones. For what sone is it, whom the fadir chastisith not?
30202	58	12	8	That if ye `ben out of chastising, whos parteneris ben ye alle maad, thanne ye ben auowtreris, and not sones.
30203	58	12	9	And aftirward we hadden fadris of oure fleisch, techeris, and we with reuerence dredden hem. Whethir not myche more we schulen obeische to the fadir of spiritis, and we schulen lyue?
30204	58	12	10	And thei in tyme of fewe dayes tauyten vs bi her wille; but this fadir techith to that thing that is profitable, in resseyuynge the halewing of hym.
30205	58	12	11	And ech chastisyng in present tyme semeth to be not of ioye, but of sorewe; but aftirward it schal yelde fruyt of riytwisnesse moost pesible to men exercisid bi it.
30206	58	12	12	For whiche thing reise ye slowe hondis,
30207	58	12	13	and knees vnboundun, and make ye riytful steppis to youre feet; that no man haltinge erre, but more be heelid.
30208	58	12	14	Sue ye pees with alle men, and holynesse, with out which no man schal se God.
30209	58	12	15	Biholde ye, that no man faile to the grace of God, that no roote of bittirnesse buriownynge vpward lette, and manye ben defoulid bi it;
30210	58	12	16	that no man be letchour, ether vnhooli, as Esau, which for o mete seelde hise firste thingis.
30211	58	12	17	For wite ye, that afterward he coueitinge to enherite blessing, was repreued. For he foond not place of penaunce, thouy he souyte it with teeris.
30212	58	12	18	But ye han not come to the fier able to be touchid, and able to come to, and to the whirlewynd, and myst, and tempest, and soun of trumpe, and vois of wordis;
30213	58	12	19	which thei that herden, excusiden hem, that the word schulde not be maad to hem.
30214	58	12	20	For thei beren not that that was seid, And if a beeste touchide the hil, it was stonyd.
30215	58	12	21	And so dredeful it was that was seyn, that Moises seide, Y am a ferd, and ful of trembling.
30216	58	12	22	But ye han come nyy to the hil Sion, and to the cite of God lyuynge, the heuenli Jerusalem, and to the multitude of many thousynde aungels,
30217	58	12	23	and to the chirche of the firste men, whiche ben writun in heuenes, and to God, domesman of alle, and to the spirit of iust perfit men,
30218	58	12	24	and to Jhesu, mediatour of the newe testament, and to the sprenging of blood, `betere spekinge than Abel.
30219	58	12	25	Se ye, that ye forsake not the spekere; for if thei that forsaken him that spak on the erthe, aschapide not, myche more we that turnen awei fro him that spekith to vs fro heuenes.
30220	58	12	26	Whos vois than mouyde the erthe, but now he ayen bihetith, and seith, Yit onys and Y schal moue not oneli erthe, but also heuene.
30221	58	12	27	And that he seith, Yit onys, he declarith the translacioun of mouable thingis, as of maad thingis, that tho thingis dwelle, that ben vnmouable.
30222	58	12	28	Therfor we resseyuynge the kingdom vnmouable, haue we grace, bi which serue we plesynge to God with drede and reuerence.
30223	58	12	29	For oure God is fier that wastith.
30224	58	13	1	The charite of britherhod dwelle in you, and nyle ye foryete hospitalite;
30225	58	13	2	for bi this summen plesiden to aungels, that weren resseyued to herborewe.
30226	58	13	3	Thenke ye on boundun men, as ye weren togidere boundun, and of trauelinge men, as ye silf dwellinge in the body.
30227	58	13	4	`Wedding is in alle thingis onourable, and bed vnwemmed; for God schal deme fornicatouris and auouteris.
30228	58	13	5	Be youre maneres withoute coueitise, apaied with present thingis; for he seide, Y schal not leeue thee,
30229	58	13	6	nether forsake, so that we seie tristily, The Lord is an helpere to me; Y schal not drede, what a man schal do to me.
30230	58	13	7	Haue ye mynde of youre souereyns, that han spokun to you the word of God; of whiche `biholde ye the goyng out of lyuynge, and sue ye the feith of hem,
30231	58	13	8	Jhesu Crist, yistirdai, and to dai, he is also into worldis.
30232	58	13	9	Nyle ye be led awei with dyuerse `techingis, and straunge. For it is best to stable the herte with grace, not with metis, whiche profitiden not to men wandringe in hem.
30233	58	13	10	We han an auter, of which thei that seruen to the tabernacle, han not power to ete.
30234	58	13	11	For of whiche beestis the blood is borun in for synne in to hooli thingis bi the bischop, the bodies of hem ben brent with out the castels.
30235	58	13	12	For which thing Jhesu, that he schulde halewe the puple bi his blood, suffride with out the gate.
30236	58	13	13	Therfor go we out to hym with out the castels, berynge his repreef.
30237	58	13	14	For we han not here a citee dwellynge, but we seken a citee to comynge.
30238	58	13	15	Therfor bi hym offre we a sacrifice of heriyng euere more to God, that is to seye, the fruyt of lippis knoulechinge to his name.
30239	58	13	16	And nyle ye foryete wel doynge, and comynyng; for bi siche sacrifices God is disserued.
30240	58	13	17	Obeie ye to youre souereyns, and be ye suget to hem; for thei perfitli waken, as to yeldinge resoun for youre soulis, that thei do this thing with ioie, and not sorewinge; for this thing spedith not to you.
30241	58	13	18	Preie ye for vs, and we tristen that we han good conscience in alle thingis, willynge to lyue wel.
30242	58	13	19	More ouer Y biseche you to do, that Y be restorid the sunnere to you.
30243	58	13	20	And God of pees, that ladde out fro deth the greet scheepherd of scheep, in the blood of euerlastinge testament, oure Lord Jhesu Crist,
30244	58	13	21	schape you in al good thing, that ye do the wille of hym; and he do in you that thing that schal plese bifor hym, bi Jhesu Crist, to whom be glorie in to worldis of worldis. Amen.
30245	58	13	22	And, britheren, Y preie you, that ye suffre a word of solace; for bi ful fewe thingis Y haue writun to you.
30246	58	13	23	Knowe ye oure brother Tymothe, that is sent forth, with whom if he schal come more hastili, Y schal se you.
30247	58	13	24	Grete ye wel alle youre souereyns, and alle hooli men. The britheren of Italie greten you wel.
30248	58	13	25	The grace of God be with you alle. Amen.
30249	59	1	1	James, the seruaunt of God, and of oure Lord Jhesu Crist, to the twelue kinredis, that ben in scatering abrood, helthe.
30250	59	1	2	My britheren, deme ye al ioye, whanne ye fallen in to diuerse temptaciouns, witynge,
30251	59	1	3	that the preuyng of youre feith worchith pacience;
30252	59	1	4	and pacience hath a perfit werk, that ye be perfit and hole, and faile in no thing.
30253	59	1	5	And if ony of you nedith wisdom, axe he of God, which yyueth to alle men largeli, and vpbreidith not; and it schal be youun to hym.
30254	59	1	6	But axe he in feith, and doute no thing; for he that doutith, is lijk to a wawe of the see, which is moued and borun a boute of wynde.
30255	59	1	7	Therfor gesse not the ilke man, that he schal take ony thing of the Lord.
30256	59	1	8	A man dowble in soule is vnstable in alle hise weies.
30257	59	1	9	And a meke brother haue glorie in his enhaunsyng,
30258	59	1	10	and a riche man in his lownesse; for as the flour of gras he schal passe.
30259	59	1	11	The sunne roos vp with heete, and driede the gras, and the flour of it felde doun, and the fairnesse of his chere perischide; and so a riche man welewith in hise weies.
30260	59	1	12	Blessid is the man, that suffrith temptacioun; for whanne he schal be preued, he schal resseyue the coroun of lijf, which God biheyte to men that louen hym.
30261	59	1	13	No man whanne he is temptid, seie, that he is temptid of God; for whi God is not a temptere of yuele thingis, for he temptith no man.
30262	59	1	14	But ech man is temptid, drawun and stirid of his owne coueiting.
30263	59	1	15	Aftirward coueityng, whanne it hath conseyued, bringith forth synne; but synne, whanne it is fillid, gendrith deth.
30264	59	1	16	Therfor, my most dereworthe britheren, nyle ye erre.
30265	59	1	17	Ech good yifte, and ech perfit yifte is from aboue, and cometh doun fro the fadir of liytis, anentis whom is noon other chaungyng, ne ouerschadewyng of reward.
30266	59	1	18	For wilfulli he bigat vs bi the word of treuthe, that we be a bigynnyng of his creature.
30267	59	1	19	Wite ye, my britheren moost loued, be ech man swift to here, but slow to speke, and slow to wraththe;
30268	59	1	20	for the wraththe of man worchith not the riytwisnesse of God.
30269	59	1	21	For which thing caste ye awei al vnclennesse, and plentee of malice, and in myldenesse resseyue ye the word that is plauntid, that may saue youre soulis.
30270	59	1	22	But be ye doeris of the word, and not hereris oneli, disseiuynge you silf.
30271	59	1	23	For if ony man is an herere of the word, and not a doere, this schal be licned to a man that biholdith the cheer of his birthe in a mirour;
30272	59	1	24	for he bihelde hym silf, and wente awei, and anoon he foryat which he was.
30273	59	1	25	But he that biholdith in the lawe of perfit fredom, and dwellith in it, and is not maad a foryetful herere, but a doere of werk, this schal be blessid in his dede.
30274	59	1	26	And if ony man gessith hym silf to be religiouse, and refreyneth not his tunge, but disseyueth his herte, the religioun of him is veyn.
30275	59	1	27	A clene religioun, and an vnwemmed anentis God and the fadir, is this, to visite fadirles and modirles children, and widewis in her tribulacioun, and to kepe hym silf vndefoulid fro this world.
30276	59	2	1	Mi britheren, nyle ye haue the feith of oure Lord Jhesu Crist of glorie, in accepcioun of persoones.
30277	59	2	2	For if a man `that hath a goldun ring, and in a feire clothing, cometh in youre cumpany, and a pore man entrith in a foul clothing,
30278	59	2	3	and if ye biholden in to hym that is clothid with clere clothing, and if ye seie to hym, Sitte thou here wel; but to the pore man ye seien, Stonde thou there, ethir sitte vndur the stool of my feet; whether ye demen not anentis you silf,
30279	59	2	4	and ben maad domesmen of wickid thouytis?
30280	59	2	5	Heere ye, my moost dereworthe britheren, whethir God chees not pore men in this world, riche in feith, and eiris of the kyngdom, that God bihiyte to men that louen him?
30281	59	2	6	But ye han dispisid the pore man. Whether riche men oppressen not you bi power, and thei drawen you to domes?
30282	59	2	7	Whether thei blasfemen not the good name, that is clepid to help on you?
30283	59	2	8	Netheles if ye performen the kingis lawe, bi scripturis, Thou schalt loue thi neiybour as thi silf, ye don wel.
30284	59	2	9	But if ye taken persones, ye worchen synne, and ben repreued of the lawe, as trespasseris.
30285	59	2	10	And who euere kepith al the lawe, but offendith in oon, he is maad gilti of alle.
30286	59	2	11	For he that seide, Thou schalt do no letcherie, seide also, Thou schalt not sle; that if thou doist not letcherie, but thou sleest, thou art maad trespassour of the lawe.
30287	59	2	12	Thus speke ye, and thus do ye, as bigynnynge to be demyd bi the lawe of fredom.
30288	59	2	13	For whi dom with out merci is to hym, that doith no mercy; but merci aboue reisith dom.
30289	59	2	14	Mi britheren, what schal it profite, if ony man seie that he hath feith, but he hath not the werkis? whether feith schal mowe saue hym?
30290	59	2	15	And if a brother ethir sister be nakid, and han nede of ech daies lyuelode,
30291	59	2	16	and if ony of you seie to hem, Go ye in pees, be ye maad hoot, and be ye fillid; but if ye yyuen not to hem tho thingis that ben necessarie to bodi, what schal it profite?
30292	59	2	17	So also feith, if it hath not werkis, is deed in it silf.
30293	59	2	18	But summan schal seie, Thou hast feith, and Y haue werkis; schewe thou to me thi feith with out werkis, and Y schal schewe to thee my feith of werkis.
30294	59	2	19	Thou bileuest, that o God is; thou doist wel; and deuelis bileuen, and tremblen.
30295	59	2	20	But wolt thou wite, thou veyn man, that feith with out werkis is idul?
30296	59	2	21	Whether Abraham, oure fadir, was not iustified of werkis, offringe Ysaac, his sone, on the auter?
30297	59	2	22	Therfor thou seest, that feith wrouyte with hise werkis, and his feith was fillid of werkis.
30298	59	2	23	And the scripture was fillid, seiynge, Abraham bileuede to God, and it was arettid to hym to riytwisnesse, and he was clepid the freend of God.
30299	59	2	24	Ye seen that a man is iustified of werkis, and not of feith oneli.
30300	59	2	25	In lijk maner, and whether also Raab, the hoore, was not iustified of werkis, and resseyuede the messangeris, and sente hem out bi anothir weie?
30301	59	2	26	For as the bodi with out spirit is deed, so also feith with out werkis is deed.
30302	59	3	1	Mi britheren, nyle ye be maad many maistris, witynge that ye taken the more doom.
30303	59	3	2	For alle we offenden in many thingis. If ony man offendith not in word, this is a perfit man; for also he may lede aboute al the bodi with a bridil.
30304	59	3	3	For if we putten bridlis `in to horsis mouthis, for to consente to vs, and we leden aboute al the bodi of hem.
30305	59	3	4	And lo! schippis, whanne thei ben grete, and ben dryuun of stronge wyndis, yit thei ben borun about of a litil gouernaile, where the meuyng of the gouernour wole.
30306	59	3	5	So also the tunge is but a litil membre, and reisith grete thingis. Lo! hou litil fier brenneth a ful greet wode.
30307	59	3	6	And oure tunge is fier, the vniuersite of wickidnesse. The tunge is ordeyned in oure membris, which defoulith al the bodi; and it is enflawmed of helle, and enflawmeth the wheel of oure birthe.
30308	59	3	7	And al the kynde of beestis, and of foulis, and of serpentis, and of othere is chastisid, and tho ben maad tame of mannus kinde; but no man mai chastise the tunge,
30309	59	3	8	for it is an vnpesible yuel, and ful of deedli venym.
30310	59	3	9	In it we blessen God, the fadir, and in it we cursen men, that ben maad to the licnesse of God.
30311	59	3	10	Of the same mouth passith forth blessing and cursing. My britheren, it bihoueth not that these thingis be don so.
30312	59	3	11	Whether a welle of the same hoole bringith forth swete and salt watir?
30313	59	3	12	My britheren, whether a fige tre may make grapis, ethir a vyne figus? So nethir salt watir mai make swete watir.
30314	59	3	13	Who is wijs, and tauyt among you? schewe he of good lyuyng his worching, in myldenesse of his wisdom.
30315	59	3	14	That if ye han bitter enuye, and stryuyngis ben in youre hertis, nyle ye haue glorye, and be lyeris ayens the treuthe.
30316	59	3	15	For this wisdom is not fro aboue comynge doun, but ertheli, and beestli, and feendli.
30317	59	3	16	For where is enuye and strijf, there is vnstidfastnesse and al schrewid werk.
30318	59	3	17	But wisdom that is from aboue, first it is chast, aftirward pesible, mylde, able to be counseilid, consentinge to goode thingis, ful of merci and of goode fruytis, demynge with out feynyng.
30319	59	3	18	And the fruyt of riytwisnesse is sowun in pees, to men that maken pees.
30320	59	4	1	Wherof ben batelis and cheestis among you? Whether not of youre coueitisis, that fiyten in youre membris?
30321	59	4	2	Ye coueiten, and ye han not; ye sleen, and ye han enuye, and ye moun not gete. Ye chiden, and maken batel; and ye han not, for ye axen not.
30322	59	4	3	Ye axen, and ye resseyuen not; for that ye axen yuele, as ye schewen opynli in youre coueitisis.
30323	59	4	4	Auowtreris, witen not ye, that the frenschip of this world is enemye to God? Therfor who euere wole be frend of this world, is maad the enemye of God.
30324	59	4	5	Whether ye gessen, that the scripture seith veynli, The spirit that dwellith in you, coueitith to enuye?
30325	59	4	6	But he yyueth the more grace; for which thing he seith, God withstondith proude men, but to meke men he yyueth grace.
30326	59	4	7	Therfor be ye suget to God; but withstonde ye the deuel, and he schal fle fro you.
30327	59	4	8	Neiye ye to God, and he schal neiye to you. Ye synneris, clense ye hondis, and ye double in soule, purge ye the hertis.
30328	59	4	9	Be ye wretchis, and weile ye; youre leiyyng be turned in to weping, and ioye in to sorewe of herte.
30329	59	4	10	Be ye mekid in the siyt of the Lord, and he schal enhaunse you.
30330	59	4	11	My britheren, nyle ye bacbite ech othere. He that bacbitith his brothir, ethir that demeth his brothir, bacbitith the lawe, and demeth the lawe. And if thou demest the lawe, thou art not a doere of the lawe, but a domesman.
30331	59	4	12	But oon is makere of the lawe, and iuge, that may lese, and delyuere.
30332	59	4	13	And who art thou, that demest thi neiybore? Lo! now ye, that seien, To dai ethir to morewe we schulen go in to thilke citee, and there we schulen dwelle a yeer, and we schulen make marchaundise, and we schulen make wynning;
30333	59	4	14	whiche witen not, what is to you in the morewe.
30334	59	4	15	For what is youre lijf? A smoke apperinge at a litil, and aftirward it schal be wastid. Therfor that ye seie, If the Lord wole, and if we liuen, we schulen do this thing, ether that thing.
30335	59	4	16	And now ye maken ful out ioye in youre pridis; euery siche ioye is wickyd.
30336	59	4	17	Therfor it is synne to hym, that kan do good, and doith not.
30337	59	5	1	Do now, ye riche men, wepe ye, yellinge in youre wretchidnessis that schulen come to you.
30338	59	5	2	Youre richessis ben rotun, and youre clothis ben etun of mouytis.
30339	59	5	3	Youre gold and siluer hath rustid, and the rust of hem schal be to you in to witnessyng, and schal ete youre fleischis, as fier. Ye han tresourid to you wraththe in the last daies.
30340	59	5	4	Lo! the hire of youre werke men, that repiden youre feeldis, which is fraudid of you, crieth; and the cry of hem hath entrid in to the eeris of the Lord of oostis.
30341	59	5	5	Ye han ete on the erthe, and in youre letcheries ye han nurschid youre hertis. In the dai of sleyng ye brouyten,
30342	59	5	6	and slowen the iust man, and he ayenstood not you.
30343	59	5	7	Therfor, britheren, be ye pacient, til to the comyng of the Lord. Lo! an erthetilier abidith preciouse fruyt of the erthe, paciently suffrynge, til he resseyue `tymeful and lateful fruyt.
30344	59	5	8	And be ye pacient, and conferme ye youre hertis, for the comyng of the Lord schal neiye.
30345	59	5	9	Britheren, nyle ye be sorewful ech to other, that ye be not demed. Lo! the iuge stondith niy bifor the yate.
30346	59	5	10	Britheren, take ye ensaumple of yuel goyng out, and of long abidyng, and trauel, and of pacience, the prophetis, that speken to you in the name of the Lord.
30347	59	5	11	Lo! we blessen hem that suffriden. Ye herden the `suffring, ethir pacience, of Joob, and ye sayn the ende of the Lord, for the Lord is merciful, and doynge merci.
30348	59	5	12	Bifor alle thingis, my britheren, nyle ye swere, nether bi heuene, nether bi erthe, nethir bi what euere other ooth. But be youre word Yhe, yhe, Nay, nay, that ye fallen not vndir doom.
30349	59	5	13	And if ony of you is sorewful, preye he with pacient soule, and seie he a salm.
30350	59	5	14	If ony of you is sijk, lede he in preestis of the chirche, and preie thei for hym, and anoynte with oile in the name of the Lord;
30351	59	5	15	and the preier of feith schal saue the sijk man, and the Lord schal make hym liyt; and if he be in synnes, thei schulen be foryouun to hym.
30352	59	5	16	Therfor knouleche ye ech to othere youre synnes, and preye ye ech for othere, that ye be sauyd. For the contynuel preyer of a iust man is myche worth.
30353	59	5	17	Elye was a deedli man lijk vs, and in preier he preiede, that it schulde not reyne on the erthe, and it reynede not thre yeeris and sixe monethis.
30354	59	5	18	And eftsoone he preiede, and heuene yaf reyn, and the erthe yaf his fruyt.
30355	59	5	19	And, britheren, if ony of you errith fro trewthe, and ony conuertith hym,
30356	59	5	20	he owith to wite, that he that makith a synner to be turned fro the errour of his weye, schal saue the soule of hym fro deth, and keuereth the multitude of synnes.
30357	60	1	1	Petre, apostle of Jhesu Crist, to the chosun men, to the comelingis of scateryng abrood, of Ponte, of Galathie, of Capadosie,
30358	60	1	2	of Asye, and of Bitynye, bi the `bifor knowyng of God, the fadir, in halewyng of spirit, bi obedience, and springyng of the blood of Jhesu Crist, grace and pees be multiplied to you.
30359	60	1	3	Blessid be God, and the fadir of oure Lord Jhesu Crist, which bi his greet merci bigat vs ayen in to lyuynge hope, bi the ayen risyng of Jhesu Crist fro deth,
30360	60	1	4	in to eritage vncorruptible, and vndefoulid, and that schal not fade, that is kept in heuenes for you,
30361	60	1	5	that in the vertu of God ben kept bi the feith in to heelthe, and is redi to be schewid in the last tyme.
30362	60	1	6	In which ye schulen make ioye, thouy it bihoueth now a litil to be sori in dyuerse temptaciouns;
30363	60	1	7	that the preuyng of youre feith be myche more preciouse than gold, that is preuyd bi fier; and be foundun in to heriyng, and glorie, and onour, in the reuelacioun of Jhesu Crist.
30364	60	1	8	Whom whanne ye han not seyn, ye louen; in to whom also now ye not seynge, bileuen; but ye that bileuen schulen haue ioye, and gladnesse that may not be teld out,
30365	60	1	9	and ye schulen be glorified, and haue the ende of youre feith, the helthe of youre soulis.
30366	60	1	10	Of which helthe profetis souyten, and enserchiden, that profecieden of the grace to comyng in you,
30367	60	1	11	and souyten which euer what maner tyme the spirit of Crist signyfiede in hem, and bifor telde tho passiouns, that ben in Crist, and the latere glories.
30368	60	1	12	To which it was schewid, for not to hem silf, but to you thei mynystriden tho thingis, that now ben teld to you bi hem that prechiden to you bi the Hooli Goost sent fro heuene, in to whom aungelis desiren to biholde.
30369	60	1	13	For which thing be ye gird the leendis of youre soule, sobre, perfit, and hope ye in to the ilke grace that is profrid to you bi the schewyng of Jhesu Crist,
30370	60	1	14	as sones of obedience, not made lijk to the formere desiris of youre vnkunnyngnesse,
30371	60	1	15	but lijk him that hath `clepid you hooli; that also `ye silf be hooli in `al lyuyng;
30372	60	1	16	for it is writun, Ye schulen be hooli, for Y am hooli.
30373	60	1	17	And if ye inwardli clepe him fadir, which demeth withouten accepcioun of persoones bi the werk of ech man, lyue ye in drede in the time of youre pilgrimage; witynge that not bi corruptible gold,
30374	60	1	18	ethir siluer, ye ben bouyt ayen of youre veyn liuynge of fadris tradicioun,
30375	60	1	19	but bi the precious blood as of the lomb vndefoulid and vnspottid,
30376	60	1	20	Crist Jhesu, that was knowun bifor the makyng of the world, but he is schewid in the laste tymes,
30377	60	1	21	for you that bi hym ben feithful in God; that reiside hym fro deth, and yaf to hym euerlastynge glorie, that youre feith and hope were in God.
30378	60	1	22	And make ye chast youre soulis in obedience of charite, in loue of britherhod; of simple herte loue ye togidre more bisili.
30379	60	1	23	And be ye borun ayen, not of corruptible seed, `but vncorruptible, bi the word of lyuynge God, and dwellynge in to with outen ende.
30380	60	1	24	For ech fleisch is hey, and al the glorie of it is as flour of hey; the hei driede vp, and his flour felde doun;
30381	60	1	25	but the word of the Lord dwellith with outen ende. And this is the word, that is prechid to you.
30382	60	2	1	Therfor putte ye awei al malice, and al gile, and feynyngis, and enuyes, and alle bacbityngis;
30383	60	2	2	as now borun yonge children, resonable, with out gile, coueite ye mylk, that in it ye wexe in to helthe; if netheles ye han tastid,
30384	60	2	3	that the Lord is swete.
30385	60	2	4	And neiye ye to hym, that is a lyuyng stoon, and repreuyd of men, but chosun of God, and onourid;
30386	60	2	5	and ye silf as quyk stoonys be ye aboue bildid in to spiritual housis, and an hooli preesthod, to offre spiritual sacrifices, acceptable to God bi Jhesu Crist.
30387	60	2	6	For which thing the scripture seith, Lo! Y schal sette in Syon the hiyeste corner stoon, chosun and preciouse; and he that schal belieue in hym, schal not be confoundid.
30388	60	2	7	Therfor onour to you that bileuen; but to men that bileuen not, the stoon whom the bilderis repreuyden, this is maad in to the heed of the corner; and the stoon of hirtyng,
30389	60	2	8	and stoon of sclaundre, to hem that offenden to the word, nethir bileuen it, in which thei ben set.
30390	60	2	9	But ye ben a chosun kyn, a kyngli preesthod, hooli folc, a puple of purchasing, that ye telle the vertues of hym, that clepide you fro derknessis in to his wondirful liyt.
30391	60	2	10	Which sum tyme were not a puple of God, but now ye ben the puple of God; which hadden not merci, but now ye han merci.
30392	60	2	11	Moost dere, Y biseche you, as comelyngis and pilgrymys, to absteine you fro fleischli desiris, that fiyten ayens the soule;
30393	60	2	12	and haue ye youre conuersacioun good among hethene men, that in that thing that thei bacbite of you, as of mysdoeris, thei biholden you of good werkis, and glorifie God in the dai of visitacioun.
30394	60	2	13	Be ye suget to ech creature, for God; ethir to the kyng, as to hym that is hiyer in state,
30395	60	2	14	ethir to duykis, as to thilke that ben sent of hym to the veniaunce of mysdoers, and to the preisyng of good men.
30396	60	2	15	For so is the wille of God, that ye do wel, and make the vnkunnyngnesse of vnprudent men to be doumb.
30397	60	2	16	As fre men, and not as hauynge fredom the keuering of malice, but as the seruauntis of God.
30398	60	2	17	Onoure ye alle men, loue ye brithirhod, drede ye God, onoure ye the king.
30399	60	2	18	Seruauntis, be ye sugetis in al drede to lordis, not oneli to good and to mylde, but also to tyrauntis.
30400	60	2	19	For this is grace, if for conscience of God ony man suffrith heuynessis, and suffrith vniustli.
30401	60	2	20	For what grace is it, if ye synnen, and ben buffatid, and suffren? But if ye don wel, and suffren pacientli, this is grace anentis God.
30402	60	2	21	For to this thing ye ben clepid. For also Crist suffride for vs, and lefte ensaumple to you, that ye folewe the steppis of hym.
30403	60	2	22	Which dide not synne, nethir gile was foundun in his mouth.
30404	60	2	23	And whanne he was cursid, he curside not; whanne he suffride, he manasside not; but he bitook hym silf to hym, that demyde hym vniustli.
30405	60	2	24	And he hym silf bar oure synnes in his bodi on a tre, that we be deed to synnes, and lyue to riytwisnesse, bi whos wan wounde ye ben heelid.
30406	60	2	25	For ye weren as scheep errynge, but ye ben now turned to the schipherde, and bischop of youre soulis.
30407	60	3	1	Also wymmen be thei suget to her hosebondis; that if ony man bileue not to the word, bi the conuersacioun of wymmen thei be wonnun with out word.
30408	60	3	2	And biholde ye in drede youre hooli conuersacioun.
30409	60	3	3	Of whiche `ther be not with outforth curious ournyng of heer, ether doyng aboute of gold, ethir ournyng of clothing;
30410	60	3	4	but thilke that is the hid man of herte, in vncorrupcioun, and of mylde spirit, which is riche in the siyt of God.
30411	60	3	5	For so sumtyme hooli wymmen hopinge in God ourneden hem silf, and weren suget to her owne hosebondis.
30412	60	3	6	As Sara obeied to Abraham, and clepide hym lord; of whom ye ben douytris wel doynge, and not dredynge ony perturbacioun.
30413	60	3	7	Also men dwelle togidre, and bi kunnyng yyue ye onoure to the wommanus freeltee, as to the more feble, and as to euen eiris of grace and of lijf, that youre preieris be not lettid.
30414	60	3	8	And in feith alle of oon wille in preier be ye eche suffringe with othere, loueris of britherhod, merciful, mylde, meke;
30415	60	3	9	not yeldinge yuel for yuel, nether cursing for cursing, but ayenward blessinge; for in this thing ye ben clepid, that ye welde blessinge bi eritage.
30416	60	3	10	For he that wole loue lijf, and se goode daies, constreyne his tunge from yuel, and hise lippis, that thei speke not gile.
30417	60	3	11	And bowe he from yuel, and do good; seke he pees, and perfitli sue it.
30418	60	3	12	For the iyen of the Lord ben on iust men, and hise eris on the preieris of hem; but the cheer of the Lord is on men that don yuels.
30419	60	3	13	And who is it that schal anoye you, if ye ben sueris and louyeris of goodnesse?
30420	60	3	14	But also if ye suffren ony thing for riytwisnesse, ye ben blessid; but drede ye not the drede of hem, that ye be not disturblid.
30421	60	3	15	But halewe ye the Lord Crist in youre hertis, and euermore be ye redi to satisfaccioun to ech man axynge you resoun of that feith and hope that is in you,
30422	60	3	16	but with myldenesse and drede, hauynge good conscience; that in that thing that thei bacbiten of you, thei ben confoundid, whiche chalengen falsly youre good conuersacioun in Crist.
30423	60	3	17	For it is betere that ye do wel, and suffre, if the wille of God wole, than doynge yuele.
30424	60	3	18	For also Crist onys diede for oure synnes, he iust for vniust, that he schulde offre to God vs, maad deed in fleisch, but maad quik in spirit.
30425	60	3	19	For which thing he cam in spirit, and also to hem that weren closid togidre in prisoun prechide;
30426	60	3	20	whiche weren sum tyme vnbileueful, whanne thei abididen the pacience of God in the daies of Noe, whanne the schip was maad, in which a few, that is to seie, eiyte soulis weren maad saaf bi water.
30427	60	3	21	And so baptym of lijk forme makith vs saaf; not the puttyng awei of the filthis of fleisch, but the axyng of a good conscience in God, bi the ayenrysyng of oure Lord Jhesu Crist, that is in the riyt half of God,
30428	60	3	22	and swolewith deth, that we schulden be made eiris of euerlastinge lijf. He yede in to heuene, and aungelis, and powers, and vertues, ben maad sugetis to hym.
30429	60	4	1	Therfor for Crist suffride in fleisch, be ye also armed bi the same thenkynge; for he that suffride in fleisch ceesside fro synnes,
30430	60	4	2	that that is left now in fleisch lyue not now to the desiris of men, but to the wille of God.
30431	60	4	3	For the time that is passid is ynow to the wille of hethene men to be endid, whiche walkiden in letcheries, and lustis, in myche drinking of wyn, in vnmesurable etyngis, and drynkyngis, and vnleueful worschiping of mawmetis.
30432	60	4	4	In whiche now thei ben astonyed, in which thing thei wondren, for ye rennen not togidere `in to the same confusioun of letcherie, and blasfemen.
30433	60	4	5	And thei schulen yyue resoun to hym, that is redi to deme the quyke and the deed.
30434	60	4	6	For whi for this thing it is prechid also to deed men, that thei be demed bi men in fleisch, and that thei lyue bi God in spirit.
30435	60	4	7	For the ende of alle thingis schal neiye. Therfor be ye prudent, and wake ye in preyeris;
30436	60	4	8	bifore alle thingis haue ye charite ech to other in you silf algatis lastynge; for charite couerith the multitude of synnes.
30437	60	4	9	Holde ye hospitalite togidere with out grutching;
30438	60	4	10	ech man as he hath resseyued grace, mynystringe it in to ech othere, as good dispenderis of the manyfold grace of God.
30439	60	4	11	If ony man spekith, speke he as the wordis of God; if ony man mynystrith, as of the vertu which God mynystrith; that God be onourid in alle thingis bi Jhesu Crist oure Lord, to whom is glorie and lordschip in to worldis `of worldis.
30440	60	4	12	Amen. Moost dere brytheren, nyle ye go in pilgrymage in feruour, that is maad to you to temptacioun, as if ony newe thing bifalle to you;
30441	60	4	13	but comyne ye with the passiouns of Crist, and haue ye ioye, that also ye be glad, and haue ioye in the reuelacioun of his glorie.
30442	60	4	14	If ye ben dispisid for the name of Crist, ye schulen be blessid; for that that is of the onour, and of the glorie, and of the vertu of God, and the spirit that is his, schal reste on you.
30443	60	4	15	But no man of you suffre as a mansleere, ethir a theef, ether cursere, ethir a disirere of othere mennus goodis;
30444	60	4	16	but if as a cristen man, schame he not, but glorifie he God in this name.
30445	60	4	17	For tyme is, that doom bigynne at Goddis hous; and if it bigynne first at vs, what ende schal be of hem, that bileuen not to the gospel?
30446	60	4	18	And if a iust man vnnethe schal be sauid, where schulen the vnfeithful man and the synnere appere? Therfor and thei that suffren bi the wille of God, bitaken her soulis in good dedis to the feithful makere of nouyt.
30447	60	5	1	Therfor Y, an euene eldre man, and a witnesse of Cristis passiouns, which also am a comynere of that glorie, that schal be schewid in tyme to comynge; byseche ye the eldre men,
30448	60	5	2	that ben among you, fede ye the flok of God, that is among you, and puruey ye, not as constreyned, but wilfulli, bi God; not for loue of foule wynnyng,
30449	60	5	3	but wilfulli, nether as hauynge lordschip in the clergie, but that ye ben maad ensaumple of the floc, of wille.
30450	60	5	4	And whanne the prince of scheepherdis schal appere, ye schulen resseyue the coroun of glorie, that may neuere fade.
30451	60	5	5	Also, ye yonge men, be ye suget to eldre men, and alle schewe ye togidere mekenesse; for the Lord withstondith proude men, but he yyueth grace to meke men.
30452	60	5	6	Therfor be ye mekid vndir the myyti hoond of God, that he reise you in the tyme of visitacioun,
30453	60	5	7	and caste ye al youre bisynesse in to hym, for to hym is cure of you.
30454	60	5	8	Be ye sobre, and wake ye, for youre aduersarie, the deuel, as a rorynge lioun goith aboute, sechinge whom he schal deuoure.
30455	60	5	9	Whom ayenstonde ye, stronge in the feith, witynge that the same passioun is maad to thilke brithirhode of you, that is in the world.
30456	60	5	10	And God of al grace, that clepide you in to his euerlastinge glorie, you suffrynge a litil, he schal performe, and schal conferme, and schal make sad.
30457	60	5	11	To hym be glorie and lordschip, in to worldis of worldis. Amen.
30458	60	5	12	Bi Siluan, feithful brother to you as Y deme, Y wroot schortli; bisechinge, and witnessinge that this is the very grace of God, in which ye stonden.
30459	60	5	13	The chirche that is gaderid in Babiloyne, and Marcus, my sone, gretith you wel.
30460	60	5	14	Grete ye wel togidere in hooli cos. Grace be to you alle that ben in Crist. Amen.
30461	61	1	1	Simount Petre, seruaunt and apostle of `Jhesu Crist, to hem that han take with vs the euene feith, in the riytwisnesse of oure God and sauyour Jhesu Crist,
30462	61	1	2	grace and pees be fillid to you, bi the knowing of oure Lord Jhesu Crist.
30463	61	1	3	Hou alle thingis of his godlich vertu, that ben to lijf and pitee, ben youun to vs, bi the knowyng of hym, that clepide vs for his owne glorie and vertu.
30464	61	1	4	Bi whom he yaf to vs moost preciouse biheestis; that bi these thingis ye schulen be maad felows of Goddis kynde, and fle the corrupcioun of that coueytise, that is in the world.
30465	61	1	5	And bringe ye in alle bisynesse, and mynystre ye in youre feith vertu, and `in vertu kunnyng;
30466	61	1	6	in kunnyng abstinence, in abstynence pacience, in pacience pitee;
30467	61	1	7	in pitee, love of britherhod, and in loue of britherhod charite.
30468	61	1	8	For if these ben with you, and ouercomen, thei schulen not make you voide, nethir with out fruyt, in the knowyng of oure Lord Jhesu Crist.
30469	61	1	9	But to whom these ben not redi, he is blynd, and gropith with his hoond, and foryetith the purgyng of his elde trespassis.
30470	61	1	10	Wherfor, britheren, be ye more bisi, that by goode werkis ye make youre clepyng and chesyng certeyn;
30471	61	1	11	for ye doynge these thingis schulen not do synne ony tyme. For thus the entryng in to euerlastynge kyngdom of oure Lord and sauyour Jhesu Crist, schal be mynystrid to you plenteuousli.
30472	61	1	12	For which thing Y schal bigynne to moneste you euere more of these thingis; and Y wole that ye be kunnynge, and confermyd in this present treuthe.
30473	61	1	13	Forsothe Y deme iustli, as long as Y am in this tabernacle, to reise you in monesting; and Y am certeyn,
30474	61	1	14	that the putting awei of my tabernacle is swift, bi this that oure Lord Jhesu Crist hath schewid to me.
30475	61	1	15	But Y schal yyue bisynesse, and ofte after my deth ye haue mynde of these thingis.
30476	61	1	16	For we not suynge vnwise talis, han maad knowun to you the vertu and the biforknowyng of oure Lord Jhesu Crist; but we weren maad biholderis of his greetnesse.
30477	61	1	17	For he took of God the fadir onour and glorie, bi siche maner vois slidun doun to hym fro the greet glorie, This is my loued sone, in whom Y haue plesid to me; here ye hym.
30478	61	1	18	And we herden this vois brouyt from heuene, whanne we weren with hym in the hooli hil.
30479	61	1	19	And we han a saddere word of prophecie, to which ye yyuynge tent don wel, as to a lanterne that yyueth liyt in a derk place, til the dai bigynne to yyue liyt, and the dai sterre sprenge in youre hertis.
30480	61	1	20	And firste vndurstonde ye this thing, that ech prophesie of scripture is not maad bi propre interpretacioun;
30481	61	1	21	for prophesie was not brouyt ony tyme bi mannus wille, but the hooli men of God inspirid with the Hooli Goost spaken.
30482	61	2	1	But also false prophetis weren in the puple, as in you schulen be maistris lieris, that schulen bringe in sectis of perdicioun; and thei denyen thilke Lord that bouyte hem, and bringen on hem silf hasti perdicioun.
30483	61	2	2	And many schulen sue her letcheries, bi whiche the weie of treuthe schal be blasfemyd;
30484	61	2	3	and thei schulen make marchaundie of you in coueytise bi feyned wordis. To whiche doom now a while ago ceessith not, and the perdicioun of hem nappith not.
30485	61	2	4	For if God sparide not aungels synnynge, but bitook hem to be turmentid, and to be drawun doun with boondis of helle in to helle, to be kept in to dom;
30486	61	2	5	and sparide not the firste world, but kept Noe, the eiythe man, the biforgoere of riytwisnesse, and brouyte in the greet flood to the world of vnfeithful men;
30487	61	2	6	and he droof in to poudre the citees of men of Sodom and of men of Gommor, and dampnede bi turnyng vpsedoun, and putte hem the ensaumple of hem that weren to doynge yuele;
30488	61	2	7	and delyuerid the iust Loth, oppressid of the wrong, and of the letcherouse conuersacioun of cursid men;
30489	61	2	8	for in siyt and hering he was iust, and dwellide amongst hem that fro dai in to dai turmentiden with wickid werkis a iust soule.
30490	61	2	9	For the Lord kan delyuere piteuouse men fro temptacioun, and kepe wickid men `in to the dai of dom to be turmentid;
30491	61	2	10	but more hem that walken aftir the fleisch, in coueytinge of vnclennesse, and dispisen lordschiping, and ben boold, plesynge hem silf, and dreden not to bringe in sectis, blasfemynge; where aungels,
30492	61	2	11	whanne thei ben more in strengthe and vertu, beren not `that was the execrable doom ayens hem.
30493	61	2	12	But these ben as vnresonable beestis, kyndli in to takyng, and in to deth, blasfemynge in these thingis that thei knowen not, and schulen perische in her corrupcioun,
30494	61	2	13	and resseyue the hire of vnriytwisnesse. And thei gessen delicis of defouling and of wemme, to be likyngis of dai, flowynge in her feestis with delicis, doynge letcherie with you,
30495	61	2	14	and han iyen ful of auowtrie, and vnceessynge trespas, disseyuynge vnstidfast soulis, and han the herte excercisid to coueitise; the sones of cursyng,
30496	61	2	15	that forsaken the riyt weie, and erriden, suynge the weie of Balaam of Bosor, which louyde the hire of wickidnesse.
30497	61	2	16	But he hadde repreuyng of his woodnesse; a doumb beest vndur yok, that spak with vois of man, that forbede the vnwisdom of the profete.
30498	61	2	17	These ben wellis with out watir, and mystis dryuun with `whirlinge wyndys, to whiche the thicke mijst of derknessis is reseruyd.
30499	61	2	18	And thei speken in pryde of vanyte, and disseyuen in desiris of fleisch of letcherie hem, that scapen a litil.
30500	61	2	19	Whiche lyuen in errour, and biheten fredom to hem, whanne thei ben seruauntis of corrupcioun. For of whom ony man is ouercomun, of hym also he is seruaunt.
30501	61	2	20	For if men forsaken the vnclennessis of the world, bi the knowyng of oure Lord and sauyour Jhesu Crist, and eftsone ben wlappid in these, and ben ouercomun, the lattere thingis ben maad to hem worse than the formere.
30502	61	2	21	For it was betere to hem to not knowe the weie of riytwisnesse, than to turne ayen aftir the knowyng, fro that hooli maundement that was bitakun to hem.
30503	61	2	22	For thilke very prouerb bifelde to hem, The hound turnede ayen to his castyng, and a sowe is waischun in walwyng in fenne.
30504	61	3	1	Lo! ye moost dereworth britheren, Y write to you this secounde epistle, in which Y stire youre clere soule bi monesting togidere,
30505	61	3	2	that ye be myndeful of tho wordis, that Y biforseide of the hooli prophetis, and of the maundementis of the hooli apostlis of the Lord and sauyour.
30506	61	3	3	First wite ye this thing, that in the laste daies disseyueris schulen come in disseit, goynge aftir her owne coueityngis,
30507	61	3	4	seiynge, Where is the biheest, or the comyng of hym? for sithen the fadris dieden, alle thingis lasten fro the bigynnyng of creature.
30508	61	3	5	But it is hid fro hem willynge this thing, that heuenes were bifore, and the erthe of water was stondynge bi watir, of Goddis word;
30509	61	3	6	bi which that ilke world clensid, thanne bi watir perischide.
30510	61	3	7	But the heuenes that now ben, and the erthe, ben kept bi the same word, and ben reseruyd to fier in to the dai of doom and perdicioun of wickid men.
30511	61	3	8	But, ye moost dere, this o thing be not hid to you, that o dai anentis God is as a thousynde yeeris, and a thousynde yeeris ben as o dai.
30512	61	3	9	The Lord tarieth not his biheest, as summe gessen, but he doith pacientli for you, and wole not that ony men perische, but that alle turne ayen to penaunce.
30513	61	3	10	For the dai of the Lord schal come as a theef, in which heuenes with greet bire schulen passe, and elementis schulen be dissoluyd bi heete, and the erthe, and alle the werkis that ben in it, schulen be brent.
30514	61	3	11	Therfor whanne alle these thingis schulen be dissolued, what manner men bihoueth it you to be in hooli lyuyngis and pitees,
30515	61	3	12	abidinge and hiyynge in to the comyng of the dai of oure Lord Jhesu Crist, bi whom heuenes brennynge schulen be dissoluyd, and elementis schulen faile bi brennyng of fier.
30516	61	3	13	Also we abiden bi hise biheestis newe heuenes and newe erthe, in which riytwisnesse dwellith.
30517	61	3	14	For which thing, ye moost dere, abidynge these thingis, be ye bisye to be foundun to hym in pees vnspottid and vndefoulid.
30518	61	3	15	And deme ye long abiding of oure Lord Jhesu Crist youre heelthe, as also oure moost dere brother Poul wroot to you, bi wisdom youun to hym.
30519	61	3	16	As and in alle epistlis he spekith `in hem of these thingis; in which ben summe hard thingis to vndurstonde, whiche vnwise and vnstable men deprauen, as also thei don othere scripturis, to her owne perdicioun.
30520	61	3	17	Therfor ye, britheren, bifor witynge kepe you silf, lest ye be disseyued bi errour of vnwise men, and falle awei fro youre owne sadnesse.
30521	61	3	18	But wexe ye in the grace and the knowyng of oure Lord Jhesu Crist and oure Sauyour; to hym be glorie now and in to the dai of euerlastyngnesse. Amen.
30522	62	1	1	That thing that was fro the bigynnyng, which we herden, which we sayn with oure iyen, which we bihelden, and oure hondis touchiden, of the word of lijf; and the lijf is schewid.
30523	62	1	2	And we sayn, and we witnessen, and tellen to you the euerlastynge lijf, that was anentis the fadir, and apperide to vs.
30524	62	1	3	Therfor `we tellen to you that thing, that we seyn, and herden, that also ye haue felowschipe with vs, and oure felowschip be with the fadir, and with his sone Jhesu Crist.
30525	62	1	4	And we writen this thing to you, that ye haue ioye, and that youre ioye be ful.
30526	62	1	5	And this is the tellyng, that we herden of hym, and tellen to you, that God is liyt, and ther ben no derknessis in him.
30527	62	1	6	If we seien, that we han felawschip with hym, and we wandren in derknessis, we lien, and don not treuthe.
30528	62	1	7	But if we walken in liyt, as also he is in liyt, we han felawschip togidere; and the blood of Jhesu Crist, his sone, clensith vs fro al synne.
30529	62	1	8	If we seien, that we han no synne, we disseyuen vs silf, and treuthe is not in vs.
30530	62	1	9	If we knowlechen oure synnes, he is feithful and iust, that he foryyue to vs oure synnes, and clense vs from al wickidnesse.
30531	62	1	10	And if we seien, we han not synned, we maken hym a liere, and his word is not in vs.
30532	62	2	1	Mi litle sones, Y write to you these thingis, that ye synnen not. But if ony man synneth, we han an aduocat anentis the fadir,
30533	62	2	2	Jhesu Crist, and he is the foryyuenes for oure synnes; and not oneli for oure synnes, but also for the synnes of al the world.
30534	62	2	3	And in this thing we witen, that we knowen hym, if we kepen hise comaundementis.
30535	62	2	4	He that seith that he knowith God, and kepith not hise comaundementis, is a liere, and trewthe is not in hym.
30536	62	2	5	But the charite of God is perfit verili in hym, that kepith his word. In this thing we witen, that we ben in hym, if we ben perfit in hym.
30537	62	2	6	He that seith, that he dwellith in hym, he owith for to walke, as he walkide.
30538	62	2	7	Moost dere britheren, Y write to you, not a newe maundement, but the elde maundement, that ye hadden fro the bigynnyng. The elde maundement is the word, that ye herden.
